\begin_layout Chapter*
Author's Preface & Acknowledgments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This book builds on the idea that students in social sciences early on can benefit from learning the foundations of mathematics and statistics relatively thoroughly.
 I have here tried to write the introduction I wish I had received when I began my university studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work overlaps with various others that introduce mathematics,
 econometrics,
 and quantitative methods in general.
 But while most books,
 possibly for good reasons,
 choose to focus on one thing at a time,
 I try here to give the reader a feel for everything simultaneously.
 My hope is that this combination both increases the possibilities to see how these things connect with each other and their connection to the methodological core of social science,
 insofar as such exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One difference from some previous methodology books is that this largely starts from our interest in making statements regarding how and why things are the way they are,
 causal relationships.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
What you will learn
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part I presents the basic foundations of mathematics,
 in a similar fashion as most people learn some math in (or around) high school.
 But perhaps unlike high school,
 this part contains some examples of economic and social theories described with mathematics,
 as well as some examples with data.
 The first chapter of part I describes the book's content,
 purpose and some tips for reading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part II also presents mathematical foundations,
 but focus on mathematical concepts often considered a more complex,
 advanced or abstract.
 For instance,
 more details on linear (matrix) algebra,
 linear programming,
 difference equations and differential equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part III introduces the basic math behind probability theory as well as gentle introduction to statistical inference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part IV introduces how we can describe and study variation and covariation,
 when two or more variables change together.
 This part put a lot of focus on regression analysis and the least squares method – a highly central concept to a lot (most?) of science.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A theme throughout this whole book is causal analysis.
 Part V discuss this in a bit more detail and introduces some common basic concepts and methods on how to study causal relationships.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part VI introduces the three analytical tools Microsoft Excel,
 Stata,
 and the programming language R.
 Analytical work is primarily performed with computers,
 but computer programs can also help us better understand mathematics and statistics.
 
\end_layout

