\begin_layout Standard
In English periods are used as decimal separators.
 Many countries instead use a comma as decimal separator.
 All integers can be written with decimals if desired.
 The integer 17 can,
 for example,
 be written as 17.0 or 17.00,
 or 17.000 and so on.
 As a rule,
 we omit the decimals when all decimals (all decimal places) are 0 in a number.
 The zeros after the decimal point do not provide the reader with any interesting information.
 The same applies if we have,
 for example,
 the number 6.8.
 It does not help the reader to write this as 6.80 or 6.8000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Real numbers can be described as being located on a number line with larger values to the right and smaller values to the left.
 Numbers above 0 are called positive numbers.
 Numbers below 0 are called negative numbers.
 If there is no sign in front of a digit,
 the number is positive.
 If there is a minus sign in front,
 the number is negative.
 Figure 
