\begin_layout Plain Layout
absolute value
\end_layout

\end_inset

A number's absolute value is the number's distance from 0 on the number line.
 The absolute value of the number 5 is 5.
 The absolute value of 
\begin_inset Formula $-5$
\end_inset

 is also 5.
 Absolute value is written with vertical bars.
 Here are three examples:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left|5\right| & =5\\
\left|-5\right| & =5\nonumber \\
\left|4-18\right| & =|-14|=14\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numbers that when divided by 2 result in a new integer are called even numbers.
 For example,
 the number 12 is even because 
\begin_inset Formula $12/2=6$
\end_inset

.
 Since 6 is an integer,
 12 is even.
 All even numbers multiplied by themselves result in a new even number.
 If the result of division by 2 becomes a number with decimals,
 the number being divided is an odd number.
 For example,
 the number 11 is an odd number because 
\begin_inset Formula $11/2=5.5$
\end_inset

.
 All odd numbers multiplied by themselves always result in a new odd number.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3\times3=9
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the number 3 and 9 are odd numbers,
 which is easy to see since 
\begin_inset Formula $3/2=1.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $9/2=4.5$
\end_inset

.
 Two other examples:
 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5=25$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $7\times7=49$
\end_inset

.
 The numbers 5,
 7,
 25 and 49 are odd numbers.
 Here are two examples:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\times2 & =4\\
6\times6 & =36\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numbers 2,
 4,
 6 and 36 are even numbers.
 Sometimes we find it useful to rewrite a fraction as a number with decimals,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2=0.5$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 Some fractions cannot be written exactly with decimals.
 One such example is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/3\approx0.33333....$
\end_inset

 Numbers that can be expressed exactly as a fraction with two integers are called rational numbers.
 Numbers that cannot be expressed as a fraction with two integers are called irrational numbers.
 A well-known example of an irrational number is pi,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\approx3.14$
\end_inset

.
 All real numbers can be written in the form of a fraction where we divide the number by 1.
 All real numbers can also be expressed as the number multiplied by 1.
 As an example,
 the number 123 is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $1*123$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $123/1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
123=1*123=\frac{123}{1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The number 1 can be written as a fraction with the same numerator and denominator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
1 & =\frac{123}{123}=\frac{5}{5}=\frac{17.3}{17.3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The four arithmetic operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have four arithmetic operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subtraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{written as }*\text{ or }\times\text{ or \,}\cdot\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Division 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{written as }/\text{ or }\div\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equals sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(=\right)$
\end_inset

 means that the result to the left of the sign becomes the same as the result to the right of the sign.
 The equals sign is also called the equality sign.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2=3$
\end_inset

.
 The left side of the equals sign is sometimes called the left-hand side,
 while the right side is called the right-hand side.
 When two or more numbers are added or subtracted,
 these numbers are called terms.
 The result of addition is called the sum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{1}_{\text{Term 1}}+\underbrace{2}_{\text{Term 2}}=\underbrace{3}_{\text{Sum}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The result from subtraction is called the difference:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{1}_{\text{Term 1}}-\underbrace{2}_{\text{Term 2}}=\underbrace{-1}_{\text{Difference}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two or more numbers are multiplied,
 the numbers are called factors.
 The result of multiplication is called the product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{1}_{\text{Factor 1}}\times\underbrace{2}_{\text{Factor 2}}=\underbrace{2}_{\text{Product}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplication can be written with any of the three symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(*,\times,\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
 There are several different symbols for the same arithmetic operation,
 but they mean exactly the same thing.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\times4*2\cdot2 & =4*2*2*2=2*2*2*4=32
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is perhaps a good example of how mathematics can be described as a language,
 a way of writing.
 The main thing is that the reader understands what you write.
 In division we have a number that we call the numerator,
 which is divided by another number,
 which we call the denominator.
 The result is called the quotient:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Quotient}=\frac{\text{Numerator}}{\text{Denominator}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Division can also be written in several ways,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

,
 which have the same meaning.
 The expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 can be read as "one divided by two" or "one over two".
 We must also take into account parentheses and powers.
 A power is a mathematical expression where a number,
 the base,
 is raised to another number,
 the exponent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Power}=\text{Base}^{\text{Exponent}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of a power expression is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which can be read as "10 to the power of 2".
 10 is the base and 2 is the exponent.
 The exponent indicates how many times the base should be multiplied by itself.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
10^{2} & =10*10=100\\
2^{3} & =2*2*2=8\nonumber \\
3^{4} & =3*3*3*3=81\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Order of operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a specific order for how we should perform the different arithmetic operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Parentheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Powers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplication and division,
 from left to right in each expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Addition and subtraction,
 from left to right in each expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now calculate an expression that contains multiplication,
 addition and subtraction.
 We therefore start with all multiplication signs,
 regardless of where in the expression they appear:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4+1*2-3=4+2-3
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression should be read as four plus one times two minus three equals four plus two minus three.
 The words "equals" mean that the result on both sides of the equals sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(=\right)$
\end_inset

 has the same value and gives the same result.
 In the next step we calculate addition and subtraction from left to right.
 In this case it doesn't matter if we first calculate addition and then subtraction,
 or vice versa:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4+2-3=4-1=6-3=3
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For plus and minus it doesn't matter in which order the numbers appear:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-1+2+3+4+5=13
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if we change the order of the terms to the left of the equals sign we get the same result,
 as long as the mathematical operator in front of the number (plus or minus) follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2-1+3+4+5=13
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that when a positive number,
 above 0,
 appears first in the expression we don't need to write out the plus sign.
 In multiplication it doesn't matter which of the numbers being multiplied comes first or last.
 In the order of operations,
 in the introduction to this section,
 points 3 and 4 describe how we should first calculate multiplication and division.
 This should also be calculated from left to right.
 Here is an example when this rule is important:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1/2/2/2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression can be read as 1 divided by 2,
 divided by 2,
 divided by 2.
 If we read the numbers from the left,
 which is correct,
 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Correct!} } & \text{Solving from the left:}\nonumber \\
\left(1/2\right)/2/2 & =\left(\left(1/2\right)/2\right)/2\\
 & =\left(1/4\right)/2\nonumber \\
 & =1/8\nonumber \\
 & =0.125\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead solve the equation from the right,
 which is incorrect,
 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\textbf{Incorrect! } & \text{Solving from the right: }\nonumber \\
1/2/\left(2/2\right) & =1/2/\left(1\right)\\
 & =1/\left(2/1\right)\nonumber \\
 & =1/2\nonumber \\
 & =0.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In row 2 we see the result from the parentheses,
 2 divided by 2,
 which gives the result 1.
 On the second-to-last row we have 1 divided by 2,
 which equals 0.5.
 That a calculation continues on the next line has no mathematical meaning.
 It is merely a way of writing to make reading easier.
 Here in the book we also use it so that the mathematical expressions fit on the pages.
 Let us take another example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\times3\div4\times5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This calculation contains both multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\times\right)$
\end_inset

 and division 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\div\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The calculation rules say that these two should be calculated simultaneously but from left to right.
 Let us calculate the answer from both left and right to compare:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{\textbf{Correct!} From the left.} & \text{\textbf{Incorrect!} From the right.}\\
2\times3\div4\times5= & 2\times3\div4\times5=\\
=6\div4\times5= & =2\times3\div20=\\
=\frac{3}{2}\times5= & =2\times\frac{3}{20}=\\
=\frac{15}{2}= & =\frac{6}{20}=\\
=7.5 & =0.3
\end{array}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The order of operations says that we should first calculate parentheses,
 powers and then multiplication and division,
 as well as addition and subtraction.
 Consider the following expression as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(1/2/2\right)^{2}\times\left(1+2\right)^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We start by calculating the contents of the parentheses.
 In the left parenthesis we calculate from left to right:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)^{2}\times\left(3\right)^{3}=\left(\frac{1}{4}*\frac{1}{4}\right)\times3^{3}=\frac{1}{16}\times9=\frac{9}{16}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When two parentheses are multiplied by each other,
 it is common for the multiplication sign to be omitted:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\times\left(3\right)=\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\left(3\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this chapter goes through in more detail how to calculate with parentheses (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Parenteser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 division (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Bråk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and powers (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Parentheses
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Parenteser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
parentheses
\end_layout

\end_inset

Parentheses can be used to make extensive mathematical expressions easier to read.
 There are special calculation rules for parentheses.
 If there is a minus sign in front of a parenthesis,
 it affects all terms inside the parenthesis.
 If we remove the parenthesis,
 all signs change from minus to plus and from plus to minus.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
1-\left(-2+3\right) & =1+2-3=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A plus sign in front of the parenthesis does not change any signs in the parenthesis:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1+\left(-2+3\right)=1-2+3=2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When multiplying numbers in parentheses,
 corresponding calculation rules apply.
 Multiplication of two negative numbers becomes a positive number.
 Multiplication of a negative and a positive number becomes a negative number.
 Examples:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-1*\left(-2+3\right) & =2-3
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or we could take:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1*\left(-2+3\right)=-2+3
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplication of a parenthesis affects all values in the parenthesis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-1\times\left(2+3+4+5\right)=-14
\]

\end_inset

All real numbers multiplied by 0 become 0:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\times-1\times\left(1-2-3-4-5\right)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here follow some illustrations of calculation rules for parentheses where we use the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\,b,\,c,\,d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 to symbolize arbitrary real numbers.
 We use letters to describe general rules.
 The reader may try replacing the letters with numbers.
 We start by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by the parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b+c\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by each letter in the parenthesis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\left(b+c\right)=ab+ac
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also possible to illustrate the same thing with numbers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\left(3+4\right) & =2*3+2*4=6+8=14
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It doesn't matter whether the number we multiply the parenthesis by is to the left or right of the parenthesis.
 Here is an example where we rewrite an expression in different ways,
 but all different writings give the same result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c\left(a+b\right)d & =cd\left(a+b\right)\\
 & =\left(a+b\right)cd\nonumber \\
 & =\left(ca+cb\right)d\nonumber \\
 & =cda+cdb\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A parenthesis may also be multiplied with another parenthesis.
 Each number in each parenthesis is then multiplied by each number in the other parenthesis.
 Let us take an example again where we rewrite an expression in different ways.
 All these different ways of writing give the same result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(a+b\right)\left(c+d\right) & =ac+ad+b\left(c+d\right)\\
 & =ac+ad+bc+bd\nonumber \\
 & =a\left(c+d\right)+b\left(c+d\right)\nonumber \\
 & =c\left(a+b\right)+d\left(a+b\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many times our work can be made easier by rewriting an expression so that it becomes a bit neater.
 When we write multiplication with letters,
 it is common to omit the multiplication sign.
 It also doesn't matter in which order the numbers appear:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a*b & =ab=ba=b*a
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same thing if we have an expression where we combine letters and numbers.
 Here is an example where the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 symbolizes an arbitrary number:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x*100 & =x100=100x
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multiplication sign may be omitted when we multiply parentheses:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4*\left(3-2\right)=4\left(3-2\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equality and inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we change something on one side of the equals sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(=\right)$
\end_inset

 we must make corresponding changes on the other side of the equals sign.
 Otherwise the meaning of the equals sign becomes incorrect.
 If we take the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2=3$
\end_inset

 for example,
 then we can subtract 2 from both sides of the equals sign:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
1+2-2 & =3-2\\
1 & =1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or we can multiply both sides by 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2*\left(1+2\right) & =2*\left(3\right)\\
2*3 & =2*3\nonumber \\
6 & =6\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inequality signs
\end_layout

\end_inset

There are also symbols for inequalities,
 so-called inequality signs.
 Here are some examples of inequality signs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
> & \quad\text{Greater than}\\
< & \quad\text{Less than}\\
\geq & \quad\text{Greater than or equal to}\\
\leq & \quad\text{LEss than or equal to}\\
\neq & \quad\text{Not equal to}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us go through some examples:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a & >4\\
b & <5\nonumber \\
c & \geq7\nonumber \\
d & \leq8\nonumber \\
e & \neq6\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first line 
\begin_inset Formula $a>4$
\end_inset

 means that the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 symbolizes a value that can be anything greater than 4.
 The second line 
\begin_inset Formula $b<5$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 symbolizes an arbitrary value that is less than 5.
 The third line 
\begin_inset Formula $c\geq7$
\end_inset

 means that c is an arbitrary value that is equal to or greater than 7.
 The fourth line 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq8$
\end_inset

 means that d is a number that is less than or equal to 8.
 In the fifth line 
\begin_inset Formula $e\neq6$
\end_inset

 the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is a value that is not equal to 6.
 This means that the letter e can symbolize any value as long as it is not 6.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $5.99$
\end_inset

 or 452.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have an expression with an inequality sign and change something on one side,
 we sometimes must also change on the other side for the inequality sign to still apply.
 Alternatively,
 we must change the inequality sign.
 When we multiply or divide by negative numbers,
 this can result in the inequality having to be changed to be correct.
 Example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-4 & >-5\\
-4\times\left(-1\right) & >-5\times\left(-1\right)\nonumber \\
\text{\textbf{Incorrect!} }\,\,4 & >5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first and second lines are correctly executed but the third line is incorrect.
 In this situation when we use multiplication by a negative value (-1) we must reverse the inequality sign:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-4\times\left(-1\right) & >-5\times\left(-1\right)\\
4 & <5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now it's correct.
 There may be multiple inequality signs in the same equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0<a<1
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 symbolizes a value that is greater than 0 but less than 1.
 Both inequalities in the expression must apply simultaneously.
 Since the inequality signs do not include the values 0 and 1,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be very close to 0 or 1,
 but not exactly 0 or 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fractions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Bråk"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
numbers!fraction
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the introduction to this chapter we described how when dividing two numbers a numerator is divided by a denominator and that the result is called a quotient.
 Another word for this is fraction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Fraction}=\text{Quotient}=\frac{\text{Numerator}}{\text{Denominator}}=\text{Numerator/Denominator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fraction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
division
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nominator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
denominator
\end_layout

\end_inset

The words "numerator" and "denominator" refer to the placement above or below the fraction line.
 The fraction line is also called the division sign.
 This can be read as numerator divided by denominator or numerator divided by denominator.
 Fractions are often used to describe a portion of something:
 "three-quarters full." It has no mathematical meaning whether we write the fraction vertically,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

,
 or on one line and separate the numerator and denominator with a slash /,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $3/4$
\end_inset

.
 We can also write division as 
\begin_inset Formula $3\div4$
\end_inset

.
 All three ways of writing mean the same thing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{3}{4} & =3/4=3\div4=0.75
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can read this as three divided by four or three quarters or 0.75.
 If we multiply a fraction by a number,
 only the numerator is multiplied:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2}\times3 & =\frac{1\times3}{2}=\frac{3}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a fraction is multiplied by another fraction,
 we multiply the numerators together and the denominators together:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2}\times3 & =\frac{1}{2}\times\frac{3}{1}=\frac{1\times3}{2\times1}=\frac{3}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same principle applies to fractions with different numerators and denominators.
 Here we have two fractions that are multiplied by each other:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a}{b}\times\frac{c}{d} & =\frac{a\times c}{b\times d}=\frac{ac}{bd}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\,b,\,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 symbolize different arbitrary numbers.
 The letters are only meant to describe that these rules are general,
 regardless of which real numbers the letters represent.
 Another example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{3}*\frac{4}{6} & =\frac{1*4}{3*6}=\frac{4}{18}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If both the numerator and denominator are multiplied by the same number,
 we can cancel this number.
 Here is an example where we cancel the letter b:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a}{b}*\frac{b}{c} & =\frac{ab}{cb}=\frac{a\cancel{b}}{c\cancel{b}}=\frac{a}{c}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or the same thing,
 but with some numbers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{3}\times\frac{3}{2} & =\frac{1\times\cancel{3}}{\cancel{3}\times2}=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1*2*3*4}{1*2*3} & =\frac{24}{6}=4
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to describe this calculation is to cancel factors that appear in both the numerator and denominator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\cancel{1*2*3}*4}{\cancel{1*2*3}}=4
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Fractions can be positive and negative.
 The fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 can be read as minus one half.
 If there is no sign in front of the fraction,
 the number is positive.
 If only one of the numerator and denominator is negative,
 the entire fraction becomes negative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{-1}{3}=-\frac{1}{3}=\frac{1}{-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Or like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\ensuremath{1+2+3+4}}{-1}+1 & =-\frac{10}{1}+1=-9
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If both the numerator and denominator are negative numbers,
 the fraction becomes positive:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{-2}{-3} & =\frac{\cancel{\left(-1\right)}2}{\cancel{\left(-1\right)}3}=\frac{2}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often it can help to convert the numbers so that two fractions get the same denominator,
 that is,
 the same value below the division line.
 We can do this by multiplying or dividing both the numerator and denominator in a fraction by the same number.
 As long as we perform multiplication or division by the same value on the entire numerator and the entire denominator,
 the value of the fraction does not change:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{2}{4} & =\frac{2/2}{4/2}=\frac{1}{2}=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same thing but we multiply both the numerator and denominator by the number 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{2*3}{4*3} & =\frac{6}{12}=\frac{1}{2}=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset

The fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $6/12$
\end_inset

 gives exactly the same result as the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $2/4$
\end_inset

,
 the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 and the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2*3}{4*3}$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to see this is to multiply both the numerator and denominator by an arbitrary number that we can call a:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{2*a}{4*a} & =\frac{2}{4}*\frac{\cancel{a}}{\cancel{a}}=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset

We cancel a from the numerator and denominator since we multiply a by the entire numerator and the entire denominator.
 Fractions can be divided by other fractions.
 This is often useful.
 Here is an example where each new expression gives the same result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{0.5}{0.5} & =\frac{\left(\frac{10}{20}\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}=\frac{2*\frac{1}{2}}{1}=\frac{2/2}{1}=\frac{1}{1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

One more example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1/2}{3/4} & =\frac{4*\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}{3}=\frac{2}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Least common denominator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will add the following two fractions:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
denominator!lowest common
\end_layout

\end_inset

To do this we need to find the least common denominator of the two fractions,
 where the denominator is the value below the division line.
 The least common denominator for two fractions is the lowest value we can use as the denominator in both fractions and still write both fractions as integers.
 To find the least common denominator we convert both fractions so that they get the same denominator.
 We do this by converting the first fraction so that its denominator becomes 6.
 To find the number we need to use for this we first divide the denominator in fraction no.
 2 by the denominator in fraction no.
 1:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{6}{3}=2
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then we multiply only the first fraction by the number 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{3}*2=\frac{2}{6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let us describe this entire calculation based on our original expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2*\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)+\frac{4}{6}=\frac{2}{6}+\frac{4}{6}=\frac{6}{6}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Another method for finding common denominators is to multiply each numerator and denominator by the denominators from all other fractions.
 Example:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}+\frac{1}{5}=\\
= & \frac{1*\left(3*4*5\right)}{2*\left(3*4*5\right)}+\frac{1*\left(2*4*5\right)}{3*\left(2*4*5\right)}+\frac{1*\left(2*3*5\right)}{4*\left(2*3*5\right)}+\frac{1*\left(2*3*4\right)}{5*\left(2*3*4\right)}=\nonumber \\
= & \frac{60+40+30+24}{120}=\nonumber \\
= & \frac{154}{120}=\nonumber \\
= & \frac{77}{60}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us take another example where we mix letters and numbers.
 The letters symbolize arbitrary numbers and it doesn't matter which numbers they are:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \,\frac{a}{2}+\frac{b}{3}+\frac{c}{4}=\\
= & \,\frac{a*3*4}{2*3*4}+\frac{b*2*4}{3*2*4}+\frac{c*2*3}{4*2*3}=\nonumber \\
= & \,\frac{12a+8b+6c}{24}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

As long as we don't know more about what the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 symbolize,
 there is also no way to solve this expression.
 If we separate the numbers so that this becomes separate fractions we easily get back to the original expression or something similar:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{12a+8b+6c}{24} & =\frac{12}{24}a+\frac{8}{24}b+\frac{6}{24}c=\frac{a}{2}+\frac{b}{3}+\frac{c}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset

A type of notation that is good to be familiar with is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a-b}{b} & =\frac{a}{b}-\frac{b}{b}=\frac{a}{b}-1
\end{align}

\end_inset

We simplify the first fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a-b}{b}$
\end_inset

 by dividing it into the two fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}-\frac{b}{b}$
\end_inset

.
 This works when we have terms in the numerator that are separated by plus and minus.
 We can also divide fractions with multiple terms in the numerator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a+b*c-d}{fg} & =\frac{a}{fg}+\frac{b}{fg}*\frac{c}{fg}-\frac{d}{fg}
\end{align}

\end_inset

In this context,
 however,
 it is important to point out a common mistake.
 While we can split the numerators and keep the denominator,
 we generally cannot split the denominator and keep the numerator.
 As an example,
 the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{b}{a-b}$
\end_inset

 generally cannot be split into two separate fractions.
 This probably becomes easier to see if we use numbers instead.
 The left side in the following example is not the same as the right side:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{6}{3-2} & \neq\frac{6}{3}-\frac{6}{2}\\
\frac{6}{1} & \neq2-3\nonumber \\
6 & \neq-1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Above we went through how we can rewrite two fractions so that they get the same denominator by multiplying different fractions by each other's denominators.
 Here is another way to describe this method:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a}{b}*\frac{d}{d}+\frac{c}{d}*\frac{b}{b} & =\frac{ad}{bd}+\frac{cb}{db}=\frac{ad+cb}{bd}\label{eq: dd bb-bråken}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first fraction's numerator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 and denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 are multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 since this is the right fraction's denominator.
 This can be described as multiplying the first fraction by a fraction consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d$
\end_inset

.
 The right fraction is instead multiplied by the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $b/b$
\end_inset

,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the left fraction's denominator.
 The same method can also be used if we have more than two fractions with different denominators.
 Here is an example with three fractions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \,\frac{a}{b}+\frac{c}{d}+\frac{e}{f}=\\
= & \,\frac{a}{b}\left(\frac{d}{d}*\frac{f}{f}\right)+\frac{c}{d}\left(\frac{b}{b}*\frac{f}{f}\right)+\frac{e}{f}\left(\frac{b}{b}*\frac{d}{d}\right)=\nonumber \\
= & \,\left(\frac{adf}{bdf}\right)+\left(\frac{cbf}{dbf}\right)+\left(\frac{ebd}{fbd}\right)=\nonumber \\
= & \,\frac{adf+cbf+ebd}{bdf}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In row two,
 each fraction's numerator and denominator are multiplied by the numerators from the other two fractions.
 This results in the three fractions getting one and the same denominator and can thereby be written as one large fraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Powers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Potenser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
