pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
powers
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the introduction to this chapter we defined power expressions (exponential expressions) as 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Power}=\text{Base}^{\text{Exponent}}$
\end_inset

.
 Powers mean,
 among other things,
 that we can express large numbers in compressed form,
 for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5^{3} & =5*5*5=125\\
5^{9} & =9,765,625\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 with exponent 2,
 this is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 squared
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We can think of it as a figure with two dimensions:
 height and width,
 where all sides of the figure are equally long,
 that is,
 a square where all four sides have length b.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a square where height and width are equal to 1.
 We can write this as 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}=1\times1=1$
\end_inset

.
 This can be read as the square where both width and height are equal to 1 has an area that is 1 area unit.
 Which unit of measurement is used doesn't matter.
 It can be centimeters or miles.
 If the square's sides are 1 cm long,
 the area is 1 square centimeter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a square where width multiplied by height becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2=2^{2}=4$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{2}=$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 square.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tre-kvadrater"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this with three squares.
 The smallest square has height and width = a with area 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}=a\times a$
\end_inset

.
 The middle square has height = width = 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and area = 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The largest square has height = width = 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and area = 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{2}$
\end_inset

.
