\begin_layout Standard
A square whose area is calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be described as being 4 area units.
 Exactly what the word area units represents depends on which unit the square's length and width are given in.
 A square whose width and height are 2 centimeters has an area of 4 square centimeters.
 If the exponent is instead 3,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 it is called cubed.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{3}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a cube with three dimensions:
 width,
 height and length.
 If this cube's width,
 height and length are 2 centimeters,
 the cube's volume is 8 cubic centimeters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Illustrating mathematics in pictures is often helpful.
 But illustrations also have their limitations.
 For example,
 no advanced method is required to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 But there is no simple way in which a four-dimensional figure can be illustrated.
 Even parentheses can have powers and then the same calculation rules for parentheses apply as otherwise.
 For example,
 if we multiply two parentheses with a negative number,
 the result becomes a positive number:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(-2\right)^{3} & =\left(-2\right)*\left(-2\right)*\left(-2\right)=\left(4\right)*\left(-2\right)=-8
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If two power expressions are multiplied with each other and they have the same base,
 the exponents can be added.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2^{2}*2^{3} & =2^{2+3}=2^{5}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This can also be seen by writing out all numbers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2^{2}*2^{3} & =\left(2*2\right)*\left(2*2*2\right)=2*2*2*2*2=2^{5}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression with the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary real numbers:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\left(a+b\right)=a^{2}+ab
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First the number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 outside the parentheses is multiplied with the first letter inside the parentheses,
 which is also an a.
 We then get 
\begin_inset Formula $a*a=a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then a outside the parentheses is multiplied with the second letter in the parentheses,
 which is b.
 We then get 
\begin_inset Formula $a*b=ab$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show the same thing but with numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\left(2+3\right) & =2^{2}+2*3=4+6=10
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When dividing powers with the same base,
 the exponents can be subtracted:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{3^{4}}{3^{2}} & =3^{4-2}=3^{2}=9
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to write the same thing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{3^{4}}{3^{2}} & =\frac{3*3*\cancel{3*3}}{\cancel{3*3}}=\frac{3*3}{1}=3^{2}=9
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also means that when a power stands as denominator in a fraction,
 the power can be written as numerator with the opposite sign in front of the exponent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
3^{-2} & =\frac{1}{3^{2}}=\frac{1}{9}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Or for example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4^{5}=\frac{1}{4^{-5}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here is another example where we move the denominator to the nominator,
 and vice versa:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{2^{-3}}{3^{-5}} & =2^{-3}*3^{5}=\frac{3^{5}}{2^{3}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A power consists of base and exponent.
 The entire power expression can in turn have an additional exponent.
 In that case the two exponents can be multiplied:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(4^{2}\right)^{3} & =4^{2}*4^{2}*4^{2}=4^{2*3}=4^{6}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Powers do not need to be whole numbers.
 A form of powers that is often used is numbers between 0 and 1.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $9^{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 the number 9 raised to one half.
 Another common way to write the same thing is the following:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
9^{\frac{1}{2}}=\sqrt[2]{9}=\sqrt{9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
square root
\end_layout

\end_inset

This expression is called the square root of 9,
 or taking the root of the number 9.
 The square root of a number a is the number that multiplied by itself becomes the number a.
 If we take the square root of 9 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $9^{1/2}=\pm3$
\end_inset

 since both 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{2}=9$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-3\right)^{2}=9$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we call the number that multiplied by itself becomes a the letter b.
 The calculation rule for square root can then be summarized:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a^{\frac{1}{2}} & =\pm b\\
\text{where }\left(\pm b\right)^{2} & =a\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

square root
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from the fact that it is precisely the number 2 we use.
 If we are only interested in the positive b-value,
 this is called seeking the positive square root.
 Often when we are to calculate the square root of a number,
 it is precisely the positive square root we seek.
 The square root is so commonly occurring that this is often described only with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{}$
\end_inset

,
 without the number 2.
 If the exponent is one third,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt[3]{}$
\end_inset

,
 this is called the cube root.
 The cube root of the number c is the number that multiplied by itself 3 times becomes c:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c^{\frac{1}{3}} & =\sqrt[3]{c}=\pm b\\
\text{where }\left(\pm b\right)^{3} & =c\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cube root of the number 8 is 2 since 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{3}=2*2*2=8$
\end_inset

.
 Any real number can be an exponent:
 positive,
 negative,
 rational and irrational numbers.
 The rules for roots follow from how powers are defined.
 As an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
8^{\frac{1}{3}}*8^{\frac{1}{3}}*8^{\frac{1}{3}} & =8^{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{3}}=8^{1}=8
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to write the same thing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
8^{\frac{1}{3}}*8^{\frac{1}{3}}*8^{\frac{1}{3}} & =2*2*2=2^{3}=8
\end{align}

\end_inset


