\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Räkneregler-för-potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 summarize some useful properties and rules for exponents and powers.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 represent arbitrary real numbers.
 The first rule means that if we multiply two power expressions with the same base,
 the exponents can be added as follows:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
powers!properties
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5*5^{2} & =5^{1}*5^{2}=5^{1+2}=5^{3}=125
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we also use the power rule 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}=a$
\end_inset

 (row 7 in the table),
 which describes how all real numbers can be written as power expressions with exponent 1.
 Row 2 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Räkneregler-för-potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 means that the sign in front of the exponent changes if the power is moved between numerator and denominator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a^{b}\left(\frac{c+d}{e-f}\right) & =\frac{1}{a^{-b}}\frac{\left(c+d\right)}{\left(e-f\right)}=\frac{c+d}{a^{-b}e-a^{-b}f}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation rule on row 8 means that all real numbers raised to the power of 0 equal 1.
 Sometimes we may encounter fractions where the numerator or denominator also consists of a fraction.
 Then it can help to rewrite the values as power expressions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{2}{\frac{1}{2}} & =\frac{2^{1}}{\frac{1^{1}}{2^{1}}}=\frac{2^{1}}{1^{1}*2^{-1}}=\frac{2^{1}*2^{1}}{1}=2*2=4
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note how the exponent for the number 2 changes sign from 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and back to 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{1}$
\end_inset

 as we move the number between numerator and denominator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Parentheses with powers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Multiplikation-med-parentes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Parentheses can also have powers.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(2+3\right)^{2} & =\left(2+3\right)\left(2+3\right)\\
 & =2*2+2*3+3*2+3*3\nonumber \\
 & =4+6+6+9\nonumber \\
 & =25\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(1+2+3\right)^{2} & =6^{2}=6*6=36
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we put a minus sign in front of this parenthesis,
 the result becomes negative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\left(1+2+3\right)^{2} & =-\left(\left(1+2+3\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =-\left(\left(6\right)^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-\left(6^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-\left(36\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-36\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is an example with negative numbers in a parenthesis squared:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(-1-2-3\right)^{2} & =\left(-6\right)^{2}=\left(-6\right)\left(-6\right)=36
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example,
 the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 och 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 represents arbitrary numbers:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(a+b\right)^{2} & =\left(a+b\right)\left(a+b\right)=a^{2}+ab+ba+b^{2}\label{eq:parentes kvadrat}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

 we may simplify this expression a bit to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(a+b\right)^{2} & =a^{2}+ab+ba+b^{2}\label{eq:parentes kvadrat ersultat}\\
 & =a^{2}+ab+ab+b^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{2}+2ab+b^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
notable products
\end_layout

\end_inset

The calculation in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:parentes kvadrat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:parentes kvadrat ersultat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is sometimes called notable products,
 meaning that they are common patterns which may be handy to learn by hand.
 The second notable product shows how a parenthesis with subtraction squared can be calculated:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(a-b\right)^{2} & =\left(a-b\right)\left(a-b\right)\\
 & =a^{2}-ab-ba+b^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{2}-2ab+b^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For multiplication of two parentheses with addition in one and subtraction in the other we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(a+b\right)\left(a-b\right) & =a^{2}-ab+ba-b^{2}=a^{2}-b^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize we have here the following notable products:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Square of the sum:} & \left(a+b\right)^{2}=a^{2}+2ab+b^{2}\label{eq: notable products}\\
\text{Square of the difference:} & \left(a-b\right){}^{2}=a^{2}-2ab+b^{2}\nonumber \\
\text{Difference of two squares:} & \left(a+b\right)\left(a-b\right)=a^{2}+ab-ab-b^{2}=a^{2}-b^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the same rules apply if we replace the letters in the equations with more comprehensive mathematical expressions.
 Suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\left(a+b\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2a$
\end_inset

 and want to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We then get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c^{2} & =\left(a+b\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(a+2a\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{2}+2a\left(2a\right)+\left(2a\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{2}+4a^{2}+4^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =9a^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Factorization and divisibility
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Faktorisering och delbarhet"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
factorization
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
To be able to simplify expressions,
 it is also good to be comfortable with factorization.
 Factorization means that we factor out a common denominator,
 a factor,
 that can be multiplied with the affected terms.
 We start with an example where we factor out the number 5 from the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5x+10=5\left(x+2\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as before,
 the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 here represents an arbitrary number.
 That we use a different letter has no mathematical significance.
 Let us now factorize the expression 25+125.
 In this case,
 we can factor out 25:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
25+125 & =25\left(1+5\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may also use the notable products in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: notable products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Suppose we have the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-25$
\end_inset

.
 This we may rewrite in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2}-25 & =\left(x+5\right)\left(x-5\right)=x^{2}-5x+5x-25=x^{2}-25
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we work with powers,
 it is often useful to think about how one may rewrite the power expression as factors with multiplication.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{3} & =\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{1*1*1}{2*2*2}=\frac{1}{8}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a parenthesis with an exponent and multiple expressions in the parenthesis,
 the entire parenthesis should be multiplied by itself.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{1}{4}+\frac{2}{5}\right)^{2} & =\left(\frac{5+8}{20}\right)^{2}=\left(\frac{13}{20}\right)\left(\frac{13}{20}\right)=\frac{169}{400}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can in turn be compared with if we multiply two different parentheses:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(3+\frac{2}{3}\right)\left(2-3\right) & =\left(\frac{11}{3}\right)\left(-1\right)=-\frac{11}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 where a and b are arbitrary integers,
 not equal to 0.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 results in a new integer that we call 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is yet another integer,
 this is called 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 being divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is in that case called a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 can be described as a factor in 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{5}{4}=1.25$
\end_inset

,
 then 4 is not a divisor of 5 since the result 1.25 is not an integer.
 The decimal value from division is also called a remainder.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{5}{4}=1+\frac{1}{4}=1$
\end_inset

 remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we now have the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}=c$
\end_inset

.
 We can now multiply the left and right sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and divide both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 In this way we swap places between 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Bråk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{a}{b} & =c\label{eq: c delare till a}\\
\frac{a}{c} & =b\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are integers,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: c delare till a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates that both 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following example with numbers.
 The number 2 is a divisor of 6:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{6}{2}=3
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number 3 is an integer,
 which is a requirement for calling 2 a divisor.
 The number 3 is also a divisor of 6 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{6}{3}=2$
\end_inset

.
 Factorization instead means that we break up the number into two or more factors.
 For the number 6,
 the numbers 3 and 2 are factors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\times3=6
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
prime numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
factorization!prime numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

Prime numbers are the positive integers greater than 1 that are only divisible by 1 and themselves.
 The number 6 is not a prime number since this number has the divisors 1,
 2,
 3 and 6.
 The first prime numbers are 2,
 3,
 5,
 7 and 11.
 Prime numbers can,
 among other things,
 be used to find all divisors of a number by writing a number as a factor of prime numbers.
 This is called prime factorization.
 Since prime numbers are only divisible by 1 and themselves,
 there is only one way to prime factorize each integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numbers 2 and 3 are prime numbers and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $2*3=6$
\end_inset

 is a prime factorization of the number 6.
 Prime factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $9=3*3=3^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us prime factorize the number 121.
 One way to do this is to test the first prime numbers.
 This is often a good method since many numbers are divisible by precisely these prime numbers.
 We try to divide 121 by 2,
 3,
 5,
 7 and 11 and get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{121}{11} & =11
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $11^{2}=121$
\end_inset

 and 11 is thus a divisor of 121.
 Based on the unique prime factorization,
 it is now possible to find all possible divisors of the number by combining the prime numbers with each other.
 Let us take the number 24 as an example.
 Prime factorization gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
24 & =2^{3}*3=2*2*2*3
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We get the divisors 
\begin_inset Formula $2*2=4$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $2*2*2=8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2*3=6$
\end_inset

.
 This we can in turn see by taking:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{24}{2} & =12\\
\frac{24}{3} & =8\nonumber \\
\frac{24}{4} & =6\nonumber \\
\frac{24}{6} & =4\nonumber \\
\frac{24}{8} & =3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sum
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Summa"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sum!symbol
\end_layout

\end_inset

The sum of a collection of numbers can be written with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

 which is the Greek letter capital sigma.
 The use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

 is so common that this is called the summation symbol or summation sign.
 Say for example that we have a set consisting of the three numbers 4,
 5 and 6.
 The set (not the sum) with these numbers we call 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and each individual number we call 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 indicates which of the numbers it is:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=4$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=6$
\end_inset

.
 In total we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 amount of numbers where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of the numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be describe like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{n=3}x_{i} & =x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}=4+5+6=15\label{eq: summa ex 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 mean that we should sum from observation number 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 up to observation number 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 indicates the number of observations,
 this means that we should sum all values.
 The summation symbol is thus an abbreviation for addition.
 This can also be combined with other arithmetic operations.
 For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{3}\frac{x_{i}}{2} & =\frac{4}{2}+\frac{5}{2}+\frac{6}{2}=7,5\label{eq: summa med div, ex 2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 and 3 above means that we sum the values 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $i=3$
\end_inset

 for all numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since division by 2 is not affected by the summation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 can be moved to the left of the summation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{3}\frac{x_{i}}{2}=\frac{1}{2}*\sum_{i=1}^{3}x_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 is constant,
 it is the same regardless of which value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 has.
 That these two expressions give the same result as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: summa ex 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: summa med div, ex 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Here is another example where we factor out multiplication by 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{3}3x_{i} & =3*4+3*5+3*6=45\\
3\sum_{i=1}^{3}x_{i} & =3*15=45\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
product!sum
\end_layout

\end_inset

If instead of addition we want to multiply a collection of values and calculate the sum of this product,
 this is called calculating the product sum,
 which is written with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 (the Greek letter capital Pi)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\prod_{i=1}^{n=3}x_{i} & =x_{1}*x_{2}*x_{3}=4*5*6=120
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Median
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Median"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
median
\end_layout

\end_inset

Median is the middle value in a collection of values.
 Mathematically this can be described as having a collection of numbers that we sort from lowest to highest.
 We call the collection of numbers for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Each number is numbered as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the amount of numbers.
 If we have the numbers 4,
 5,
 6 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=4,x_{2}=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=6$
\end_inset

,
 and the amount of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 The median depends on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an even or odd number:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Median }=x_{\frac{n+1}{2}} & \text{, if }n\text{ is an odd number}\label{eq: median}\\
\text{Median }=\frac{x_{\frac{n}{2}}+x_{\frac{n+2}{2}}}{2} & \text{, if }n\text{ is an even number}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This might look more complicated than it is.
 We have the three numbers 4,
 5,
 6 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an odd number,
 we use the upper definition from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: median"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 which gives us:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{\frac{n+1}{2}} & =x_{\frac{3+1}{2}}=x_{2}=5
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the second number in our collection.
 Let us take an example where we seek the median in the following collection of values:
