\begin_layout Standard
The upper row 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the values and the lower row 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are the order numbers.
 We have here 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16$
\end_inset

,
 which is why we use the median's second definition in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: median"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{x_{\frac{n}{2}}+x_{\frac{n+2}{2}}}{2} & =\frac{x_{\frac{16}{2}}+x_{\frac{16+2}{2}}}{2}=\frac{6+7}{2}=6,5
\end{align}

\end_inset

The median is between the eighth and ninth values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{8}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{9}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Mean
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Medelvärde"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mean
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another useful measure for average value is the mean,
 which is defined in the following way:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Mean}=\frac{\text{Total of the numbers we want to calculate the mean for}}{\text{Amount of numbers}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us calculate the mean for the three numbers 4,
 5 and 6.
 The sum of the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4+5+6\right)$
\end_inset

 is divided by the amount of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Mean} & =\frac{4+5+6}{3}=\frac{15}{3}=5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean is often written with a bar over it,
 which is why the mean for all the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The calculation of this mean can then be described:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}}{n}\label{eq: medelvärde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall calculate the mean of the numbers 3,
 5,
 4,
 6 and 7.
 Each value we call 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=3,x_{2}=5,x_{3}=4,x_{4}=6$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}=7$
\end_inset

.
 The entire collection of the five numbers we call 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{X} & =\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{5}x_{i}}{5}=\frac{3+5+4+6+7}{5}=5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=2}^{4}$
\end_inset

 we sum the second,
 third and fourth values in the number series.
 Since we now take the mean of three numbers,
 the denominator in the expression will change from 5 to 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{X} & =\frac{\sum_{i=2}^{4}x_{i}}{3}=\frac{5+4+6}{3}=5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Weighted mean
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Viktat-medelvärde"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mean!weighted
\end_layout

\end_inset

A type of mean that is often useful is what is called weighted mean.
 As the name suggests,
 this is a mean where each value is weighted.
 Suppose we have two school classes,
 A and B,
 with 10 and 20 students in each class respectively.
 On the latest math test,
 the students in the two classes had on average 32 and 42 points respectively.
 If we just take the mean of these two values we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Mean: }\frac{32+42}{2}=37
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this mean takes no account of the fact that one school class is twice as large and therefore does not give a correct picture of the students' average result.
 The weighted mean is calculated by taking the sum of each value multiplied by weight and dividing by the sum of the weights:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Weighted mean: }\bar{X}_{\text{Weighted}}=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}v_{i}}{\sum v_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where n is the number of observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the value for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the weight that belongs to each value.
 Let us use this equation to calculate a weighted mean where we use the number of students in each class as weight.
 We multiply the two test scores by the number of students in the classes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{X}_{\text{viktat}} & =\frac{\sum_{i}^{2}x_{i}v_{i}}{\sum_{i}^{2}v_{i}}=\frac{32*10+42*20}{10+20}\approx38.67
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weighted mean becomes approximately 38.67.
 This gives a more representative picture of the students' test results,
 compared to the unweighted mean.
 The denominator in the equation is the sum of the weights.
 The weights in this case are the number of school students in each class:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{2}v_{i}=10+20$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider another example.
 An unweighted mean of the three values 1,
 2 and 3 is 
\begin_inset Formula $6/3=2$
\end_inset

.
 Now we shall redo this calculation but let value 3 have twice as much weight as values 1 and 2.
 We therefore give value 3 the weight 50% and values 1 and 2 the weight 25% each:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{X}_{\text{weighted}} & =\frac{\sum\text{obs}_{i}\text{weight}_{i}}{\sum\text{weight}_{i}}=\frac{1*0.25+2*0.25+3*0.5}{0.25+0.25+0.5}=2.25
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Percent and per mille
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Procent-och-promille"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
per mille
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
percent
\end_layout

\end_inset

Fractions can be used to calculate a portion of something,
 for example percent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\%\right)$
\end_inset

 or per mille 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\permil\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The word percent means per hundredth and per mille means per thousand.
 Another way to describe per hundredth and per thousandth is as fractions divided by one hundred and one thousand respectively:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{One percent} & =\frac{1}{100}=1\%\\
\text{One per mille} & =\frac{1}{1,000}=1\permil\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have 100,000 apples and shall throw away 13% of these.
 To calculate how many apples we shall throw away we take:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
100,000\times\frac{13}{100} & =\frac{100,000\times13}{100}=\frac{1,300,0\cancel{00}}{1\cancel{00}}=13,000
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes the word percentage rate is used to describe a proportion in percent.
 In this example,
 the percentage rate of apples that we shall throw away is 13%.
 When calculating with percent,
 one sometimes wants to calculate percentage change as well as change in number of percentage points.
 Say for example that you have 500 and receive 25,
 so your total wealth has increased from 500 to 525.
 To calculate how large the increase is calculated in percent,
 we take the increase as a percentage share of the original amount,
 25/500,
 and divide both numerator and denominator by 5,
 so that the numerator becomes 100:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{25}{500}=\frac{25/5}{500/5} & =\frac{5}{100}=0.05=5\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that you receive an additional 25.
 This increase in percent becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{25}{525}\approx0.0476=4.76\%
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 means approximately equal to.
 The number 0.0476 is 4.76 percent.
 To know how many percent your wealth has increased from the original sum 500,
 we divide the total increase 50 by the original sum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{50}{500} & =\frac{50/5}{500/5}=\frac{10}{100}=10\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The International Labour Organization (ILO),
 an agency under the organization United Nations,
 UN,
 estimates that in 2016 on average 40 million people in the world lived under slavery-like conditions.
 The same year,
 the earth's population was 7.426 billion.
 Let us calculate what proportion of the earth's population lived under slavery-like conditions,
 calculated as percent and per mille:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Percent: }\frac{40}{7,426}*100 & =0.00539*100=0.539\%\\
\text{Per mille: }\frac{40}{7,426}*1000 & =0.00539*1,000=5.39\permil\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These figures suggest that approximately half a percent,
 or 5.4 per mille,
 of the earth's population live under slavery-like conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a tax that is 32% on average.
 In fraction form this is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{32}{100}$
\end_inset

 or with decimals 0.32.
 If a person has 20,000 USD that shall be taxed at this percentage rate.
 To calculate 32% of 20,000 USD:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{32}{100}*20,000 & =\frac{32*20,000}{100}=6,400
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the number 20,000 can also be written as a fraction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{32}{100}*\frac{20,000}{1} & =\frac{32*20,000}{100*1}=\frac{640,000}{100}=6,400
\end{align}

\end_inset


