\begin_layout Section
Interest
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Procent potents ränta på ränta"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
interest
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Procent-och-promille"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through percent,
 hundredth,
 and per mille,
 thousandth.
 Now we will calculate how much the interest will be if we deposit money in a bank account with two percent interest per year.
 Since we deposit money in the bank,
 this may be described as lending money to the bank and the interest we receive on our account is the compensation that the bank gives us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two percent can be written with numbers as either 2 % or as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the interest we multiply this value with the amount of money we deposit in the account.
 Suppose we deposit 100 USD.
 The interest then becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $100*0.02=2$
\end_inset

 USD.
 After one year we have 100 USD + the interest that the bank gives us:
 
\begin_inset Formula $100+2=102$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to calculate this is to multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $100*1.02=102$
\end_inset

.
 We multiply our savings with 1 plus the interest rate 2%:
 
\begin_inset Formula $1+0.02=1.02$
\end_inset

.
 This shows how much money we have after the interest is added to our savings amount.
 If we let the money remain in the account for another year,
 we will next year receive interest on the amount 102.
 The result after year 2 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $102*1.02=104.04$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to describe this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
102*1.02 & =\left(100*1.02\right)*1.02\\
 & =100*1.02*1.02\nonumber \\
 & =100*\left(1.02\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =104.04\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that all rows in the equation give exactly the same result.
 On the third row we write together 
\begin_inset Formula $1.02*1.02$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1.02\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is read as 
\begin_inset Formula $1.02$
\end_inset

 raised to the power of two and is a power expression,
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interest on interest
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Ränta-på-ränta"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
interest!on interest
\end_layout

\end_inset

When interest is added to money that has already increased due to interest,
 this is called interest on interest,
 or compound interest or cumulative interest.
 Suppose we deposit 5,000 USD in a savings account where the annual interest is two percent.
 We let the money remain in the account for three years.
 The first year we receive the interest that is generated on our 5,000 USD.
 Our savings amount after the first year then becomes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Savings after year 1} & =5,000*1.02\\
 & =5,000*1+5,000*0.02\nonumber \\
 & =5,000+100\nonumber \\
 & =5,100\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We here multiply the original amount with 1 plus the interest rate 0.02 since we shall calculate the total amount that we will have after the interest is paid out.
 The two following years we receive interest both on our original savings plus interest on the money we have received in interest previous years.
 Let us write it with one equation per year.
 After year 1 we have:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5,000*1+5,000*0.02 & =5,000+100=5,100\label{eq: ränta på ränta}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After year 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5,100*1.02 & =5,100+102=5,202
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After year 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5,202*1.02 & =5,306.04
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These three calculations can also be written in one and the same equation as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
5,000*1.02*1.02*1.02=5,306.04
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as before,
 powers can be used to make this calculation even more compact.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $1.02$
\end_inset

 as the base in a power expression and define the exponent equal to the number of years:
 3.
 Our total amount after three years:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
5,000*1.02^{3}=5,306.04
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we take a loan we instead have to pay interest on interest.
 Say for example that you use a credit card with 
\begin_inset Formula $12\%$
\end_inset

 annual interest.
 A credit card allows you to borrow money from the bank when making purchases and pay interest on the loan.
 The interest is in this case added per month.
 To calculate the monthly interest we take the annual interest,
 
\begin_inset Formula $12\%$
\end_inset

,
 and divide by the number of months in a year,
 12:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Interest per month: }0.12/12 & =0.01=1\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that you use the credit card to shop for 20,000 and wait three months to pay.
 How much will the interest be?
 The interest starts in this example being added to your loan directly when you shop and is calculated at the beginning of each month on the debt that then applies.
 New interest is added to old interest for each month that the loan is not repaid.
 After one month:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
20,000*1.01=20,200
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After two months:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
20,200*1.01=20,402
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After three months:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
20,402*1.01=20,606.02
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us write this using a power expression.
 After three months your loan has grown to the following amount:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
20,000*1.01^{3}=20,606.02
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sum!cumulative
\end_layout

\end_inset

The interest cost for borrowing for three months on the credit card becomes in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $20,606.02–20,000=606.02$
\end_inset

 USD.
 This phenomenon is called interest on interest or cumulative interest.
 The word cumulative refers here to that the interest is added and forms a sum,
 whereupon interest is added to that sum and so on.
 A related concept is cumulative sum,
 which describes a sum that is calculated per value in a series,
 including all values in the series up to that point.
