\begin_layout Standard
Let us also calculate the percentage change of the population size between each year.
 This will show the growth rate per ten-year period (per decade).
 We do this by calculating the difference between the two values for two different time points and dividing by the value for the earlier time point.
 We start with the difference in population size 1960 and 1950:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{180-154}{154} & =\frac{180}{154}-\frac{154}{154}\approx1.169-1=0.169
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results for all years are shown in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: befolkning prc diff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we were to calculate percentage change for the index in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Index pop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we would get the same result.
 We can see this by inserting the definition of index from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:index def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into our equation for percentage change:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Percent change between year }t\text{ and year }t-1=\frac{\text{value}_{t}}{\text{value}_{t-1}}-1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We insert the definition of index for the two values:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\left(\frac{\text{Value}_{t}}{\text{Value}_{\text{base year}}}\right)100}{\left(\frac{\text{Value}_{t-1}}{\text{Value}_{\text{base year}}}\right)100}-1 & =\frac{\text{Value}_{t}*\cancel{\text{Value}_{\text{base year}}^{-1}*100}}{\text{Value}_{t-1}*\cancel{\text{Value}_{\text{base year}}^{-1}*100}}-1\\
 & =\frac{\text{Value}_{t}}{\text{Value}_{t-1}}-1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the same thing as percentage change without indexing.
 
\end_layout

