\begin_layout Standard
One way to compare different time periods is to calculate average GDP growth for five years at a time.
 An average for GDP growth in the years 2010–2014 and an average for the years 2015–2019.
 We denote these two averages as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Delta y_{1}}$
\end_inset

,
 for the period 2010–2014 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Delta y_{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 for the period 2015–2019.
 These are calculated in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{\Delta y_{1}} & =\frac{1.68\%+0.83\%+1.53\%+1.14\%+1.54\%}{5}=1.34\%\\
\bar{\Delta y_{2}} & =\frac{1.95\%+0.93\%+1.60\%+2.40\%+1.83\%}{5}=1.74\%\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mean!moving
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to compare development over time while simultaneously smoothing out short-term variations is to use what is called a moving average.
 With a moving average we calculate an average of the values closest to the current time point.
 This can be done in several ways.
 Our moving average for the GDP change in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 we call 
\begin_inset Formula $gm\left(y_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate a three-year moving average for year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 we summarize the three values year 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

,
 year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and year 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 and divide by 3:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
gm\left(\Delta y_{t}\right)=\frac{y_{t-1}+y_{t}+y_{t+1}}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $gm\left(y_{t+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 we instead take:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
gm\left(\Delta y_{t+1}\right)=\frac{y_{t}+y_{t+1}+y_{t+2}}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

