\begin_layout Standard
Since the beginning of the 1800s,
 the average child mortality in the world has decreased from on average over 400 deaths per 1,000 children (40%),
 down to approximately 20% in 1950 and to approximately 4% in 2016.
 That is,
 a decrease of 16 percentage points:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4-20=-16\,\text{percentage points}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The countries in Africa have during the period seen child mortality decrease from 302 to 62.7 per 1,000 children.
 Calculated in percentage points this becomes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{62.7-300}{1,000} & =\frac{-237.3}{1,000}=-0.2373=-23.73\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Europe the average child mortality decreased from 86.7 to 4.9 per 1,000 children.
 Expressed in percentage points:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{4.9-86.7}{1,000} & =\frac{-81.8}{1,000}=-0.0818=-8.18\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Interest on a loan is often stated in percent.
 If you take a loan of 5,000 with 20% interest,
 the interest is 5,000 * 20/100 = 1,000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Interest on interest,
 or compound interest or cumulative interest,
 describes how the interest for the next period is added to both the principal amount and the interest that has been added.
 Example:
 a savings amount in the first time period increases with the interest that is added to the amount.
 The next time period,
 interest is given on both the savings amount and the first period's interest.
 The same phenomenon applies to loans but in reverse,
 interest is added to the interest as the loan is not repaid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Effective interest rate is the actual total cost of a loan.
 Besides ordinary interest,
 this can also include fees that the lender charges,
 such as for example "setup fee" or "notification fee".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An index can be calculated by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $100*\left(\text{value year }t\right)/\left(\text{value base year}\right)$
\end_inset

 where the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 symbolizes year.
 The base year here gets the value 100 but can have any value whatsoever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To calculate percentage change of a sum a between time point 1 and 2,
 we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{2}-a_{1}\right)/a_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the values that the sum has at two different time points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To calculate real prices and wages,
 we adjust for nominal price changes.
 This is called deflating,
 which can be done with a price index.
 Real price = nominal price * (price index base year / price index).
 A commonly occurring price index is the consumer price index (CPI).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One way to calculate the growth rate for something is to calculate the percentage change per time period.
 A time period can for example be one year.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{t}-x_{t-1}\right)/x_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the phenomenon we are to calculate the change for and the letter t symbolizes time period and 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 the previous time period.
 A moving average is calculated on values from time points simultaneously:
 2010–2012,
 2011–2013 and so on.
\end_layout

