\begin_layout Chapter
Functions and graphs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Funktioner-och-diagram"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter introduces mathematical functions and graphs.
 Functions are central to a large amount of mathematical work and can within social science be used both to discuss both theory and empirical data.
 In later chapters we use mathematical functions in many examples.
 A graph is some kind of illustration of quantitative values,
 which can be used to illustrate both theory and data.
 Sometimes the words diagram,
 plot or figure are used with a similar meaning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Mathematical functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function
\end_layout

\end_inset

A mathematical function takes an input value and connects this to an output value.
 Example of a mathematical function:
 Take each input value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and multiply by 2.
 We call the result 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=2x\label{eq: den första funktionen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!independent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!dependent
\end_layout

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x=52$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=104$
\end_inset

,
 and so on.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are called variables here.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which we see because 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 stands to the left of the equals sign and everything else,
 including variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 stands to the right of the equals sign.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the input value and variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the output value.
 This can also be described as the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 being explained by the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the explanatory,
 or independent,
 variable.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the explained,
 or dependent,
 variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which input values that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can take we may also determine and describe.
 This is called defining for which values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: den första funktionen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 applies.
 It can for example be any real number or all numbers within an interval.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is any number between 1 and 100,
 the minimum value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=2*1=2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
parameter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
constant
\end_layout

\end_inset

and the largest value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2*100=200$
\end_inset

.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: den första funktionen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the number 2 indicates how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 The number 2 represents a constant that is always 2,
 regardless of whether 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x=14$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2*5=10$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=6$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2*6=12$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases from 5 to 6,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 increases by 2.
 In the equation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are called variables as mentioned.
 The number 2 in the equation is called a coefficient or parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function can also be described in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression can be read as 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 where we now call the mathematical function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 doesn't mean anything particular other than that a function exists in some form.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is arbitrarily chosen.
 A mathematical function that we define ourselves we may also name whatever we want.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be both simple and advanced.
 The only thing we can discern from 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is that it uses the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as input value and results in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 where we only know that the function uses the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 As long as we have not said anything more about the functions' form,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be the same function.
 Functions don't have to do anything spectacular.
 A function can for example be:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=h\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

