\begin_layout Section
Function as theory
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Funktion-som-teori"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
causality
\end_layout

\end_inset

Mathematical functions can among other things be used to describe how we think about relationships between different phenomena in reality,
 or to describe theories about causal relationships.
 A causal relationship can for example be formulated:
 Variations in phenomenon A cause variations in phenomenon B.
 Or:
 An increase in X will lead to a decrease in Y.
 These types of formulations do not necessarily mean that one phenomenon explains everything that happens in the other phenomenon.
 Variations in one phenomenon may only explain a small part of the variation in the other phenomenon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a theory that higher income for some reason causes people to live longer.
 One way to describe causal relationships is with arrows:
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\rightarrow Y$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 symbolizes annual income calculated in thousands of USD and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 stands for life expectancy in years.
 The arrow goes from income 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 which symbolizes how we believe the relationship works:
 changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 cause changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 With the help of mathematics one may specify the theory,
 for example in the form of the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a*X\label{eq:y=bx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are just designations.
 If we prefer we may write out the words,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{life expectancy}=a*\text{income}$
\end_inset

,
 but equations often become hard to read if we write out long words.
 The coefficient a is an unknown value,
 which symbolizes how much 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes by 1.
 In this case a is a constant,
 a number that doesn't change even if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes.
 We don't know what value a has,
 only that this number is the same for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This means that regardless of whether 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes from 3 to 5,
 or if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes from 543 to 600,
 a will have the same value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Purely mathematically the coefficient a can be both positive,
 negative or 0.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 it means that Y doesn't change when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes,
 which in that case means that there is no relationship between the variables.
 As equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y=bx"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is formulated we mean that a person with 0 USD in income will have a life expectancy of 0 years:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a*0=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That doesn't sound like a credible theory.
 Let us assume that there is a lower limit,
 so that even if one doesn't earn any money one can manage to get by somehow.
 We call this theoretically expected life expectancy b and add it to our equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=aX+b
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A person with zero income can now,
 according to our theory,
 be expected to live for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 years:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a*0+b=b
\end{equation}

\end_inset

What is a variable and coefficient should always be clear from the context,
 but can sometimes be hard to keep apart.
 There is no rule for which letters one uses for what.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us assume that we have our theory about income and life expectancy formulated as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y=bx"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and that we have arrived at 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0.01$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 for every 1,000 USD a person's annual income increases,
 the person lives 0.01 years longer,
 regardless of at what income or age this occurs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of whether any such relationship exists or not,
 this theoretical model is a clumsy description of reality.
 But with mathematics we can more easily discuss the details.
 There might be parts of the theory that still seem to match reality while other parts need to be rewritten.
 With mathematics it also becomes easier to be more exact in which parts of the theory seem to match better or worse with reality.
\end_layout

