Functions of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 can be drawn in graphs.
 This is useful for many different reasons.
 Often we draw graphs with two axes,
 one for height and one for width.
 Another word for this is dimensions:
 a vertical dimension for the height,
 and a horizontal dimension for the width.
 By tradition the horizontal axis,
 the width,
 is called the x-axis while the vertical axis,
 the height,
 is called the y-axis.
 These names of the axes in the graph have no mathematical meaning however.
 It is just a common way to describe them.
 We may call the axes in the graph whatever we want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A graph with x- and y-axis illustrates combined values of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The values for the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are placed in the graph with regard to the horizontal x-axis while the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are placed with regard to the vertical y-axis.
 Consider the following function as an example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=10x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


