\begin_layout Standard
The functions we work with in this book are defined so that for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that a function uses,
 this 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 will only connect to at most one value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In a two-dimensional graph this means that the line for the function in the graph only coincides with one point on the x-axis and never goes over or under itself,
 since the current 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-value would then be connected to several values on the y-axis.
 This also means that when you see a line in a graph with unique y-values for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 this line can always be drawn with a mathematical function,
 regardless of how the line looks.
 A function that connects a unique value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to several values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is called a multi-valued function but is not described here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equation of a straight line
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Den-räta-linjens"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
linear equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

A particularly important type of equation is the equation of a straight line.
 The most basic form of this equation can be written in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+bx\label{eq:räta linjens funktion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are variables and the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constant coefficients or parameters.
 Every straight line in a graph can be drawn with an equation of this form.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicates how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 indicates the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 which we can check by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 into the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =a+bx=a+b*0=a
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
slope coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

The first coefficient,
 in this case called 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 is also called the y-intercept,
 or just intercept.
 This is since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the y-value where the line intersects the y-axis when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is called the slope coefficient,
 since it indicates the slope of the line (the change in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1).
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Funktion-som-teori"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described a theory about the relationship between income and life expectancy with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=aX$
\end_inset

.
 This is also a form of the equation of a straight line but the coefficient that indicates the y-intercept is in this case equal to 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:räta linjens funktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =a+bx=0+bx=bx
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have one function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=bx$
\end_inset

 and from earlier the function 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=aX$
\end_inset

.
 The two functions can describe exactly the same relationship between the two variables.
 That we use different letters in the two functions has no mathematical significance.
 The important thing when we use letters is that we explain what the letters symbolize.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_straight_line_example1.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:En-rät-linje"

\end_inset

A straight line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:En-rät-linje"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 an example of a line in a graph is shown.
 We don't know yet what equation the line has.
 But since the line is straight we know that it can be represented by an equation with the corresponding form as 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

.
 Now we are going to calculate the values for the two constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 can be calculated from the graph.
 We find coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by comparing where the line intersects the y-axis when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 which is at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5$
\end_inset

.
 We substitute the values 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5$
\end_inset

 into our equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =a+bx\\
5 & =a+b*0\nonumber \\
5 & =a\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to calculate the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Two points to the left of the y-axis we see that the line intersects the x-axis at the point where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-10$
\end_inset

.
 Here follow two methods for calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 the slope of the line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Method 1:

\series default
 The point on the line where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-10$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=5$
\end_inset

.
 We substitute these values into our equation to get b:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =a+bx\\
0 & =5+b(-10)\nonumber \\
10b & =5\nonumber \\
b & =\frac{5}{10}=\frac{1}{2}=0.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Method 2:

\series default
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the line,
 how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 We have noted two points for the line in the graph:
 point 1 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(-10,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and point 2 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{2},y_{2}\right)=\left(0,5\right)$
\end_inset

.
 From these the slope of the line can be calculated by comparing how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 and how much 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 changes between 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
b & =\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}=\frac{5-0}{0-(-10)}=\frac{5}{10}=\frac{1}{2}=0.5\label{eq: lutningskoefficenten def 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Sometimes the equation of a straight line is written with other letters,
 for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}\Gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The important thing is what the letters symbolize and that this is clearly evident.
 In this case the Greek letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 (small and capital gamma) are two different variables,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 (alpha 1 and 2) are the equation's constant coefficients.
 That we add the subscript numbers 1 and 2 to the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 is only a way of writing.
 The subscript numbers indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a different coefficient than 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Just as above,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 indicates the line's y-intercept (the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=0$
\end_inset

) while coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 indicates the line's slope.
\end_layout

