\begin_layout Plain Layout
The equation of a straight line is central to a large amount of analytical work and one of the red threads through most of this book.
 Therefore,
 make sure to take a little extra time to ensure that you are following along this far.
 Feel free to go back and review the text.
 If something feels unclear or strange,
 it can sometimes help to read other descriptions of the same phenomena online or in other books.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many situations we want to solve for a variable from an equation,
 for example variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This means that we rewrite our equation so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 stands on one side of the equality sign and everything else in the equation stands on the other side.
 Here is an example where we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by dividing both sides by 4:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
4x & =5\label{eq: x=1,25}\\
x & =\frac{5}{4}\nonumber \\
x & =1.25\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since we have found a solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 we are done with the task.
 Consider another example where we shall solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3+2x=10
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we change both the left and right side of the equality sign simultaneously.
 We start by subtracting 3 from both sides:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
3+2x & =10\label{eq: 3,210}\\
3+2x-3 & =10-3\nonumber \\
2x & =7\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Then we divide both sides by 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2x & =7\\
\frac{\cancel{2}x}{\cancel{2}} & =\frac{7}{2}\nonumber \\
x & =\frac{7}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

To solve for a variable often means that we create a new equation.
 Let us take the following expression as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a+bx=c
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The letter x is our variable that we shall solve for.
 The letters a,
 b and c now symbolize different constants,
 any real numbers.
 Even though we don't know what numbers the letters represent,
 we can still solve for x.
 The result becomes a new equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a+bx & =c\\
bx & =c-a\nonumber \\
x & =\frac{c-a}{b}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Numbers and different letters can also be combined in the same function.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=h\left(p\right)=3+5a+8p+ab
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where z and p are variables and a and b are coefficients.
 We solve for p:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z & =3+5a+8p+ab\\
 & =3+a\left(5+b\right)+8p\nonumber \\
-8p & =3+a\left(5+b\right)-z\nonumber \\
p & =\frac{-3-a\left(5+b\right)+z}{8}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In the next example we shall solve for x:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x\left(5+58\right) & =3+4\\
x & =\frac{7}{63}\nonumber \\
x & =\frac{1}{9}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have a combination of numbers,
 letters that represents numbers and the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
9x\left(a+b\right) & =a+b\\
x & =\frac{1}{9}\left(\frac{a+b}{a+b}\right)\nonumber \\
x & =\frac{1}{9}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Often we encounter situations when the variable we shall solve for stands on both sides of the equality sign.
 Here is an example with an equation where we shall solve for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We move all parts where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 appears to the left side:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z\left(\frac{25}{80+20}\right) & =4\left(z-2\right)\\
z\frac{25}{100} & =4z-8\\
z\frac{1}{4}-z4 & =-8
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now we have all terms where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 appears on the left side of the equality sign.
 But the equation can be simplified further to solve for an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore move everything else in the equation to the right side:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z\frac{1}{4}-z4 & =-8\\
z\left(\frac{1}{4}-4\right) & =-8\nonumber \\
z & =\frac{-8}{-15/4}\nonumber \\
z & =\frac{32}{15}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here follows another example where we shall now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Initially we now have several terms where the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 appears.
 In the equation,
 besides 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 there are also numbers and the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 What 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 represents is not crucial for this example.
 It can be another variable or only a constant written as a letter.
 To solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we move all terms which does not include any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to the right hand side:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-17x-14y-\frac{60x}{30} & =-5y\\
-17x-\frac{60x}{30} & =-5y+14y\nonumber \\
-17x-2x & =9y\nonumber \\
19x & =-9y\nonumber \\
x & =-\frac{9}{19}y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is an example where we have a larger equation with the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 with several parameters,
 constants.
 Let us simplify this a bit:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
17x+14y-\frac{60x}{30} & =5y\\
17x-2x & =5y-14y\nonumber \\
15x & =-9y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This looks a bit more comfortable.
 But we may also continue to simplify from here,
 for example to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=-\frac{9}{15}y
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =-\frac{9}{15}y\\
-9y & =15x\nonumber \\
9y & =-15x\nonumber \\
y & =-\frac{15}{9}x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is difficult to do much more with this equation unless we get more information about 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Even if we rewrite it,
 we need to know something more to be able to find a unique solution for the variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:När är ekvation linjär"

\end_inset


\end_layout

