\begin_layout Plain Layout
equation!linear
\end_layout

\end_inset

The equation of a straight line,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

,
 can be used to draw a straight line in a graph with two axes,
 one horizontal and one vertical.
 More generally,
 a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined as linear if the following two conditions are fulfilled:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Condition 1: } & f\left(x_{1}+x_{2}\right)=f\left(x_{1}\right)+f\left(x_{2}\right)\text{ for all }x_{1}\text{ and }x_{2}\label{eq: linjär f villkor 1}\\
\text{Condtion 2: } & f\left(ax\right)=af\left(x\right)\text{ for all }a\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two different input values on the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which are used in function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Let us illustrate with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=0.25x$
\end_inset

.
 We try the values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=10$
\end_inset

.
 Condition 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(5+10\right) & =f\left(5\right)+f\left(10\right)\\
0.25*15 & =0.25*5+0.25*10\nonumber \\
3.75 & =3.75\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We try condition 2 with the values 
\begin_inset Formula $a=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(5*3\right) & =5f\left(3\right)\\
0.25*15 & =5*0.25*3\nonumber \\
3.75 & =3.75\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


