\begin_layout Standard
This means that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=0.25x$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Let us now check if the following function is linear:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=3+x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For condition 1 we try 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=10$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(5+10\right) & =f\left(5\right)+f\left(10\right)\\
3+\left(15\right)^{2} & =\left(3+5^{2}\right)+\left(3+10^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
3+225 & \neq28+103\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The function does not fulfill the condition and is therefore not linear.
 Due to the term 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 we also see that the equation is not drawn as a straight line in a graph.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ickelinjärt ex"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrate this,
 where line is curved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A bit of set theory
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Lite-mängdlära"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
numbers!set
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!theory
\end_layout

\end_inset

A collection of numbers is called a set or number set.
 A set can consist of many numbers or a few.
 Here is an example of a number set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 2,6,13\right\} $
\end_inset

 which is called 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and contains the three numbers 2,
 6 and 13.
 In a number set the order of the numbers has no significance,
 unless this is explicitly stated.
 For example the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 2,6,13\right\} $
\end_inset

 can also be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 13,2,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 or as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 6,2,13\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In the introduction to the chapter we described the integers,
 which are usually symbolized by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{Z}=\left\{ ...,-2,-1,0,1,2,...\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

,
 are an example of a number set.
 There are infinitely many integers and all are included in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We also work with the rational numbers,
 which are symbolized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

,
 where all numbers are included that can be expressed as a fraction with two integers where the denominator is not 0.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{13},\,\frac{78}{84},\,\frac{3}{2},\,\frac{140}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!difference
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
numbers!real
\end_layout

\end_inset

We also work with the irrational numbers,
 which are the numbers that cannot be written as a fraction of two integers.
 Here we have for example 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 (the square root of 2),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(\text{the number pi}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (Euler's number,
 approximately 2.718,
 discussed more below).
 The real numbers are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 One way to describe a set that includes all irrational numbers is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\backslash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

,
 where the backslash is called set difference.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\backslash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 can be read as "the real numbers,
 excluding the rational numbers".
 Another useful symbol is 
\begin_inset Formula $\in$
\end_inset

,
 which means "in" or "belongs to",
 such as for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3\in\mathbb{R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the number 3 belongs to the real numbers.
 Above we described the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{Z}\in\mathbb{Q}\in\mathbb{R},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are included in the rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

,
 which are included in the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Since all integers are included in the rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The condition for something to be described as a subset is that every value is included in the larger set.
 And since all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 are included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is also a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Subset can be written with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{Z}\subseteq\mathbb{Q}\subseteq\mathbb{R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
superset
\end_layout

\end_inset

Conversely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a superset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

,
 which is a superset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Superset can be written with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\supseteq$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{R}\supseteq\mathbb{Q}\supseteq\mathbb{Z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!closed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!open
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
numbers!set
\end_layout

\end_inset

A common way to define number sets is with parentheses and brackets:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Both these expressions describe an interval between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 1.
 Parentheses,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\right)$
\end_inset

,
 mean that the number set includes all values between the interval but not the endpoints,
 the values 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 1.
 This is called the number set being open.
 Brackets,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\right]$
\end_inset

,
 mean that the set also includes the endpoint values 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 1,
 which is called the number set being closed.
 Say for example that we have a letter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 which represents a value between 1 and 5.
 This can be written:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\in\left[1,5\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is one of all possible values between 1 and 5.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can symbolize the number 1 or the number 2.43.
 To define an interval where the boundary values 1 and 5 respectively are not included,
 we write instead:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\in\left(1,5\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this case the number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be any of all values between 1 and 5,
 but not exactly 1 or 5.
 Parentheses mean that all values are included in the intervals except the boundary values 1 and 5.
 For example 1.000001 and 4.999999967 and all other decimal values that come infinitely close to 1 and 5 are included,
 but not the integers themselves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have described how the small letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can assume a value between 1 and 5.
 If we instead want to define a set of numbers that contains all values in an interval,
 for example 1 to and including 5,
 we may write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\left\{ x|x\in\left[1,5\right]\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph on

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
set!complement
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 now symbolizes the set of values.
 Each value in set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is represented by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,5\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The complement set to a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set with all values that are not included in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The complement set to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\complement}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A^{\complement}=\left\{ x|x\in\left(-\infty,1\right)\text{ och }x\in\left(5,\infty\right)\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!null
\end_layout

\end_inset

The values in 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\complement}$
\end_inset

 consist of all real numbers from negative infinity up to 1 as well as from 5 up to positive infinity.
 Positive and negative infinity is not real values and therefore not included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 either.
 If a set contains only the number 0 this can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and is called the null set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a set is empty and contains no value at all,
 not even the number 0,
 this is called the empty set,
 which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The empty set is by definition a subset of every other set.
 For example,
 if we have the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(14,17\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the values 14 to 17,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\in\left(14,17\right)$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Suppose we have the two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 respectively and shall create a new set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 that consists of all unique values in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 together.
 This can be written with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

,
 which is called union:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=A\cup B
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

 is not the same thing as addition.
 Say for example that we have the following two sets:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5\right\} , & \quad B=\left\{ 3,4,5,6,7\right\} 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the union of these two sets we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=A\cup B=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6,7\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead want the new set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to contain the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that are not found in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 we can remove these with the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\setminus$
\end_inset

 (set difference),
 which we also mentioned above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=A\setminus B=\left\{ 1,2\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that the new set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 should contain the values from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 that they have in common.
 This we can achieve with the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset

,
 which is called the intersection:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=A\cap B=\left\{ 3,4,5\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!discrete
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!continuous
\end_layout

\end_inset

If all decimal values are included in an interval this is called a continuous interval.
 If we have a continuous interval,
 all decimals between 0 and 1,
 we by definition always have an infinite set of values,
 since the number of decimals can always increase.
 If we instead have a set that only contains the integers 1 to 3 the set is not continuous since the values between the integers are not included in the set.
 Instead this is a discrete set,
 where the word discrete means that the number of values included in the set can be counted.
 Let us now take the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x},\forall x\in(-\infty,0)\cup\left(0,\infty\right)\label{eq: mängdlära y = 1/x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!continuous
\end_layout

\end_inset

The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall$
\end_inset

 means "for all".
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x\in$
\end_inset

 therefore means "for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in".
 The entire expression means that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 except the following values:
 negative infinity,
 0 and positive infinity.
 The reason why 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 then goes to infinity,
 not a real value.
 The reason for this is,
 somewhat simplified,
 the following.
 If we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $x*\left(1/x\right)=\left(x/x\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 But there is no real number that can be multiplied with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/0$
\end_inset

 to get 1,
 since any number multiplied with 0 equals 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function that is defined over a collection of real values and does not have any interruptions or "sudden" changes between two adjacent values is called continuous.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: mängdlära y = 1/x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is continuous over the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 the function is not continuous for intervals that include the value 0.
 Let us now take the following example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1+x, & \forall x\in(-\infty,5)\\
20-x & \forall x\in[5,\infty)
\end{cases}\label{eq:non-cont function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=1+x$
\end_inset

 for all real 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (negative infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 is not a real number) up to just below 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

 up to just below positive infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 the function is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=20-x$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=4.99$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
h\left(x=4.99\right) & =1+4.99=5.99\\
h\left(x=5\right) & =20-5=15\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is not continuous,
 which is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:En-icke-kontinuerlig-funktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The small ring symbolizes that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined infinitely close to 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

.
 At the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

 the function's value is instead the filled point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(5,15\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The slope of the lines differ in the manner described in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:non-cont function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

