\begin_layout Section
Domain for a function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
set!theory
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us again take our theory about the relationship between income and life expectancy that we used in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Funktion-som-teori"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=ax$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is life expectancy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is income and coefficient a indicates how much the life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 changes when the income 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 increases by one unit.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 cannot assume just any values.
 Neither 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can in this example be negative,
 below 0.
 We therefore say that for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is not defined.
 Another way to describe this is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=ax,\:\forall x\geq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
domain
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
codomain
\end_layout

\end_inset

The entire expression can be read as 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\forall x\right)$
\end_inset

 that is equal to or above zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\geq0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The values that a function can result in,
 the values that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can take,
 are called the codomain.
 The input values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 for which our function is defined,
 are called the domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us take another example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x},\:\forall x\ne0\label{eq: mängdlära ex 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This new function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that are not equal to 0.
 Another way to write the same thing is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x},\:x\in\mathbb{R}^{+}\cup\mathbb{R}^{-}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{+}\cup\mathbb{R}^{-}$
\end_inset

 mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\in\right)$
\end_inset

 the number set the positive real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbb{R}^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 as well as (union,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

) the negative real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbb{R}^{-}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 that is the positive and negative real numbers but not 0.
 This can also be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x},\:x\in\mathbb{R}\setminus0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}\setminus0$
\end_inset

 mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\in\right)$
\end_inset

 the number set the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 excluding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\setminus\right)$
\end_inset

 the number zero 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now look at the following function that has the two input variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(x,z\right)=z+3x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is defined for the positive integers,
 the natural numbers excluding zero,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbb{N}\backslash0$
\end_inset

,
 and variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is defined for the positive real numbers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we instead have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=g\left(x,z\right)$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Both input variables are defined over all real numbers,
 which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,z\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponent 2 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 refers to the fact that we have two number lines:
 one number line for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and one for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn creates a two-dimensional field,
 a plane surface.
 The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=g\left(x,z\right)$
\end_inset

 is also defined for all real numbers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 thus has the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the codomain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Combining functions with operations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: komb funktioner med operationer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that two or more functions have overlapping domains (the values a function is defined for) one can use addition,
 subtraction,
 multiplication and division on these.
 Suppose we have the two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 defined over the same interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following applies:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)\\
\left(f-g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)-g\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
\left(f*g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)*g\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
\left(f/g\right)\left(x\right) & =\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us apply this to the following example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x\right) & =3+2x\\
g\left(x\right) & =x^{3}-4\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we add the functions we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)=3+2x+x^{3}-4
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subtraction with functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f-g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)-g\left(x\right)=3+2x-\left(x^{3}-4\right)=-x^{3}+2x+7
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplication of the two functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f*g\right)\left(x\right) & =f\left(x\right)*g\left(x\right)\\
 & =\left(3+2x\right)\left(x^{3}-4\right)\nonumber \\
 & =3x^{3}-12+2x^{4}-8x\nonumber \\
 & =2x^{4}+3x^{3}-8x-12\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Division:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f/g\right)\left(x\right) & =\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}=\frac{3+2x}{x^{3}-4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
function!composite
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
Another way to combine functions is to create a composite function,
 which means that we put one function inside another function.
 Say for example that we have two separate functions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y=g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y=g\left(x\right) & =2x\label{eq: g(x) funktion i funktion}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 as a function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 through function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=f\left(y\right)=y^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the parentheses of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we may now write 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 so that we get 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to write this is 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)=f\circ g\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we get from equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: g(x) funktion i funktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z & =f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)=f\left(2x\right)=\left(2x\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This can be read as 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Or expressed differently,
 the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 which is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This is then calculated as usual,
 so if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(g\left(3\right)\right) & =\left(2*3\right)^{2}=36
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we have the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t\left(x\right) & =\frac{3x}{2}\\
h\left(x\right) & =x+5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now looking for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(h\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that we now call the variable in both functions by the same letter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has no mathematical significance.
 We can still work with the functions as a composite function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t\left(h\left(x\right)\right) & =t\left(x+5\right)=\frac{3\left(x+5\right)}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t\left(h\left(3\right)\right) & =t\left(3+5\right)=\frac{3\left(3+5\right)}{2}=12
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A mathematical function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 takes the input value,
 input,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and connects this to an output value,
 output,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Written this way we do not know what function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 looks like.
 Mathematical functions can among other things be used to describe social science theories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The values that the output value 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can take are called the codomain.
 The values that the input value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can take,
 for which the function is defined,
 are called the domain.
 A function that is defined over all real values over an interval without exceptions or sudden interruptions is called continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Functions can be illustrated in graphs with two axes:
 height and width.
 The height,
 the vertical axis,
 is often called the y-axis.
 The width,
 the horizontal axis,
 is often called the x-axis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The equation of a straight line can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is called the y-intercept and is a constant that indicates the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the slope coefficient and indicates how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

:
 the function's line in the graph has positive slope.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b<0$
\end_inset

:
 negative slope.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

:
 the line is horizontal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A function is linear if the following two conditions are fulfilled:
 (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{1}+x_{2}\right)=f\left(x_{1}\right)+f\left(x_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 for the two different 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

;
 and (2) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(ax\right)=af\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Elasticity = how much one variable changes in percentage terms with respect to percentage change in another variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A collection of numbers is called a set,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $117\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 means that the number 117 belongs to the real numbers.
 The complement set to set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\complement}$
\end_inset

 and includes all values that are not included in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The null set contains only the value 0 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The empty set contains no value and is written 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 For the two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq B$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B=C$
\end_inset

 where all values that are included in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 respectively are included.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\backslash B$
\end_inset

 is the set difference,
 the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that are not found in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=C$
\end_inset

 includes the values that are common to sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A closed interval is written with brackets,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

,
 which includes all values between 0 and 1 including the boundary values 0 and 1.
 An open interval can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which includes all values between 0 and 1 without including the boundary values 0 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given that the two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 have overlapping domains,
 these two functions can be combined with addition:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

;
 subtraction:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f-g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)-g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

;
 multiplication:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f*g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)*g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

;
 division:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f/g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)/g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A composite function consists of a function whose input value is the result of another function.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 uses the result of function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

,
 which has the input variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

