\begin_layout Chapter
Logarithms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Logaritmer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm
\end_layout

\end_inset

This chapter introduces logarithms,
 which among other things can be used to facilitate calculations with powers.
 Logarithms can be used to solve equations with unknown exponents,
 compare percentage changes,
 linearize exponential relationships,
 and analyze exponential growth such as economic development over long periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Base,
 exponent,
 logarithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: grundläggande matematik 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described powers with a base and an exponent:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{power}=\text{base}^{\text{exponent}}$
\end_inset

.
 Logarithms is another way to write power expressions.
 The logarithm of the number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 must be raised to to get the value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a & =b^{x}\label{eq:log-funktion 1a}\\
\text{log}_{b}a & =x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we for example take the logarithm with base 3 of the number 9,
 this is equal to the value that the base 3 must be raised to for us to get 9:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{3}\left(9\right)=2\text{ since }3^{2}=9
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logarithmic calculation is a designation for the computational exercise we do when we search for a specific exponent in a power expression.
 Logarithmic calculation is a form of mathematical function called 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(\right)$
\end_inset

:
 the logarithm function.
 Sometimes logarithms are written with parentheses 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 and sometimes without parentheses 
\begin_inset Formula $\log a$
\end_inset

,
 but the parentheses does not have any specific mathematical function.
 Sometimes one can see the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $^{b}\log a=x$
\end_inset

,
 with the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 written to the left of the word 
\begin_inset Formula $\log$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logarithms is not defined for negative values,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\log-9$
\end_inset

,
 since there is no base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 which can be raised to any exponent and get 
\begin_inset Formula $-9$
\end_inset

,
 or any other negative value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{b}a=x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and want to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{b}a$
\end_inset

 as an exponent to the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 At the same time we us the right-hand side also as an exponent to base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{b}a & =x\label{eq:anti-log}\\
b^{\log_{b}a} & =b^{x}\nonumber \\
a & =b^{x}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is the same example but instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we use base 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{3}9 & =2\\
3^{\log_{3}9} & =3^{2}\nonumber \\
9 & =3^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The common logarithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!common
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!ten
\end_layout

\end_inset

A common base for logarithmic calculation is 10.
 It is so common that when one sees an equation where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 appears but no base is defined,
 it is usually logarithmic calculation with base 10 that is meant,
 which is called the common logarithm.
 Just as above,
 the common logarithm means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}a$
\end_inset

 is equal to the value that 10 must be raised to for us to get the value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is some number.
 Here are some examples of logarithms with base 10:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}10 & =1\;\text{since \ensuremath{10^{1}=10}}\\
\log_{10}100 & =2\;\text{since \ensuremath{10^{2}=100}}\nonumber \\
\log_{10}1,000 & =3\;\text{since \ensuremath{10^{3}=1,000}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The common logarithm means that for the number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 we have:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=10^{\log_{10}\left(a\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logarithmic calculation is useful for several things.
 Say for example that we want to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the following function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
1,000,000 & =100^{x}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this we take the common logarithm of the numbers on both sides:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}\left(1,000,000\right) & =x\log_{10}\left(100\right)\\
6 & =x*2\nonumber \\
x & =3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us go through the equation above step by step.
 In the left side we get the logarithm of 1,000,000 with base 10,
 which is equal to the number that 10 must be raised to for us to get 1,000,000.
 The answer is 6.
 In the right side,
 logarithmic calculation means that one can move down the exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $100^{x}$
\end_inset

 and write this in front of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(100\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Generally it applies for exponents that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a^{b}\right)^{c}=a^{b*c}$
\end_inset

 and we know that the common logarithm of 100 is 2,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}=100$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
100^{3} & =\left(10^{2}\right)^{3}=10^{2*3}=10^{6}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
\end_inset

 we may write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}\left(10^{6}\right) & =\log_{10}\left(10^{2}\right)^{3}=3*\log_{10}\left(10^{2}\right)=3*2=6
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\log100=2$
\end_inset

 we can also write:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
100 & =10^{\log100}=10^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the logarithm function appears in an equation we must remember that it is the result of the function that should be used in the calculation and nothing else.
 Consider the following equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log1,000+42$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate this we take the result of the first term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log1,000=3$
\end_inset

,
 and add 42:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}1,000+42 & =3+42=45
\end{align}

\end_inset

Same thing if we have several logarithmic expressions in the same equation.
 Here is an example with two terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}100+\log_{10}10 & =2+1=3
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of logarithms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Logaritmlagar"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!properties
\end_layout

\end_inset

Logarithms have the following properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Product rule: }} & \log\left(a*b\right)=\log\left(a\right)+\log\left(b\right)\label{eq: logaritmlagar}\\
\text{\textbf{Quotient rule: }} & \log\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)=\log\left(a\right)-\log\left(b\right)\nonumber \\
\text{\textbf{Power rule: }} & \log\left(x^{a}\right)=a\log\left(x\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see what these three rules mean we can take some simple examples.
 Let us start with multiplication,
 the product rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log1,000 & =\log\left(100*10\right)\\
 & =\log100+\log10\nonumber \\
 & =2+1\nonumber \\
 & =3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the difference between the following two expressions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log a & *\log b\neq\log a+\log b\\
\log ab & =\log a+\log b\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see the meaning of this difference we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 with numbers and use the common logarithm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{10}5+\log_{10}2 & =\log_{10}\left(5*2\right)=\log_{10}10=1\\
\log_{10}5*\log_{10}2 & \approx0.699*0.3\approx0.21\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now illustrate the Quotient rule,
 using the following example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log100 & =\log\frac{1,000}{10}=\log1,000-\log10=3-1=2
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we work with logarithms and powers one can use the Power rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log10,000 & =\log100^{2}=2\log100=2*2=4
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Power rule states that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log x^{a}=a\log x$
\end_inset

.
 This can also be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a\log x & =\log\left(x^{a}\right)=\log\left(10^{\log x}\right)^{a}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Natural logarithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Naturliga-logaritmen"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!natural
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Euler's number
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have previously mentioned the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

,
 which is approximately 3.14.
 Another commonly occurring constant is Euler's number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 which is approximately 2.718.
 Just as the number 10,
 the number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (approximately 2.718) is a common base for logarithmic calculation,
 which is called the natural logarithm and is often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln x=\text{the number we need to raise \ensuremath{e} to obtain the value \ensuremath{x}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Another way to write the same thing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =\ln\left(x\right)\\
\text{where }e^{y} & =x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as for other logarithms it applies that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x\right)=\ln\left(1\right)=0$
\end_inset

,
 since all numbers raised to 0 equal 1.
 Above we went through how 
\begin_inset Formula $100=10^{\log_{10}100}=10^{2}=100$
\end_inset

.
 When we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 we instead have the base 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 raised to the natural logarithm of the number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 equals just 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Since the natural logarithm uses the number e as base,
 the following applies:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=e^{\ln\left(a\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anti-log"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through how by using the logarithm on a power expression one can isolate the exponent.
 If we have a power expression where Euler's number e is the base we may do the same with the natural logarithm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
e^{y} & =x\\
\ln e^{y} & =\ln x\nonumber \\
y & =\ln x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
exponential function
\end_layout

\end_inset

The antilogarithm of the natural logarithm has a specific function called the natural exponential function and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =\ln x\\
\exp\left(y\right) & =\exp\left(\ln x\right)\nonumber \\
e^{y} & =e^{\ln x}\nonumber \\
e^{y} & =x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now calculate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e^{\ln8+\ln2}+4
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by summing the exponent in the first term,
 where we use the logarithm law for addition,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln a+\ln b=\ln ab$
\end_inset

:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
e^{\ln8+\ln2}+4 & =e^{\ln16}+4\label{eq: e ln 16}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first term is now 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 raised to the natural logarithm of 16.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(16\right)$
\end_inset

 by definition is the number that 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 must be raised to in order to get 16,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\ln16}=16$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this,
 we now have the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
e^{\ln16}+4 & =16+4=20
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Change of base for logarithms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Basbyte-för-logaritmer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!change base
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have so far worked with logarithmic calculation where the logarithmic terms in the expressions have the same base.
 Sometimes we may however encounter expressions where we have logarithms with different bases in the same expression.
 Then it can be useful to know how we can change the base of a logarithmic expression.
 This also facilitates the understanding of logarithmic calculation generally.
 Suppose we have the expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=a^{\log_{a}x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note how the right side only says that a raised to 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{a}x$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 as base,
 is the same thing as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We now take the natural logarithm on both sides.
 Since we shall describe base change of logarithms we now write the natural logarithm as 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{e}\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We now get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log_{e}x & =\log_{e}\left(a^{\log_{a}x}\right)\label{eq: log ändra bas-ekvationen}\\
\log_{e}x & =\left(\log_{a}x\right)\left(\log_{e}a\right)\nonumber \\
\log_{a}x & =\frac{\log_{e}x}{\log_{e}a}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last line describes the calculation rule for how to change the base from the logarithm with base 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to any other base.
 Here we used the natural logarithm,
 where we wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{e}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln$
\end_inset

.
 But the same principle applies for any other base we would want to change to.
 As an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{a}x=\frac{\log_{e}x}{\log_{e}a}=\frac{\ln x}{\ln a}=\frac{\log_{5}x}{\log_{5}a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first term we have the logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with base 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 In the second and third terms we have the natural logarithm in numerator and denominator.
 In the fourth term we have the logarithm with base 5 in numerator and denominator.
 This calculation rule can also be illustrated with an example.
 We have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
100=10^{\log_{10}100}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall rewrite this expression to a form where we instead use the natural logarithm.
 We may then take the natural logarithm of both sides:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln\left(100\right) & =\ln\left(10^{\log_{10}100}\right)=\left(\log_{10}100\right)\ln\left(10\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

We move the parts with natural logarithm to one side so that we get a new definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}100$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{10}100=\frac{\ln100}{\ln10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}100=2$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}=100$
\end_inset

.
 That the right side with natural logarithm is also equal to 2 we can see by taking:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\ln100}{\ln10} & =\frac{\ln10^{2}}{\ln10}=\frac{2\ln10}{\ln10}=2
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Using natural log to calculate percentage change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!percent
\end_layout

\end_inset

The natural logarithm has several useful properties.
 One of these is that for small changes,
 the difference between the natural logarithm of two values is approximately the same as the percentage difference.
 That is,
 for small 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 the following applies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln(1+a)\approx a
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that if we raise Eulers number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 to the small value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $1+a$
\end_inset

.
 For instance,
 the value 102 is 2 percent higher than 100:
 
\begin_inset Formula $102/100-1=0.02=2\%$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the natural log of 
\begin_inset Formula $102/100=1.02$
\end_inset

 we get approximately 2 percent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln\left(\frac{102}{100}\right) & =\ln(102)-\ln(100)\\
 & \approx4.62497-4.60517\nonumber \\
 & \approx0.0198\nonumber \\
 & \approx2\%\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This may seem like a complicated way to measure percent.
 But this is very useful in a lot of statistical analysis,
 which we will introduce in part III.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that it is only natural logarithms that work as an approximation for small percent change.
 With another log base we get other results.
 For instance,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}\left(105/100\right)\approx0.02$
\end_inset

,
 which is of course wrong.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For small differences the natural logarithm gives an acceptable approximation of percentage differences.
 But when the difference between the values increases,
 this no longer applies.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln\left(\frac{30}{15}\right) & \approx0.69=69\%
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is wrong,
 since a change from 15 to 30 is 100%.
 If we know in advance how much the percentage change is,
 it is possible to create a correct measure by changing the base of the logarithms.
 The details are not included here,
 but explained pedagogically by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "huntington-kleinLinearRescalingAccurately2021"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Say for example that we have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with the values 10,
 15,
 22.5,
 and 33.75.
 For each value x increases by 50% compared to the previous value.
 Value no.
 2 is 15,
 which is 150% of the value before that,
 10.
 Value no.
 3 is 
\begin_inset Formula $22.5/15=150\%$
\end_inset

 compared to the value before that.
 Same thing with the fourth value 33.75,
 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $33.75/22.5=150\%$
\end_inset

 of the previous value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we take natural logarithms of these values,
 the difference between the logarithmic values becomes approximately 0.41.
 Since we know the true percentage change in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we can use the base 
\begin_inset Formula $1+p$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the relative change in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 Our function for logarithmic calculation then becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{1.5}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A unit difference in 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{1.5}x$
\end_inset

 can now be read as p where p is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p & =\text{base}-1=1,5-1=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset

Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Logaritm med bas 1+p"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes calculations and results for this example.
 In the rightmost column we see that the difference between respective values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{1.5}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is 1.
 One unit of this variable can be read as one unit p,
 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5=50\%$
\end_inset

.
 This is what we are looking for,
 since we know that the percentage difference between respective values in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is just 50%.
\end_layout

