\begin_layout Section
Logarithms for linearity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Logaritmering-för-linjäritet"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!linearity
\end_layout

\end_inset

A lot of analysis is based on more or less linear relationships,
 such as if we increase (decrease) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 this will result in an increase (decrease) of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 There is a lot of important associations that are not linear.
 But some of them we may want to recalculate so that they become more linear.
 One such example is exponential growth,
 where something is increasing at an increasing rate.
 If we take logarithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see how logarithmic transformation can create a more linear relationship between different values we look at the four graphs in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: x x^2 lnx lnx^2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The figure shows four different combinations of values for the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x,x^{2},\ln x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln x^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which is also described in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Avrundade-värden-för"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Of the four graphs (a),
 (b),
 (c) and (d),
 it is only in graph (d) we have a linear relationship between the variables.
 In graph (d) the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 are shown on the y-axis and values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln x$
\end_inset

 on the x-axis.
 The line in the graph is straight,
 which means that it by definition must be able to be drawn with a variant of the straight line equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =a+bx\\
\ln\left(x^{2}\right) & =a+b\left(\ln x\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In graph (a) we have plotted combined values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The line grows exponentially and is therefore not linear.
 In graph (b) combined values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 are shown.
 The line is curved and the rate of increase decreases with higher values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which is not a linear relationship.
 Graph (c) shows combined values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which also does not result in a linear function.
\end_layout

