\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Den-räta-linjens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we defined the slope of the straight line as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b=\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we compare the distance between two points where the first point has coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the second point has coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{2},y_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Now will use this again to calculate the slope of the function that draws the straight line in graph (d) in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: x x^2 lnx lnx^2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let us use the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(2,4\right)$
\end_inset

 and the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{2},y_{2}\right)=\left(3,9\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
b & =\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}\\
 & =\frac{\left(\ln x_{2}^{2}\right)-\left(\ln x_{1}^{2}\right)}{\left(\ln x\right)_{2}-\left(\ln x\right)_{1}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\ln\left(x_{2}^{2}/x_{1}^{2}\right)}{\ln\left(x_{2}/x_{1}\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\ln\left(9/4\right)}{\ln\left(3/2\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result 2 is the same thing as the exponent in the term 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For the logarithm law about powers in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: logaritmlagar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(x^{a}\right)=a\ln x$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we have a function of type 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we take logarithms of both sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln y & =\ln\left(x^{2}\right)\\
\ln y & =2\ln x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a linear function,
 a function of the same form as the straight line equation.
 This might become even easier to see if we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y=z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln x=q$
\end_inset

.
 We then get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=2q
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are now our variables and 2 is a constant.
 This equation can be described as a variant of the straight line equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Taking logarithms to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Logaritmering lös ut x"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Logaritmlagar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the logarithm law for powers and saw that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(a^{b}\right)=b\log\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes we want to use this to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in an equation.
 Consider the following example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3^{x}=21
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We take logarithms of both sides:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
3^{x} & =21\\
\log\left(3^{x}\right) & =\log\left(21\right)\nonumber \\
x\log3 & =\log21\nonumber \\
x & =\frac{\log21}{\log3}\approx2.77\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us go through this calculation step by step.
 We start by taking logarithms of both sides of the equation,
 which allows us to move down x from exponent to multiplier for 
\begin_inset Formula $\log3$
\end_inset

.
 The result becomes the same thing regardless of which base we use when we take logarithms,
 as long as we use the same base on both sides of the equals sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
utility function
\end_layout

\end_inset

Suppose now that we wish to know what makes people happy and satisfied.
 Within social science the concept utility function is often used in these contexts.
 The concept "utility" is used here to describe preferences and what a person finds useful depends on their preferences.
 Say now that we have a theory that a person's utility is a result of two things:
 work and leisure.
 On a somewhat abstract level utility = percent of the year that we feel happy,
 work = working hours per year while leisure = all time that is not used for work.
 We describe our theory with the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N=A^{z}F^{1-z}\label{eq: nyttofunkt CobbD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 stands for utility,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 for work and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 for leisure.
 The exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a constant that describes what significance the two explanatory variables have for the person's utility.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are included in the equation based on our general theory of how the world works,
 the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 can be calculated based on information about 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 (more about this later).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Within economics this form is often called Cobb-Douglas,
 after two economists who were early in using this type of function to describe production of goods and services 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cobbTheoryProduction1928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We feel satisfied with the theory itself but we want to rewrite the equation to a linear function.
 This can be done with logarithmic transformation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln N=\ln\left(A^{z}F^{1-z}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The next step is to use the Product law for logarithms (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: logaritmlagar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln N & =\ln\left(A^{z}\right)+\ln\left(F^{1-z}\right)=z\ln A+\left(1-z\right)\ln F
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us substitute some symbols to make it even clearer:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n=\beta_{1}a+\beta_{2}f
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where small letters 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 symbolize logarithmic versions of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 symbolize our slope coefficients,
 which were previously 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Why would we want to rewrite our equation?
 Partly it becomes easier to illustrate the relationship between the variables,
 partly the linear equation is easier to work with if we shall compare our theory against reality,
 which we return to in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: Variation och samvariation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Log GDP
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: log linjär ex BNP"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
GDP!logarithmized
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm!linearity
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this section we shall again work with gross national product,
 GDP (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Ekonomisk-tillväxt BNP ex 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: inc and ln(inc)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows nominal GDP for the US for every ten years 1800–2000.
 The third column contains the natural logarithm of GDP.
 The natural logarithm is here rounded to one decimal place.
 Year 1800 GDP was 0.486 billions USD and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(0.486\right)\approx-0.7$
\end_inset

,
 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-0.7}\approx-0.486$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the table we see how an equally large relative change in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the same absolute change of the natural logarithm.
 Every time GDP doubles,
 regardless of from which level,
 the change in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(GDP)$
\end_inset

 is approximately 0.7.
 Every time GDP triples,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(GDP\right)$
\end_inset

 increases by approximately 1.1.
 When GDP increases tenfold,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(GDP\right)$
\end_inset

 increases by approximately 2.3.
 
