\begin_layout Standard
If we compare relative differences in income Sweden has a little more than three times as high average income as Brazil,
 which has almost three times as high average income as Congo.
 This is also reflected in the logarithmic values,
 where Sweden's 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}\left(\text{GDP}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 1.7,
 Brazil's 1.1 and Congo's 0.7.
 Logarithmic transformation facilitates relative comparisons since the difference between logarithmic values is the same for corresponding relative differences in absolute values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative differences in income covariate relatively well with life satisfaction.
 Exactly why this is the case is impossible to say,
 especially based on only the information we use here.
 An important part of the explanation might be that an income increase of a fixed sum,
 for example 100 USD,
 usually is not as valuable for a rich person as it is for a poor.
 However,
 a relative income increase,
 such as 10%,
 are useful no matter if you are poor or rich to begin with.
 That is,
 life satisfaction might increase even among very high income earners if their income increase sufficiently much.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right graph has a striking pattern.
 But note that not even this in itself is any proof of a direct causal relationship between happiness and income.
 High income countries are usually very different from poor countries in many aspects,
 and these things also might affect life satisfaction.
 It is therefore not correct to say that we here see a direct causal relation from just income.
 Therefore we cannot draw any conclusions about how much happiness in a population would increase if incomes would increase.
 To understand this,
 just think about the different ways that income could increase in theory,
 while other parts of life could get worse at the same time.
 Part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part: samvariation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 introduce methods to study causal relationships.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Logarithms are another way to write powers.
 In a power expression 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{x}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is called the base and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the exponent.
 Given the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{b}x=$
\end_inset

 the number that 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 must be raised to obtain the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
 if base 
\begin_inset Formula $=b=10$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}100=2$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}=100$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 often uses base 10.
 This is so common that if it only says 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 this usually means that the base is 10.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\log$
\end_inset

 with Euler's number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (approximately 2.718) as base.
 For all bases it applies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log1=0$
\end_inset

 since all numbers,
 all bases,
 raised to 0 become 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The logarithm laws:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(ab\right)=\log a+\log b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Division:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(a/b\right)=\log a-\log b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Powers:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log x^{a}=a\log x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To change base for the logarithm it applies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{b}x=\frac{\log_{a}x}{\log_{a}b}=\frac{\ln x}{\ln b}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are real numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For small differences the difference between the natural logarithm of two values is approximately equal to the percentage difference.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(102/100\right)=\ln102-\ln100\approx0.02$
\end_inset

,
 approximately 2%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Logarithmic transformation can among other things be used to compare relative differences,
 create linear equations and solve expressions with powers.
\end_layout

