\begin_layout Chapter
Polynomial Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Polynomekvationer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial
\end_layout

\end_inset

This chapter introduces polynomials.
 A polynomial is an equation with variables and constants combined with addition,
 subtraction and multiplication and with a positive integer exponent.
 This is useful for a lot of things in analytical work,
 for instance describing different theories about how humans behave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quadratic Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Andragradsekvationer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following expression is an example of a polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{2}+3\label{eq: polynom 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The following expression is not a polynomial because the exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 is negative:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{-2}+3\label{eq:polynom 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
equation!degree
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial!degree number
\end_layout

\end_inset

The degree of the polynomial is given by the largest positive integer exponent in the expression.
 Let us now take the following polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{2}+x+2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
equation!second degree
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial!third degree
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial!second degree
\end_layout

\end_inset

Since the exponent in the term 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 2,
 this is called a second-degree polynomial (quadratic equation).
 If the largest exponent in the expression had been 3,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 this would have been a third-degree polynomial (cubic equation).
 If the largest exponent is 4,
 it is called a fourth-degree equation,
 and so on.
 Examples:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Quadratic polynomial: } & x^{2}-25x+321\\
\text{Cubic polynomial: } & x^{3}+x^{2}-11x+20\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we want to find an equation's zeros:
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values for which the entire equation equals 0.
 This is also called the real solutions to the equation.
 A polynomial's degree determines the number of possible solutions.
 A quadratic equation can have at most two zeros:
 two,
 one or no solution.
 A cubic equation can have at most three solutions:
 three,
 two,
 one or none.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_x2_plots.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: andragradsekvationer"

\end_inset

Examples of quadratic equations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the solutions,
 zeros,
 of an equation we set the equation equal to 0 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes we may also find the solutions using graphs.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: andragradsekvationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 six graphs are shown with one quadratic equation each,
 written as functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The solution for each function is the point where the function's line crosses the x-axis.
 Let us go through graphs (a) to (f) in order.
 
\series bold
Graph (a)
\series default
 illustrates the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 indicates that this is a quadratic equation and it has at most two solutions.
 In this case there is only one x-value that gives the result 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and that is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(0\right) & =0^{2}=0
\end{align}

\end_inset

We write the solution as 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Graph (b)
\series default
 shows the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=x^{2}-9\label{eq: andragradsekvation diagram b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The function's line crosses the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis at two points,
 where the function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 equals 0:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

.
 These are the function's solutions.
 When we have more than one solution we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=3$
\end_inset

.
 We may also see this if we set the function equal to 0 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x\right)=x^{2}-9 & =0\\
x^{2} & =9\nonumber \\
\left(x^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}} & =9^{\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber \\
x^{2*\frac{1}{2}} & =9^{\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber \\
x & =\pm3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In row three we take the square root of both sides,
 that is exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We get the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-3$
\end_inset

 and can also test these by substituting them into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: andragradsekvation diagram b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y= & x^{2}-9\\
x_{1}^{*}=3\Rightarrow y= & 3^{2}-9=0\nonumber \\
x_{2}^{*}=-3\Rightarrow y= & \left(-3\right)^{2}-9=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Graph (c)
\series default
 illustrates the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=4-x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The line crosses the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=2$
\end_inset

.
 We can also solve for the function's zeros:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
4-x^{2} & =0\\
x^{2} & =4\nonumber \\
x^{*} & =\pm2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Graph (d)
\series default
 illustrates the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=x^{2}+9
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
real solution
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the graph the function's line does not cross the x-axis.
 This means that the function lacks a solution that is a real number,
 the function lacks a real solution.
 If we calculate the function's solutions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2}+9 & =0\\
x & =\left(-9\right)^{1/2}\nonumber \\
 & =\pm\sqrt{-9}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
imaginary unit
\end_layout

\end_inset

To calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we must here take the square root of a negative number,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-9}$
\end_inset

,
 which is not defined for any real numbers.
 We can however instead use the imaginary unit,
 which is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The imaginary unit 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has the following properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
i & =\left(-1\right)^{1/2}\\
i^{2} & =-1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =\pm\sqrt{-9}=\pm\sqrt{-1*9}=\pm\sqrt{i^{2}*3^{2}}=\pm3i
\end{align}

\end_inset

The equation's solutions are 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=3i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-3i$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Graph (e)
\series default
 illustrates the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\left(2-x\right)^{2}\label{eq: diagram e (2-x)^2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the graph the line passes through the x-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=2$
\end_inset

.
 For equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: diagram e (2-x)^2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to equal zero,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 must be 2.
 All other values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 result in 
\begin_inset Formula $y>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Graph (f)
\series default
 shows the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =\left(x+3\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 we need 
\begin_inset Formula $x+3=0$
\end_inset

,
 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=-3$
\end_inset

,
 which can also be seen in the graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Factoring Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Faktorisera-andragradsekvationer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
factorization
\end_layout

\end_inset

This section and the two following go through methods for solving polynomials.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Faktorisering och delbarhet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 introduced factorization of integers.
 An equation can also be factorized.
 We illustrate this with the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(x+1\right)\left(x+2\right)=0\label{eq: (x+1)^2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entire expression on the left side must equal 0.
 The two parentheses are multiplied together,
 making each parenthesis a factor.
 For the entire expression to equal 0,
 one or both parentheses must equal 0.
 This gives us the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-2$
\end_inset

.
 If we multiply the parentheses in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: (x+1)^2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 this results in a quadratic polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(x+1\right)\left(x+2\right) & =0\\
x^{2}+3x+2 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

If we have a quadratic polynomial of this type,
 it can facilitate our work if we succeed in factorizing so that we get the two parentheses.
 To be sure that we have found the correct solutions,
 we substitute our x-values into the quadratic polynomial and check:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{2}+3x+2=0\\
x=-1\Rightarrow & \left(1\right)^{2}+3\left(-1\right)+2=0\nonumber \\
x=-2\Rightarrow & \left(-2\right)^{2}+3\left(-2\right)+2=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both values result in the quadratic polynomial becoming 0,
 which confirms that these x-values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-2$
\end_inset

 are solutions to the equation.
 Now we shall find the possible solutions to the following quadratic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{2}+5x=0\label{eq: exempel med 2a grad}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 appears in both terms on the left-hand side.
 We factor out 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and put the rest of the expression in parentheses:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x\left(x+5\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the left-hand side to equal 0,
 we must have either 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x+5=0$
\end_inset

,
 which in that case requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-5$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-5$
\end_inset

,
 which we can test by substitution in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: exempel med 2a grad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{2}+5x=0\\
x_{1}^{*}=0\Rightarrow & \left(0\right)^{2}+5*0=0\nonumber \\
x_{2}^{*}=-5\Rightarrow & \left(-5\right)^{2}+5\left(-5\right)=25-25=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both these 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values result in the equation becoming 0,
 which confirms that these are solutions to our equation.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(x+5\right)=x^{2}+5x$
\end_inset

 is a quadratic equation we seek at most two solutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be difficult to find expressions that can be factorized from an equation.
 Sometimes one must try different approaches.
 Or draw the equation in a graph to find a first solution and then try from there.
 Even if a polynomial at first glance can look complicated,
 we can often make it more manageable with simple means.
 Consider the following quadratic polynomial as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3x^{2}+3x-168=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to find the zeros and start by dividing by 3:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{3x^{2}}{3}+\frac{3x}{3}-\frac{168}{3} & =0\\
x^{2}+x-56 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression is easier to factorize.
 We seek two factors that result in the product 56.
 Since we shall factor out two factors we also use the fact that the second term should become 
\begin_inset Formula $+x$
\end_inset

,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+1\right)x$
\end_inset

.
 We can here try different approaches until we succeed in rewriting the expression:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2}+x-56 & =0\\
\left(x+8\right)\left(x-7\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us two proposed solutions:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-8$
\end_inset

 respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=7$
\end_inset

.
 We test these proposed solutions by substituting the x-values into the quadratic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{2}+x-56=0\\
x=-8\Rightarrow & \left(-8\right)^{2}+\left(-8\right)-56=0\nonumber \\
x=7\Rightarrow & 7^{2}+7-56=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both these 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values result in the equation becoming 0,
 which means that they are solutions,
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=7$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now find the solutions (zeros) of the following polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{2}+2x-8=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We factorize this expression and get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2}+2x-8 & =0\\
\left(x+4\right)\left(x-2\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us the solutions
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=2$
\end_inset

.
 Feel free to test the solutions yourself using substitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rational Roots
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Rationella-rötter"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial!rational roots
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another method for finding an equation's solutions is to search for its rational roots.
 We illustrate this with the following quadratic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2x^{2}+x-3\label{eq: rationella rötter polynom}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
factor
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
The method we will now go through is based on the polynomial having a rational root,
 which in that case is also a solution to the equation.
 If the equation has a root,
 this is found among the numbers we can put together as the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is an integer factor to the equation's constant,
 where the constant in this case refers to the number 3.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is an integer factor to the number that is multiplied with the power with the largest integer exponent.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $2x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the term in the equation with the largest exponent,
 and the number that is multiplied with the power is thus 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
 Potential factors for the number 3 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm3$
\end_inset

,
 where the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 is called the plus-minus sign and indicates that the values 1 respectively 3 can be both positive (plus) and negative (minus).
 Potential candidates for p are 
\begin_inset Formula $-3,-1,1$
\end_inset

 and 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

:
 The number 2 has the potential integer factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm2$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 we get the candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $-2,-1,1$
\end_inset

 and 2.
 We combine the possible integer factors in the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 and thereby get the equation's possible rational roots:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p}{q}=\pm1,\pm\frac{1}{2},\pm3,\pm\frac{3}{2}\label{eq: rationella rötter ec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These roots we test in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rationella rötter polynom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and check if the result becomes 0,
 which in that case indicates that the value is a solution.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x=1\Rightarrow & 2\left(1\right)^{2}+1-3=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\frac{3}{2}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x=-\frac{3}{2}\Rightarrow & 2\left(-\frac{3}{2}\right)^{2}-\frac{3}{2}-3\\
 & =2\left(\frac{9}{4}\right)-\frac{3}{2}-3\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{9-3}{2}-\frac{6}{2}=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two values are our solutions:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-\frac{3}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now take the following quadratic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{2}+4x-5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study its solutions we start by checking the equation's potential rational roots.
 The constant 5 gives that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 and 5,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

.
 Potential rational roots are in this case:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p}{q}=\pm1,\pm5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through substitution we can see that:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{2}+4x-5\\
x=1\Rightarrow & 1^{2}+4*1-5=0\nonumber \\
x=-5\Rightarrow & \left(-5\right)^{2}+4\left(-5\right)-5=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us the solutions
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Quadratic Formula
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Pq-formeln"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the quadratic formula
\end_layout

\end_inset

A third method for solving quadratic equations is the the quadratic formula.
 Suppose we have the following quadratic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ax^{2}+bx+c=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are constants and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The solutions for this equation can be calculated with the the quadratic formula:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{*} & =-\frac{p}{2}\pm\sqrt{\left(\frac{p}{2}\right)^{2}-q}\label{eq:pq-formeln}\\
\text{where }p & =\frac{b}{a},\text{ och }q=\frac{c}{a}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

