\begin_layout Section
Factorizing Polynomials of Higher Degree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Polynomials of higher degree can be more difficult to solve.
 Sometimes we can rewrite equations so that we first succeed in solving a quadratic equation and solve this with one of the methods above,
 like the the quadratic formula.
 Consider the following cubic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{3}+2x^{2}-5x-6
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We seek the zeros of this equation.
 When one should factorize it can be difficult to know how to start and sometimes one has to try different approaches.
 We set the equation equal to 0 and see after some puzzling that we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{3}+2x^{2}-5x-6=0\\
x^{3}+3x^{2}-x^{2}-3x-2x-6=0\nonumber \\
\left(x^{2}-x-2\right)\left(x+3\right)=0\nonumber \\
\left(x+1\right)\left(x-2\right)\left(x+3\right)=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have factorized out the three parentheses in the last row we can more easily find proposals for the equation's zeros:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=-1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=-3$
\end_inset

.
 We test our solutions by substituting these 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values into the third-degree polynomial on the first line:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{3}+2x^{2}-5x-6=0\\
x=-1\Rightarrow & \left(-1\right)^{3}+2\left(-1\right)^{2}+5-6=0\nonumber \\
x=2\Rightarrow & 2^{3}+2*2^{2}-5*2-6=0\nonumber \\
x=-3\Rightarrow & \left(-3\right)^{3}+2\left(-3\right)^{2}-5(-3)-6=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All these three 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values are solutions to the polynomial:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=-1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{*}=-3$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now study if the following cubic equation with variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has any solutions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{3}-2x^{2}-x\label{eq: 3gradspolynom 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set the equation equal to 0 and factor out 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{3}-2x^{2}-x & =0\\
x\left(x^{2}-2x-1\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us our first proposed solution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

,
 which we see since we now have two factors:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 respectively the parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{2}-2x-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 At least one of these factors must be 0.
 The expression in the parenthesis is a quadratic equation that we can solve with for example the the quadratic formula.
 This gives us two new proposed solutions:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=1-2^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{*}=1+2^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Test these solutions yourself by substituting these values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 3gradspolynom 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take the following cubic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2x^{3}+3x^{2}+\frac{1}{4}x=0\label{eq:exempel 3egrad}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since all terms contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we can factor this out:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x\left(2x^{2}+3x+\frac{1}{4}\right)=0\label{eq: 3egradsekv parentes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us our first solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

,
 which we test by putting it into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exempel 3egrad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x=0\Rightarrow & 2*0^{3}+3*0^{2}+\frac{1}{4}*0=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now it remains to find the remaining solutions to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exempel 3egrad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by calculating what is left in the parenthesis in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 3egradsekv parentes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This we did above when we derived the the quadratic formula,
 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pq-härledning 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Divisions of Polynomials of Higher Degree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polynomial division
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another useful method for solving polynomials of higher degree is polynomial division.
 The method is based simply on having a polynomial of higher degree and having found one of the solutions which we use to factorize.
 To find the remaining solutions we can divide the remaining polynomial by our factor and thereby solve for new factors.
 Consider the following fourth-degree polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{4}-2x^{3}-13x^{2}+14x+24\label{eq: polynomdiv ex1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constant 24 indicates that the polynomial's roots should be found among the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1,\pm2,\pm3,\pm4,\pm6,\pm8,\pm12,\pm24$
\end_inset

.
 To proceed we try substituting these numbers in our equation and see if the result becomes 0.
 In that case we have found a root.
 We start by testing 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-2$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-2$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{4}-2x^{3}-13x^{2}+14x+24\\
x=-2\Rightarrow & \left(-2\right)^{4}-2\left(-2\right)^{3}-13\left(-2\right)^{2}+14\left(-2\right)+24\neq0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-2$
\end_inset

 the equation is not equal to 0,
 which is why this is not a solution or root.
 Let us try 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 instead:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x=2\Rightarrow & \left(2\right)^{4}-2\left(2\right)^{3}-13\left(2\right)^{2}+14(2)+24=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=2$
\end_inset

 is a solution to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: polynomdiv ex1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $x-2$
\end_inset

 is a factor in the equation.
 To find the remaining solutions to the polynomial we shall now divide the polynomial by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x-2$
\end_inset

.
 For this we use polynomial division with the help of long division:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
long division
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

