\begin_layout Standard
On the bottom row there is now 0.
 The equation has divided evenly and what now stands on the top row is the expression that we can multiply our denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-2\right)$
\end_inset

 by to get our original fourth-degree polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{4}-2x^{3}-13x^{2}+14x+24 & =\\
=\left(x-2\right)\left(x^{3}-13x-12\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now do the same thing also with the longer factor,
 the third-degree polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{3}-13x-12\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But now we again need to find a new root to divide with.
 The constant 12 indicates the following potential roots:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1,\pm2,\pm3,\pm4,\pm6,\pm8$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm12$
\end_inset

.
 By testing these in our equation we find our second root:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=-1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{3}-13x-12\\
x=-1\Rightarrow & \left(-1\right)^{3}-13\left(-1\right)-12=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore divide the third-degree polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-13x-12$
\end_inset

 by the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x+1$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

