\begin_layout Chapter
Systems of Linear Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Linjära ekvationssystem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
system of equations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!linear
\end_layout

\end_inset

So far we have worked with functions that we solve individually.
 Several linear functions can also be connected and apply simultaneously.
 This is called equations belonging to a system of equations.
 This is a central part of many analytical methods and is widely used in both empirical and theoretical work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A linear system of equations consists of two or more linear equations.
 The word "system" means that all the equations apply simultaneously.
 We begin with a simple example with two equations and two variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =2x+3\\
x & =y-1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!substitution
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we shall investigate if there exists a unique solution for this system.
 A unique solution for the system would mean that there exist unique values for variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that fit in the equations simultaneously.
 A linear system of equations of this type can have either a unique solution,
 infinitely many solutions or no solution,
 see next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we are to investigate a system of equations' solutions,
 a useful method is what is called substitution.
 The idea is based on that we replace,
 substitute,
 parts of one equation with parts from the other.
 For example to use the definition of a variable from one equation and insert this into the other equation.
 We begin by taking the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the lower equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y-1$
\end_inset

.
 This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we insert at the place 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 stands in the upper equation.
 The upper equation now becomes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =2x+3\\
y & =2\left(y-1\right)+3\nonumber \\
y & =2y-2+3\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =-1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now obtained a new definition of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 We mark this solution candidate with an asterisk,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 since we need to verify it satisfies both equations.
 We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 into the lower equation and thereby also obtain a candidate solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =y^{*}-1\\
x^{*} & =\left(-1\right)-1=-2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must always test substituting our solutions into the original system of equations to see that they really are correct.
 We check 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 by substituting this into the first equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =2x^{*}+3\\
y & =2\left(-2\right)+3=-1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since this gives the same result this confirms that we have found the unique solutions for our two variables:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=-2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can assume other values,
 but no other values will result in the two equations being satisfied simultaneously.
 Therefore,
 these other values are not solutions to the system.
 Let us now study the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =1+y\\
x & =2-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations are now formulated as two functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We can also here use substitution and therefore replace 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the upper equation with the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the lower equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2-y & =1+y\\
1 & =2y\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =\frac{1}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =2-y^{*}\\
x^{*} & =2-\frac{1}{2}=\frac{3}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test substituting this solution into the upper equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{*} & =1+y\\
\frac{3}{2} & =1+y\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =\frac{1}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that we have found the solution for both 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Previously we went through how we may illustrate one or more functions with two variables in graphs with two axes.
 Let us look at the first system of equations we went through above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =2x+3\\
x & =y-1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To more easily be able to see how this looks in a graph we can rewrite the lower equation,
 so that we get another expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =2x+3\\
y & =x+1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_2lines.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Två-ekvationer-i"

\end_inset

Two equations in one graph
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have two functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that we can draw in a graph,
 which is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-ekvationer-i"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 One line per function.
 The two lines meet at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(-2,-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These values for x and y are the only possible solution to our system of equations.
 This is also the only point where the two lines meet.
 We know this because we are here working with linear equations.
 Even if we were to extend the lines far beyond the points that are visible in the graph the lines will never bend and meet at any other point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Number of solutions in the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a system of equations with two straight lines (linear functions) we can either have a unique solution,
 no solution or infinitely many solutions.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Möjligt-antal-lösningar linjära sy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows three plot with illustrations of the possibilities for number of solutions.
 Each plot illustrate two lines,
 drawn with one equation each.
 In the left graph the lines meet at one point and this system of equations has 
\series bold
one unique solution
\series default
 (compare figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-ekvationer-i"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 In the middle graph the lines are parallel and the system therefore 
\series bold
lacks a solution
\series default
.
 In the right graph the lines go along the same points and therefore meet an infinite number of times.
 The system of equations for the right graph therefore has an 
\series bold
infinite number of solutions
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_nonlinearsolutions.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Möjligt-antal-lösningar linjära sy"

\end_inset

Possible number of solutions for linear systems of equations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
A linear system of equations lacks a solution
\series default
 if the two straight lines never meet at any point.
 This applies if the slope of the lines is the same,
 which means that the lines are parallel.
 In that case there are no values for x and y that satisfy the system of equations in its entirety.
 If we for example have the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =5x-4\\
10x & =2y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can from the second,
 lower,
 equation solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5x$
\end_inset

.
 If we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first equation with this we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =5x-4\\
5x & =5x-4\nonumber \\
5x-5x & \neq-4\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last line leads to a paradox.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-5x$
\end_inset

 equals 0 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $-4$
\end_inset

.
 The system lacks a solution.
 We have infinitely many solutions if the equations instead can be described with the same slope and the same value for the y-intercept.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =3x\\
13+12x & =4y+6+7
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We rewrite the second equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
13+12x & =4y+6+7\\
12x & =4y+6+7-13\nonumber \\
3x & =y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!solutions
\end_layout

\end_inset

This means that the system of equations can be written:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y & =3x\\
3x & =y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since the two equations is the same the has an infinite number of solutions.
 Another situation that leads to an infinite number of solutions is if we have a linear system of equations with more variables than equations,
 since we then cannot find any unique definitions for the variables in the system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Row Reduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Radreduktion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!row reduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!elimination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian elimination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
row reduction
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another useful method that can be used to find the solution for linear systems of equations is elimination,
 also called row reduction or Gaussian elimination.
 Suppose we have the following system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x=6+2y\\
2x=3-8y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we use row elimination we can both add and subtract an entire row with the values from another row,
 and multiply individual rows with a constant.
 These two operations can also be combined.
 To find the solution to the system we can therefore multiply row 1 by the number 2:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\left(x=6+2y\right)\times2\\
2x=3-8y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We then get the system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
2x=12+4y\\
2x=3-8y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We then take row 2 minus row 1 (we subtract row 1 from row 2):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\left(2x=12+4y\right)\\
\underline{\left(2x=3-8y\right)}\nonumber \\
0=-9-12y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third row,
 below the line,
 shows the difference between row 2 minus row 1.
 From the bottom row we can solve for y and then get the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-9-12y & =0\\
y^{*} & =-\frac{3}{4}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This value we can then substitute for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the original row 1 in the system of equations.
 This gives us the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =6+2y^{*}\\
x^{*} & =6+2\left(-\frac{3}{4}\right)=9/2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us check our solution by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 into row 2 and calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\left(\frac{9}{2}\right) & =3-8y\\
y^{*} & =\frac{1}{8}\left(3-9\right)=-\frac{3}{4}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This seems to be correct.
 The result becomes the same as when we used substitution.
 We can see this if we for example take the definition 
\begin_inset Formula $x=6+2y$
\end_inset

 from row 1 and substitute into row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2x & =3-8y\\
2\left(6+2y\right) & =3-8y\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =-\frac{3}{4}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Taking logarithms in systems of equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even when we have systems of equations we can benefit from being able to add or remove logarithms.
 Here is a linear system of equations with two equations and an equal number of variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Other letters symbolize constants:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y+12 & =3\\
5^{x}+12y & =8
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The upper equation gives us the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=-9$
\end_inset

.
 This we can substitute into the lower equation.
 Thereafter we can rewrite in logarithmic form to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
5^{x}+12y^{*} & =8\\
5^{x}+12*\left(-9\right) & =8\nonumber \\
5^{x} & =8+108\nonumber \\
\ln5^{x} & =\ln116\nonumber \\
x\ln5 & =\ln116\nonumber \\
x^{*} & =\frac{\ln116}{\ln5}\approx2.95\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following example of logarithmic functions in a system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\log x+2\log y & =4\\
\log y-3 & =\log x
\end{cases}\label{eq: linjärt system med log}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore use 
\begin_inset Formula $\log x=\log y-3$
\end_inset

 in the upper equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log x+2\log y & =4\\
\left(\log y-3\right)+2\log y & =4\nonumber \\
3\log y & =7\nonumber \\
y^{3} & =10^{7}\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =10^{\frac{7}{3}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have a definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 which we substitute into the lower equation in the system of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: linjärt system med log"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log y^{*}-3 & =\log x\\
\log\left(10^{\frac{7}{3}}\right)-3 & =\log x\nonumber \\
\frac{7}{3}-3 & =\log x\nonumber \\
-\frac{2}{3} & =\log x\nonumber \\
x & =10^{-\frac{2}{3}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=10^{\frac{7}{3}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=10^{-\frac{2}{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 Verify these solutions by substitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Three or more variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have only gone through systems of equations with two variables but systems of equations can also have several variables.
 Let us look at the following system as an example,
 where we have the three variables
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =5+y\\
y & =13-z\\
z & =x+y
\end{cases}\label{eq: system with 3 ex 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now investigate if the system has one or infinitely many solutions.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 from row 3 we can substitute into row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =13-z\\
y & =13-\left(x+y\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

From this we solve for a new definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =13-x-y\label{eq: x tre linjära ekvationer}\\
x & =13-2y
\end{align}

\end_inset

This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we substitute into row 1 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: system with 3 ex 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which gives the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =5+y\\
\left(13-2y\right) & =5+y\nonumber \\
3y & =8\nonumber \\
y^{*} & =\frac{8}{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we can in turn find solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: x tre linjära ekvationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =13-2y^{*}\\
x^{*} & =13-2*\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)=\frac{23}{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using the solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 in the third equation in the system we get the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z^{*}=\frac{23+8}{3}=\frac{31}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us check this by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}$
\end_inset

 into row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y^{*} & =13-\frac{31}{3}=\frac{8}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That seems to be correct.
 We can also use row elimination,
 but to facilitate understanding in this case we arrange all terms in the same order on all rows.
 We start from the system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =5+y\\
y & =13-z\\
z & =x+y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We rewrite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =5+y\\
0 & =13-z-y\\
x & =z-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We add row 3 to row 2::
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =5+y\\
x & =13-2y\\
x & =z-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We subtract row 1 from row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x & =5+y\\
0 & =8-3y\\
x & =z-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From row two we now get the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=\frac{8}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This we can substitute into row 1,
 whereupon we find the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=\frac{23}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These two solutions we can then substitute into row 3 and then find 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}=\frac{23}{3}+\frac{8}{3}=\frac{31}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Some more examples 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now investigate the solution to the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=1+x\\
x=2-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case we can relatively easily create two definitions for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and set these equal to each other and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by rewriting the second equation in the system so that we get 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2-x$
\end_inset

.
 We set these equal to each other and thereby find the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2-x & =1+x\\
x^{*} & =\frac{1}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We substitute this into the first equation and get the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =1+x^{*}\\
y^{*} & =1+\frac{1}{2}=\frac{3}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Verify these solutions by substitution.
 Consider a similar example but with fractions and test whether we can find a solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=-\frac{3}{4}-\frac{5}{6}x\\
x=-1+y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The lower equation in the system we can rewrite to 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x+1$
\end_inset

.
 We set the two definitions for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 equal to each other and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+1 & =-\frac{3}{4}-\frac{5}{6}x\\
\frac{11}{6}x & =-\frac{7}{4}\\
x^{*} & =-\frac{21}{22}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This gives us the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y^{*} & =-\frac{3}{4}-\frac{5}{6}\left(-\frac{21}{22}\right)=\frac{1}{22}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Try yourself to substitute the solutions into the original system of equations to check that it is correct.
 Here we have a system of equations with the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x=y+2z\\
y=5-x+3z\\
z=1
\end{cases}\label{eq: ekvsys övning 3 var abc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Already from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ekvsys övning 3 var abc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This we can use in row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =2-x+3z^{*}\\
y & =5-x+3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as well as row 3,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

,
 we can substitute into row 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =y+2z\\
x & =\left(5-x+3\right)+2\nonumber \\
x^{*} & =5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Row 3,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=5$
\end_inset

 we can substitute into row 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =5-x+3z\\
y^{*} & =5-5+3=3\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now found the three solutions we are looking for the system:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=5,\,y^{*}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Verify these solutions by substitution.
 Consider the following expression with the same letters,
 but new numbers and equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x=10-0.3z\\
y=x+5\\
z=x-y
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Row 2 and 3 in combination give:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z^{*} & =x-x-5=-5
\end{align}

\end_inset

We substitute
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}$
\end_inset

 into row 1 and get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{*} & =10-0.3*\left(-5\right)=11.5
\end{align}

\end_inset

This we can substitute into row 2:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y^{*} & =11,5+5=16,5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take the following system of equations as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x=23-5y+z\\
x=2+8z
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since this system of equations has more variables (three:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

) than equations (two),
 the system has an infinite number of solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Beyond the third dimension
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Bortom trredje dimensionen"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that an ordinary graph with two axes has two dimensions:
 height and width,
 the vertical and the horizontal axis,
 which are usually called y and x.
 As we went through above there is no limitation for how many variables that can be included in an equation.
 However,
 it becomes considerably more complicated to illustrate relationships between more than two variables.
 We can draw two variables in a graph with two axes.
 If we have three variables we can draw this in a three-dimensional graph as a cube.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also use other tricks to add additional dimensions,
 for example let a variable determine the size of the dots in a graph,
 or illustrate one or more variables with the help of colors.
 But there is still a limitation of how much information that can be illustrated in one and the same graph.
 Already three variables in the same graph often becomes difficult to overview.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does this mean that it is meaningless to use more than three variables simultaneously?
 No.
 Suppose we have a theory that a person's life expectancy depends on their income and that this can be written in the form of the equation for a straight line:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
linear equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+bx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
slope coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are coefficients.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant that indicates the value that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 takes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 the line's y-intercept.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the constant slope coefficient that indicates how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by one unit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we in addition to income also think that life expectancy in various ways depends on an additional five variables:
 (1) the person's gender,
 (2) genetic conditions,
 (3) eating habits,
 (4) alcohol consumption and (5) number of kilometers the person jogs each week.
 These other variables we can in that case describe as additional dimensions in our theoretical model.
 We now have six explanatory variables and can write these into our linear equation as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\;x_{2},\;x_{3},\;x_{4},\;x_{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Each variable gets its own slope coefficient,
 which we call 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\;b_{2},\;b_{3},\;b_{4},\;b_{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Each slope coefficient describes how 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when the respective explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},...,x_{6}\right)$
\end_inset

 changes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+b_{1}x_{1}+b_{2}x_{2}+b_{3}x_{3}+b_{4}x_{4}+b_{5}x_{5}+b_{6}x_{6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We are thus often interested in relationships,
 covariations and correlations that are difficult to illustrate in graphs and pictures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model with several variables have a longer equation compared to what we have worked with earlier.
 But despite this we still describe a relatively "simple" linear relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and the each explanatory variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 To see why this is a rather simple approach,
 we can for example imagine that the different explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},...,x_{6}\right)$
\end_inset

 also might affect each other and also affect each other's slope coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b_{1},...,b_{6}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Parts of the relationship between the variables might only apply under certain conditions,
 and so on.
 It is not difficult to reason about several changes to the theory that would require more complex mathematics to be described.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our everyday life we often consider complex relationships and correlations between different phenomena.
 We can easily understand that our lives are affected by many different types of phenomena that in many cases also affect each other.
 Certain phenomena we additionally have limited or no influence over.
 Despite this we seem to have surprisingly easy to become convinced by simple arguments about complex and significant causal relationships through banal arguments within politics or in advertising,
 how one phenomenon causes another phenomenon.
 It is difficult to be human.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A system of equations consists of several equations that are valid simultaneously.
 Linear systems of equations can have a unique solution,
 infinitely many solutions or lack a solution.
 For a system of equations with two equations a unique solution means that the equations' lines in a graph meet at one point.
 An infinite number of solutions means that the lines have the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

- and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-values at all points.
 If the system lacks a solution the lines never meet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find solutions to a system of equations we can use substitution or row reduction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A graph with two axes is a good way to illustrate how two variables,
 for example
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 relate to each other.
 It is usually difficult to illustrate the relationship between three or more variables.
\end_layout

