\begin_layout Chapter
Theories of life,
 death and dating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we will go through how we can use mathematics to describe social science theories.
 The examples are greatly simplified and intended only as illustration.
 In this part of the work we are only superficially interested in reality.
 Later on,
 in part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part: samvariation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:Sannolikhetslära-för-samhällsvet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we will go through how we can use mathematics to more carefully compare our theories against information about reality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Income and life expectancy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a theory that higher income extends life for people.
 We describe our theory in the following way:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a*X
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the number of years a person lives,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the number of USD the person has in income during their adult life and a is a coefficient that describes in what way 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 affects 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 On an overall level it seems reasonable that people with higher incomes live longer.
 Many people with higher incomes have better opportunity to choose healthy alternatives,
 greater opportunities to rest and so on.
 But our model feels a bit too simple so we could think about whether we can improve it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As our model is written right now the relationship is linear,
 for each USD of higher income life is extended by a.
 But that might not be so credible.
 The large effect of higher income might arise primarily at low incomes,
 for example when going from 0 USD to a small income.
 In that case we now have a theory that income 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a diminishing effect on life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 One way to describe this mathematically is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=X^{b},\,0<b<1
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is between 0 and 1.
 Exactly what value 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 has we are a bit uncertain about.
 We might plan to study it by collecting data on people's life expectancy and incomes,
 but not right now.
 For our theoretical discussion this information is sufficient as it is now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That a single variable,
 income,
 could give a complete explanation to such a complex phenomenon as life expectancy also doesn't seem so credible.
 Let us therefore also add a variable that summarizes all hereditary biological conditions,
 for example risks for certain diseases.
 We call this new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Our theoretical model now becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=X^{b}+G,\,0<b<1
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our theoretical model is still very limited and if we wish we could add more variables.
 There are no mathematical limitations for what we add.
 What should be included in the model simply depends on what we are going to use the mathematics for.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Mathematical adventures in national income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
GDP
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have earlier compared data on GDP.
 Alongside reality we can also describe GDP theoretically,
 for example like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=C+G+I+X-M
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is GDP,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is private households' consumption of goods and services,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is public sector consumption,
 I is investments in machines and factories,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is export of goods and services and M is import.
 This is a common way to describe GDP and you can find real data on these parts online.
 But here we only discuss these things as abstract concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically there is nothing that prevents us from adding more letters.
 Say for example that we want to distinguish investments I into two parts:
 investments in manufacturing industries that create things and investments in service industries that create services.
 We call these two components 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also want to distinguish household consumption with a variable for rich households and a variable for poor households.
 We call these variables 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\text{rich}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\text{poor}}$
\end_inset

.
 We need not define precisely where to draw the line for rich and poor respectively.
 We now get the following definition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=C_{\text{rich}}+C_{\text{poor}}+I_{t}+I_{s}+X-M
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can continue to build on our description if we feel like it.
 We might for example also want to add letters that symbolize natural resources and divide this into more or less environmentally harmful production.
 We might want to have a measure of export and import that occurs in contact with certain types of countries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But now we are mostly adding things because we can.
 What should be included in the equation depends primarily on what the purpose is,
 what we are going to use the mathematics for and what we want to discuss or illustrate.
 We can for example use such an equation to show how different things in the economy affect each other or how important they are for our economic prosperity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A matter of class
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A large amount of social science is interested in how the population can be categorized into social classes,
 which in turn can mean slightly different things.
 For example working class and capitalist class.
 If we are to work analytically with this we need a precise definition and then mathematics can help us.
 Say for example that we make the following division into three classes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The working class in society consists of those individuals whose total income during a year comes more than 50% from wage income,
 earned through employment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The capitalist class in society consists of those individuals whose income during a year comes more than 50% from capital income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Other individuals in society,
 whom we call "others".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We disregard all possible conceivable problems with this division,
 for example ambiguities in the definitions,
 difficulties in collecting data and so on.
 Would this division work in practice for analytical work?
 Again,
 just as in the preceding examples,
 it depends on what we hope to be able to discuss,
 illustrate and examine.
 There are certainly arguments and phenomena where this division can serve a purpose.
 And there are guaranteed questions where this division is far too crude or just meaningless in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another discussion about class with a long tradition is that about differences in lifestyles.
 Say for example that we have a theory about people's relationship to opera performances and that this relationship depends partly on what income the person's household has and partly on the number of years the person spent on university education.
 We formulate this mathematically:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O_{i}=C_{i}^{a}+U_{i}^{b},\:0<a<1,\:1<b\leq2
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{i}$
\end_inset

 is interest in opera for person 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}^{a}$
\end_inset

 is income for person 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's household.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient that describes what significance 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 has for 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
 We here define a condition for this:
 
\begin_inset Formula $0<a<1$
\end_inset

,
 which means that income indeed increases the person's interest in opera but that the effect is diminishing.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{b}$
\end_inset

 is the person's time in university education and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient with the following condition:
 
\begin_inset Formula $1<b\leq2$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is over 1 this means that the longer the person studies,
 the more the interest increases and the rate of increase also increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Supply and demand
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Utbud-och-efterfrågan"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset

Within social science,
 linear equation systems are used among other things to reason about how we think that supply and demand work for a good or service,
 and how this contributes to determining the price for a good or service.
 The word "supply" refers to how much goods or services the sellers in a market want to offer at a given price.
 The word "demand" refers to how large a quantity of goods or services the buyers want to pay for at a given price.
 The word "equilibrium" refers in this case to the system having a solution for our variables.
 Mathematics is only one way to describe how we think reality can work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now give an example of a linear equation system for supply and demand.
 You can yourself think of what good or service this might be thought to describe.
 The simplest is probably to think of a clearly bounded market with a physical good that is sold and demanded by a limited group of producers and consumers,
 perhaps in the style of some competing vegetable vendors at a market square.
 In reality,
 markets can be very difficult to clearly bound.
 Supply and demand can moreover work in several complex ways.
 In this case we have two linear equations for supply and demand,
 which we can write as an equation system:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{cases}
q_{\text{supply}} & =3p\\
q_{\text{demand}} & =20-2p
\end{cases}\label{eq:ekvationssystem}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are our variables.
 The other numbers are coefficients.
 In this case our equation system consists of two definitions of q:
 one equation for supply and one for demand in the market.
 Our coefficients describe how we think theoretically that supply and demand work for a good or service.
 The two equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ekvationssystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describe precisely this,
 how supply and demand of the production quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 relate to the price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_supplydemand.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Utbud-och-efterfrågan linjära"

\end_inset

Supply and demand based on two linear equations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we are looking for is the point where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\text{supply}}=q_{\text{demand}}$
\end_inset

.
 In this situation we think that the market is in equilibrium,
 when supply and demand are equal.
 We can start by drawing up the system in a graph,
 see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Utbud-och-efterfrågan linjära"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the graph the lines meet at a unique point,
 which defines the equilibrium price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and the equilibrium quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the equilibrium price we set 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\text{supply}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\text{demand}}$
\end_inset

 equal to each other and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
q_{\text{supply}} & =q_{\text{demand}}\\
3p & =20-2p\nonumber \\
p^{*} & =20/5=4\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 we can substitute into the equation system and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 for supply and demand in equilibrium:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
q_{\text{supply}}= & 3p=12\\
q_{\text{demand}}= & 20-2p=12\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Both equations give that 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}=12$
\end_inset

,
 whereupon we have the system's unique solution.
 We can check that this is correct with the help of substitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Two types of cookies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear equations can also be used to describe alternatives in a choice situation.
 For example:
 ahead of this year's big cake sale the local scout organization should choose strategy in the big bake.
 One alternative is that the scouts bake real cakes with expensive ingredients.
 The cakes will in that case become exquisite,
 but expensive to make.
 The profit per sold package will be 20 USD.
 We can describe this in the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{profit}_{1}=20*\text{cookies}_{1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Another alternative is to bake the cakes with water and that big sack of old flour they found in the container behind the clubhouse last summer.
 No other ingredients.
 Since these cakes are super cheap to make,
 the profit will now be 50 USD per cake tin.
 The disadvantage is that the organization will incur fines of 1,000 USD for having poisoned some of their customers.
 The expected profit from this alternative can be described in the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{profit}_{2}=50*\text{cookies}_{2}-1,000
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_cookies.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: kakförsäljning"

\end_inset

Profit from two different types of cookies
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How many cake tins must the scouts sell for the expected profit in alternatives 1 and 2 to become equivalent?
 An equivalent profit means that the two equations should have the same value.
 We can thus calculate the number of cake tins by setting the two equations equal to each other.
 This means that we have a linear equation system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\text{profit}_{1} & =20*\text{cookies}_{1}\\
\text{profit}_{2} & =50*\text{cookies}_{2}-1,000
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We now define
\begin_inset Formula $\text{cookies}_{1}=\text{cookies}_{2}=\text{cookies}$
\end_inset

 and calculate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
50*\text{cookies}-1,000 & =20*\text{cookies}\\
30*\text{cookies} & =1,000\nonumber \\
\text{cookies}^{*} & =100/3\approx33.33\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 33.3 sold cake tins the two alternatives are equivalent.
 The profit then becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Alternative 1: }\text{profit} & =20*33.3=667\\
\text{Alterantive 2: }\text{profit} & =50*33.3-1,000=667\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: kakförsäljning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 where the profit for the two alternatives is described with two lines.
 The lines meet at the solution we have calculated:
 33.3 sold cake tins with 667 USD profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Finding the one
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Dejting"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we calculate data about reality we like to use material that is easy to quantify,
 that easily allows itself to be measured.
 One such thing is money,
 which is moreover a unit of measurement that many people understand.
 The disadvantage is that many decisions in reality are more complex.
 As mentioned earlier,
 however,
 mathematics can help us discuss reality even when we are interested in phenomena that can be harder to put numbers on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take an example where we say that the numbers instead measure how fun something is.
 We begin by describing this example with numbers,
 which possibly can be easier to understand.
 After that we will go through how we can work with the same type of theory without numbers,
 which many times is at least as useful and sometimes better.
 The point of this is to illustrate how mathematics can help us reason,
 even if we cannot calculate exact answers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example we use a simplified happiness scale from 0-100 as a pedagogical tool.
 While it is difficult (to say the least) to measure happiness in reality,
 numbers help us understand the mathematical principles.
 What matters is not the exact values,
 but how we can use systems of equations to compare strategies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Erik wants to get married as soon as possible and is considering different strategic alternatives for meeting the right one.
 Erik doesn't intend to jump between strategies and the marriage goal must happen this year.
 It is thus about choosing a strategy and sticking to it.
 Erik estimates their happiness today at 80 on a scale from 0 to 100,
 and hopes to be able to increase their happiness to 100 by meeting a partner.
 Erik doesn't like dating however and each date brings down Erik's happiness a little.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strategy 1:
 Using a free dating app.
 Just installing the app and starting to go through the profiles lowers Erik's happiness by 50 percentage points.
 For each date Erik has to go on,
 Erik's happiness drops by an additional two percentage points.
 Let us describe this in an equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{happiness}=80-2*date_{\text{app}}-50
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strategy 2:
 Erik's best friend has chosen four candidates who are ready for marriage.
 Since the social effort is now a bit higher,
 each date lowers Erik's happiness by 22 percentage points:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{happiness}=80-22*date_{\text{friend's friend}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us a linear equation system with two equations.
 Now we wonder at what number of dates the two strategies can be considered equivalent,
 as well as what level of (un)happiness this would entail.
 Let us denote the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}=date_{\text{app}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=date_{\text{friend's friend}}$
\end_inset

 and calculate how many dates are required for the two strategies to be considered equivalent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\text{happiness} & =80-2d_{1}-50\\
\text{happiness} & =80-22d_{2}
\end{cases}\label{eq: kims dejter}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the number of dates when both strategies give the same expected result we define 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}=d_{2}=d$
\end_inset

 and set the two equations equal to each other:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
80-22d & =80-2d-50\nonumber \\
50 & =20d\nonumber \\
2,5 & =d^{*}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 2.5 dates the two strategies can be considered equivalent.
 We can also see this by trying to substitute the result for 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{*}$
\end_inset

 into our system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Strategy 1: }\text{happiness} & =80-2*2,5-50=25\\
\text{Strategy 2: }\text{happiness} & =80-22*2,5=25\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for the system is 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{*}=2.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{happiness}^{*}=25$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: dejting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the two strategies as straight lines in the graph and the equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(d^{*},\text{happiness}^{*}\right)=\left(2.5,\,25\right)$
\end_inset

 as the point where the two lines meet.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_dejting.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: dejting"

\end_inset

Two different strategies for dating
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Measuring happiness on a scale from 0 to 100 is a bit clumsy.
 But by setting up equations we can more clearly discuss what conditions must be fulfilled for one or the other relationship to hold.
 If we take our example with dating we could write out the equations but use letters instead of numbers for our coefficients.
 For example,
 in the case of Erik's dating the equation system could be written like this instead:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\text{happiness} & =m-ad_{1}-b\\
\text{happiness} & =m-cd_{2}
\end{cases}\label{eq: dejting ex med bokstäver}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter m is current level of happiness,
 the two types of dates are symbolized by 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 (the app) and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset

 (friend's friend),
 a and c are the slope coefficients (the cost) for going on different types of dates and b is the emotional cost of starting the dating app.
 From this we can solve out the following definitions for the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 (number of dates) and happiness:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d^{*} & =\frac{b}{c-a}\\
\text{happiness}^{*} & =\frac{mc-ma-cb}{c-a}=\frac{m\left(c-a\right)-cb}{c-a}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows us to describe how the different variables are connected and what is required for 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{*}$
\end_inset

 to assume a positive value.
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $c>a$
\end_inset

 must hold.
 That is,
 given that happiness decreases when Erik opens the dating app 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b>0\right)$
\end_inset

,
 then the happiness decrease from going on a date with the friend's friend 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(c\right)$
\end_inset

 must be greater than the happiness decrease per date via the app 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us explore an alternative scenario where Erik's happiness increases from going on dates.
 While there's no single correct way to model this experience mathematically,
 a straightforward modification is to change the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 from minus to plus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\text{happiness} & =m+ad_{1}-b\\
\text{happiness} & =m+cd_{2}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Erik's happiness still decreases from opening the app,
 which we see through the fact that the term 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is negative.
 Whether Erik in this situation prefers to date friends' friends or use the dating app depends on what values the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A theory about work
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: nairu teori"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example we will describe the labor market with a linear equation system.
 The theories are simplified to make the mathematical description easier.
 While this example to some degree illustrate how we can think about real labor markets,
 the models (just as in all theoretical examples in this book) make several unrealistic assumptions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our equation system consists of two equations that give a simplified picture of how we can imagine that wages 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(W\right)$
\end_inset

 and prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

 are determined:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\text{Wage-setters: }\frac{W}{P}=\frac{a}{U^{b}}, & b>0\\
\text{Price-setters: }\frac{P}{W}=\frac{c}{U^{d}}, & c\geq0
\end{cases}\label{eq: nairu system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first equation describes how wages W are set with a markup,
 coefficient a,
 over prices 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 So if workers face higher prices they also demand higher wages.
 The second equation describes how prices 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are set with a markup 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 on wages 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 If companies face higher wages they set higher prices.
 Unemployment 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 has a negative effect on both wages and prices,
 and this effect is determined by coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 are constants that summarize the phenomena that affect wages and prices.
 Exactly what this symbolizes we don't worry about here.
 It could for example be taxes,
 legislation or how employees and employers negotiate wages and conditions via their trade unions and employer organizations.
 The first equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(W/P\right)$
\end_inset

 is also called the wage-setting curve,
 which can be described as a supply curve for labor.
 The second equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P/W\right)$
\end_inset

 is also called the price-setting curve and can be described as a demand curve for labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now seek a solution for the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

,
 real wage (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Deflatera-priser-och"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

,
 percent unemployment.
 We begin by rewriting the second equation and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P=U^{d}/c$
\end_inset

.
 We substitute this into the first equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W}{P} & =\frac{a}{U^{b}}\label{eq: Uc = aU}\\
\frac{U^{d}}{c} & =\frac{a}{U^{b}}\nonumber \\
U^{d+b} & =ac\nonumber \\
U^{*} & =\left(ac\right)^{\frac{1}{b+d}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}$
\end_inset

 we can then use to solve out 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(W/P\right)^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}$
\end_inset

 into the first equation in the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nairu system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)^{*} & =\frac{a}{\left(U^{*}\right)^{b}}\\
 & =\frac{a}{\left(ac\right)^{\frac{b}{b+d}}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{a^{1-\frac{b}{b+d}}}{c^{\frac{b}{b+d}}}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{\frac{d+b-b}{b+d}}c^{\frac{-b}{b+d}}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{\frac{d}{b+d}}c^{\frac{-b}{b+d}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or we can start from the left side of the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Uc = aU"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}$
\end_inset

 there:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)^{*} & =\frac{\left(U^{*}\right)^{d}}{c}=\frac{\left(ac\right)^{\frac{d}{b+d}}}{c}=a^{\frac{d}{b+d}}c^{\frac{-b}{b+d}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we have the solution for the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(U^{*},\left(W/P\right)^{*}\right)=\left(\left(ac\right)^{\frac{1}{b+d}},a^{\frac{d}{b+d}}c^{\frac{-b}{b+d}}\right)\label{eq: nairu lösning ickelinjär}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
equilibrium unemployment
\end_layout

\end_inset

The parenthesis in the right side describes the solutions for the respective variable.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}$
\end_inset

 is a definition of what in social sciences is called equilibrium unemployment.
 This is not a linear equation system but with the help of logarithmization we can make it linear.
 We therefore take the logarithm of both sides of the respective equation in the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nairu system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{cases}
\log\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)=\log\left(\frac{a}{U^{b}}\right), & b>0\\
\log\left(\frac{P}{W}\right)=\log\left(\frac{c}{U^{d}}\right), & c\geq0
\end{cases}\label{eq: nairu log form}\\
\begin{cases}
\log W-\log P=\log a-\log U^{b}\\
\log P-\log W=\log c-\log U^{d}
\end{cases}\nonumber \\
\begin{cases}
w-p=\log a-bu\\
p-w=\log c-du
\end{cases}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p=\log\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bu=b\log U$
\end_inset

.
 The letter u is the logarithm of percent unemployment and a,
 b,
 c and d are coefficients that define how our variables are connected.
 Just like above we rewrite the second equation,
 set the two definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p$
\end_inset

 equal to each other and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 To save space we do not write out 
\begin_inset Formula $\log()$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
du-c & =a-bu\\
u\left(b+d\right) & =a+c\nonumber \\
u^{*} & =\frac{a+c}{b+d}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
equation!non-linear
\end_layout

\end_inset

The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the logarithmized version of the solution in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nairu lösning ickelinjär"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 To convert to unemployment in percent we take the exponent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\exp\left(u^{*}\right) & =\frac{1}{b+d}\exp\left(a+c\right)\\
U^{*} & =ac^{\frac{1}{b+d}g}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: nairu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows how this model can be illustrated in a graph.
 The relationship between W/P and U is described with the two functions for supply and demand,
 also called the wage- and price-setting curve.
 If we read the x-axis from left to right the axis measures percent of the workforce that has work,
 employment rate.
 Employment rate can be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $1-U$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is percent unemployed.
 The solution for the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(W/P\right)^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the point where the lines meet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the diagram to the left is shown how the lines look in ordinary form,
 as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nairu system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the diagram to the right are shown the logarithmized functions,
 as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nairu log form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
