system of equations!non-linear
\end_layout

\end_inset

Non-linear equations can also be included in systems together.
 This can help us describe theories and reason about different phenomena.
 Non-linear equation systems can be more difficult to work with compared to linear equation systems.
 But sometimes this type of equations can also be solved in similar ways to linear ones.
 This chapter gives a brief introduction with some examples from social science.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solutions with non-linear systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described above,
 for linear equation systems we can know in advance how many solutions we can expect given certain conditions:
 none,
 one or infinitely many solutions.
 With non-linear equation systems there are no such rules.
 If the lines in a graph are not straight they can meet 0,
 1,
 2,
 3 or however many times up to infinity.
 This can be illustrated by comparing the following equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{cases}
f\left(x\right) & =2x^{3}-x^{2}+7\\
g\left(x\right) & =5x\\
h\left(x\right) & =10+x
\end{cases}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and plot these in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Exempel-på-ickelinjära"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is no 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-value for which all three functions meet,
 so a system with these three functions thus lacks solutions.
 The first function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is the solid line.
 The second function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is the dotted line and the third function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is the dashed line.
 
