\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is non-linear while the other two are linear.
 Since function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 only has one slope coefficient,
 the number 5,
 and no coefficient for y-intercept,
 the line intersects the y-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=0$
\end_inset

.
 At this point,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

,
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 also intersects the y-axis,
 which is also seen in the figure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lines for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 meet at three points.
 A system with only these two functions would therefore have three solutions.
 The lines for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 meet at one point and a system with only these two functions would therefore have a unique solution.
 The lines for 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 meet at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=10/4=2.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
