\begin_layout Plain Layout
substitution
\end_layout

\end_inset

There are several basic methods that we can use to solve non-linear equation systems.
 One of these is substitution.
 Suppose we have a system with the following two equations and the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=x\\
y=\left(x-2\right)^{2}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first equation is linear and the second is non-linear.
 This system we can solve by taking the definition of y from the first equation and substituting into the lower equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =\left(x-2\right)^{2}\\
x & =x^{2}-4x+4\nonumber \\
0 & =x^{2}-5x+4\nonumber \\
0 & =\left(x-4\right)\left(x-1\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation is 0 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=1$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Let us test these solutions by substituting the values into the system.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=4$
\end_inset

 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=4\\
y=\left(4-2\right)^{2}=4
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=1\\
y=\left(1-2\right)^{2}=1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

