\begin_layout Standard
We get the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4,4\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ickelinjärt system 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the two equations and the two points where the equations meet.
 Let us now examine the following equation system:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=f\left(x\right)=\left(2-\frac{1}{x^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
y=g\left(x\right)=x^{2}
\end{cases},\forall x>0\label{eq: ickelinjära system substitutering ex2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have two definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that we can set equal to each other:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(1-\frac{1}{x^{2}}\right)^{1/2} & =x^{2}\label{eq: 4egrads poly för 2 jämvikter}\\
x^{4}+\frac{1}{x^{2}}-2 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to simplify our work now is to define a new variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=x^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{4}+\frac{1}{x^{2}}-2 & =0\\
t^{2}+\frac{1}{t}-2 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression we can rewrite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t^{3}-2t+1=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find candidate solutions to this third-degree polynomial we try 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t=0\Rightarrow & \left(0\right)^{3}-2*0+1\neq0\\
t=1\Rightarrow & 1^{3}-2*1+1=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 is a solution and that 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 is thereby a factor of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{3}-2t+1$
\end_inset

.
 To find more roots we can use polynomial long division (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Polynom-av-högre grad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

