\begin_layout Standard
Since the division worked out evenly,
 we got 0 at the bottom,
 this confirms that 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 is a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{3}-2t+1$
\end_inset

.
 On the top row we get the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}+t-1$
\end_inset

,
 which is a second-degree polynomial that we can solve with the the quadratic formula.
 This gives us two additional solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t & =-\frac{1}{2}\pm\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}}\\
t_{2} & =-0.5-\sqrt{1.25}\nonumber \\
t_{3} & =-0.5+\sqrt{1.25}\approx0.618\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we have three solutions for t that we can use in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 to solve out 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the square root is not defined for negative real numbers we only have use of 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0$
\end_inset

.
 Our first solution was 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=1$
\end_inset

,
 which gives two candidate solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{1,2} & =\pm\sqrt{1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since the equation system is only defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 is a possible solution.
 We test by substitution in the system in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ickelinjära system substitutering ex2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=f\left(1\right)=\left(2-\frac{1}{1}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}=1\\
y=g\left(1\right)=1
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is correct.
 Of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{3}$
\end_inset

 we are only interested in 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{3}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =\pm\sqrt{t_{3}}\\
x & =\pm\sqrt{0.618}\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow x_{2} & =0.786\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We are only interested in the positive square root,
 which gives us a second solution for x.
 We test this by substitution in our equation system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=f\left(0.786\right) & =\left(2-\frac{1}{\left(0.786\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}=0.618\\
y=g\left(0.786\right) & =\left(0.786\right)^{2}=0.618
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


