\begin_layout Section
Row reduction with non-linear equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!elimination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
system of equations!row reduction
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another useful method for solving non-linear equation systems is row reduction,
 or elimination,
 in a similar way as we did for linear equation systems in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Radreduktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The principle is based on that we can add and subtract equations in the same system with each other and thereby eliminate terms so that we get new definitions of the variables.
 To illustrate this method we can check if the following equation system has any solutions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=20-2x^{2}\\
y=x^{2}-10
\end{cases}\label{eq: ickelinjärt ekvations sys 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We subtract row 2 from row 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
0=30-3x^{2}\\
y=x^{2}-10
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From row 1 we can now find the solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2} & =10\\
x^{*} & =\pm10^{\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


