\begin_layout Section
Example 1:
 Two friends
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: ska vi börja röka"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earlier we used linear equation systems to describe some examples of social science discussions.
 Non-linear equations and equation systems also occur abundantly in social science.
 Here follow some simplified examples that have drawn inspiration from more comprehensive academic works and research articles.
 In the first example we have two friends,
 Erik and Maria,
 who do everything together.
 Both are considering whether they should start smoking.
 Erik's relationship to smoking can be described with the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Erik's smoking}=y=x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a variable that describes how much Maria smokes.
 Maria's smoking can in turn be described with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Maria's smoking}=x=y^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have the following equation system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=x^{2} & \forall x\in\left[0,1\right]\\
x=y^{2} & \forall y\in\left[0,1\right]
\end{cases}\label{eq: rökning ekv.sys}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system describes how Erik's smoking is a positive function of Maria's smoking,
 which in turn is a positive function of Erik's smoking.
 Both equations are only defined for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 One way to find the system's solutions is to rewrite equation two to 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 and then use this in the first equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2} & =x^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
x^{2}-x^{\frac{1}{2}} & =0\nonumber \\
x^{\frac{1}{2}}\left(x^{\frac{3}{2}}-1\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can see that the system's solutions are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\frac{1}{2}}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{\frac{3}{2}}-1\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\frac{1}{2}}=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 must be 0,
 which is the first solution:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{\frac{3}{2}}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 we get a second solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{\frac{3}{2}}-1 & =0\\
\left(x^{3}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}} & =1\nonumber \\
x_{2}^{*} & =1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=1$
\end_inset

,
 which gives us the solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{1}^{*}\left(x_{1}^{*}\right) & =0^{2}=0\\
y_{2}^{*}\left(x_{2}^{*}\right) & =1^{2}=1\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solution 1 gives the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1}^{*},y_{1}^{*}\right)=\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and solution 2 gives the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{2}^{*},y_{2}^{*}\right)=\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These solutions mean that either none of the friends smoke 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 or both smoke all the time 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the value 1 can be described as much as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These solutions can be described as the system's stable equilibria.
 If one of the friends tries smoking with less than 1 pack per day,
 such as smoking half a pack,
 the equation system moves toward the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Say for example that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left(0.5\right)^{2}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 if one smokes half a pack then the other only smokes a quarter pack.
 Since both friends influence each other,
 the next day we get 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(0.25\right)^{2}=0.0625$
\end_inset

,
 whereupon 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left(0.0625\right)^{2}\approx0.0039$
\end_inset

,
 approaching closer to 0 to infinity.
 This process continues indefinitely,
 with both smoking levels decreasing toward zero—
making 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 a stable equilibrium.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 is a stable equilibrium if any of the two friends start there,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}=\left(1\right)^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this theoretical example they cannot smoke more than the value 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two functions and the two solutions (the two stable equilibria) are illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-vänners-rökvanor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The lines meet at the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

