\begin_layout Section
Example 2:
 More smoking
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us continue calculating Erik and Maria's smoking but based on other equations.
 The purpose of this example is to illustrate how we by changing a little in the equations can illustrate different types of theories and patterns.
 Suppose we now have the following equation system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=x^{2}+\frac{1}{4} & \forall x\in\left[0,1\right]\\
x=y^{2}+\frac{1}{4} & \forall y\in\left[0,1\right]
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 still symbolize the two friends' smoking and how smoking is affected by the other's smoking.
 In both equations we have added the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 This constant can be interpreted as both liking to smoke a little bit but that the other's smoking can also affect one's own smoking.
 To solve out the system's solutions we start by taking the definition of y from the upper equation and substituting this into the lower equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =\left(x^{2}+\frac{1}{4}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{4}\\
 & =x^{4}+\frac{x^{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{16}+\frac{1}{4}\nonumber \\
0 & =x^{4}+\frac{x^{2}}{2}-x+\frac{5}{16}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have a fourth-degree equation from which we can proceed and solve out x.
 We first rewrite the equation so that we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
16x^{4}+8x^{2}-16x+5=0\label{eq: rökning ex 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this it is easier to see the equation's potential rational roots,
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Rationella-rötter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We seek 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is an integer factor of the constant 5 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is an integer factor of 16,
 the multiplier of the power expression in the equation that has the largest exponent.
 Possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm5$
\end_inset

.
 Possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1,\pm2,\pm4,\pm8,\pm16$
\end_inset

.
 We now get the following potential roots:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p}{q}=\pm1,\pm\frac{1}{2},\pm\frac{1}{4},\pm\frac{1}{8},\pm\frac{1}{16},\pm\frac{5}{2},\pm\frac{5}{4},\pm\frac{5}{8},\pm\frac{5}{16},\pm5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By testing these roots in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rökning ex 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{p}{q}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 is a root for the equation.
 This value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 happens to also be the system's only solution.
 This results in the corresponding solution for y:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y^{*} & =\left(x^{*}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{4}=\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{4}=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system's unique solution is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This equation system thus results in Erik and Maria smoking half a pack of cigarettes per day.
 Suppose now that the two friends' smoking can be described with the following equation system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=1-x^{2} & \forall x\in\left[0,1\right]\\
x=1-y^{2} & \forall y\in\left[0,1\right]
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us start by interpreting the equations in ordinary words.
 In both equations the respective variable is a negative function of the other variable.
 This is an illustration that both smoke,
 given that the other does not smoke.
 The system has three solutions.
 Let us look at the first two:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(1,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Both of these solutions mean that one person smokes one pack per day while the other does not smoke at all.
 There is also a third solution:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right) & =\left(\frac{5^{1/2}-1}{2},\frac{5^{1/2}-1}{2}\right)\approx\left(0.62,\,0.62\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be interpreted as both being able to consider smoking simultaneously,
 but in that case they will smoke less than they would have done if they smoked separately.
 They will both smoke somewhat half-heartedly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This simple example illustrates how we with the help of mathematics can describe social relationships,
 or at least parts of these.
 We can of course rewrite or expand the equations to thereby describe in more detail how we imagine people behave in different situations or how the process could develop over time.
 We can also use several variables to describe how several people in a group affect each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Example 3:
 They call it love
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Dejting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we looked at an example concerning Erik's dating strategies.
 Say now that Erik has found a partner and wants to work to make their relationship function.
 But Erik doesn't want to put more work into the relationship than what Erik's partner does.
 The partner feels the same and also doesn't want to engage unless Erik does it.
 We can describe with the help of a non-linear equation system in a similar way as the example with smoking:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
K=P^{2}+0.1\\
P=K^{2}+0.1
\end{cases}\label{eq: system Kim och partner}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 symbolize Erik and Erik's partner and 0.1 is a constant that symbolizes how much work they are prepared to put in regardless of how much the other one exerts themselves.
 From the lower equation we solve an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K=\left(P-0.1\right)^{1/2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have two definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that we can set equal to each other:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(P-0.1\right)^{1/2} & =P^{2}+0.1\\
P-0.1 & =\left(P^{2}+0.1\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
P-0.1 & =P^{4}+2*0.1*P^{2}+\left(0.1\right)^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the right-hand side on the bottom row we now have the following fourth-degree polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{4}+0.2P^{2}-P+0.11=0\label{eq: fjärdegradspolynomet Kims relation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From here we can continue by testing rational roots (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Rationella-rötter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) or different values for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and see if we can find the first root.
 After that we can work further with polynomial division.
 We test 
\begin_inset Formula $P=0,\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{For }P=0: &  & 0+0-0+0.11 & =0.11\neq0\\
\text{For }P=\frac{1}{2}: &  & \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{4}+0.2\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}+0.11 & =-0.2775\neq0\nonumber \\
\text{For }P=1: &  & 1+0.2-1+0.11 & =0.31\neq0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of these were a solution,
 but note how the results for the polynomial are positive for 
\begin_inset Formula $P=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P=1$
\end_inset

,
 but negative for 
\begin_inset Formula $P=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 There should be one or more values for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 between these values that result in the polynomial being equal to 0,
 meaning there is a solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 1/2,
 as well as another solution between 1/2 and 1.
 Another method to find these solutions is to plot a graph for the functions in question,
 either by hand or with the help of a computer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fjärdegradspolynomet relationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the line for the fourth-degree polynomial in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: fjärdegradspolynomet Kims relation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The line passes 0 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is just over 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 and just under 
\begin_inset Formula $0.9$
\end_inset

.
 This is the system's two stable equilibria,
 and the solutions to the equations.
\end_layout

