\begin_layout Section
Example 4:
 Another theory about work
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: nairu med flera jämvikter"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: nairu teori"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through an equation system that described a theory for work.
 That system was non-linear in its first form but with the help of logarithmization we got linear equations.
 In that example,
 linearity did not affect the number of solutions to the system.
 We calculated a unique solution for the two variables in both cases.
 However,
 there are discussions around labor market and social economy where we can also benefit from non-linear equation systems with multiple equilibria.
 We will therefore look at yet another simplified model that can be used to reason around the labor market and the equilibrium levels for employment,
 unemployment and real wage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example we have two non-linear functions,
 one for wage-setting and one for price-setting:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\frac{W}{P}=\frac{a}{U} & ,b>0\\
\frac{P}{W}=\frac{c}{d\left(1-U\right)^{1/2}} & ,d>0
\end{cases}\label{eq: S multp eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 symbolize wages and prices.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

 is real wage,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is percent unemployment.
 The parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-U\right)$
\end_inset

 is the share of the workforce that is employed.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 are positive coefficients.
 The first equation in the system is the wage-setting curve and the second equation is the price-setting curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: nairu teori"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we now assume that the price-setting curve also has a positive slope.
 This means that the curves can meet more than once and that we thereby get at least two solutions.
 Now we will check the conditions for this.
 We start by rewriting the second equation so that this gives us an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

.
 We set this new expression equal to the first equation's definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

,
 which gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d\left(1-U\right)^{1/2}}{c} & =\frac{a}{U}\\
U\left(1-U\right)^{1/2} & =\frac{ac}{d}\nonumber \\
U^{2}-U & =\left(\frac{ac}{d}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
U^{2}-U-h & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in the last row is a designation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{ac}{d}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We now have a second-degree polynomial that we can solve with for example the the quadratic formula (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pq-formeln"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U & =-\left(\frac{-1}{2}\right)\pm\sqrt[2]{\left(\frac{-1}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(-h\right)}\\
U_{1} & =\frac{1}{2}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}+h}\nonumber \\
U_{2} & =\frac{1}{2}+\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}+h}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These solutions we can substitute into the system's equations and solve for the solutions of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $W/P$
\end_inset

.
 For the first equation this gives two solutions:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)_{1} & =\frac{a}{U}=\frac{a}{\frac{1}{2}+\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}+h}}\\
\left(\frac{W}{P}\right)_{2} & =\frac{a}{U}=\frac{a}{\frac{1}{2}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}+h}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-jämvikter-på arbetsmarknaden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the two equations and solutions.
 At the point (solution) down to the left in the figure the amount of jobs and wages are relatively smaller,
 compared to the point (solution) up to the right.
\end_layout

