\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above,
 a central assumption in this example is that the curves slope in the same direction.
 If the curves slope in different directions they can only meet once,
 in the way we went through in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: nairu teori"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Exactly why the curves according to this theory would slope in the same direction is not covered in this review.
 We simply accept it as a theoretical assumption.
 Another approach would be that we start the reasoning on a more fundamental level and describe how workers and employers behave 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see"
key "manningImperfectCompetitionMultiple1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Non-linear equations can be included in equation systems.
 For non-linear equations there are no general rules for number of solutions.
 Non-linear equations can meet anywhere between 0 and infinitely many times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find solutions to a non-linear equation system we can use row reduction and substitution in similar ways as we use it for linear equation systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another way to find solutions for a non-linear equation system is to use polynomial division.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Non-linear equation systems can among other things be used to describe theoretical questions where we have more than one solution to the system,
 more than one equilibrium.
 This can for example be used to describe macroeconomic perspectives on wage and price formation or social dynamics between friends or partners.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve the equation system 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{cases}
y=x\\
y=\left(x-2\right)^{2}
\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Substitute the first equation into the second and write the resulting equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find all solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write the complete solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)$
