\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative
\end_layout

\end_inset

This chapter introduces the derivative.
 The derivative is a function for calculating the slope of a line at a specific point.
 The derivative can be used to find a function's maximum and minimum values,
 which is central to a large amount of analytical work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
limit
\end_layout

\end_inset

Before we get to derivatives,
 we shall introduce limits.
 The limit is the value that a function approaches at a specific point.
 Limits can be used to handle expressions that are not defined for all numbers.
 Suppose we have the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a real number.
 The real numbers are not defined for division by 0.
 To understand why,
 see what happens with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{For }x=0.1\text{ is }\frac{1}{x^{2}} & =\frac{1}{0.01}=100\label{eq: 1/x mot noll}\\
\text{For }x=0.01\text{ is }\frac{1}{x^{2}} & =\frac{1}{0.0001}=10,000\nonumber \\
\text{For }x=0.0001\text{ is }\frac{1}{x^{2}} & =\frac{1}{0.0000001}=100,000,000\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x^{2}$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity.
 Infinity is written with the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

,
 which is not a real number.
 This means that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=1/x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 To describe that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 except 0 one may write:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x^{2}},\,\forall x\neq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that are not equal to 0.
 That equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 1/x mot noll"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 approaches infinity as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0 can be described in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow0}f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}=\infty
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\rightarrow0}$
\end_inset

 stands for limes,
 which means limit.
 To describe how function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 behaves when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward positive infinity,
 we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow\infty}f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward positive infinity,
 the limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=1/x=0$
\end_inset

.
 The function goes toward the value 0.
 For many expressions,
 it's possible to find the limit by calculating the expression for values close to the limit,
 as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 1/x mot noll"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Suppose we seek the limit for the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x-1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow1}x-1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To find the limit,
 we calculate values close to 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

