\begin_layout Standard
We get the same limit regardless of whether we approach 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from above or from below.
 The limit for an expression can however differ depending on whether we approach the limit from above or from below.
 Take for example the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\frac{1}{x}\,\forall x\neq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that are not equal to 0.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

,
 the same limit still applies as for 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=1/x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0 from values above 0,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 goes toward positive infinity.
 But if we instead look at how 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0 for values below 0,
 we get the following result instead:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{For }x=-1\text{ is }y=\frac{1}{x} & =\frac{1}{-1}=-1\\
\text{For }x=-0.2\text{ is }y=\frac{1}{x} & =\frac{1}{-0.2}=-5\nonumber \\
\text{For }x=-0.0001\text{ is }y=\frac{1}{x} & =\frac{1}{-0.0001}=-10,000\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


