limit!right-hand
\end_layout

\end_inset

The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward 0 from the positive side of the input value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x>0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is also called a right-hand limit,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches from the right on the number line.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow0^{-}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 0 from smaller values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x<0\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which is called a left-hand limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simplify first
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We often benefit from simplifying the function we are working with as far as possible.
 This also applies when we seek limits.
 Consider now the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=g\left(x\right)=\frac{x^{3}-2x^{2}+4x-8}{x-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g\left(2\right) & =\frac{2^{3}-2*2^{2}+4*2-8}{2-2}=\frac{0}{0}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 the nominator and denominator is zero,
 which is undefined for real values.
 It is however possible to calculate the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 2 and thereby get a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But first we factorize the numerator so we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y=g\left(x\right) & =\frac{x^{3}-3x^{2}+3x-9}{x-2}=\frac{\left(x^{2}+4\right)\left(x-2\right)}{x-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since we have the parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-2\right)$
\end_inset

 in both numerator and denominator,
 we can cancel this and get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g\left(x\right) & =\frac{\left(x^{2}+4\right)\cancel{\left(x-2\right)}}{\cancel{\left(x-2\right)}}=x^{2}+4
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this simplified form the function is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=g\left(2\right)=2^{2}+4=8
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since this is a simplified version of the function we call this value 8 the function's limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

,
 which we write as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow2}g\left(x\right)=\frac{x^{3}-2x^{2}+4x-8}{x-2}=8
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose now that we have the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y=f\left(x\right) & =\frac{\left(x^{2}+3\right)\left(x-3\right)}{x-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 the denominator is zero and therefore undefined.
 First we can expand the numerator:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{2}+3\right)\left(x-3\right)=x^{3}-3x^{2}+3x-9$
\end_inset

.
 We cannot simplify the expression more.
 In this case we have two limits.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 2 from the left 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x<2\right)$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 approaches positive infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $+\infty$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approaches 2 from the right 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x>2\right)$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 approaches negative infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\lim_{x\rightarrow2^{+}}f\left(x\right) & =\frac{x^{3}-3x^{2}+3x-9}{x-2}=-\infty\\
\lim_{x\rightarrow2^{-}}f\left(x\right) & =\frac{x^{3}-3x^{2}+3x-9}{x-2}=+\infty\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While limits help us understand function behavior near problematic points,
 they also enable us to solve a fundamental question:
 how can we measure the exact slope of a curved line at a single point?
 This leads us to the derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Derivata"

\end_inset

Differentiating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative
\end_layout

\end_inset

The derivative can be used to calculate the slope of a line at a specific point.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Den-räta-linjens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through the equation of the straight line.
 In a function of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the line and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the value 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 takes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 b is a measure of how much 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 Since the line is straight,
 it has the same slope regardless of which value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has.
 The slope between the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{2},y_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 we may calculate as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b=\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead have a line that is not straight over all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 one may use the derivative to calculate the slope at a specific value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Let us illustrate with the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Funktionen x2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates how the slope of the line for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 varies depending on the value for x.
 The solid curved line is drawn with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the dashed straight lines show the slope at two points on the curved line.
 At the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 the solid line has slope 0 and is horizontal.
 At the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(2,4\right)$
\end_inset

 the slope is instead positive,
 up toward the graph's right corner.
 
