\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!h-definition
\end_layout

\end_inset

The derivative indicates the limit of the line's slope.
 The limit here refers to how much the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 changes at a small change in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This is described by the derivative's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-definition,
 where the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 describes the distance between two values in the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f'\left(x\right)=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{f\left(x+h\right)-f\left(x\right)}{h}\label{eq: derivatans h-def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: derivatans h-def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be read as the derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which we write as 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is given by the function value at point x+h minus the function value at point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 goes toward 0,
 divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-definition therefore describes the limit when the distance between the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+h$
\end_inset

 shrinks toward 0.
 For function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 we derive this by substituting this function into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: derivatans h-def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'\left(x\right) & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{f\left(x+h\right)-f\left(x\right)}{h}\\
 & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(x+h\right)^{2}-x^{2}}{h}\nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(x+h\right)\left(x+h\right)-x^{2}}{h}\nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{h^{2}+2xh+x^{2}-x^{2}}{h}\nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{h^{2}+2xh}{h}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

All terms in the numerator and denominator contain 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

,
 which we may simplify:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'\left(x\right) & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{h\times\cancel{h}+2x\cancel{h}}{\cancel{h}}=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}h+2x=2x
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have shown that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 has the derivative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=f'\left(x\right)=2x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have two functions that both use the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 on one hand 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and on the other hand its derivative,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)=2x$
\end_inset

.
 Let us also figure out what slope the line has in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Funktionen x2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The derivative of our function is 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)=2x$
\end_inset

.
 To get the slope of the line at a specific point,
 that is how much y changes when x increases by 1,
 we substitute the value for x at the current point.
 In the figure,
 the points at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=4$
\end_inset

 are marked with dashed lines.
 If we substitute these values for x into the derivative's function,
 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'\left(2\right) & =2*2=4\\
f'\left(4\right) & =2*4=8\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which shows how the line for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 slopes at these points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dashed lines in the figure are straight lines,
 which we may calculate backwards in the following way.
 We know that the derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)=2x$
\end_inset

 and that at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(2\right)=2*2=4$
\end_inset

.
 The last is the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 at this point.
 To get the dashed straight line's equation,
 we therefore substitute the values we know into such an equation.
 We seek the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+bx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We already know the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y,b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4=a+4*2
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This gives the following value for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=4-8=-4
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation for the dashed line at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Funktionen x2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is therefore:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=-4+4x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above walkthrough was relatively elaborate.
 Fortunately,
 there are several calculation rules that we may use to avoid doing this process every time we need to use derivatives (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: räkneregler derivata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 The calculation rule for the above example can be formulated as if we have the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=x^{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

its derivative is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f'\left(x\right)=ax^{a-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The next derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the derived version of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 the following notations say exactly the same thing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=f'\left(x\right)=\frac{df\left(x\right)}{dx}=\frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\label{eq: Leibniz notation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Leibniz notation
\end_layout

\end_inset

The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 here have the same meaning as the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $dy/dx$
\end_inset

 can be read as a small change of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 divided by a small change of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This notation is called Leibniz notation,
 after Wilhelm Leibniz (1646–1716).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have only worked with the first derivative.
 If we take the derivative of the first derivative,
 we get the second derivative.
 This is calculated and written in a similar way as the first derivative.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Function:} & y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}\label{eq: från f till andraderivatan}\\
\text{First derivative: } & \frac{\partial y}{\partial x}=f'\left(x\right)=3x^{2}\nonumber \\
\text{Second derivative } & \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\right)=f''\left(x\right)=2*3x=6x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_x3.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: y=x^3"

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

 and its first and second derivative
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are three different mathematical expressions:
 the function,
 the first derivative and the second derivative.
 All three expressions are different mathematical functions that use the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as input value,
 which is evident from the parenthesis with x in the name of each function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right),f'\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: y=x^3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrate all these three functions in one graph each,
 with variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 on the vertical axis and variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on the horizontal axis.
 In all three graphs,
 the slope of the line is marked at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate the value for each function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: från f till andraderivatan"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Function: }f\left(2\right) & =2^{3}=8\\
\text{First derivative: }f'\left(2\right) & =3*2^{2}=12\nonumber \\
\text{Second derivative: }f''\left(2\right) & =6*2=12\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the derivative of the second derivative,
 we get what is called the third derivative.
 The derivative after that is called the fourth derivative and so on.
 If we start here from the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 then we have:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'=f'\left(x\right) & =3x^{2}\\
y''=f''\left(x\right) & =6x\nonumber \\
y'''=f'''\left(x\right) & =6\nonumber \\
y''''=f''''\left(x\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where rows 3 and 4 are the third and fourth derivatives of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The fourth derivative is the slope of the slope of the slope of the line's slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 which is 0 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We can see this already in the third derivative,
 which is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $y'''=6$
\end_inset

 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which in a graph becomes a horizontal line at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=6$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exponent,
 logarithm and 
\emph on
e
\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: derivata exponential e log"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
exponential function
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have so far worked with functions where the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 stands as the base in a power expression,
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{a}$
\end_inset

,
 where exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Potenser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 In an exponential function,
 the variable is instead the exponent.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=b^{x}\label{eq: a^x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient and the exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a variable.
 Sometimes the expression the exponential function is used in definite form,
 which then refers to 
\begin_inset Formula $y=e^{x}$
\end_inset

 with the number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 as base.
 This is sometimes also written as 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\exp\left(x\right)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us derive the derivative for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=b^{x}$
\end_inset

 using the derivative's h-definition (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: derivatans h-def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'_{x} & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{b^{x+h}-b^{x}}{h}\label{eq: gränsvärdet för b^x}\\
 & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{b^{x}\left(b^{h}-1\right)}{h}\nonumber \\
 & =b^{x}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{b^{h}-1}{h}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the last step,
 we factor out 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{x}$
\end_inset

 since this is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and therefore is not affected by 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 going toward 0.
 The limit for the expression is dependent on the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 which is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Betydelsen-av-basen b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The solid line shows values for the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\left(b^{h}-1\right)/h$
\end_inset

 for different 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1$
\end_inset

,
 the limit is 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_derive_ax.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Betydelsen-av-basen b"

\end_inset

The importance of the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Euler's number
\end_layout

\end_inset

The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\left(b^{h}-1\right)/h$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gränsvärdet för b^x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is equal to 1 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is equal to approximately 2.718,
 which is also marked in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Betydelsen-av-basen b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This number is so commonly occurring that it has received its own name,
 Euler's number,
 and is abbreviated e.
 We have mentioned this number before.
 The natural logarithm of the base b in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gränsvärdet för b^x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is the number that 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (approximately 2.718) must be raised to in order to get 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the general result for the equation can be described as the natural logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Say now that we have a function with the following form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=b^{x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x}\left(x\right)= & b^{x}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{b^{h}-1}{h}\right)=b^{x}\log_{e}b=b^{x}\ln b
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the logarithm's base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is equal to the number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
b^{x}\log_{e}b=e^{x}\ln e=1*e^{x}=e^{x}\label{eq: log_e b}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that if we have a function of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

,
 then its derivative is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'_{x}=e^{x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is,
 the derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is also equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The second derivative of this function is similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $y''_{xx}=e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now derive the derivative of the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(x\right)=e^{ax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 according to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is Euler's number.
 To calculate the derivative of this function,
 we again use the derivative's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-definition:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'_{x} & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{e^{a\left(x+h\right)}-e^{ax}}{h}=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{e^{ax}\left(e^{ah}-1\right)}{h}=e^{ax}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{e^{ah}-1}{h}\right)\label{eq: e^ax h-definition}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the third step,
 we factor out 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ax}$
\end_inset

 from the parenthesis,
 which is possible since this factor is not affected by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 Moving out 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ax}$
\end_inset

 thus does not affect the limit.
 To proceed from here,
 we may multiply both numerator and denominator in the parenthesis by the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 an arbitrary real number.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the numerator also does not affect the limit,
 we move this out of the parenthesis.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the denominator we leave in place:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'_{x} & =e^{ax}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{a}{a}\times\frac{e^{ah}-1}{h}\right)\\
 & =ae^{ax}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{e^{ah}-1}{ah}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =ae^{ax}\left(\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{e^{ah}-1}{ah}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =ae^{ax}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we move a out of the parenthesis,
 both numerator and denominator go toward 0,
 which is why the limit goes toward 1.
 In the last line we therefore remove the limit and only have 
\begin_inset Formula $y'_{x}=ae^{ax}$
\end_inset

 left.
 This expression has the same form as what we derived in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: log_e b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We may summarize this as a general calculation rule.
 If we have a function with the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=e^{g\left(x\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

its derivative is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'_{x}=g'_{x}e^{g\left(x\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These examples also make it easy to continue with other types of functions,
 for example the following power function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=b^{ax}\label{eq: b^ax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the letters b and a are coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are variables.
 One way to derive the derivative of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: b^ax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is to rewrite the expression as a power with base 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 Euler's number:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=b^{ax}=e^{\ln b^{ax}}=e^{ax\ln b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We here take the natural logarithm of our function 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{ax}$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln b^{ax}=ax\ln b$
\end_inset

.
 We use this as an exponent to the base 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 which gives us an expression that we can differentiate:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x}\left(x\right) & =\left(a\ln b\right)e^{ax\ln b}=\left(a\ln b\right)b^{ax}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\log x}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now differentiate the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\log x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\log x$
\end_inset

 is the logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with arbitrary base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 We use the derivative's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-definition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'=\left(\log x\right)' & =\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{\log\left(x+h\right)-\log\left(x\right)}{h}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\log a-\log b=\log\left(a/b\right)$
\end_inset

 we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{\log\left(1+\frac{h}{x}\right)}{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We factor out the numerator 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{h}\log\left(1+\frac{h}{x}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now define 
\begin_inset Formula $z=h/x$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $1/h=\frac{1}{z}\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{x}\frac{1}{z}\log\left(1+z\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as well.
 The multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $1/z$
\end_inset

 in front of the logarithm we move up to the exponent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'=\frac{1}{x}\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\log\left(1+z\right)^{1/z}\label{eq: gränsvärde dx log x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We shall now look more closely at the part of the expression that consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1+z\right)^{1/z}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us temporarily rewrite this to the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\left(1+z\right)^{1/z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and look at some values in a graph.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: y=1+z ^1/z"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the line for this function over some values for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 2.
 Due to the exponent,
 this function is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_lim_logx.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: y=1+z ^1/z"

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left(1+z\right)^{1/z}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note how the limit for this function approaches the value 2.718 as z approaches 0.
 The number 2.718 we recognize already as Euler's number,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 The limit for the expression in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gränsvärde dx log x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y' & =\frac{1}{x}\left(\lim_{z\rightarrow0}\log\left(1+z\right)^{1/z}\right)=\frac{1}{x}\log e
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned at the beginning of the example,
 the logarithm here has base b.
 Let us now change base to e,
 so that we get the natural logarithm.
 We went through this in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Basbyte-för-logaritmer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: log ändra bas-ekvationen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we had the general rule for changing base between logarithms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{a}x=\frac{\log_{b}x}{\log_{b}a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this case this means:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log_{b}e=\frac{\ln e}{\ln b}=\frac{1}{\ln b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log x$
\end_inset

 then becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'_{x}\left(x\right)=\left(\log_{b}x\right)'_{x}=\frac{1}{x\ln b}\label{eq: derivata av log x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we have base 
\begin_inset Formula $b=e$
\end_inset

 the derivative is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y'_{x}=\left(\ln x\right)'_{x}=\frac{1}{x}\label{eq: derivata av ln x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
L'Hôpital's rule
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:L'Hôpitals-regel"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
L'Hôpital's rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here follows a simplified description of L'Hôpital's rule (also called Bernoulli's rule),
 which is a useful calculation rule for derivatives.
 Suppose we have the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and these go toward 0 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity.
 We calculate a constant derivative sufficiently close to the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 in such a way that we get the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f'}{g'}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For these functions the following then applies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}=\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f'_{x}\left(x\right)}{g'_{x}\left(x\right)}\label{eq: L'Hôpitals regel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is called L'Hôpital's rule and means that the limit for function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 divided by function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the same as the limit for the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 divided by the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes toward 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate the usefulness of L'Hôpital's rule with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=k\left(x\right)=\frac{x^{2}+3}{x-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

,
 since the denominator then becomes 0.
 To facilitate the calculation of the limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

,
 we then use L'Hôpital's rule.
 We define the numerator as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}+3$
\end_inset

 and the denominator as 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=x-2$
\end_inset

.
 We have the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=2x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'_{x}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we calculate the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow2$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{x\rightarrow2}k\left(x\right)=\lim_{x\rightarrow2}\frac{2x}{1}=4
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number 4 comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2x=2*2=4$
\end_inset

.
 The limit for the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow2$
\end_inset

 is thus 4.
 According to L'Hôpital's rule,
 this is also the limit for the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Partial derivative
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Partiell-derivata"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we took the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 above,
 we wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and since we only have one variable in the function,
 we understand that this refers to taking the derivative with respect to the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We may also write to our variable to be extra clear:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f'_{x}\left(x\right)=\text{the derivative of \ensuremath{f} with respect to variable \ensuremath{x}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we have several variables,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

,
 we may calculate the derivative for each variable.
 This is called the partial derivative.
 For the derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 respectively,
 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 If we differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to one variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we do not differentiate with respect to other variables in the same function.
 Other terms in the function are treated as constants.
 Take the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x,y\right) & =x^{2}+y^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We shall differentiate this with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 and thereafter differentiate the results with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 again:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x} & =2x\\
f'_{y} & =2y\nonumber \\
f''_{xx} & =2\nonumber \\
f''_{yy} & =2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may also differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 first with respect to first 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and get 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=2x$
\end_inset

,
 and then differentiate this function with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f''_{xy}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same thing if we instead differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 first with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f''_{yx}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us take another example with the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g\left(x,y\right) & =x^{2}y^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first and second derivatives of function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g'_{x} & =2xy^{2}\\
g''_{xx} & =2y^{2}\nonumber \\
g'_{y} & =2yx^{2}\nonumber \\
g''_{yy} & =2x^{2}\nonumber \\
g''_{xy} & =4xy\nonumber \\
g''_{yx} & =4yx\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

