\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: komb funktioner med operationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through how we may use addition,
 subtraction,
 multiplication and division on functions,
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the same section we introduced composite functions,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes calculation rules for derivatives where two functions are added (row 1),
 subtracted (row 2),
 multiplied (row 3),
 divided (row 4) or composed (row 5).
 We illustrate these calculation rules with the functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x\right) & =x^{2}\\
g\left(x\right) & =3-2x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first derivative of each function with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x}\left(x\right) & =2x\\
g'_{x}\left(x\right) & =-2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the functions are added,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f+g & =x^{2}+3-2x\\
\left(f+g\right)'_{x}=f'+g' & =2x-2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With subtraction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f-g & =x^{2}-3+2x\\
\left(f-g\right)'_{x}=f'-g' & =2x+2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Row three in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\emph on
 
\emph default
describes what is called the product rule:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!product rule
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\times g & =x^{2}\left(3-2x\right)\\
\left(f\times g\right)'_{x}=f'g+fg' & =2x\left(3-2x\right)-2x^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!quotient rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

Row four in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the quotient rule.
 This shows how to calculate the derivative when one function is divided by another function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{f}{g} & =\frac{x^{2}}{3-2x}\\
\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)'_{x}=\frac{f'g+fg'}{g^{2}} & =\frac{2x\left(3-2x\right)-2x^{2}}{\left(3-2x\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!chain rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

Row five in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the chain rule,
 which shows how to calculate the derivative for composite functions.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(g\left(x\right)\right) & =\left(3-2x\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'_{x}=-2$
\end_inset

 och 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{g\left(x\right)}=2\left(3-2x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)'_{x} & =f'_{g}\left(g\right)g'_{x}=2\left(3-2x\right)\left(-2\right)=-4\left(3-2x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Elasticity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Elasticitet"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
elasticity
\end_layout

\end_inset

A measure that is often used in social science is elasticity.
 This indicates how much one variable changes in percentage terms at a percentage change in another variable.
 Say for example that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the number of sold units of this good (the market's demand),
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the price for this good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Change between two price levels can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p=p_{2}-p_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 which we read as the difference between price level 1 and price level 2.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 (the Greek letter capital delta) symbolizes change here.
 Change between two quantities:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q=q_{2}-q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The price elasticity can then be defined as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{price elasticity: }\frac{\frac{\Delta q}{q}}{\frac{\Delta p}{p}}=\frac{\frac{q_{2}-q_{1}}{q_{1}}}{\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{p_{1}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is percentage change of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 divided by percentage change of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If demand 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 changes a lot when 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 changes,
 this means that the good have high price elasticity,
 customers are very price-sensitive.
 If demand 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 barely changes at all when 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 changes,
 price elasticity is low and customers are relatively price-insensitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Leibniz notation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described the derivative using the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative gives us the slope of the line at a specific point.
 Similarly,
 we may compare the elasticity at a specific point,
 which is called point elasticity.
 Say for example that a large store sells milk for 10 USD per package.
 Every week 100 packages are sold.
 In January,
 the store decides to raise the price by 20%,
 to 12 USD per package.
 In the long run,
 sales drop to 97 packages per week.
 The price elasticity of demand for milk is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial q/q}{\partial p/p} & =\frac{-0.03}{0.2}=-0.15
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the price increases by 20%,
 demand decreases by 3%,
 which is why the price elasticity is 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.15\%$
\end_inset

.
 We do not know if this elasticity applies to all price levels.
 Studying price elasticity in reality is more complex than this example,
 see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols kvasiexperiment"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The limit,
 limes,
 for a function describes the value the function approaches when it comes infinitely close to a point.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{x}=\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The derivative is a function that describes the limit for a line's slope at a point.
 The derivative's 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-definition:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)=\lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{f\left(x+h\right)-f\left(x\right)}{h}$
\end_inset

,
 where h indicates the distance between two values in the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we may write the first derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 the second derivative as 
\begin_inset Formula $f''_{xx}$
\end_inset

 and the third derivative as 
\begin_inset Formula $f'''_{xxx}$
\end_inset

.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=3x^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f''_{xx}=6x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'''_{xxx}=6$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=a+bx$
\end_inset

 has the slope 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that the function is defined for.
 The derivative can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Partial derivative:
 differentiate a function with several variables with respect to one variable at a time.
 Example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x,z\right)=x^{2}+z^{2}$
\end_inset

 has first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=2x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{z}=2z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Examples of differentiation rules:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=bx^{a}+c$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=abx^{a-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=b^{ax}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $g'_{x}\left(x\right)=\left(a\ln b\right)b^{ax}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=\log x$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $h'_{x}\left(x\right)=1/\left(x\ln b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
• Examples of differentiation with combined and composite functions 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f+g\right)\left(x\right)'_{x}=f'_{x}+g'_{x}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f-g\right)\left(x\right)'_{x}=f'_{x}-g'_{x}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{f\left(x\right)}\right)'_{x}$
\end_inset

=
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\left(x\right)^{-1}\right)'_{x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $=-f'_{x}f^{-2}=\frac{-f'_{x}}{\left(f\left(x\right)\right)^{-2}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Product rule:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)\right)'_{x}=\left(\left(f\times g\right)\left(x\right)\right)'_{x}=f'g+g'f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Quotient rule:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}\right)'_{x}=\frac{f'_{x}g+fg'_{x}}{g}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chain rule:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(g\left(x\right)\right)'_{x}=g'f'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
L'Hôpital's rule:
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}=\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f'_{x}\left(x\right)}{g'_{x}\left(x\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

