\begin_layout Chapter
Optimization with functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Optimering-utifrån-funktioner"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter introduces optimization,
 which we shall use here to find a desired solution based on a function.
 In social science,
 we may for example use this to describe how a company can maximize its profit or describe how a person can maximize their utility and happiness or minimize their unhappiness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extreme values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
extreme value
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
critical point
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
maximum value
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
minimum value
\end_layout

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:En-funktion med min och max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows a line drawn with an unknown function where two points are marked.
 The lowest point on the line is the function's minimum value and the highest point is the maximum value.
 Both of these two are examples of what are called extreme values,
 also called extreme points or critical points.
 Consider the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2},\forall1\le x\le10
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall$
\end_inset

 means "for all".
 The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

 means "less than or equal to".
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall1\le x\le10$
\end_inset

 should be read as "for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that are greater than or equal to 1 and less than or equal to 10".
 This means that this function is defined over the interval 1 to 10 on the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_minmax.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:En-funktion med min och max"

\end_inset

A function with a maximum and minimum value
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 here can only take a value between 1 and 10,
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 will only assume values between 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}=100$
\end_inset

.
 Our function is relatively simple and we may therefore see that the function's smallest and largest value in this case are given by these input values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Smallest value = minimum value: }f\left(1\right) & =1^{2}=1\\
\text{Greatest value = maximum value: }f\left(10\right) & =10^{2}=100\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All other values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 between 1 and 10 result in values for y that are located between these two results.
 Even a function that is defined over a set can lack extreme values.
 We can illustrate this with the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=x,\,\forall x\in\left(0,3\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
open interval
\end_layout

\end_inset

In a graph,
 this function would create a straight line.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is defined over an open interval,
 the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3,3\right)$
\end_inset

 are not included.
 The function is defined infinitely close to the values 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

.
 But for every decimal close to these values,
 there will be a decimal that is even closer.
 The function therefore lacks minimum and maximum values.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Differentiate to find extreme values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative with respect to a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 gives us the slope of the line at a specific point.
 This is a measure of how much the function or the dependent variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 changes when variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases by 1.
 We can use this information for different purposes.
 Suppose we have the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=-x^{2},\quad\forall x\in\left[-\infty,\infty\right]\label{eq: -x2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 describes a desirable phenomenon and we therefore seek the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is maximized.
 We seek the function's maximum value,
 which the derivative can help us with.
 The function is defined over a bounded interval and is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:extrempunkt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If the first derivative is equal to 0 at a value on the variable and the line at the point is therefore horizontal and lacks slope,
 this is an extreme point,
 minimum or maximum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_minx2.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:extrempunkt"

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we know the function's second derivative,
 the slope of the slope,
 this can also give us more information about what type of extreme point it is.
 If the second derivative is negative at an extreme point,
 it means that the points adjacent to the extreme value are smaller than the point and we then know that the extreme value is a maximum point.
 If the second derivative is positive,
 the slope of the slope increases,
 then the extreme value is a minimum point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the function's extreme points,
 we calculate the first derivative and set the result equal to 0.
 This gives us what is called a first-order condition.
 A first-order condition is a mathematical expression that describes the condition that at the point that is maximum,
 the first derivative must be equal to 0.
 From this we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: -x2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we get the following first derivative which we set equal to 0:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
first degree conditions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'\left(x\right) & =-2x=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This first derivative is equal to 0 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 which is why we from 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

 can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is the function's only extreme value.
 We check the function's second derivative to see if this is a maximum or minimum point:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f''\left(x\right) & =-2
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the second derivative is negative,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f''<0$
\end_inset

,
 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x=0\right)$
\end_inset

 must be a maximum point.
 The derivative is not the only way to find a function's extreme values.
 Function f is defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[-\infty,\infty\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The function's minimum is therefore given by the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\infty$
\end_inset

,
 negative and positive infinity,
 where the function goes toward negative infinity.
 Note that this is based on the function being defined for infinity.
 If the domain instead is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left(-\infty,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where negative and positive infinity are excluded from the domain,
 then the function lacks a minimum point.
 There will always be an x-value that results in lower 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is however still the function's maximum point.
 Consider now the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(k\right)=k^{2}-k+3,\quad\forall x\in\left[-\infty,\infty\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the name of the function and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the variable.
 To find out for which values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the function has its highest and lowest values,
 we take the first and second derivative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
h'_{k}\left(k\right) & =2k-1\\
h''_{kk}\left(k\right) & =2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the first derivative we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{*}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the second derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $h''_{kk}>0$
\end_inset

,
 we assume that this is a minimum point.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{*}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 we have:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
h\left(k^{*}=\frac{1}{2}\right) & =k^{2}-k+3=\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{2}+3=2+\frac{3}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function's line is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Linjen för h(k)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where the minimum point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k,y\right)=\left(\frac{1}{2},2.75\right)$
\end_inset

 is marked.
 The function's maximum is given by the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\infty$
\end_inset

,
 where function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 goes toward positive infinity.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_min_ex2.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Linjen för h(k)"

\end_inset

The line for 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(k\right)=k^{2}-k+3$
\end_inset

 and its minimum point
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Global and local
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
extreme point!local and global
\end_layout

\end_inset

Maximum and minimum points can be global and local.
 A local maximum value is the point within an interval where a function assumes its largest value.
 A global maximum value is the point that gives the function's largest value over all values that the function is defined for.
 The same thing for minimum values.
 Let us illustrate with the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}-x^{2}-x+2,\quad\forall x\in\left[-10,10\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a third-degree function defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $-10$
\end_inset

 to plus 10.
 The first and second derivatives give:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x} & =3x^{2}-2x-1\\
f''_{xx} & =6x-2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the first derivative we solve for two zero points,
 two values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 where the first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 0:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
3x^{2}-2x-1=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the the quadratic formula we see that:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=-\left(-\frac{2/3}{2}\right)\pm\sqrt{\left(-\frac{2/3}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(-1/3\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=-\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 At these two points 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=0$
\end_inset

.
 We check the solutions by substituting the values into the second derivative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f''_{xx}\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right) & =6\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right)-2=-4\\
f''_{xx}\left(1\right) & =6*1-2=4\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first row means that the second derivative is negative at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This indicates that this is a maximum point.
 The second row gives that the second derivative is positive at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

,
 which suggests that this is a minimum point.
 Let us also calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 at these points:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y=f\left(x=-\frac{1}{3}\right) & =x^{3}-x^{2}-x+2\\
 & =\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right)^{3}-\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right)^{2}-\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right)+2\\
 & =-\frac{1}{27}-\frac{1}{9}+\frac{1}{3}+2\\
 & =2+\frac{5}{27}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y=f\left(x=1\right) & =x^{3}-x^{2}-x+2=\left(1\right)^{3}-\left(1\right)^{2}-\left(1\right)+2=1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
end points
\end_layout

\end_inset

The function is defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[-10,10\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let us also calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for the endpoints (the outer values) 
\begin_inset Formula $-10$
\end_inset

 and 10.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-10$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y=f\left(x=-10\right) & =x^{3}-x^{2}-x+2\\
 & =\left(-10\right)^{3}-\left(-10\right)^{2}-\left(-10\right)+2\\
 & =-1,000-100+10+2\\
 & =-1,088
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=10$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y=f\left(x=10\right) & =x^{3}-x^{2}-x+2\\
 & =\left(10\right)^{3}-\left(10\right)^{2}-\left(10\right)+2\nonumber \\
 & =1,000-100-10+2\nonumber \\
 & =892\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function's value at x=-10 is smaller than the value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $-1,088<1$
\end_inset

 and the function's value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=10$
\end_inset

 is larger than at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $892>2+\frac{5}{27}$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore conclude that the function's global minimum is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(-10,-1,088\right)$
\end_inset

 and its global maximum is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(10,892\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally,
 the function has a local minimum at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and a local maximum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(-\frac{1}{3},2+\frac{5}{27}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next question is how local these extreme values are,
 within which intervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are these points maximum and minimum?
 We start by looking at this in a graph,
 which is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: lokala globala min max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The two local extreme values are marked along the line with points.
 The global extreme values at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=10$
\end_inset

 are outside the picture and marked with arrows.
