\begin_layout Standard
From the picture we see that the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 is a minimum for the function for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-values from 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and upward.
 For all values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 above 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 up to 10 (the function's domain),
 the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 is the one that gives the lowest value.
 For the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(-\frac{1}{3},2+\frac{5}{27}\right)$
\end_inset

 we see that this is the function's maximum for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from approximately 1.6 and downward.
 
