\begin_layout Section
More examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us find the extreme values for some functions.
 We seek the largest and smallest value,
 maximum and minimum value.
 Let us start with the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x,\quad\forall x\leq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq0,y=f\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 is the function's largest value,
 its global maximum value.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined for all negative values,
 y goes toward negative infinity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

,
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 does the same,
 which is the function's global minimum value.
 If we instead have the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x,\quad\forall x<0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the value 0 is excluded from the domain,
 then the function lacks a global maximum value.
 We only come infinitely close to 0.
 The minimum value is also here negative infinity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now take the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=3x,\quad\forall x\in\left(2,12\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,12\right)$
\end_inset

 excludes the values 2 and 12.
 The function therefore lacks global minimum and maximum values.
 If the function is instead defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[2,12\right]$
\end_inset

,
 the function's global minimum value is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(2\right)=6
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function's global maximum value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(12\right)=36
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now calculate the global minimum and maximum value for the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}-x,\quad\forall x\in\mathbb{R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take the first and second derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y'_{x} & =2x-1\\
y''_{xx} & =2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the first derivative we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the following value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{2}=-\frac{1}{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The second derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $y''_{xx}>0$
\end_inset

 which means that this is a global minimum value.
 Since the function is defined over the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

,
 which does not include infinity,
 the function lacks a global maximum value.
 
\end_layout

