\begin_layout Section
Optimization with constraints
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: optimera villkor, lagrange"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have worked with optimization to find extreme values in functions without any particular form of limitation,
 other than the function itself.
 Often,
 however,
 we have use of being able to add constraints to our calculations.
 We often have use of this in social science,
 for example in reasoning about how people and organizations try to achieve their goals based on limited means or opportunities.
 Constraints can however make it more difficult to find the solution to optimization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common method for finding extreme points with constraints is the Lagrange method.
 We begin by describing the method on a brief overall level.
 Suppose we shall optimize function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to a constraint that we formulate generally as function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by just writing this as a function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\max_{x}f\left(x\right),\quad\text{w.r.t. }g\left(x\right) & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 shall be maximized with respect to variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 so that function g is equal to 0.
 The abbreviation "w.r.t" stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with respect to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes the abbreviation "s.t." is used which stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

subject to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Then we set up the Lagrange function:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lagrange!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(x,\lambda\right)=f\left(x\right)+\lambda g\left(x\right)\label{eq: lagrangefunktionen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Greek letter small lambda 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 symbolizes the Lagrange multiplier,
 which in the Lagrange function is a new variable that is connected with the Lagrange method.
 We shall return to the interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For the functions f and g to be able to be set up in this way,
 we may need to rewrite them.
 To find the extreme points,
 we differentiate the Lagrange function with respect to the two variables x and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{x} & =f'_{x}+\lambda g'_{x}\\
\mathcal{L}'_{\lambda} & =g\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we set these expressions equal to 0,
 we get the first-order conditions and can solve for any solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 has a specific interpretation depending on the maximization problem itself and can for example indicate changes with respect to if the constraint,
 which 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by,
 changes by one unit.
 Let us illustrate by maximizing the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 we shall fulfill the following constraint:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}=2$
\end_inset

.
 We call this expression function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and move all terms in the function to one side of the equals sign so that we get 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g\left(x\right) & =x^{2}-2=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we set up the Lagrange function in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}\left(x,\lambda\right) & =f\left(x\right)+\lambda g\left(x\right)\\
\mathcal{L}\left(x,\lambda\right) & =x^{2}+\lambda\left(x^{2}-2\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the function's solutions,
 we take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with respect to x and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 .
 By setting these respective derivatives equal to 0,
 we get the first-order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{x} & =2x+2x\lambda=0\\
\mathcal{L}'_{\lambda} & =x^{2}-2=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}'_{x}$
\end_inset

 we get the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\lambda^{*} & =-1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}'_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 we get the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\sqrt{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that if we shall maximize the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 so that the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-2=0$
\end_inset

 is fulfilled,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=2^{1/2}\approx1,41$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now take the following maximization problem with constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Maximize }f\left(x,y\right) & =x^{2}y\\
\text{under the condition }g\left(x,y\right) & =x+y=10\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We solve this by setting up the Lagrange function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(x,y,\lambda\right)=x^{2}y+\lambda\left(x+y-10\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we derive the partial derivatives and set these equal to 0 to get the first-order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{x}: & 2xy+\lambda=0\\
\mathcal{L}'_{y}: & x^{2}+\lambda=0\nonumber \\
\mathcal{L}'_{\lambda}: & x+y-10=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}'_{x}=\mathcal{L}'_{y}=0$
\end_inset

,
 we create respective definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{x}:\lambda & =2xy\\
\mathcal{L}'_{y}:\lambda & =x^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By setting the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 equal to each other,
 we get a new constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{2} & =2xy\label{eq:L-villkor}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We simplify this by dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =2y\label{eq: L-villkor förenkl}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have the constraint left:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x+y-10=0\label{eq:L-villkor 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on this we now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2y$
\end_inset

,
 which we substitute into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L-villkor 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x+y-10 & =0\\
2y+y-10 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=\frac{10}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 we use in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: L-villkor förenkl"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2y$
\end_inset

,
 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\frac{20}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These are the values for x and y that optimize
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)=x^{2}y$
\end_inset

,
 while the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=10$
\end_inset

 is fulfilled:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right) & =f\left(\frac{20}{3},\frac{10}{3}\right)=\left(20/3\right)^{2}\left(10/3\right)=\frac{4,000}{27}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A function can have maximum and minimum points where the function's value is maximized or minimized.
 These are called extreme points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One way to find extreme points is to use derivatives and calculate a line's slope at a specific point.
 The first derivative gives the line's slope,
 the second derivative gives the slope of the slope,
 and so on.
 To calculate the derivative we use limits,
 limes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example:
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 has first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=2x$
\end_inset

 and second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f''=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the first derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=0$
\end_inset

 at a point,
 this is a maximum point if 
\begin_inset Formula $f''<0$
\end_inset

,
 minimum point if 
\begin_inset Formula $f''>0$
\end_inset

 and terrace point if 
\begin_inset Formula $f''=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Lagrange method is a method for solving maximization or minimization problems with constraints.
 The general form for the Lagrange function is
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(x,\lambda\right)=f\left(x\right)+\lambda g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier and
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the function for the constraint.
\end_layout

