\begin_layout Chapter
Theories about cake and monopoly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous chapter,
 we went through how we can use derivatives to search for a function's extreme values,
 for example which input value in a variable gives the lowest or highest value in a function.
 This chapter shows examples of how we can use this type of methods to discuss theories about the world.
 The examples are simplified but inspired by more advanced theories within social science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The optimal amount of cake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cake is delicious but we get nauseous if we eat too much.
 Let us describe this with mathematics.
 We think that cake makes us happy and call the variable happiness 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we measure happiness on a scale from 1 to 5,
 where 5 is the greatest possible conceivable happiness.
 Happiness,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 is in turn a function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 of how many cakes we eat.
 We denote the number of eaten cakes as the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 For each cake we consume,
 our happiness increases by 3 units,
 which we may describe with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Happiness}=y=f\left(x\right)=3x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is continuous and for each bite of cake we eat we become happier.
 But we also become more full and eventually our happiness start to decrease if we eat more.
 This negative effect on happiness we can insert into our function by adding the term 
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is quadratic,
 raised to the power of 2.
 This means that for low values,
 for example 0.5,
 the negative effect will be relatively small.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(0.5\right)^{2}=-0.25$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(0.1\right)^{2}=-0.01$
\end_inset

.
 But for higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the negative effect will instead become increasingly larger,
 such as for example 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(2\right)^{2}=-4$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(5\right)^{2}=-25$
\end_inset

.
 The entire function is now:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=3x-x^{2}\label{eq: tårtlyckofunktionen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a maximization problem where we choose the amount of cake to eat,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 to maximize our happiness,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{\text{w.r.t. }x}f\left(x\right)=3x-x^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To calculate which amount of cake leads to the greatest possible happiness we calculate the first and second derivatives of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f'_{x} & =3-2x\label{eq: FOC 1 tårtlycka}\\
f''_{xx} & =-2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the happiness-maximizing amount of cake we set the first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

 equal to 0 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\frac{3}{2}=1,5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f''_{xx}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: FOC 1 tårtlycka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is negative.
 This indicates that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1.5$
\end_inset

 is a maximum point.
 The amount of cake that leads to the greatest possible happiness is one and a half cakes.
 To calculate the amount of happiness at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=1.5$
\end_inset

 we take:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x^{*}=1,5\right) & =3*1,5-\left(1,5\right)^{2}=4,5-2,25=2,25
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One and a half cakes gives 2.25 in happiness,
 where happiness is measured on a scale from 1 to 5.
 However,
 exactly how much happiness is achieved through cake eating is not central in this example.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Den-optimala-mängden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this example and its solution.
 To the left and right of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1.5$
\end_inset

 we see that happiness is less than 2.25.
\end_layout

