\begin_layout Plain Layout
marginal!effect
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to describe this phenomenon is with the help of the concept of marginal effect.
 Generally,
 the concept of marginal effect refers to how a result changes with small changes in a variable.
 In this case,
 how much the total amount of happiness changes with small changes in the amount of cake.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We seek the amount of cake where marginal happiness equals 0,
 where the first derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 0,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}=0$
\end_inset

 is an extreme point.
 If the second derivative is negative,
 small changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 mean that happiness decreases.
 In that case,
 the extreme point is a local maximum point.
 Since equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: tårtlyckofunktionen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 only has one maximum point,
 this is also a global maximum point,
 that is,
 the point where the happiness given by cake eating is the greatest possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example is trivial but introduces the fundamental logical starting points in a large number of theories that occur abundantly within social science.
 Much social science theory can be formulated as people trying to achieve one or several goals,
 by choosing between different action alternatives.
 Many theories about human behavior are often formulated directly or indirectly as maximization or minimization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of how ingenious a theoretical model may be,
 it says nothing in itself about how someone thinks when they are going to eat cake,
 or make any other type of decision.
 To know something about reality,
 we need information about reality.
 In part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part: samvariation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:Sannolikhetslära-för-samhällsvet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 commonly occurring methods for how we can study information about reality and compare against theory are introduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
To work or not to work
\begin_inset CommandInset label
