status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
utility function
\end_layout

\end_inset

The example with cake in the previous section is an abstract illustration of how an individual must choose the right level to get the best possible result from a situation.
 Now we shall look at a similar example but with a clearer connection to social science.
 Say that Erik shall maximize his utility,
 N,
 by choosing between the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Erik's possibility to buy goods and services is financed through working and getting wages.
 This entire phenomenon we call 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Erik's leisure time,
 which we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Erik's utility maximization thus depends on a choice between work and leisure.
 What effect 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 have on Erik's utility we describe with the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N=u\left(C,L\right)=C^{1/2}L^{1/2}\text{ , }\forall C,L>0\label{eq: ex nytta CobbD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is explained by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 with the included variables 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Both variables can only assume positive values,
 since Erik cannot have negative consumption or leisure.
 The exponents for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

,
 the fraction 1/2,
 describe how much 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 increases when the respective variable changes by one unit,
 for example one USD and one clock hour respectively.
 The question is now at which amounts of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 Erik's utility is maximized.
