To better understand the utility function we start by illustrating the theoretical relationship,
 which is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: util indifference curves 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The two-dimensional graph shows three variables:
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

,
 where each curved line shows a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The two axes in the graph,
 horizontal and vertical axis,
 measure consumption and leisure.
 Higher up along the vertical axis = more consumption.
 Further to the right along the horizontal axis = more leisure.
 The curved lines in the graph are called indifference curves.
 Along one and the same indifference curve,
 utility 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the same for different combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This theory means that Erik is indifferent to exactly which combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 it becomes,
 as long as we remain on the same line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Erik can accept less leisure as long as he can compensate with greater consumption,
 up to the left in the graph,
 and less consumption if he can compensate with more leisure.
 The lines further away from the origin represent combinations of consumption and leisure that together result in greater utility.
 Erik's consumption and leisure are also limited by Erik's budget,
 which is determined partly by how much he chooses to work and partly by his wage.
 This condition can be described with the following budget function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
C & =w\left(T-L\right)=wT-wL\label{eq:Eriks budgetekv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is wage,
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is total available waking time and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is still leisure time.
 The parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T-L\right)$
\end_inset

 describes how much leisure time Erik gives up and instead spends on work and thereby gets wages.
 The higher the wage,
 the less leisure needs to be sacrificed to consume the same amount of goods and services.
 The budget function can be used to draw a straight line in the graph with the indifference curves.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: indifferenskurvor budgetlinjer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the budget line and indifference curves.
 The two axes are consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(C\right)$
\end_inset

 and leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

