\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: indifferenskurvor budgetlinjer"

\end_inset

The budget line and different indifference curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

If Erik spent all available time on work,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $C=wT$
\end_inset

,
 a point along the vertical axis,
 consumption.
 This is the maximum amount of consumption that Erik can achieve,
 given the current wage.
 The line slopes negatively down toward the horizontal axis and the slope is determined by w.
 The budget function can therefore be written out as a straight diagonal line.
 Higher wage gives a steeper line and enables greater consumption higher up on the vertical axis.
 The further away from the origin that the budget line lies,
 the more Erik can consume.
 All combinations of consumption and leisure,
 C and L,
 within the budget line are possible to choose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that Erik wants to maximize his utility and this works in the way that it is described in the utility function,
 Erik will choose a combination of consumption and leisure where one of the indifference curves just touches the budget line.
 This is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Nyttomaximering indiff tangens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the budget line and three examples of indifference curves.
 As long as Erik has the same income,
 same budget line,
 and Erik's utility can be described as it is done in the utility function,
 same shape of the indifference curves,
 this is the only logical result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_utilitymaxbudget.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Nyttomaximering indiff tangens"

\end_inset

Maximum utility and budget
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why doesn't he choose a point within the budget line?
 At every point within the budget line,
 the gray area in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: indifferenskurvor budgetlinjer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 there is another point further away from the origin where Erik can get a greater amount of utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why doesn't he choose another point along the budget line?
 At every point on the budget line closer to the vertical or horizontal axis,
 Erik's utility will instead be defined by another indifference curve closer to the origin,
 which thus means a smaller amount of total utility.
 Let us now set up Erik's maximization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\max_{\text{w.r.t. }C,L} & C^{1/2}L^{1/2}\\
\text{under condition } & C\leq w\left(T-L\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

This we solve by setting up the Lagrange function:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lagrange!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(C,L\right):C^{1/2}L^{1/2}+\lambda\left(wT-wL-C\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}_{C}': & \frac{1}{2}C^{-1/2}L^{1/2}-\lambda\\
\mathcal{L}_{L}': & \frac{1}{2}C^{1/2}L^{-1/2}-\lambda w\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{L}'$
\end_inset

 we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{1}{w}\frac{1}{2}C^{1/2}L^{-1/2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 we put into the first-order condition we got from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}'$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2}C^{-1/2}L^{1/2} & =\frac{1}{w}\frac{1}{2}C^{1/2}L^{-1/2}\\
w & =\frac{\frac{1}{2}C^{1/2}L^{-1/2}}{\frac{1}{2}C^{-1/2}L^{1/2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

This equation shows how wage w relates to Erik's valuation of consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 at the point that maximizes Erik's utility.
 In the numerator we have the first derivative of the utility function with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u'_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 In the denominator we have the first derivative of the utility function with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 which we write as 
\begin_inset Formula $u'_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore rewrite this equation to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w=\frac{u'_{L}}{u'_{C}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This means exactly what we saw in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Nyttomaximering indiff tangens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 where the utility-maximizing point on the budget line is the one where one of the curved indifference curves touches the budget line.
 At this point,
 the slope of the budget line which is determined by w,
 is the same as the slope of the indifference curve that touches the budget line,
 which is determined by the form of the utility function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Maximum possible tax level
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Den-optimala-skattenivån"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Laffer curve
\end_layout

\end_inset

A large amount of social science deals with taxes and how they affect people's lives.
 A well-known example is the so-called Laffer curve,
 named after the American economist Arthur Laffer.
 Corresponding theories within social science can be traced back to at least the 1400s.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The mathematics in this section is borrowed and inspired by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lundbergLafferCurveHigh2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by imagining that we have a society without taxes.
 People work and produce goods and services that are bought and sold.
 The total income in society we call 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 whose value is not decisive for the example.
 Now the government wants to introduce a tax that shall be set as a percentage rate on all incomes and is called 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 can be a value between 0 and 1,
 between 0 and 100%.
 The state's total tax revenue,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

,
 can then be calculated to:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i=ty\label{eq: skatteintäkter 1a kr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all incomes in society sum to 1,000 USD and the tax is 5%,
 the state's tax revenue becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $i=ty=1000*0.05=50$
\end_inset

 USD.
 The incomes that are taxed,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 are also called the tax base.
 However,
 the tax also affects people's willingness to work and pay tax.
 The higher the tax becomes,
 the less people want to work,
 which in turn brings down the state's tax revenue.
 This mechanism we want to take into account in our equation over tax revenue.
 We therefore rewrite equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: skatteintäkter 1a kr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 so that we instead get the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i=ty\left(1-t\right)^{b}\label{eq: lafferkurvan-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicates how the people in society react to a tax increase,
 which is also called tax base elasticity.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is 0,
 people work exactly as much regardless of how high the tax is.
 A higher positive value of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 means that tax increases have a greater negative effect on people's willingness to work.
 A negative value 
\begin_inset Formula $b<0$
\end_inset

 means that people work more at higher tax.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: lafferkurvan-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is an example of the Laffer curve.
 From this equation we see that if the tax is set to 100% then 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and in that case the tax revenue becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

.
 So if the state wants to maximize its tax revenue,
 the tax must be set somewhere between 0 and 100%.
 To find the tax level that gives the greatest possible tax revenue we set this up as a maximization problem where we shall calculate the maximum of tax revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with respect to tax level 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{\text{w.r.t. }t}i=ty\left(1-t\right)^{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the maximization problem we take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i'_{t}=y\left(1-t\right)^{b}-by\left(1-t\right)^{b-1}t
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we use the chain rule for derivatives (table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We then set the first derivative equal to 0 and solve for t using logarithms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y\left(1-t\right)^{b}-by\left(1-t\right)^{b-1}t & =0\\
\ln y+b\ln\left(1-t\right)-\ln b-\ln y-\ln t-\left(b-1\right)\ln\left(1-t\right) & =0\nonumber \\
\ln\left(1-t\right)-\ln t-\ln b & =0\nonumber \\
\ln\left(\frac{1-t}{t}\right) & =\ln b\nonumber \\
\frac{1}{t}-1 & =b\nonumber \\
t^{*} & =\frac{1}{1+b}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

 in the last line gives us an expression for the greatest possible tax revenue,
 that is,
 the value for t that maximizes the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The greatest possible tax revenue depends on the tax base elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government in our fictitious society wants to introduce tax but is uncertain about the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 To get more clarity they compare with two other countries.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-Lafferkurvor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the Laffer curves for these two societies that represent two different types of society.
 In the figure,
 both lines go toward 0 tax revenue as the tax level approaches 100%,
 where we imagine that no one wants to pay tax.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_laffer.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Två-Lafferkurvor"

\end_inset

Two Laffer curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first country,
 the public sector functions inefficiently.
 People have low trust in the political system and the taxes that the state collects are not used for anything that people benefit from.
 The taxes are designed in a complicated and inefficient way.
 The tax base elasticity is in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $b=3$
\end_inset

.
 The greatest possible tax revenue is achieved in this case at a tax level of:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\left(b=3\right)=\frac{1}{1+3}=0.25
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that if the state wants to maximize tax collection it must set the tax at 25%.
 All other tax levels result in lower total tax revenue.
 In the graph this is illustrated with the solid line at "Inefficient system".
 The curve's highest point is at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 This means that already at a relatively low tax level,
 further increases in tax will cause total tax revenue to decrease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second society,
 the public sector functions relatively well.
 The inhabitants get back for their tax money a large amount of services of good quality and have high trust in the political system.
 The tax system is moreover efficiently designed and easy to follow for those who want to.
 The tax base elasticity is in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0.5$
\end_inset

 and the greatest possible tax revenue is reached at the tax level:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\left(b=0.5\right)=\frac{1}{1+0.5}=\frac{2}{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Expressed as a percentage,
 that corresponds to approximately 66.7%.
 In the graph this society is described with the dashed line,
 marked with "Efficient system".
 This line's highest point is at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.667$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the government can continue to raise taxes to relatively high percentages before a further increase causes tax revenue to start decreasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Consumption and saving
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Konsumtion-och-sparande"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
real interest
\end_layout

\end_inset

A popular topic within social science is people's relation to consumption and saving.
 If we think of consumption as the money people spend on goods and services today,
 we regard saving as consumption that is postponed to some time in the future.
 To the extent that we have the possibility to save something for the future,
 a common challenge is how much we should consume today and in the future respectively to become as satisfied as possible.
 Here follows a simple example of how we can use mathematics to describe this phenomenon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theoretical description here is a simplified version of what is called Fisher's model for intertemporal choice,
 or intertemporal consumption.
 The word "intertemporal" refers to the theory describing how people make decisions in different time periods that affect later time periods.
 Irving Fisher was one of the early 1900s' most famous economists and presented these ideas in his book Theory of Interest 1930,
 which can be read for free online.
 Let us assume that we divide the entire life into two time periods:
 1 (today) and 2 (the future).
 We shall now use the following notations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 = consumption during time period 1 and 2 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 = income during period 1 and 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 = saving during time period 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 = real interest rate plus 1.
 If the interest rate is 5%,
 then r=1.05.
 Real interest rate is nominal interest rate adjusted for price changes,
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Deflatera-priser-och"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also assume for simplicity's sake that we consume all our income at the latest during time period 2.
 So if we consume our entire income during each respective time period we get 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=y_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 where the amount of consumption corresponds to the amount of income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we save a little during the first time period and consume the rest,
 we describe this as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=y_{1}-s_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In time period 2,
 the income will then be 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}+s_{1}*r$
\end_inset

,
 where we multiply saving by interest rate to describe the interest income we received on our savings from time period 1.
 We therefore have two budget constraints,
 one for each time period:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c_{1}+s_{1} & =y_{1}\\
c_{2} & =y_{2}+s_{1}*r\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=y_{1}-c_{1}$
\end_inset

 from the first line and substitute into the second:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c_{2} & =y_{2}+\left(y_{1}-c_{1}\right)r\\
c_{1}*r+c_{2} & =y_{1}*r+y_{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We can think of the interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 here as the price for consuming today,
 during time period 1.
 The interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is therefore multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 If we instead save for the future,
 the income today (time period 1) will have increased by the interest rate tomorrow (time period 2).
 The interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is therefore also multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now divide both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{r}=y_{1}+\frac{y_{2}}{r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This version of the budget can be described as the value of consumption and income in period 2,
 adjusted for the interest rate.
 That is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}/r$
\end_inset

 is the relative value of consumption in period 2,
 relative to consumption in period 1.
 Let us now also assume that increased consumption increases our utility.
 But we content ourselves with describing this only in abstract terms.
 Let us assume that there exists a mathematical function 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

,
 which in some form describes what utility we get during life from our consumption during both time periods:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Utility}=U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)\label{eq: fishers nyttofunktion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We imagine that our total utility function has the following properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)'_{c_{1}}>0 & ,\,U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)'_{c_{2}}>0\\
U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)''_{c_{1}c_{1}}<0 & ,\,U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)''_{c_{2}c_{2}}<0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first line describes how the first derivative is positive for both 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (more consumption,
 more utility).
 The second line describes how the second derivative is negative in both cases,
 which means that the more we consume,
 the less utility increases with additional consumption.
 The question is now how much we should consume during each respective time period.
 If the interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is high,
 it may be wise to save a little to thereby be able to consume even more in time period 2,
 and vice versa.
 This we formulate as a maximization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\max_{\text{w.r.t.}c_{1},c_{2}} & U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)\\
\text{under condition } & c_{2}=y_{2}+\left(y_{1}-c_{1}\right)r\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lagrange!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have a utility function that shall be maximized subject to a budget constraint.
 We set up the Lagrange function (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: optimera villkor, lagrange"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}:U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)+\lambda\left(y_{2}+\left(y_{1}-c_{1}\right)r-c_{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier.
 The first-order conditions we get by differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 and setting the results equal to 0:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{c_{1}}:U'_{c_{1}}+\lambda\left(-r\right) & =0\\
\mathcal{L}'_{c_{2}}:U'_{c_{2}}+\lambda\left(-1\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we solve for different definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 from both conditions.
 The first first-order condition gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{U'_{c_{1}}}{r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the second first-order condition we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=U'_{c_{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set the two definitions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 equal to each other and rewrite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{U_{c_{1}}'}{U_{c_{2}}'}=\frac{1}{r}\label{eq: fisher resultat 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression describes how the marginal utility of consumption in time period 1,
 divided by the marginal utility of consumption in time period 2 will be equal to 1 divided by the real interest rate.
 That is,
 if the interest rate rises we have greater utility from consumption in period 2.
 This is logical in the sense that the consumption we postpone becomes worth more.
 The result is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Konsumera-idag-eller"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The two straight lines describe two different interest rate levels:
 one line if the interest rate is "low" and one line if the interest rate is "high".
 Both these lines are drawn from the budget constraint:
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=y_{2}+\left(y_{1}-c_{1}\right)r$
\end_inset

.
 The line's slope is given by r,
 which is illustrated in the figure.
 The line's y-intercept is given by the incomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 as well as saving in period 1:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}-c_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The curved line,
 the indifference curve,
 describes our preferences for consumption today and tomorrow respectively and is given by the utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_intertemporal.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Konsumera-idag-eller"

\end_inset

Consume today or tomorrow
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lines in this figure can be compared with those in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Nyttomaximering indiff tangens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 There may be many straight lines depending on our budget.
 If our incomes increase,
 the straight lines' y-intercept moves up to the right in the graph,
 away from the origin.
 The curved line shows where the budget lines meet our preferences.
 The curved line touches the budget line since we use our entire budget and consume all our income during period 1 and 2.
 Now we shall develop the theory a little further by adding impatience.
 Say that our total utility function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: fishers nyttofunktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be divided into two separate functions,
 one for each time period:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Utility }=U\left(c_{1},c_{2}\right)=U\left(c_{1}\right)+\beta U\left(c_{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the same relation to consumption in both time periods.
 The function U therefore also has the same form in both periods,
 but different input values:
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 (Greek letter beta) describes how much we value future consumption,
 the consumption that takes place in time period 2.
 Or expressed differently,
 how impatient we are.
 High 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 = we are patient.
 Low 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 = we are impatient.
 Say now that the first derivative of function U for each respective variable only contains the variable that we differentiate with respect to:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U\left(c_{1}c_{2}\right) & '_{c_{1}}=U'_{c_{1}}\left(c_{1}\right)\\
U\left(c_{1}c_{2}\right)'_{c_{2}} & =\beta U'_{c_{2}}\left(c_{2}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case we may rewrite our result in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: fisher resultat 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{U'_{c_{1}}\left(c_{1}\right)}{\beta U_{c_{2}}'\left(c_{2}\right)} & =\frac{1}{r}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is almost the same thing as our first result.
 The difference now is that our valuation of consumption in period 1 and 2 respectively also depends on how highly we value future consumption,
 that is,
 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 A smaller value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 means that we are more impatient and value consumption today (period 1) higher than consumption in the future (period 2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example in this section illustrates how we can use maximization problems to reason about decisions that affect the outcome both today and later.
 Similar mathematics can be used to reason about all possible types of decisions that have more or less long-term effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A profit-maximizing company
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Optimering 1 ftg perf konk"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A company manufactures the two products 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and wants to maximize its profit.
 The amount of produced units of the two products we denote with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The selling prices for the two goods are controlled by the market,
 which the company cannot influence.
 The company can,
 however,
 choose how large an amount of the products should be produced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For product 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we have price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}=10$
\end_inset

 and for product 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{y}=20$
\end_inset

.
 The company's revenue can be described as a function of price multiplied by quantity.
 The function for total revenue we call 
\begin_inset Formula $TR$
\end_inset

 after total revenue:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Total revenue}=TR\left(x,y\right) & =p_{x}x+p_{y}y=10x+20y\label{eq: revenue ex 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: revenue ex 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
TR & =10x+20y
\end{align}

\end_inset

Different combinations of the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can result in equally large revenues.
 Say that the company wants the revenue to be equal to 2,000 USD.
 This can be achieved by producing 100 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 0 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 or producing 0 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 200 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Or 80 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 40 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 and so on.
 This we may describe in the following way:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=2,000-\frac{1}{2}x,\,\forall x,y\geq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the same way we set up this equation for other sums in total revenue and illustrate these as lines in a diagram.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: revenue graf 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

shows this for the following equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y & =2,000-0.5x\\
y & =1,600-0.5x\nonumber \\
y & =1,200-0.5x\nonumber \\
y & =800-0.5x\nonumber \\
y & =400-0.5x\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_revcombos.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: revenue graf 1"

\end_inset

Company revenue from product 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total production costs consist of fixed expenses of 10 USD and variable costs for manufacturing products 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
Y
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Total cost}=TC\left(x,y\right)=x^{2}+2y^{2}+10\label{eq: TC perf konkurrens}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $TC$
\end_inset

 is the name of the function.
 The company's profit is equal to revenue minus costs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $TR-TC$
\end_inset

,
 which we may write as a function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(x,y\right) & =TR-TC=10x+20y-\left(x^{2}+2y^{2}+10\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit is a function of the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 which can be described as the company wanting to maximize its profit by choosing the amount to produce of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{\text{\text{w.r.t\emph{.}} }x,y}V\left(x,y\right)=10x+20y-\left(x^{2}+2y^{2}+10\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem we solve by taking the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 We do this because we are looking for a maximum point where the first derivative is equal to 0 and the second derivative is negative.
 The first derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V'_{x} & =10-2x\label{eq:v_x}\\
V'_{y} & =20-4y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have two expressions that describe how 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 changes when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 respectively increase by one unit.
 We set the expressions in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v_x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 equal to 0,
 which gives us the first-order conditions,
 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 These values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are the solutions we are looking for,
 which we write as 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x^{*} & =10/2=5\\
y^{*} & =20/4=5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also see that the second derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is negative by differentiating the expressions in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v_x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 once more:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V''_{xx} & =-2\\
V''_{yy} & =-4\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
marginal!profit
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
marginal!effect
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to describe what we just did is marginal effect and marginal profit.
 The marginal effect refers here to how much V changes with small changes in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit is maximized when the marginal profit is equal to 0,
 that is,
 when the first derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}'=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate how much profit the company will make by substituting these values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=V\left(5,5\right)$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(5,5\right)= & 10*5+20*5-\left(5^{2}+2*5^{2}+10\right)=65
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
marginal!cost
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
Given the prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}=10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{y}=20$
\end_inset

 and current production costs,
 the company can maximize its profit by producing 5 units of product A and 5 units of product B,
 and then makes a profit of 65 USD.
 The company's total costs are given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: TC perf konkurrens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we take the first derivative with respect to x and y of this function we get the company's marginal cost,
 
\begin_inset Formula $MC$
\end_inset

,
 marginal cost:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MC_{x}=C'_{x} & =2x\\
MC_{y}=C'_{y} & =2y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit is optimized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(5,5\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the marginal costs are:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MC_{x}=C'_{x}\left(x^{*}\right) & =2*5=10\\
MC_{y}=C'_{y}\left(y^{*}\right) & =2*5=10\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the company produces the quantities 5 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 5 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 the marginal costs,
 at exactly this production quantity,
 are equal to 10 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 10 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The company thus maximizes its profit when the marginal cost is equal to the price for the products,
 given that the price is determined by the market:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{*}=MC\label{eq: p = mc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we imagine that perfect competition prevails,
 all companies have the same cost and revenue functions.
 All companies will in that case produce in this way,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{*}=MC$
\end_inset

.
 At the production quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=5$
\end_inset

,
 profit in the company is maximized.
 If the company produces more or less of product 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 than these amounts,
 the profit will be smaller.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Vinstmaximering"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows an illustration of this.
 For each given production quantity of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 the line in the diagram shows the relationship between profit and produced quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

