\begin_layout Section
Profit maximization with constraints
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Vinstmaximering-med-villkor"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose now that we have a profit-maximizing company,
 but this time we add a constraint in the form of the company's production.
 The company sells a good where the price,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 is determined by the market.
 The company's costs for production are given by the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
TC=10+q^{2}+wL
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the amount of production that the company delivers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the wage for the company's employees and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 the number of full-time employees,
 or full-time positions.
 The wages,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

,
 are also determined by the outside world,
 in this case the labor market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company can,
 however,
 choose how much it should produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 and how many full-time positions it should have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The company's production is determined by the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q\left(L\right)=2L
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
production function
\end_layout

\end_inset

This is a simplified example of what in economics is called a production function.
 The production function describes the relationship between the company's inputs and its production,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
 the company's only input is labor,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The demand for the company's products is given by the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
q & =100-4p
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this equation we solve for an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=25-\frac{q}{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total revenue is given by the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
TR & =pq=\left(25-\frac{q}{4}\right)q=25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company's profit is now given by the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V & =TR-TC=25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}-\left(10+q^{2}+wL\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wage on the labor market for the company's employees is 
\begin_inset Formula $w=2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V=25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}-\left(10+q^{2}+2L\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must also take into account the constraint,
 which is a result of the company's production conditions (the production function):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2L\geq q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 must be less than or equal to 5 times the number of full-time positions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This is important because the company maximizes its profit,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 by choosing production quantity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

,
 and number of full-time employees,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 All this we set up as a maximization problem:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{\text{w.r.t. }q,L}V=25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}-\left(10+q^{2}+2L\right),\text{ s.t. }2L\geq q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lagrange!function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lagrange!multiplier
\end_layout

\end_inset

To solve this we set up the Lagrange function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(q,L\right)=25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}-10-q^{2}-2L+\lambda\left(2L-q\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier.
 We differentiate with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

,
 which leads us to the first-order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}'_{q} & =25-\frac{2}{4}q-2q-\lambda\\
\mathcal{L}'_{L} & =-2+\lambda2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We put 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}'_{L}=0$
\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{*}=\frac{2}{2}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We put 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{*}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}'_{q}$
\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
25-\frac{2}{4}q-2q-1 & =0\\
24 & =q\left(2+\frac{1}{2}\right)\nonumber \\
q & =\frac{24}{5/2}\nonumber \\
q^{*} & =48/5=9.6\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the production function we see that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
q^{*} & =2L\\
9,6 & =2L\nonumber \\
L^{*} & =4.8\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This results in the following profit:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(q^{*},L^{*}\right) & =25q-\frac{q^{2}}{4}-\left(10+q^{2}+2L\right)=124.4
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Monopoly
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Monopol"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
monopoly
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us take another example with a company that sells goods or services on a market,
 but this time we assume that the company has a monopoly on the market.
 Monopoly means that the company is the sole seller and thereby has power to influence both price and quantity.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Optimering 1 ftg perf konk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 above we went through an example where companies in competition had to accept the price that the market determines for its goods or services.
 The monopoly seller can instead choose to produce a smaller quantity at a higher price and thereby make greater profit.
 Let us illustrate with an example.
 A company produces the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 of a good,
 which entails total costs corresponding to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
TC=10+Q^{2}\label{eq: monopol kostnadsfunktion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $TC$
\end_inset

 is abbreviation for Total Cost.
 The company's customers demand goods in relation to price 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 in a way that we can describe with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Demand: }Q & =20-\frac{P}{5}\label{eq: monopol efterfrågekurvan}\\
\Rightarrow P & =100-2Q\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total revenue is given by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $TR$
\end_inset

 which consists of price multiplied by the quantity of production 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
TR & =PQ=\left(100-2Q\right)Q=100Q-2Q^{2}\label{eq: TR monopol}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The monopolist wants to maximize its profit 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 which is a result of revenue minus costs:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\max_{Q,P}V & =TR-TC\label{eq: monopol vinst}\\
 & =PQ-TC\nonumber \\
 & =Q\left(100-2Q\right)-\left(10+Q^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =100Q-2Q^{2}-10-Q^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =100Q-3Q^{2}-10\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the first-order condition we differentiate the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect to the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V'_{Q}=100-6Q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set this expression equal to 0 and solve for the profit-maximizing production quantity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
100-6Q & =0\\
Q & =\frac{100}{6}\nonumber \\
Q^{*} & =16+\frac{2}{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The monopoly company maximizes its profit at 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}=16+\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

,
 whereupon the selling price is given by customers' demand,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: monopol efterfrågekurvan"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P^{*}\left(Q^{*}\right) & =100-2Q^{*}=100-2*\left(16+\frac{2}{3}\right)=66+\frac{2}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company's total profit is given by the function for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: monopol vinst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(Q^{*}\right) & =100Q-3Q^{2}-10\\
 & =100\left(16+\frac{2}{3}\right)-3\left(16+\frac{2}{3}\right)^{2}-10\nonumber \\
 & =823+\frac{1}{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a hypothetical market with so-called perfect competition,
 the equilibrium price on the market will approach the marginal cost.
 Perfect competition is a hypothetical state that rarely or never occurs in reality.
 Regardless,
 we may describe this price level in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{*}=MC
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

