\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Prissättning-för-monopolist"

\end_inset

Monopoly
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This we saw in the example in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Optimering 1 ftg perf konk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 As seen in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: TR monopol"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 total revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $TR$
\end_inset

 is a function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the first derivative of this function we get the function for the monopoly company's marginal revenue,
 
\begin_inset Formula $MR$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
MR=TR'_{Q}=100-4Q\label{eq: monopol marginal revenue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the company produces the profit-maximizing quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}=16+2/3$
\end_inset

 this gives marginal revenue:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MR\left(Q^{*}\right) & =100-4Q=100-4\left(16+2/3\right)=33+\frac{1}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function for total costs,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: monopol kostnadsfunktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 is also a function of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the first derivative of this we get the function for the company's marginal costs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $MC$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
MC=TC'_{Q}=2Q
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which at the profit-maximizing production quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}=16+2/3$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MC\left(Q^{*}\right) & =2Q=2\left(16+2/3\right)=33+\frac{1}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same result as we found for 
\begin_inset Formula $MR\left(Q^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A profit-maximizing monopoly company produces quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $MR=MC$
\end_inset

,
 while profit-maximizing companies in perfect competition produce a quantity so that 
\begin_inset Formula $MC=P^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Prissättning-för-monopolist"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the monopoly company's pricing,
 where the equilibrium quantity is determined by the point where the curves for 
\begin_inset Formula $MR$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $MC$
\end_inset

 meet.
 The purpose of this exercise is primarily to see how the behavior of companies in competition can differ from companies with monopoly.
 The reasoning is simplifications of reality and builds on specific assumptions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Monopsony
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Monopsoni"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
monopsony
\end_layout

\end_inset

Monopsony describes a situation when instead of a single seller (monopoly) we have a single buyer,
 which in turn means that the buyer has power to influence the conditions for their purchases,
 both quantity and price.
 In reality,
 elements of monopsony occur in,
 for example,
 geographically delimited areas and in markets that are subject to special laws.
 Monopsony can also occur in the labor market,
 for example if there is only one or a few companies that employ a certain type of professional group.
 Let us illustrate with an example.
 Assume that a company buys quantity q of a good at price p.
 The supply for the good on the market is given by the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Supply: }q & =2p_{\text{purchases}}\label{eq: monopsoni utbud}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by solving for a definition of the purchase price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{purchases}}=\frac{q}{2}\label{eq: p inköp monopsoni}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The company in turn uses the purchased good to produce its own goods.
 Total manufacturing costs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $tc$
\end_inset

,
 are given by price multiplied by quantity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
tc=p_{\text{purchases}}q\label{eq: tc monopsoni}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We substitute the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{inköp}}$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p inköp monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $tc$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
tc & =p_{\text{purchases}}q=\left(\frac{q}{2}\right)q=\frac{q^{2}}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $tc$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 gives us the marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $mc$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mc=tc'_{q}=q\label{eq: mc monopsoni}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The company produces goods,
 whose demand is determined by the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Demand: }q & =10-p_{\text{sales}}\label{eq: D monopsoni egna prod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We simplify a little and use the designation 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 also for this good.
 We may think of this example as the company purchasing an input-good to its own production.
 From this function for demand we solve for the company's selling price for its own goods:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{sales}}=10-q\label{eq: p sälj monopsoni}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company's total revenue,
 
\begin_inset Formula $tr$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
tr & =p_{\text{sales}}q
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{sales}}$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p sälj monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and substitute into the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $tr$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
tr & =\left(10-q\right)q=10q-q^{2}\label{eq: tr monopsoni}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
marginal!revenue
\end_layout

\end_inset

From this expression for total revenue we take the first derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

,
 which gives us marginal revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $mr$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mr=tr'_{q}=10-2q\label{eq: mr monopsoni}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company's profit 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is total revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $tr$
\end_inset

 minus total cost 
\begin_inset Formula $tc$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
v & =tr-tc
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $tc$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $tr$
\end_inset

 with the definitions from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: tc monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: tr monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
v\left(q\right) & =\left(10q-q^{2}\right)-\frac{q^{2}}{2}=10q-\frac{3}{2}q^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function for the company's profit 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 is determined by what quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 the company chooses to purchase and produce.
 Based on this we formulate the company's maximization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{q}v\left(q\right)=10q-\frac{3}{2}q^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the maximization problem we take the first derivative of the profit function 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v'_{q}=10-3q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set this expression equal to 0 to get the first-order condition:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v'_{q}:\,10-3q=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we may solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

,
 the quantity that maximizes the company's profit:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q^{*}=\frac{10}{3}\approx3,33
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before,
 we mark this quantity with an asterisk,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The purchase price for the good that the company is the sole buyer of is given by the supply function,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: monopsoni utbud"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p_{\text{purchases}}\left(q^{*}\right) & =\frac{q^{*}}{2}=\frac{10/3}{2}=\frac{5}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The selling price for the company's own production is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p sälj monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p_{\text{sales}}\left(q^{*}\right) & =10-q^{*}=10-\frac{10}{3}=\frac{20}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company's marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $mc$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

 is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: mc monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
mc\left(q^{*}\right) & =q^{*}=\frac{10}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and the company's marginal revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $mr$
\end_inset

 is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: mr monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
mr\left(q^{*}\right) & =10-2q^{*}=10-2*\left(\frac{10}{3}\right)=\frac{10}{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The company will maximize its profit by choosing such a quantity so that the company's marginal revenue is equal to its marginal costs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $mr=mc$
\end_inset

.
 When we went through examples with companies in markets with perfect competition we could instead see that the company's production occurs where the marginal costs are equal to the market price 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{*}=MC$
\end_inset

,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p = mc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates profit maximization for monopsony according to the model we have now gone through.
 The lines show the company's marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $mc$
\end_inset

,
 marginal revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $mr$
\end_inset

,
 demand for the company's products from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: D monopsoni egna prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as well as supply of the purchased good,
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p inköp monopsoni"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

