\begin_layout Section
If we do not optimize
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we have used different examples to illustrate how people maximize their utility or profit.
 The world is also full of examples that cannot easily be described as utility-maximizing.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ska vi börja röka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through an example with two friends,
 Erik and Maria who make decisions about whether they should start smoking,
 based on what their friend does.
 The decisions were summarized in the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
y=x^{2}\\
x=y^{2}
\end{cases}\label{eq: rökning icke-optimering}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 describe Erik's and Maria's smoking.
 The system has two solutions:
 both smoke or no one smokes.
 We call smoking the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 means no one smokes and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1$
\end_inset

 that they smoke.
 Now we let Erik and Maria have 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as input variable in their utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Expressed as an optimization problem we may describe it as wanting to optimize utility 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by choosing a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{r}U\left(r\right),\forall r\geq0\label{eq: nyttomax rökning}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 must be greater than or equal to 0 since the amount of smoking cannot be negative.
 In our system of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rökning icke-optimering"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 smoking 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is not included,
 other than indirectly.
 The primary decision factor is the other person's smoking,
 which is what the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 describe.
 This means that in the system of equations we  have maximized utility (which is not written out) both in the situation when no one smokes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r=0\right)$
\end_inset

 and when both smoke 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r=1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all possible alternatives of a phenomenon can result in utility maximization,
 it is not particularly helpful to describe this as a utility maximization problem for this utility (smoking,
 the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

) as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: nyttomax rökning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The example we have gone through here concerns whether the persons can be described as completely rational,
 which is a concept with special meaning within social science and which is discussed among other things within the part of economics called microeconomics.
 Here we content ourselves with noting that such examples exist and among other things illustrate that it can be difficult to draw conclusions regarding all types of behaviors we observe in the world.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimization problems can be used for many different social science questions.
 For example,
 to find the optimal amount of cake a person should eat or what is the optimal balance between work and leisure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can use optimization problems both to describe phenomena that we often think of as economic,
 for example a company's decision to produce or not produce different goods or services.
 We can also use this method for phenomena that we think of as more social,
 for example how people optimize their utility or happiness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even if we may describe an optimization problem where a company should maximize its profit or an individual should maximize their utility,
 it is not given what the result will be.
 Seemingly simple problems can have several solutions that are not always easy to interpret.
\end_layout

