\begin_layout Chapter
Integration
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Integraler"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integration
\end_layout

\end_inset

This chapter introduces integration,
 also called integrating.
 Integration can be described as finding a function's "anti-derivative".
 Integrals can among other things be used to calculate the area between two lines in a graph,
 or the volume and mass of an object.
 This we can in turn use for describing theories and calculate probability,
 which is a central aspect of all empirical analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The primitive function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral
\end_layout

\end_inset

Suppose we have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

 which is the derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 With integration we seek a function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 whose derivative gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The function we then get through integration is called integral.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the integral to function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 and function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the integrand.
 Consider the following function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=x^{a}+b\label{eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 Taking the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dx}F\left(x\right)=f'_{x}\left(x\right)=ax^{a-1}\label{eq: derivatan av x^a+b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!indefinite
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!primitive
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
primitive function
\end_layout

\end_inset

Function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the primitive function to 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Another expression for primitive function is indefinite integral,
 which is described more thoroughly below.
 The primitive function is the function whose derivative gives us the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 If we are to calculate the integral of function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we instead seek a primitive function to function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of the primitive function we in that case seek should result in function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integration is often described with two symbols:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset

 and the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the variable that the integration should be performed with respect to.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 can be read as "with respect to variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

".
 The description of the integral of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 can be written in different ways:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int\left(f\left(x\right)\right)dx & =\int f\left(x\right)dx=\int dxf\left(x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical meaning in these three ways of writing is the same.
 The three expressions can all be read as "the integral of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 with respect to variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

".
 We may also write out the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 to clarify which expression we seek an integral for.
 Taking the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and insert between the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int f\left(x\right)dx=\int\left(x^{a}+b\right)dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we have two terms that should be integrated:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 When we differentiate we subtract 1 from the exponent.
 When we integrate we instead add 1.
 For the first term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

,
 we integrate by adding 1 to the exponent:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a+1}$
\end_inset

.
 We also divide the same term by the new exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\left(x^{a}\right)dx=\frac{x^{a+1}}{a+1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That we divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $a+1$
\end_inset

 means that when differentiating the integral we will get back 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

 as result.
 Let us check this by taking the derivative of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x^{a+1}}{a+1}$
\end_inset

 with respect to x:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{x^{a+1}}{a+1}\right)'_{x}=\frac{\left(a+1\right)x^{a+1-1}}{a+1}=x^{a}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponent moves down from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in front of the expression.
 Since the expression is divided by the same exponent we cancel these.
 The next term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is the constant b.
 When we integrate we add 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to terms that consist only of constants.
 The next term in our integral therefore becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $bx$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\left(b\right)dx=bx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Last in the integral we add another constant that we call 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 This because when differentiating we cancel the terms where the current variable is not included.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 thus represents an arbitrary number,
 for example all conceivable constants that could be included in a primitive function to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We now get the following primitive function that we call 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right) & =\int\left(f\left(x\right)\right)dx=\int\left(x^{a}+b\right)dx=\frac{x^{a+1}}{a+1}+bx+C\label{eq: integral exempel 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a primitive function,
 the integral,
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We check the integral by differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right)'_{x} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left[\frac{x^{a+1}}{a+1}+bx+C\right]=\frac{a+1}{a+1}x^{a}+b=x^{a}+b
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This results in the same expression as function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex1 = x^a + b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which indicates that our integral was correct.
 With the same method we can also integrate longer equations with several terms.
 As long as each term,
 separated by addition and subtraction,
 has similar form as above we can use the same method for each term separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(x\right)=x^{3}+2x^{2}+4x\label{eq: integration ex h och H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A primitive function for 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H\left(x\right) & =\int h\left(x\right)dx\\
 & =\int\left(x^{3}+2x^{2}+4x\right)dx\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{4}}{4}+\frac{2x^{3}}{3}+\frac{4x^{2}}{2}+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 becomes function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integration ex h och H"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H'_{x}\left(x\right)=x^{3}+2x^{2}+4x=h\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The meaning of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{C}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition there are infinitely many primitive functions to a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To see this we take the following function as an example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=2x\label{eq:   f=2x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A primitive function to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can look like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{1}\left(x\right)=x^{2}\label{eq: prim f ex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Or like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{2}\left(x\right)=x^{2}+5\label{eq: prim f exempel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Or like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{3}\left(x\right)=x^{2}+123+a^{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant coefficient (or a variable) that we do not differentiate over.
 If we differentiate the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the result in all three cases becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2x$
\end_inset

.
 To handle this when we calculate integrals we always assume that a constant that we call 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is included in all primitive functions.
 Let us now take the following function as an example:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(x\right)=x^{3}+4
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral of this function,
 which we call 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G\left(x\right) & =\int g\left(x\right)dx=\int\left[x^{3}+4\right]dx=\frac{x^{4}}{4}+4x+C
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with respect to x again gives function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G'_{x}=x^{3}+4
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

