 a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is again included.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 can be any value the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 can assume infinitely many different definitions,
 depending on the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Integral konstant C olika värden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates some examples of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and the meaning of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 In the graph four lines are drawn with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=G\left(x\right)=\frac{x^{4}}{4}+4x+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The four lines have different values for the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C:-1,0,1$
\end_inset

 and 2 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Primitive function with conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Primitive functions can also be combined with conditions.
 Say for example that we have the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\left(x\right)=3x+5
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and seek an expression for its primitive function given the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(0\right)=2$
\end_inset

,
 which means that the primitive function 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 equals 2 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to say the same thing is that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 passes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The primitive function to 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T\left(x\right)=\frac{3x^{2}}{2}+5x+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 can be any number but in this case there is only one version of function 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 that fulfills the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(0\right)=2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
T\left(x\right)_{1} & =\frac{3x^{2}}{2}+5x+2
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this function,
 which fulfills the condition,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 fulfills the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(0\right)=2$
\end_inset

 we can see by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}\left(x=0\right):$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
T\left(0\right)_{1} & =\frac{3\left(0\right)^{2}}{2}+5\left(0\right)+2=2
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Primitive function for an exponent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: derivata exponential e log"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through how we may differentiate exponential functions such as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[e^{x}\right]'_{x} & =e^{x},\; & \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left[e^{ax}\right]=ae^{ax}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the included variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is Euler's number and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 We see among other things that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

 has derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}\left(x\right)=e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind we shall now go through how we can find a primitive function when we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as exponent in a power expression.
 Let us start with the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=e^{x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now derive a primitive function for this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int f\left(x\right)dx & =F\left(x\right)=e^{x}+C
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 If we take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F'_{x}\left(x\right)=e^{x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same thing as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us also take the integral of a function of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=e^{ax}$
\end_inset

.
 The integral to this function we call 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G\left(x\right) & =\int g\left(x\right)dx=\int e^{ax}dx=\frac{e^{ax}}{a}+C
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as in the examples in the previous section we add the denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to the term 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ax}$
\end_inset

 so that the derivative of the primitive function 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us differentiate the function 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G'_{x}=a*\frac{e^{ax}}{a}=e^{ax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same thing as 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: derivata exponential e log"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we also went through the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{x}$
\end_inset

 where a is an arbitrary constant and x is variable:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[a^{x}\right]'_{x}=a^{x}\ln a
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Euler's number
\end_layout

\end_inset

If the base 
\begin_inset Formula $a=e$
\end_inset

 (Euler's number) and we have function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=a^{x}$
\end_inset

,
 the derivative is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(x\right)'_{x}=a^{x}\ln a=a^{x}=e^{x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now derive a primitive function for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=a^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the same logic as above we now add a denominator and a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and then get the following primitive function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H\left(x\right) & =\int h\left(x\right)dx=\int\left(a^{x}\right)dx=\frac{a^{x}}{\ln a}+C
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us illustrate these rules with two examples where we write out numbers instead of letters.
 Suppose we have the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q\left(x\right)=e^{12x}+5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we seek a primitive function for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which we  call 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\left(x\right)=\frac{e^{12x}}{12}+5x+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a general term this is called that we have determined all primitive functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us take another example with several terms.
 This time we seek a primitive function for the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v\left(x\right)=3^{x}+e^{2x}+4+\frac{x^{3}}{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we call 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(x\right) & =\int v\left(x\right)dx\\
 & =\int\left[3^{x}+e^{2x}+4+\frac{x^{3}}{2}\right]dx\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{3^{x}}{\ln\left(3\right)}+\frac{e^{2x}}{2}+4x+\frac{x^{4}}{8}+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note how we in this example on the third line take the opportunity to use several different rules that we have introduced earlier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Calculate area with integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
area
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!area
\end_layout

\end_inset

Integrals can among other things be used to calculate an area,
 for example the area between the line for a function and the horizontal x-axis,
 or the area between the lines in a graph.
 Let us start with how we calculate the area in a graph without integral for the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=4,\forall0\leq x\leq4\label{eq: y=4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 equals 4 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 4.
 The line for this function is horizontal.
 The area between this line and the x-axis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{width }\times\text{ height} & =\text{area}\label{eq: simpel area}\\
4\times4 & =16\text{ area units}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_y4.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Arean under y=4"

\end_inset

The area under the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=4,\forall0\leq x\leq4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_yequalx.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: arean för y=x"

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

 and the area under the line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\emph on
area units
\emph default
,
 a.u.,
 is a general concept that we use since we have not specified any unit of measurement for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Area units can for example be square centimeters or square meters.
 The function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: y=4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and the area under the line is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Arean under y=4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we instead have the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(x\right)=x,\forall0\leq x\leq5\label{eq: y=x integral area}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

this is,
 in a graph,
 a straight line between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(5,5\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The area for the surface under the line down to the x-axis is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{Area} & =\frac{\text{height}\times\text{width}}{2}=\frac{5\times5}{2}=12.5\text{ a.u.}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function and the area are illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: arean för y=x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let us now calculate the area for these two examples with the help of integrals.
 We start with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=4$
\end_inset

.
 The integral for function f:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=4x+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary constant.
 To calculate the area we derive the primitive function over the interval 0 to 4.
 We calculate the area by taking the integral for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 over the values 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 0 to 4.
 This integral is written 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{a}^{b}f\left(x\right)dx & =\left[F\left(x\right)\right]_{a}^{b}=F\left(b\right)-F\left(a\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We calculate the integral from the smaller to the larger value.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[F\left(x\right)\right]_{a}^{b}$
\end_inset

 means that we calculate the primitive function for a and b,
 which is then set up as 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 minus 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We set up the equation with the integral with the higher value as input value,
 minus the integral with the lower value.
 In this case we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{0}^{4}f\left(x\right)dx & =F\left(4\right)-F\left(0\right)\\
 & =\left(4\left(4\right)+C\right)-\left(4\left(0\right)+C\right)\nonumber \\
 & =16\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same result as we found in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: simpel area"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is written out in both equations but since we get a positive and a negative 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 both can be canceled.
 Let us now take the integral to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=h\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H\left(x\right) & =\int h\left(x\right)dx=\int\left[x\right]dx=\frac{x^{2}}{2}+C
\end{align}

\end_inset

To calculate the area:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{a}^{b}h\left(x\right)dx=H\left(b\right)-H\left(a\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have 
\begin_inset Formula $b=5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{0}^{5}h\left(x\right)dx & =\int_{0}^{5}\left[x\right]dx\\
 & =H\left(5\right)-H\left(0\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{\left(5\right)^{2}}{2}+C\right)-\left(\frac{\left(0\right)^{2}}{2}+C\right)\nonumber \\
 & =12.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!definite
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!indefinite
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is the same result as the answer we got above.
 As long as the integral lacks integration limits,
 that is an interval for x,
 this is called an indefinite integral.
 When we specify the interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 as in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{5}$
\end_inset

,
 this is called a definite integral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=g\left(x\right)=x^{2}\label{eq: x^2  integral ex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Its integral is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G\left(x\right) & =\int\left(x^{2}\right)dx=\frac{x^{3}}{3}+C
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_area_x2.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:y=x2 area"

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We shall now calculate the area for 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for the values 
\begin_inset Formula $-3\leq x\leq6$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\left(x\right)=\int_{-3}^{6}g\left(x\right)dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our integral has the boundary values 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=6$
\end_inset

.
 Since the integral has a specified interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 this means that this is a definite integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G\left(x\right) & =\int_{-3}^{6}g\left(x\right)dx=\left[G\left(x\right)\right]_{-3}^{6}=G\left(6\right)-G\left(-3\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $G\left(6\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(-3\right)$
\end_inset

 is the primitive functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=6$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-3$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{-3}^{6}g\left(x\right)dx & =G\left(6\right)-G\left(-3\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{3}\left(6\right)^{3}+C\right)-\left(\frac{1}{3}\left(-3\right)^{3}+C\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{216}{3}+C-\frac{\left(-27\right)}{3}-C\nonumber \\
 & =63\text{ a.u.}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In row 3 we set the function 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x=6\right)$
\end_inset

 as positive term and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x=-3\right)$
\end_inset

 as negative term.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:y=x2 area"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the line to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the area between the horizontal x-axis and the function's line for
\begin_inset Formula $-3\leq x\leq6$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The area under the x-axis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have only calculated the area for lines above the x-axis.
 But as we have seen in previous examples functions can also have negative y-values,
 whereupon the lines pass below the x-axis.
 The form for definite integrals that we used above is defined in such a way that it calculates the area between a line and the horizontal x-axis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{b}^{a}f\left(x\right)dx=F\left(b\right)-F\left(a\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The area between the x-axis and a line above the x-axis becomes a positive value.
 The area between the x-axis and a line below the x-axis becomes a negative value.
 If we calculate the area based on a function that both passes above and below the x-axis we get the net area.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{5}\left[-2+x\right]dx & =F\left(5\right)-F\left(0\right)\\
 & =\left(-2\left(5\right)+\frac{\left(5\right)^{2}}{2}\right)-\left(-2\left(0\right)+\frac{\left(0\right)^{2}}{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(-10+12.5\right)\\
 & =2.5
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function and the two surfaces are illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Area-över-och under x"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where the first area 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the surface below the x-axis,
 which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
 The second area 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the surface above the x-axis,
 which equals 4.5.
 The net result is thus the area for the part that is above 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 minus the surface that is below 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_negative1.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Area-över-och under x"

\end_inset

Area above and under the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we instead want to calculate all surface between the function's line and the x-axis,
 regardless of whether the line is above or below the x-axis,
 and sum this area to one value.
 In that case we divide the integral and put a minus sign for the part that is below the x-axis.
 We divide the integral at the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 where the line intersects the x-axis,
 which is where 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 We start by calculating the x-value we seek:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-2+x & =0\\
x^{*} & =2\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we divide the integral into two parts and put a minus sign in front of the part that is below the x-axis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Total area:}-\int_{0}^{2}f\left(x\right)dx+\int_{2}^{5}f\left(x\right)dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we calculate the two integrals and sum:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\int_{0}^{2}f\left(x\right)dx+\int_{2}^{5}f\left(x\right)dx & =-\left[-2x+\frac{x^{2}}{2}\right]_{0}^{2}+\left[-2x+\frac{x^{2}}{2}\right]_{2}^{5}\\
 & =-\left[-4+2\right]+\left[\left(-10+12,5\right)-\left(-4+2\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & =6,5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\size default
The total area between the line and the x-axis is 6.5 area units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The area between two lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!continuous
\end_layout

\end_inset

Integrals can also be used to calculate the area between two curves.
 Suppose we have the following two continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g\left(x\right)= & -x+x^{3}-x^{2}+10\label{eq: g och x, arean mellan 2 funk}\\
h\left(x\right)= & 2+2x-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Over an interval of x-values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)\geq h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded for this interval upward by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and downward by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and can be calculated as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\int_{a}^{b}\left[g\left(x\right)-h\left(x\right)\right]dx\label{eq: arean mellan 2 f}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lines and the area are illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Arean-mellan-två funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We shall now calculate the area between these for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x\leq3$
\end_inset

 and therefore set up equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: arean mellan 2 f"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the functions from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: g och x, arean mellan 2 funk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and calculate the integral:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{0}^{3}g\left(x\right)-h\left(x\right)dx & =\int_{0}^{3}\left[-x+x^{3}-x^{2}+10-\left(2+2x-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}\right)\right]dx\\
 & =\int_{0}^{3}\left[x^{3}-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}-3x+8\right]dx\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\frac{x^{4}}{4}-\frac{x^{3}}{6}-\frac{3x^{2}}{2}+8x\right]_{0}^{3}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{3^{4}}{4}-\frac{3^{3}}{6}-\frac{3\left(3\right)^{2}}{2}+8\left(3\right)\right)-\left(\frac{0^{4}}{4}-\frac{0^{3}}{6}-\frac{3*0^{2}}{2}+8*0\right)\nonumber \\
 & =20.25+4.5-13.5+24\nonumber \\
 & =44.25\text{ a.u.}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

