\begin_layout Standard
The reason for the absolute value is that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 holds for all real numbers except 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln x$
\end_inset

 is only defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

,
 see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Logaritmer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The fourth calculation rule describes the integral:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\left(\frac{1}{ax+b}\right)dx=\frac{1}{a}\ln\left|ax+b\right|+C\label{eq: integral 1/(ax+b)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
chain rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 This we see from the chain rule for derivative of composite functions,
 which gives that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\circ g\right)'_{x}=g'\left(f'\circ g\right)$
\end_inset

,
 see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Deriveringsregler för 2 funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let us consider the natural logarithm as function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+b$
\end_inset

 as function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Now we shall calculate the derivative of the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{a}\ln\left(ax+b\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We rewrite this in the following way:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{1}{a}\ln\left(ax+b\right)\right)'_{x} & =\frac{1}{a}\left(f\circ g\right)'_{x}\\
 & =\frac{1}{a}g'_{x}\left(f'_{x}\circ g\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{a}\left(ax+b\right)'_{x}\left(\ln\left(ax+b\right)\right)'_{x}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{a}\left(a\right)\left(\frac{1}{ax+b}\right)+0\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{ax+b}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

