\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Räkneregler-integraler 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes some common rules for integrals.
 The first rule describes how we can factor out the constant a from the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not affected by the integration.
 We illustrate with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=4x^{2}+16x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=\frac{4x^{3}}{3}+8x^{2}+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 so we get 
\begin_inset Formula $4\left(x^{2}+4x\right)$
\end_inset

 and call the content in the parentheses 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the integral of this we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\left(x\right)=\frac{x^{3}}{3}+2x^{2}+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From here we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $4G\left(x\right)=F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which is what the first calculation rule in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Räkneregler-integraler 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes.
 The other two integration rules can also be illustrated with function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=4x^{2}+16x$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we divide this function into the two functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(x\right)=4x^{2},\quad k\left(x\right)=16x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Their respective integrals are then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H\left(x\right)=\frac{4x^{3}}{3}+C,\quad K\left(x\right)=8x^{2}+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $H+K=F$
\end_inset

.
 If we sum the two constants 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 we get a new arbitrary constant,
 which has the same meaning for the integrals and is not affected by the integration.
 This is what the second calculation rule in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Räkneregler-integraler 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third calculation rule is a variant of the second calculation rule.
 In a similar way as above we check that the following holds::
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\left(h-k\right)dx=\int\left(4x^{2}-16x\right)dx=\frac{4x^{3}}{3}-8x^{2}+C=H-K
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which confirms the third rule.
 For definite integrals we may also describe some additional rules.
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function over an interval where the values 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\,b,\,c$
\end_inset

 are included the following holds for definite integrals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{a}^{b}f\left(x\right)dx= & -\int_{b}^{a}f\left(x\right)dx\label{eq:integral delad}\\
\int_{a}^{a}f\left(x\right)dx= & 0\nonumber \\
\int_{a}^{c}f\left(x\right)dx= & \int_{a}^{b}f\left(x\right)dx+\int_{b}^{c}f\left(x\right)dx\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first of these rules says that if we take the integral over an interval from 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 it corresponds to the same value but negative if we take the integral from 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 instead.
 If we take the following function as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=f\left(x\right)=x^{3}+4
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We calculate its integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{1}^{2}f\left(x\right)dx & =\left[\frac{x^{4}}{4}+4x\right]_{1}^{2}=\left(4+8\right)-\left(\frac{1}{4}+4\right)=7+\frac{3}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\int_{2}^{1}f\left(x\right)dx & =-\left[\frac{x^{4}}{4}+4x\right]_{2}^{1}\\
 & =-\left(\left(\frac{1}{4}+4\right)-\left(4+8\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =7+\frac{3}{4}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second calculation rule means:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{a}^{a}f\left(x\right)dx= & F\left(a\right)-F\left(a\right)=0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third calculation rule means that if we have a continuous function where the values a,b,c are included within an interval the integral can be divided into two integrals and give the same result as if we had taken the integral over the entire interval directly.
 We will illustrate this with the following example where the integral to the left sums the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,3\right]$
\end_inset

 and the two integrals in the right side sum 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,2\right]$
\end_inset

 as well as the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[2,3\right]$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{1}^{3}x^{2}dx= & \int_{1}^{2}x^{2}dx+\int_{2}^{3}x^{2}dx\\
\left[\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right]_{1}^{3}= & \left[\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right]_{1}^{2}+\left[\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right]_{2}^{3}\nonumber \\
9-\frac{1}{3}= & \left(\frac{8}{3}-\frac{1}{3}\right)+\left(9-\frac{8}{3}\right)\nonumber \\
8+\frac{2}{3}= & 8+\frac{2}{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Both sides give the same final result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
More examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now calculate the primitive function for the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=x+12
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The primitive function for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right) & =\int\left(x+12\right)dx\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}x^{1+1}+12*x+C\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}}{2}+12x+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead have the following function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=4x^{2}+3y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the primitive function fort his is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(x\right)=\frac{4x^{3}}{3}+3yx+C
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extensive equations can at first glance look more complicated than they actually are.
 For example the function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=a+2bx+3c+4x^{5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With the help of similar methods as in previous examples we see that the primitive function for this function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right) & =ax+bx^{2}+3cx+\frac{4x^{6}}{6}+C\\
 & =\frac{2}{3}x^{6}+bx^{2}+\left(a+3c\right)x+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second row we rearrange a little and put the term with the highest exponent of x first in the expression.
 Sometimes we also benefit from rewriting the equation before we calculate the integral.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(k\right)=k^{5}ak^{^{-2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be written:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(k\right)=ak^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The primitive function for function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\left(k\right)=\frac{ak^{4}}{4}+C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now take the following function 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left(T\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k\left(T\right)=T^{-1}+36T-\frac{1}{T^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The primitive function for this function 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K\left(T\right)=\ln T+18T^{2}+T^{-1}+C
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Multiple integral
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Multipelintegral"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!multiple
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we have several variables in the same function,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

,
 we can use a multiple integral.
 Consider now the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=f\left(x,y\right)=x^{2}+y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a function of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we shall calculate an integral with respect to both 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 over the interval 0 to 1 for both variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}\left(x^{2}+y\right)dxdy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate this integral we solve one integral at a time,
 in the same way as when we calculated integrals above.
 We start by taking the integral with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and calculate the area between 0 and 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}\left(x^{2}+y\right)dxdy & =\int_{0}^{1}\left[\frac{x^{3}}{3}+xy\right]_{0}^{1}dy=\int_{0}^{1}\left(\frac{1}{3}+y\right)dy
\end{align}

\end_inset

Then we take the integral with respect to y and calculate this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{0}^{1}\left(\frac{1}{3}+y\right)dy & =\left[\frac{y}{3}+\frac{y^{2}}{2}\right]_{0}^{1}=\frac{5}{6}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The result is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{5}{6}$
\end_inset

 volume units.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we calculated the integral for a function with one variable we calculated among other things the area for the surface under a line in a graph.
 Since we now calculate the area under a two-dimensional surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

-plane,
 the result becomes a three-dimensional volume.
 In this example we have the dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 When we have two variables this is called a double integral or surface integral.
 Integration over three variables is called triple integral and can be calculated in a corresponding way.
\emph on

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
integral!surface
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!double
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integral!triple
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Partial integration
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Partiell-integration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integration!partial
\end_layout

\end_inset

Partial integration,
 or integration by parts,
 is a method for finding the solution to integrals that are the product of two or more functions.
 The need for this method arises when the integral of a product is not equal to the product of the factors' integrals.
 Suppose we have the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=h\left(x\right)=x^{2}a^{2x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the included variable and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 consists of the two factors 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2x}$
\end_inset

,
 which we describe as separate functions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
h\left(x\right) & =x^{2}a^{2x}=f\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the integral for the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 we get the primitive functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F=\int x^{2}dx=\frac{x^{3}}{3}, & \qquad G=\int a^{2x}dx=\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 respectively with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 results in the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 But the derivative of the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $F\times G$
\end_inset

 does not result in the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\times g=x^{2}a^{2x}$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(F\times G\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 becomes instead:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[F\left(x\right)\times G\left(x\right)\right]'_{x} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left[\frac{x^{3}}{3}*\frac{a^{2x}}{2}\right]=\frac{a^{2x}\ln\left(a\right)*x^{3}}{3}+\frac{a^{2x}x^{2}}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we use the differentiation rules from section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: räkneregler derivata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 To calculate the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we must instead use partial integration.
 The general form for this,
 given that we divide function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 into the two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 looks as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Partial integration:}}\int fg'dx=fg-\int f'gdx\label{eq: partiell integration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=f'_{x}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=g'_{x}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To use this method we seek to begin with an expression that can be formulated as the left side in this equation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f\left(x\right)g'_{x}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now choose which of the two expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2x}$
\end_inset

 from function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we should define as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'_{x}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 This choice in turn affects how the rest of the calculation.
 Suppose we define 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=a^{2x}$
\end_inset

.
 We call the primitive function we seek 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H=\int fg'dx & =fg-\int f'gdx=x^{2}\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\int2x\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}dx
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=2x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}$
\end_inset

.
 The second term consists of a new integral of a product.
 In this term we can cancel the number 2 in the numerator and denominator and factor out the denominator,
 since this does not contain the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and therefore is not affected by the integration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int2x\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}dx=\frac{1}{\ln a}\int xa^{2x}dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve this integral we again use partial integration based on equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: partiell integration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int fg'dx=fg-\int f'gdx$
\end_inset

.
 We now choose to define 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=a^{2x}$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}$
\end_inset

.
 The primitive function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 now becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H & =\int fg'dx\\
 & =x^{2}\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\frac{1}{\ln a}\left(x\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\int\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}dx\right)\nonumber \\
 & =x^{2}\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\frac{1}{2\left(\ln a\right)^{2}}\left(xa^{2x}-\int a^{2x}dx\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the far right in the equation we again get a new integral.
 But this time it is only the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2x}$
\end_inset

 that should be integrated.
 This we can solve without partial integration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H & =\int fg'dx\\
 & =x^{2}\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\frac{1}{2\left(\ln a\right)^{2}}\left(xa^{2x}-\int a^{2x}dx\right)\nonumber \\
 & =x^{2}\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\frac{1}{2\left(\ln a\right)^{2}}\left(xa^{2x}-\frac{a^{2x}}{2\ln a}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}a^{2x}}{2\ln a}-\frac{xa^{2x}}{2\left(\ln a\right)^{2}}+\frac{a^{2x}}{4\left(\ln a\right)^{3}}+C\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{2\left(\ln a\right)^{2}x^{2}a^{2x}-2\ln\left(a\right)xa^{2x}+a^{2x}}{4\left(\ln a\right)^{3}}+C\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{a^{2x}\left(2\ln\left(a\right)x\left(\ln\left(a\right)x-1\right)+1\right)}{4\left(\ln a\right)^{3}}+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are finished and we have now found the primitive function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=x^{2}a^{2x}$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the first derivative of function 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 it certainly requires a somewhat cumbersome calculation but the result becomes again function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us take another example.
 We now seek the integral to the following function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v\left(x\right)=x^{2}e^{2x}\label{eq: integral ex 2, v(x)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also requires partial integration.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=e^{2x}$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=2x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2x}/2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int v\left(x\right)dx & =fg-\int f'gdx\\
 & =x^{2}\frac{e^{2x}}{2}-\int2x\frac{e^{2x}}{2}dx\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}e^{2x}}{2}-\int xe^{2x}dx\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 and therefore have that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=e^{2x}/2$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the following integral,
 which we call 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V\left(x\right) & =\int fg'dx\\
 & =\frac{x^{2}e^{2x}}{2}-\int xe^{2x}dx\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}e^{2x}}{2}-\left(\frac{xe^{2x}}{2}-\int\frac{e^{2x}}{2}dx\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}e^{2x}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\left(xe^{2x}-\int e^{2x}dx\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x^{2}e^{2x}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\left(xe^{2x}-\frac{e^{2x}}{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{e^{2x}\left(2x^{2}-2x+1\right)}{4}+C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have found a primitive function to function 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: integral ex 2, v(x)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us try to solve the same function again but this time define the temporary functions f and g the opposite way compared to what we just did.
 We thus have the same function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(x\right)=x^{2}e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 but this time we set 
\begin_inset Formula $f=e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=x^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=2e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=x^{3}/3$
\end_inset

.
 Partial integration gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int v\left(x\right)dx & =fg-\int f'gdx\\
 & =e^{2x}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-\int2e^{2x}\frac{x^{3}}{3}dx\nonumber \\
 & =e^{2x}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-\frac{2}{3}\left(\int e^{2x}x^{3}dx\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now define 
\begin_inset Formula $f=e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=2e^{2x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=x^{4}/4$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int v\left(x\right)dx & =e^{2x}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-\frac{2}{3}\left(\int e^{2x}x^{3}dx\right)\\
 & =e^{2x}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-\frac{2}{3}\left(e^{2x}\frac{x^{4}}{4}-\int2e^{2x}\frac{x^{4}}{4}dx\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now unfortunately a pattern begins to emerge.
 We continue to solve integrals but the new integrals become rather more complicated than the previous ones,
 which counteracts the purpose.
 This illustrates that we can benefit greatly from setting up our problem in as manageable a way as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
