\begin_layout Standard
Now we instead want to use mathematical functions to describe the income distribution.
 This may be useful if we want to reason theoretically.
 Let the following function describe what percentage share of the society's incomes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 goes to a percentage share of the population,
 x:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=L\left(x\right)=x^{a},\,a\geq1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant coefficient.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 the function becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 and the inhabitants have the same income.
 The percentage cumulative amount of the population increases at the same pace as the incomes.
 Say now that we have a society where the income distribution can instead be described with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{1}=L_{1}\left(x\right)=x^{3}\text{ (Distribution 1)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now something happens that causes the income distribution to change.
 It could for example be some form of technological change,
 a change in demography between one generation and the next or that the government changes taxes and transfers.
 Regardless of the reason the new income distribution can instead be described with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{2}=x^{2}\text{ (Distribution 2)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gini coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we shall find out how much the total income distribution has changed.
 This we can calculate with the help of the so-called Gini coefficient,
 named after the Italian statistician and sociologist Corrado Gini.
 The Gini coefficient indicates what share of the incomes must be redistributed for everyone to have the same income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say for example that we have two people where one person has 0 in income and the other has 100 USD in income.
 In that case 50% of the incomes must be redistributed if both people shall have the same income,
 50 USD.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the area under the Lorenz curve and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the area between the Lorenz curve and the diagonal line we calculate the Gini coefficient,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=\frac{A}{A+B}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we by definition know that 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=1/2$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=\frac{A}{A+B}=\frac{A}{\frac{1}{2}}=2A
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we also see that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A+B & =\frac{1}{2}\label{eq: gini 1-2b}\\
2A & =1-2B=G\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

