\begin_layout Standard
The Gini coefficient for the income distribution before tax can be calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1-2B$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the area under a Lorenz curve.
 In this case we have two Lorenz curves,
 which describe two examples of distributions:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{3}$
\end_inset

 (Gini before) and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 (Gini after) respectively.
 To see how the income distribution has changed we calculate the area under each curve and compare.
 Gini before:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G_{1} & =1-2\int_{0}^{1}x^{3}dx=1-2\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)=\frac{1}{2}=50\%
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gini after:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{2}=1-2\int_{0}^{1}x^{2}dx=1-2\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)=\frac{1}{3}=33,3\%
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The income spread has according to this measure decreased from 50% to 33.3%.
 The difference is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gini i teorin"
