\begin_layout Itemize
Integration can be described as "anti-derivative".
 This gives us the integral for a function.
 Example:
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 has the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x^{3}/3+C$
\end_inset

.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the integral and is also called the primitive function.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the integrand.
 In these functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a variable and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 an arbitrary constant.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 can be any number,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has an infinite number of primitive functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Primitive functions can also be calculated based on conditions.
 Example:
 we have the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and seek the primitive function so that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(0\right)=2$
\end_inset

 is fulfilled.
 This gives the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x^{3}/3+C$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Integrals can among other things be used to calculate the area under a curve down to the x-axis.
 Example:
 to calculate the area between the line for 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,4\right]$
\end_inset

 we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{4}f\left(x\right)dx=F\left(4\right)-F\left(0\right)=\left(4^{3}/3+C\right)-\left(0^{3}/3+C\right)=21+1/3$
\end_inset

 area units.
 To calculate the area below and above the x-axis we divide the integral into two parts,
 one for the region above and one for the region below the x-axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The area between two curves is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\left[g\left(x\right)-h\left(x\right)\right]dx$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)\geq h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 over an interval of x-values and the area is bounded upward by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and downward by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Examples of integration rules:
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{a}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant coefficient,
 gives integral 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x^{a+1}/\left(a+1\right)+C$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=e^{kx}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a constant coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is Euler's number,
 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=e^{kx}/k+C$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a^{x}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=a^{x}/\ln a+C$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\ln x$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x\ln x-x+C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Within social science integrals can among other things be used to discuss theoretical distributions of variables,
 for example distribution of incomes in a population.
\end_layout

