\begin_layout Standard
Now the bakery wants to make 10 breads,
 5 pastries,
 and 3 cakes and we wish to calculate the resources needed.
 For this we can use matrix multiplication to find total ingredient.
 First we define the production vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\left[\begin{matrix}10 & 5 & 3\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate how much ingredients the bakery need in total for this production we can use matrix multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $PR$
\end_inset

.
 The new matrix will have the same number of rows as the first matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (3 rows) and the same number of columns as the second matrix in the multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (1 column),
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
PR=\left[\begin{matrix}10 & 5 & 3\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}2 & 0 & 1\\
1 & 3 & 0\\
1 & 4 & 1
\end{matrix}\right]=\left[\begin{matrix}10*2+5*1+3*1\\
10*0+5*3+3*4\\
10*1+5*0+3*1
\end{matrix}\right]=\left[\begin{matrix}28\\
27\\
13
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the amounts needed of flour (28 kg),
 sugar (27 kg) and yeast (13 kg).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
