\begin_layout Standard
The data in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Input-output-tabell"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we use to calculate how changed production in one part of the economy affects other parts.
 We begin by placing the table's values in matrices.
 We collect the flows to and from the industries in a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 (the flow matrix),
 final consumption in column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and the sum in the last column in column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\left[\begin{matrix}2 & 1\\
1 & 3
\end{matrix}\right],\quad C=\left[\begin{matrix}3\\
3
\end{matrix}\right],\quad S=\left[\begin{matrix}6\\
7
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flows to and from industries 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Z\right)$
\end_inset

 we divide by each industry's total production 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(S\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{ij}=\frac{y_{ij}}{y_{j}}\label{eq: a-elementen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is production from industry i that is delivered to industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the total production that industry j produces.
 For each value in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 we calculate a value 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and collect in a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To do this calculation with matrices we first calculate the multiplicative inverse (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Inversen av matris"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) of each element in S,
 that is place the values as denominators in separate fractions with numerator 1.
 Industry A gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

 and industry B 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{7}$
\end_inset

.
 We collect these values in a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset

 and place in a diagonal matrix,
 which we describe as 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!diagonal
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)=\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1}{6} & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{7}
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 we now matrix multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A & =Z*\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)\\
 & =\left[\begin{matrix}2 & 1\\
1 & 3
\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1}{6} & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{7}
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{2}{6} & \frac{1}{7}\\
\frac{1}{6} & \frac{3}{7}
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 we define total production 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 as the sum of input production to all industries plus production to final consumption,
 which in this case becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{j}=a_{j1}y_{1}+a_{j2}y_{2}+c_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 are the weights we defined in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: a-elementen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the total production from industry 1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 is total production from industry 2,
 or industry A and B as we called them.
 We do not know the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 yet but we can calculate it using the matrices.
 We collect the elements of total production in column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and can now describe 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =AY+C\label{eq: y=(i-a)^-1 s}\\
Y-AY & =C\nonumber \\
IY-AY & =C\nonumber \\
\left(I-A\right)Y & =C\nonumber \\
Y & =\left(I-A\right)^{-1}C\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 has the same dimensions as A.
 Column matrix Y describes how much production is required from each industry to companies in the same and other industries as well as to final consumption:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =\left(I-A\right)^{-1}S=\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{8}{5} & \frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{7}{15} & \frac{28}{15}
\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}3\\
3
\end{matrix}\right]\approx\left[\begin{matrix}12,4\\
15,9
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This shows how much industry A and B must produce in total for input goods and final consumption.
 We call the inverted matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B=(I-A)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the same dimensions as matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with the values from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Input-output-tabell"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
B & =\left(I-A\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{matrix}\right]-\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{2}{6} & \frac{1}{7}\\
\frac{1}{6} & \frac{3}{7}
\end{matrix}\right]\right)^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{4}{6} & -\frac{1}{7}\\
-\frac{1}{6} & \frac{4}{7}
\end{matrix}\right]^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{8}{5} & \frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{7}{15} & \frac{28}{15}
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we now in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 calculate the sum of a column for an industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 we get the total amount of production for all industries that would be required if the final consumption for industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 were to increase by one unit.
 This shows how much other industries must deliver in input goods to industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 This measure is called production multiplier in this context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we for matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 calculate the sum of a row for an industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 we get a measure of how much extra production in total in society that is enabled if industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 increases its production of input goods by one unit.
 This is called input multiplier.
\end_layout

