\begin_layout Standard
In network analyses,
 one sometimes wants to use measures to calculate how important or influential actors in the network are.
 A basic measure of this is degree centrality,
 which in this case is a measure of how many connections each node,
 person or industry,
 has to some other node in the network.
 The concept of centrality also occurs in statistics but then means something else.
 Degree centrality for a node j is the sum of the number of contacts and can be described with the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{j}^{D}\left(a\right)=\sum_{i}^{n}a_{ji}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call degree centrality 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{D}$
\end_inset

.
 In this equation 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 represents whether there is any contact from node j to another node i.
 Nodes are then for example individual persons,
 industries or actors,
 depending on what we study.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 symbolizes the amount of nodes in the network.
 For our social network everyone has sent messages to everyone else,
 except Jose who has not sent anything to Mohammed.
 Mohammed thus has 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{D}=3$
\end_inset

 while the other three actors have 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{D}=4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we want to adjust our measures for the maximum number of possible connections.
 In this case we adjust degree centrality to take into account the maximum number of possible connections in the network by dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{j}^{D}\left(a\right)=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}a_{ji}}{n-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formalized network analysis has existed at least since the 1700s.
 An early example is a famous text by Leonhard Euler about the seven bridges in Königsberg in Prussia,
 present-day Kaliningrad in Russia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "eulerSolutioProblematisAd1741"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Euler's article laid the foundation for the part of mathematics called graph theory.
 Leonard Euler is by the way the same Euler as in Euler's number,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A mathematical quantity with one value is called scalar.
 A vector is a quantity with multiple values,
 for example a person's weight and height.
 A vector can contain a large amount of values.
 The values in a vector can be described as variables,
 dimensions or elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Vectors with the same number of dimensions can be added or subtracted.
 Example:
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=\left(a_{1},a_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\left(b_{1},b_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 give 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}+\vec{b}=\left(a_{1}+b_{1},a_{2}+b_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplication of vector by scalar:
 
\begin_inset Formula $s*\vec{a}=s\left(a_{1},a_{2}\right)=\left(sa_{1},sa_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 where s is any number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication of two vectors results in a scalar,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}*\vec{b}=\left(a_{1},a_{2}\right)*\left(b_{1},b_{2}\right)=a_{1}b_{1}+a_{2}b_{2}=s$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is any number.
 A vector's norm,
 length,
 can be calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\vec{a}\Vert=\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A matrix is a collection of values organized as a rectangle,
 with columns and rows.
 Dimensions for a matrix are given with rows 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 columns or 
\begin_inset Formula $r\times k$
\end_inset

.
 Example 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has 2 rows and 3 columns.
 The values in a matrix are called elements.
 Element 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{12}$
\end_inset

 is the value at row 1 column 2.
 A matrix where 
\begin_inset Formula $r=k$
\end_inset

 is square.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrices with the same shape can be added and subtracted,
 whereby the value at position 
\begin_inset Formula $rk$
\end_inset

 is added or subtracted with the value in the other matrix at the corresponding position.
 Example:
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 where the elements are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{rk}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{rk}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{11}+b_{11}$
\end_inset

 and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication of matrix by scalar means that all elements are multiplied by the scalar:
 
\begin_inset Formula $sA=\left[\begin{matrix}sa_{11} & sa_{12}\\
sa_{21} & sa_{22}
\end{matrix}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrix multiplication:
 the rows in the left matrix are multiplied by the columns in the right matrix.
 Matrix multiplication of matrices A and B is defined for AB given that number of rows in A = number of columns in B.
 If we switch places of the matrices we do not necessarily get the same result,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $AB\neq BA$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

:
 transposed matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{rk}^{T}=a_{kr}$
\end_inset

.
 Generally:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A^{T}\right)^{T}=A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)^{T}=B^{T}A^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Transposition does not affect scalars:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(sA\right)^{T}=sA^{T}$
\end_inset

,
 where s is scalar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A matrix where all elements outside the matrix's diagonal are 0 is called diagonal matrix.
 The elements in the diagonal in a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are those elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{rk}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r=k$
\end_inset

,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{11},a_{22},...,a_{nn}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is any number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A diagonal matrix where all values on the diagonal are 1 is called identity matrix or unit matrix.
 A square matrix where only the elements on one side of the diagonal are equal to 0 is called triangular matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The determinant of matrix A is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Example:
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[\begin{matrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{matrix}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=ad$
\end_inset

.
 For a triangular matrix the determinant is equal to the product of the diagonal's elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can use row reduction in matrices in the same way as for linear equation systems,
 among other things to edit a matrix until it becomes triangular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inverse of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 the inverse matrix,
 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse matrix can be calculated with Gauss-Jordan elimination:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $r\times k$
\end_inset

 we add an 
\begin_inset Formula $r\times k$
\end_inset

 identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{r}$
\end_inset

,
 so that we get 
\begin_inset Formula $AI$
\end_inset

.
 Edit 
\begin_inset Formula $AI$
\end_inset

 until the right part becomes an identity matrix,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $IA^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 where the right half is the inverse matrix we seek.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Vectors and matrices can be used to describe and study networks and flows between actors,
 for example goods and services between different industries or contacts in a social network.
\end_layout

