For this collection of values,
 the mode = 9 since the number 9 occurs most frequently.
 The median for these numbers is the value 6 since it is the middle value.
 The mean is the sum divided by the number of values 
\begin_inset Formula $=89/15\approx5.93$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare how the values are spread around the average value,
 we use different types of measures of dispersion.
 One way to get a picture of the spread in a collection of values is to calculate the range,
 the difference between the highest and lowest value.
 For the 15 numbers above,
 the range is 
\begin_inset Formula $9-1=8$
\end_inset

.
 A useful measure of dispersion is percentiles,
 which are the values that divide a collection of values into 100 parts.
 Similarly,
 other divisions are also used,
 such as deciles,
 quintiles and quartiles.
 A decile divides a collection of values into ten parts,
 quintile into five and quartile into four.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Percentiles are indicated with corresponding numbers 1–100,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{10}$
\end_inset

 symbolizes the tenth percentile and is the value that is greater than 10% of the values in the collection.
 Here we are content with a simplified example.
 Consider all the integers 0 to 1,000.
 The tenth percentile for this set is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{10}=100$
\end_inset

,
 since the value 100 delimits the bottom 10 percent of the values.
 The fourteenth percentile is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{14}=140$
\end_inset

.
 The twentieth percentile is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{20}=200$
\end_inset

,
 and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Percentiles 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{10},\:P_{20},\:P_{30},\:P_{40},\:P_{50},\:P_{60},\:P_{70},\:P_{80}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{90}$
\end_inset

 are the same values as the deciles.
 Deciles can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 for decile 1,
 which is the same value as 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{10}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 for decile 2,
 and so on.
 Percentiles 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{20},\:P_{40},\:P_{60}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{80}$
\end_inset

 are the same values as the quintiles,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{20}=K_{1}$
\end_inset

 for quintile 1.
 Percentiles 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{25},\:P_{50}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{75}$
\end_inset

 are the same values as the quartiles,
 which divide the collection into four parts.
 Quartiles are often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1},\:Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{50}=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 marks the middle value in the collection,
 which is the same thing as the median.
 Sometimes the concepts interquartile range and quartile deviation are used.
 Interquartile range is the difference between the third and first quartile:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{3}-Q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Quartile deviation is interquartile range divided by 2:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Q_{3}-Q_{1}\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
