\begin_layout Section
Variance and standard deviation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
standard deviation
\end_layout

\end_inset

Two other common measures of dispersion are variance and standard deviation.
 Both of these are very central to all statistical analysis,
 which is why we go through them a bit more thoroughly here.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: population urval superpopulation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced population and sample.
 When we work with information and data variables,
 for example data that describes some phenomenon in society,
 we very rarely have access to reliable information about the population.
 When we study causal relationships,
 we lack observations for the counterfactual scenario that we are actually interested in and therefore do not have access to all data.
 Instead,
 we are then referred to trying to estimate what the population looks like by studying the sample data we have access to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we are interested in variable x.
 In the population for this variable there are N number of observations and from this population we take n number of observations for our sample.
 Our goal is to find out what the spread in the population looks like and we use our sample data to study this.
 Note here that what we are actually constantly seeking are the values that exist in the population.
 We make calculations on our sample data to estimate the values in the population.
 The expressions estimate and estimate mean the same thing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have access to population data,
 the mean is known.
 To mark this,
 the population's mean is usually written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}$
\end_inset

 (the Greek letter mu).
 The mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is an estimate of the population's 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\sum_{i}x_{i}/n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study spread,
 we calculate distance from the mean.
 In the population,
 the difference between observation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}-\mu_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 where letter 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 means observation number 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 With our sample data we take 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}-\bar{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of differences from the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is always 0,
 which we see by writing:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right) & =\sum x_{i}-n\bar{x}\label{eq: sum of diff from mean}\\
 & =\sum x_{i}-n\frac{1}{n}\sum x_{i}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum x_{i}-\sum x_{i}\nonumber \\
 & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to measure deviations from the mean is to estimate mean absolute deviation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Mean absolute deviation} }=\frac{1}{n}\sum\left|x_{i}-\bar{x}\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance
\end_layout

\end_inset

We can also replace the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 with some other measure of central tendency such as median or mode.
 Another way to sum deviations from the mean to a positive value is to square the deviations:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we divide the sum of the squared differences by the number of observations n,
 we get the variance for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Variance: }}var\left(x\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\label{eq: varians def 1, div med n}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 shall be calculated for each observation and summed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}=\left(x_{1}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}+\left(x_{2}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}+...+\left(x_{n}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By squaring each deviation from the mean we get a positive measure.
 This also means that greater deviations from the mean will have a greater weight for the estimated variance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the same way that the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is an estimate of the population's 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is an estimate of the variance in the population.
 The variance in the population is often denoted with the Greek letter small sigma squared,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which indicates that this is the population value for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard deviation for a collection of observations is the positive square root of the variance.
 For population,
 standard deviation is often denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Estimated standard deviation for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $sd_{x}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
standard deviation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Standard deviation:} } & s_{x}=+\sqrt{var\left(x\right)}=\left(\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}{n}\right)^{1/2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we estimate the mean with sample data 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{x}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 this often deviates from the population's mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This deviation tends to lead to our estimate of the population's variance becoming too small.
 To correct for this,
 in the equation for variance (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: varians def 1, div med n"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) we divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This new definition of variance is called corrected variance or sample variance:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Sample variance: }}var\left(x\right)=\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\label{eq: varians def 2, div n-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bessel's correction
\end_layout

\end_inset

Division by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 is called Bessel's correction and often results in the estimated variance being closer to the population's variance.
 Many computer programs have ready commands for estimating (calculating) variance and then use Bessel's correction as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: varians def 2, div n-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 For standard deviation we also use Bessel's correction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\textbf{Sample standard deviation: }s_{x} & =\left(\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}{n-1}\right)^{1/2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a constant a that represents an arbitrary value,
 the variance for this is 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(a\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is because a single value has no spread.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 the variance for 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}var\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We see this by taking:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(ax\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}\left(ax_{i}-a\bar{x}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}\left(a^{2}x_{i}^{2}-2a^{2}\bar{x}+a^{2}\bar{x}^{2}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not affected by the summation,
 we factor out all 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(ax\right) & =a^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum\left(x_{i}^{2}-2\bar{x}+\bar{x}^{2}\right)\label{eq: var(ax) = a2 var(x)}\\
 & =a^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =a^{2}var\left(x\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For standard deviation we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
s_{x}\left(ax\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}\left(ax_{i}-a\bar{x}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}\left(a^{2}x_{i}^{2}-2a^{2}\bar{x}+a^{2}\bar{x}^{2}\right)\right)^{1/2}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(a^{2}\right)^{1/2}\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\nonumber \\
 & =\left|a\right|s_{x}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

