\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
standardization
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is difficult to compare variance between two different variables if the variables are measured in different units,
 for example,
 such as weight and height.
 One method to facilitate comparisons between variables is standardization and normalization.
 Standardized values for a variable x are a measure of how far a value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 in a variable is from the variable's mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 counted in number of standard deviations.
 This is a very useful measure that is often used in statistics.
 Standardized values are also called standard scores,
 z-scores or z-values.
 Standardized values for a variable x can be calculated in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Standardized value: }}x_{i}=z_{i}=\frac{x_{i}-\bar{x}}{s_{x}}\label{eq: standardiserat värde 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is each respective value in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the standardized value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is the mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Each observation's distance to the mean is divided by the standard deviation for the current variable.
 Standardized variables always get the mean 0 and standard deviation 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take our variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that we used as examples in the previous section and convert these to standardized values,
 we get the two new variables 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Calculations and results are reported in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Standardiserade-värden x y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Observations 1 and 2 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{y}$
\end_inset

 become negative since these values lie below their respective means.
 
\end_layout

