\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
normalization
\end_layout

\end_inset

Normalization can mean slightly different things in statistics.
 One meaning is to convert a variable so that all values become between 0 and 1.
 Normalization of a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is done in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Normalized value:} }x_{norm}=\frac{x_{i}-x_{min}}{x_{max}-x_{min}}\label{eq: normalisering}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is observation i for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{min}$
\end_inset

 is the lowest value in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{max}$
\end_inset

 is the highest value for the variable.
 Similar to standardization,
 this can also be used to compare variables that otherwise differ from each other.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Normaliserade-värden-för"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows normalized values for variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

