\begin_layout Section
Covariation 1:
 Covariance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Kovarians"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
covariance
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we shall introduce our first statistical measure of linear covariation:
 covariance.
 Covariance is a measure of covariation between two variables,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 For population data:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
cov(x,y)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}(x_{i}-\bar{x})(y_{i}-\bar{y})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our goal is to estimate the covariation in a population and possibly a superpopulation.
 From our population we take a sample of observations that we use to estimate the covariation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous examples we have worked with populations for one variable.
 Since we are now interested in covariation,
 our population consists of two variables.
 The covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in a population is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 (compare the notation for the population's variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

).
 Positive covariance means positive covariation:
 higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are associated with higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Negative covariance means negative covariation,
 that higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are associated with smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and vice versa.
 It does not matter in which order we write the variables in the parentheses:
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(x,y\right)=cov\left(y,x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the covariance for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and the same variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 we get the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
cov\left(x,x\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =var\left(x\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also apply Bessel's correction here to reduce the underestimation of the spread in the population that we risk making.
 This gives us what is called sample covariance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Sample covarians: }}cov\left(x,y\right)=\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\right)\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)\label{eq: cov sample}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

