\begin_layout Standard
Let us estimate the covariance between variables x and y that we used in the previous section.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: data för kovarians 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes our four observations in a table to the left and a graph to the right.
 In the table we have one observation per row and one variable per column.
 In the graph each observation is represented by a point.
 The point furthest to the left is observation 1:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(3,3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The point furthest to the right is observation 4:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)=\left(7,4\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Row 1 in the table consists of the first value for x and y respectively and represents values that belong together in some way.
 If we work with observed data,
 collected information,
 each observation represents an observation unit,
 for example information about a person or perhaps a country.
 Our four observations could thus represent four people,
 four countries or something else.
 In table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-för-kovarians"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have calculated the parts we need to get the covariance between x and y (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cov sample"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
cov\left(x,y\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\right)\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)=\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)\times5=\frac{5}{3}\label{eq: cov ex 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(x,y\right)=\frac{5}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This positive value indicates positive covariation.
 Covariance is useful for getting an estimate of whether the covariation between two variables is positive or negative,
 but it is difficult to say much more than that.
 There are no limitations for which values covariance can take.
 The value of covariance depends on which unit the variables' values have.
 For example,
 we will get different results depending on whether we use a variable that describes income in USD or in thousands of USD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Covariation 2:
 The correlation coefficient
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Pearsons-r"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pearsons r|see
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{correlation coefficient}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
correlation coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another measure of linear covariation is Pearson's 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
 also called Pearson's correlation coefficient or the correlation coefficient.
 The correlation coefficient for variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is denoted for population 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{xy}$
\end_inset

 (Greek rho):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Correlation coefficient:} }\rho_{xy} & =\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma_{x}\sigma_{y}}\label{eq: pearsons r population}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
standardization
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the population,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 are standard deviation in the population for each respective variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to describe this is that the correlation coefficient is standardized covariance (compare section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Standardiserade-värden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The correlation coefficient can only take values between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 1,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 means perfect negative correlation and 1 means perfect positive correlation.
 If the correlation coefficient equals 0,
 this indicates that there is no linear covariation between the variables.
 Since all results for the correlation coefficient are within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

,
 different correlation coefficients are comparable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we work with sample data,
 the correlation coefficient is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $corr\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{xy}=\frac{cov\left(x,y\right)}{s_{x}s_{y}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we instead have estimated covariance in the numerator and estimated standard deviation for the two variables in the denominator.
 The different parts in this equation we have defined earlier in this chapter.
 We write out the equations and add Bessel's correction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{xy} & =\frac{cov\left(x,y\right)}{s_{x}s_{y}}\label{eq: pearsons r sample}\\
 & =\frac{\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\left(\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}{n-1}\right)^{1/2}\left(\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}{n-1}\right)^{1/2}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\left(n-1\right)^{-1}\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\left(n-1\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\left(\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since Bessel's correction is included in all three measures,
 we cancel 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 from both numerator and denominator in the last row.
 Let us again demonstrate by estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}$
\end_inset

 for the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and their four observations from figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: data för kovarians 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We reuse the results for covariance (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cov ex 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and standard deviation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: standardavvikelse ex1 x y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{xy} & =\frac{cov\left(x,y\right)}{s_{x}s_{y}}\approx\frac{5/3}{\left(+\sqrt{\frac{10}{3}}\right)\left(+\sqrt{\frac{5}{3}}\right)}\approx0.71\label{eq: pearsons = 0,71}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result indicates a positive correlation.
 High values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coincide with high values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coincide with low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Different correlation coefficients can be compared but it is still difficult to interpret this type of result more precisely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Frequency distribution shows number of observations per value or interval and can be reported in for example a table or a graph.
 A special type of bar graph that is often used in these cases is histogram,
 which shows frequencies per interval.
 In statistics,
 different measures of dispersion are used to measure distribution of values in a variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Variance in the population for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Estimated variance with sample data for the same variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma_{x}}=var\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{n}\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is number of observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is observation i of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Standard deviation for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $+\sqrt{\sigma_{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 For sample data:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{x}=s_{x}=+\left(var\right)^{1/2}=\left(\frac{\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)}{n}\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bessel's correction means that we divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This reduces the error that risks arising when we use sample data to estimate measures of dispersion for a population.
 Bessel's correction can also be used for other measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Standardized value,
 also called z-value or z-score,
 indicates a value's difference with the mean divided by standard deviation.
 For variable x this can be calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{x}=\frac{x_{i}-\bar{x}}{s_{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 Normalized values for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{norm}=\frac{x_{i}-x_{min}}{x_{max}-x_{min}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Covariance is a measure of linear covariation between two variables.
 For the population for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

.
 Estimated with sample data:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{xy}=cov\left(x,y\right)=\frac{1}{n}\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The correlation coefficient (Pearson's r) for population:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{xy}=\frac{cov\left(x,y\right)}{s_{x}s_{y}}$
\end_inset

.
 Sample data:

\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}=\sum\left(\frac{x_{i}-\bar{x}}{s_{x}}\right)\left(\frac{y_{i}-\bar{y}}{s_{y}}\right)$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 is standard deviation for variable
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

