noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The reason we use these numbers is to make the mathematical calculations easy.
 In the hypothetical examples here,
 it is irrelevant exactly what the population represents and calculated examples are used only as illustration of the method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All straight lines in a graph can be described with an equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX$
\end_inset

,
 that is,
 the equation of the straight line (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Den-räta-linjens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The constant coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the line's y-intercept or intercept while the constant coefficient b is the line's slope,
 or slope coefficient.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are in this case our variables.
 The line we will draw will give us an illustration of the average change in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as we move from relatively lower to relatively higher values on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

