\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Regressionsanalys"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!explained
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!dependent
\end_layout

\end_inset

The least squares method is one of several methods in regression analysis.
 In regression analysis we determine the variable whose variation we will map based on the variation in one or several other variables.
 Variation in an explanatory variable is used to explain some or all of the variation in an explained variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regression analysis is a method for mapping patterns in data.
 We then use this to study causal relationships.
 But as discussed in earlier sections it is important to remember that patterns (covariation) are no proof of a causal relationship (chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: kontrafaktisk analys"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The term "explanatory variable" therefore does not mean that one variable necessarily is the cause behind the state of the other variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now,
 based on the least squares method,
 estimate the linear covariation between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 where we determine that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is our explained variable and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is our explanatory variable.
 How we decide this depends on what idea underlies our analysis,
 for example a theory about GDP and happiness.
 Based on this,
 we set up the following regression model:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+V\label{eq: regressionsmodell 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 stands to the left of the equals sign in the regression model,
 it is the explained variable.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 to the right of the equals sign,
 is the explanatory variable.
 This regression model exists in our population,
 it is the population model or the population's regression model.
 With sample data,
 we can estimate this population model.
 Depending on the purpose of the study,
 we may also have an interest in our regression model representing a relation in a superpopulation (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: population urval superpopulation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the model's coefficients or parameters.
 The slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 should be read as a marginal increase in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 being associated with on average 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 change in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 the constant,
 is the line's y-intercept.
 We do not know what values 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 have in the population model.
 That is what we want to estimate.
 The estimated versions of the coefficients' population values 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we write as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The hat symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\hat{}\right)$
\end_inset

 is estimated values,
 that is,
 our estimates with sample data of population values (compare figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 without the hat symbol refer to their population values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a population with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 number of observations,
 from which we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of observations for our sample,
 we use these 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations to estimate the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 and thereafter 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 The line we will draw is called the regression line (already drawn in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 When we have estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 we can with the help of the observations in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 also estimate new values for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The estimated version of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

,
 which is the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-value on the regression line.
 The estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 that we seek in this case are constants,
 which means that they have the same values regardless of which values for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 we compare against.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the regression model,
 the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 represents what is called the error term.
 Regression analysis aims to measure the extent to which variations in the explanatory variable(s) coincide with variations in the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The error term indicates the difference between each observation's 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-value and the regression line in the population.
 Estimated error terms are called residuals,
 written 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

,
 and are the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-values along the regression line) and observed 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
residual
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{V}_{i}=Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\label{eq: residulaen def 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we insert the estimated coefficients,
 the residuals and the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 into the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regressionsmodell 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{Y}=\hat{a}+\hat{b}X+\hat{V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 can also be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{i}=a+bX_{i}+V_{i}\label{eq: regressionsmodell 1a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is an index for observation number.
 In this case,
 we use the four observations in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: data för ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\left\{ 1,2,3,4\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If we take observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i=2$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}=a+bX_{2}+V_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The two values for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constant for all observations and these therefore do not have any index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we go through the mathematics around the least squares method,
 we look at the equation for the regression line in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 increases by 1,
 this is associated with an on average 0.5 higher value on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the regression line's slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 in this case is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{b}=0.5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value for the regression model's y-intercept is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 which we estimate by taking the straight line's equation 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX$
\end_inset

,
 but substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 with estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and rearranging a bit:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =\hat{a}+\hat{b}X\\
\hat{a} & =Y-\hat{b}X\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have a definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we see that the regression line passes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,Y\right)=\left(3,\;2.5\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If we insert these values for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =Y-\hat{b}X=2,5-0.5*3=1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have the results for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 as well as the values for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Now we also estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 and thereby draw the regression line:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{Y_{i}}=\hat{a}+\hat{b}X_{i}\label{eq: yhat def 1a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkning-av"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows our calculations for estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 with the observed values for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The values in the table are the same as in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The point on the diagonal line that the vertical dashed lines meet is the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 If we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 for other values for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 we get other points along the regression line.
 
\end_layout

