\begin_layout Plain Layout
prediction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!predicted
\end_layout

\end_inset

In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the line slopes upward to the right and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

>0,
 which means that we have a positive covariation between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}<0$
\end_inset

,
 we have a negative covariation,
 whereupon the line would have sloped downward to the right in the graphs.
 Larger values in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then covariate with on average smaller values in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and smaller values in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 coincide with on average higher values in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0$
\end_inset

,
 the line is horizontal and lacks slope,
 which in that case indicates that we do not find any linear covariation between the variables.
 Estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 is also called predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Error term and residual
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Felterm-och-residual"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!residual
\end_layout

\end_inset

The error term 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 represents the variation in our explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that cannot be explained by the regression model and the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Our regression model should be designed in such a way that all variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that depends on other factors should be evenly and randomly distributed over the error terms' different values,
 which we will return to later.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: yhat def 1a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we defined predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y_{i}}=\hat{a}+\hat{b}X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We now insert this definition into our equation for the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{V}_{i} & =Y_{i}-\hat{Y}_{i}=Y_{i}-\left(\hat{a}+\hat{b}X_{i}\right)=Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a function of the observations in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 as well as the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkning-av vhat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows estimated results for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 from the observations in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: data för ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we read the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

 as the vertical distance between the diagonal line and each point.
 For observation 3 in the graph,
 we have written out the calculation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{V}_{3} & =Y_{i}-\hat{Y}_{i}=5-4=1
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that the sum of the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 0:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\hat{V_{i}}=\sum\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)=0\label{eq: summan av residualerna ej i kvadrat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that the sum of the vertical distance between the line and the points above the line is equal to the sum of the distance between the line and the points below the line.
 For the same reason,
 the mean of the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\hat{V}_{i}/n=0$
\end_inset

.
 If the sum of the error terms were equal to 0,
 all observations would lie on the regression line and the regression model would provide a complete explanation for the variation in the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 There is no reason why we should strive for such a regression model.
 There can be many reasons why the sum of the error terms and the residuals are not close to 0,
 which we will return to later.
 
