\begin_layout Section
Calculating with Least Squares
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset

We estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 earlier by comparing a regression line in a graph.
 Now we will use the least squares method to estimate the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 based on the observations in our variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 In practice,
 the calculations are usually performed by a computer and many analysis programs have ready-made commands for this.
 The method does not require advanced mathematics but when we have many variables and observations,
 the calculations can take a long time if we do them by hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example,
 we have only four observations and two variables (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: data för ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 which is why it is relatively simple to do the calculation by hand.
 Manual calculations help us understand the method better.
 The least squares method gives us the following definitions for estimating the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =\bar{Y}-\hat{b}\bar{X}\label{eq: OLS konstanter definition 1}\\
\hat{b} & =\frac{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
estimators
\end_layout

\end_inset

These equations are called the coefficients' estimators.
 With the help of sample data,
 we estimate the coefficients in the population.
 Let us go through these equations step by step.
 The definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated constant coefficient,
 which indicates the regression line's 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-intercept for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 are means of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 estimated with the sample data we have for each variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated value of the constant coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 the line's slope.
 We need 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}$
\end_inset

 means the sum of all observations,
 where the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 refers to how the observations are indexed:
 observation 1 to 4.
 We sum all observations from 1 to 4,
 which is why we in this case have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}=\sum_{i=1}^{n=4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset

 means that we for each observation i of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 subtract the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)$
\end_inset

 means the same thing for each observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 For each observation we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The numerator in the definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 means that we for each observation calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)$
\end_inset

 and sum these.
 This we divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 where we for each observation take the parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset

 squared and sum over all observations.
\end_layout

