Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Exempel-med-minstakvadratmetoden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the calculations we need for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Go carefully through each step in the table and make sure you understand what happens in each column.
 The sum of the observations in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n=4}X_{i}=3+4+6+7=20$
\end_inset

.
 The mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=20/4=5$
\end_inset

.
 We begin with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 which we need the value for to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b} & =\frac{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}=\frac{5}{10}=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

 means that an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by one unit is on average associated with a 0.5 higher 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since we now have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 we also estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =\bar{Y}-\hat{b}\bar{X}=3.5-0.5\times5=1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

 means that for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The results 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

 are the same as we saw in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: minstakvadratmetoden ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let us now calculate the points on the straight line by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given by the regression model,
 the estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and the observations from the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We get the following definition for estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{Y}_{i} & =\hat{a}+\hat{b}X_{i}=1+0.5X_{i}\label{eq: yhat def 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the observations for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 we may also estimate the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The results are presented in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkning-av- y och v"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the column for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 we see the values for the vertical 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-axis along the regression line.
 We only have values on the regression line that coincide with the values we have for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Try yourself to draw the points in a graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{1},\hat{Y}_{1}\right)=\left(3,2.5\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4,3\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6,4\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(7,4.5\right)$
\end_inset

.
