\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Kovarians"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced covariance.
 The estimator for coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 for the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 can also be defined as the covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 divided by the variance of the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{cov\left(X,Y\right)}{var\left(X\right)} & =\frac{\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}=\hat{b}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We here see that this is the same definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OLS konstanter definition 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Other straight lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The least squares method helps us find the regression line that minimizes the sum of the vertical distance between the regression line and the observations.
 All other straight lines result in a larger summed value for the squared distance between these lines and the points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This we may illustrate with the help of an example where we use the same four observations for x and y in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: data för ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that we used in the previous section.
 But instead of the regression line that we estimated based on the least squares method,
 we now have a horizontal line where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=3.5$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 which is the same as the mean for Y in our four observations:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}=\left(3+4+5+6\right)/4=3.5$
\end_inset

.
 A horizontal line has slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate the sum of the squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sum_{i}\hat{V_{i}}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 for this line:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!residual
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i}\hat{V_{i}}^{2} & =\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(3-3.5\right)^{2}+\left(4-3.5\right)^{2}+\left(5-3.5\right)^{2}+\left(6-3.5\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =9\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is more than 2.5.
 The regression line we could draw based on our regression model that we estimated with the least squares method is therefore better if we are to minimize the summed vertical distance.
 Let us exemplify with another line,
 which passes through observation 1 and 4,
 that is,
 the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,Y\right)=\left(3,3\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(7,4\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Based on these values for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 we know that when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 increases from 3 to 7,
 this is associated with an average change in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 from 3 to 4,
 which is why the line's slope is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b} & =\frac{Y_{4}-Y_{1}}{X_{4}-X_{1}}=\frac{4-3}{7-3}=\frac{1}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 we calculate with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(3,3\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =Y_{i}-\hat{b}X_{i}=3-\frac{1}{4}*3=\frac{9}{4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the line passes through observation 1 and 4,
 we know that the residual for these two is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 For observation 2,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=4$
\end_inset

,
 which gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{Y}_{2} & =9/4+\frac{1}{4}*4=13/4
\end{align}

\end_inset

For observation 3,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X=6$
\end_inset

 which gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{Y}_{3} & =9/4+\frac{1}{4}*6=15/4
\end{align}

\end_inset

For observation 2 and 3,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{3}=5$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i}\hat{V}_{i}^{2} & =\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(Y_{1}-\hat{Y}_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(Y_{2}-\hat{Y}_{2}\right)^{2}+\left(Y_{3}-\hat{Y}_{3}\right)^{2}+\left(Y_{4}-\hat{Y}_{4}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =0+\left(2-13/4\right)^{2}+\left(5-15/4\right)^{2}+0\nonumber \\
 & =3.1875>2.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

