\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: anscombe"

\end_inset

Four examples of linear covariation,
 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anscombeGraphsStatisticalAnalysis1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: anscombe"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows four examples where combined values for the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (horizontal axis) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (vertical axis) are plotted.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-variables in each graph all have the same mean:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}=7.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=9$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 that draw the regression lines in each graph have the same values in all four graphs:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The lines slope upward to the right in each graph,
 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}>0$
\end_inset

.
 In all four graphs,
 we thus use the least squares method to find a positive covariation that looks the same in the regression model.
 The example illustrates that despite the patterns in the four graphs differing drastically,
 calculated results can easily give the impression that different collections of data have more in common than they actually do.
 The four graphs were first presented in 1973 by the British statistician Francis John Anscombe 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "anscombeGraphsStatisticalAnalysis1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The examples illustrate the importance of both calculating covariation and studying data in graphs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the points in the graphs being placed in different patterns,
 we get the same positive linear covariation in all four examples.
 In the upper left graph,
 we see that the points lie spread along the diagonal line up toward the right corner of the graph.
 In the upper right graph,
 the points lie in a concave arc,
 up toward the graph's right corner.
 The points' pattern is clearly nonlinear,
 but we still calculate a linear positive covariation.
 In the lower left graph,
 all points except one lie on a straight line.
 In the lower right graph,
 all points except one lie on a vertical line.
\end_layout

