Consider two more examples on a similar theme.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: weird ols 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes two graphs where the dots again show combined values of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The straight lines are regression lines calculated based on the least squares method.
 Now the lines are horizontal,
 which means that the slope coefficients are equal to 0 in both cases.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases,
 this is not associated with any change in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But when we look at the graphs in the figure,
 we clearly see that the dots in the two graphs lie in different patterns,
 which suggests different types of covariation.
 In the left graph,
 the relationship between the variables is clearly positive,
 but only if we study the observations as two groups.
 In the right graph,
 a nonlinear covariation is visible when we look at all observations.
 If we look only at the left half of the graph,
 a positive covariation is visible,
 while the points in the right half of the graph have a negative covariation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Another example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: OLS ex 2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us now estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\alpha+\beta K+U\label{eq: ols reg modell 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 are variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients that we shall estimate based on the least squares method and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 That we now use other letters does not affect the mathematics.
 Let us repeat our method:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have an idea that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 covariates with 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 This is a statement about covariation,
 not a theory about a causal relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We formulate our statement about covariation in the form of a regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols reg modell 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use the least squares method to find the estimators (the equations) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset

,
 where the hat symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{}$
\end_inset

 indicates that they are estimated versions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After we have estimated the coefficients,
 we estimate the regression line's equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=\hat{\alpha}+\hat{\beta}K$
\end_inset

 and draw the regression line in a graph.
 The values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

 indicate the regression line's values on the vertical axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}=Z-\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the vertical distance (y-axis) between the regression line's 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

 and each observation 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

