\begin_layout Section
Which model fits the data best?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: ssr sse sst vilken modell är bäst"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sum of squares!residuals
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
TSS,
 SSE,
 SSR
\end_layout

\end_inset

To compare how well different statistical models fit the data they aim to describe the pattern for,
 there are several commonly used methods.
 An important part in the evaluation of the regression model is to compare the residuals,
 that is,
 the distance between the data we used in our explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the predicted values for the same variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to compare how well a regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 fits the data that the model is estimated against is to compare the Sum of Squared Errors (SSE):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SSE=\sum_{i}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}=\sum_{i}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\label{eq: RSS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SSE is the amount of variation in the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that cannot be explained by the regression model.
 Another useful measure is the Sum of Squares due to Regression (SSR):
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sum of squares!explained
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SSR=\sum_{i}^{n}\left(\hat{Y}_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}\label{eq: SSE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SSR can be described as the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that can be explained by the regression model.
 As mentioned earlier,
 the concept "explained" in this context does not necessarily mean causal explanation.
 The total sum of squares is the sum of SSE and SSR.
 TSS can be interpreted as the amount of variation that occurs in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 before the regression model is estimated and written as the sum of the squared difference between observed 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
TSS & =SSR+SSE\label{eq: SST}\\
\sum_{i}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2} & =\sum_{i}^{n}\left(\hat{Y}_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_rssesstss.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Differens-mellan- y ybar yhat"

\end_inset

Difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i},\bar{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to illustrate the differences between SSE,
 SSR and TSS is given in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Differens-mellan- y ybar yhat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We use here again the four observations for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\left\{ 2,3,4,5\right\} $
\end_inset

 that we used in our first example in this chapter.
 In the figure the residuals are highlighted with dashed vertical lines between the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the regression line 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The abbreviations TSS,
 SSR and SSE are common to use.
 Unfortunately,
 other abbreviations also occur to describe the same thing.
 The essential thing is of course what each designation or abbreviation represents in each context,
 thus the mathematics itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the sums of squares,
 we can estimate the coefficient of determination,
 which is usually denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
coefficient of determination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r@
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R^{2} & =\frac{SSR}{TSS}=\frac{TSS-SSE}{TSS}=1-\frac{SSE}{TSS}=1-\frac{\sum\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mean squares
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 measures what proportion of the variation in the explained variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 that can be explained by the regression model and the variation in the explanatory variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 can take values between 0 and 1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 means that nothing of the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 can be explained by the regression model and the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 means that all variation in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is explained by the regression model and the variation in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put simply,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a measure of how well we manage to explain the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 In social science we study human behavior,
 which often is the result of many phenomenons and complex relationships.
 It is therefore only natural that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is usually relatively low for any regression model which try to explain human life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance,
 say we wish to explain variations in happiness between countries,
 as discussed in the introduction to this chapter.
 We can easily come up with a long list of variables which might affect how the population of different countries feel about their lives.
 Most regression models will therefore probably only explain a limited part of the variation in happiness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study how well a regression model fits against data,
 we compare the mean sum of squares,
 also called mean squares.
 To get the mean squares,
 we divide each sum of squares by the number of degrees of freedom.
 In statistics,
 degrees of freedom refers to the number of parameters that can vary in a calculation,
 which we will return to below.
 The Mean Squares of Errors (MSE):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MSE=\frac{SSE}{n-p} & =\frac{\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\label{eq: MSr}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $n-p$
\end_inset

 shows the number of degrees of freedom,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of estimated coefficients in the regression model.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Differens-mellan- y ybar yhat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

.
 If we have the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 for the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Simplified,
 a low MSE can mean that the regression model's predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 ends up relatively close to the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The Mean Squares of the Regression (MSR) is calculated by dividing SSR by the number of explanatory variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
MSR=\frac{SSR}{p-1}=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(\hat{Y}_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}}{p-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

