\begin_layout Standard
Earlier in this chapter we have used two different collections of observations (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: data för ols 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-med- z k"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to estimate the two regression models in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regressionsmodell 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols reg modell 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 based on the least squares method.
 One way to compare which regression model best fits a dataset is to compare MSE for each regression model.
 We begin with the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regressionsmodell 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna x y , vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 repeats the observations for the variables x and y as well as some calculations that we need,
 which gives MSR:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MSE_{\text{model 1}} & =\frac{\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{n}=\frac{2,5}{4}=0.625
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us calculate MSE also for the second regression model,
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols reg modell 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\alpha+\beta K+U$
\end_inset

,
 with the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna z k vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 repeats the variables' values and summarizes some calculations,
 which gives:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
MSE_{\text{model 2}} & =\frac{5}{4}=1.25
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $MSE_{\text{model 2}}>MSE_{\text{model 1}}$
\end_inset

,
 this suggests that the first regression model's predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 lies closer to observed 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 compared to how well the second regression model succeeds in predicting the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 in that model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MSR is calculated using the observations we use and the result can therefore change if we add or subtract observations,
 alternatively if we specify our regression models in some other way.
 Let us also estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For the first regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 we get (see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna x y , vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\text{model 1}}^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}}=1-\frac{2.5}{5}=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=1/2$
\end_inset

 indicates that half of the variation in Y can be explained by the regression model and the variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let us also calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the second regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\alpha+\beta K+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 (see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna z k vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\text{model 2}}^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum_{i}\left(Z_{i}-\hat{Z_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(Z_{i}-\bar{Z}_{i}\right)^{2}}=1-\frac{5}{9}=\frac{4}{9}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{9}<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

,
 this indicates that the first regression model has a higher degree of explanation compared to the second model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Derivation of the Estimators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Härled OLS med vanliga f"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
least squares method!derivation
\end_layout

\end_inset

For the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{i}=a+bX_{i}+V_{i}\label{eq:OLS för härledning}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 are variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term,
 we introduced estimators for the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regressionsmodell 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Now we shall go through how we derive these.
 The least squares method allows us to define the estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 so that we minimize the sum of the squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}=\sum\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The estimators can therefore be derived from a minimization problem (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Optimering-utifrån-funktioner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The sum of the squared residuals becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2} & =\hat{V}_{1}^{2}+\hat{V}_{2}^{2}+...+\hat{V}_{n}^{2}\label{eq: härled ols residualsumman}\\
 & =\left(Y_{1}-\hat{Y}_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(Y_{2}-\hat{Y}_{2}\right)^{2}+...+\left(Y_{n}-\hat{Y}_{n}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where n is the number of observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 is predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 To be able to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=\hat{a}+\hat{b}X$
\end_inset

,
 we need to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OLS för härledning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we take the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and insert into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: härled ols residualsumman"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2} & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\left(\hat{a}+\hat{b}X_{i}\right)\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right)^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have an equation where the sum of squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\hat{V_{i}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a function of estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 It is this function that we shall minimize with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 which we write as a minimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\text{w.r.t. }\hat{a},\hat{b}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right)^{2}\label{eq: OLS minimeringsproblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
least squares method!first degree conditions
\end_layout

\end_inset

We differentiate the right-hand side with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 By setting the results equal to 0,
 we get two first-order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}\right]_{\hat{a}}^{'} & =-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right)=0\label{eq:OLS FOC a}\\
\left[\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}\right]_{\hat{b}}^{'} & =-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right)=0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where both results arise by differentiating the parenthesis (moving down exponent 2) and differentiating the contents of each parenthesis.
 When we differentiate with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 we get –1.
 When we differentiate with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $–X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We put 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 to the left of the summation sign since these things are not affected by the summation.
 From the two first-order conditions,
 we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin with the first condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right) & =0\\
\left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-\left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{a}-\left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i} & =0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since all terms are multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

,
 we cancel this factor.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is constant over all observations,
 the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is the same thing as the number of observations times 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}\hat{a}=n\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
 We now write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0= & \left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-\left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{a}-\left(-2\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i}\\
0= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{a}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i}\nonumber \\
0= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-n\hat{a}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i}\nonumber \\
n\hat{a}= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We divide by n so that the term farthest to the right becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}\sum\hat{b}X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 which gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}Y_{i}-\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{b}X_{i}\label{eq: härledd version av a-hat}\\
\hat{a} & =\bar{Y}-\hat{b}\bar{X}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
 To derive 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 we begin with the second first-order condition in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OLS FOC a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We take the opportunity here to simplify the writing of the summation signs 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}=\sum$
\end_inset

 but the meaning is still the same.
 Summation is done over the expressions that have subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\sum_{i}-2x_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\sum X_{i}\hat{a}-\sum X_{i}\hat{b}X_{i}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the constants are not summed,
 we move these to the left of the summation signs.
 In the term farthest to the right we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}*x_{i}=x_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 with the definition from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: härledd version av a-hat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\hat{a}\sum X_{i}-\hat{b}\sum X_{i}X_{i}\\
 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\hat{a}\sum X_{i}-\hat{b}\sum x_{i}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\left(\bar{Y}-\hat{b}\bar{X}\right)\sum X_{i}-\hat{b}\sum X_{i}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum X_{i}+\hat{b}\bar{X}\sum X_{i}-\hat{b}\sum X_{i}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum X_{i}-\hat{b}\left(\sum X_{i}^{2}-\bar{X}\sum X_{i}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We move
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 to the left side of the equals sign:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b}\left(\sum X_{i}^{2}-\bar{X}\sum X_{i}\right) & =\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum X_{i}\label{eq:OLS b härled}\\
\hat{b} & =\frac{\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum X_{i}}{\sum X_{i}^{2}-\bar{X}\sum X_{i}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 For it to look the same as in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: minstakvadratmetoden ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we rewrite a bit.
 The final result remains the same:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b} & =\frac{\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum Y_{i}}{\sum X_{i}^{2}-\bar{X}\sum X_{i}}\\
 & =\frac{\sum X_{i}Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\sum_{i}X_{i}-\bar{X}\sum y_{i}+\bar{X}\sum Y_{i}}{\sum X_{i}^{2}-\bar{X}\sum X_{i}-\bar{X}^{2}\sum1+\bar{X}^{2}\sum1}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\sum\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have the same thing as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OLS b härled"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that the first condition in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OLS FOC a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 means:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\hat{V}_{i}=0\label{eq: ols foc 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the second condition can be described as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum X_{i}\hat{V}_{i}=0\label{eq: ols foc 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This we will have use for later on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The least squares method (often referred to as 
\emph on
Ordinary Least Squares
\emph default
,
 OLS) is a method for studying linear covariation between two or more variables and thereby describing patterns in data.
 The least squares method is one of several methods within regression analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Based on an idea about covariation,
 we formulate a regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}=a+bX_{i}+V_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the explained variable and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the explanatory variable,
 both noted for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients that we shall estimate.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term,
 which measures the variation in the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that the regression model and the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 cannot explain.
 The estimated error term is called residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 and indicates the difference between estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and observed 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Symbols with a hat over them are estimated versions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The least squares method allows us to define how a and b shall be estimated so that the sum of the squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}=\sum_{i}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is minimized.
 We estimate the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and thereafter 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The coefficients are estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=\bar{Y}-\hat{b}\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=\frac{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum_{i}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 are means.
 The results for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 are constants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicates the line's slope.
 Result 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}>0$
\end_inset

 indicates positive covariation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}<0$
\end_inset

 indicates negative covariation.
 Result 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0$
\end_inset

 indicates that there is no linear covariation between 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 indicates the y-intercept.
 If coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=0$
\end_inset

,
 we have the model 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y_{i}}=\hat{b}X_{i}+\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 for which the straight line passes through the origin,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If coefficient
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0$
\end_inset

,
 we have the model
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}=\hat{a}=\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

,
 where
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the mean for
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 meaning
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

 for all observations
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

