\begin_layout Standard
Let us now calculate standardized values for life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and GDP 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,
 by dividing the difference to the mean by standard deviation.
 We call the standardized values of each respective variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Standardiserade d och m"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standardized values are easier to compare and already in the table we see that the variables display a tendency toward positive covariation:
 several observations whose values deviate negatively in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{L}$
\end_inset

 also deviate negatively in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{G}$
\end_inset

,
 and vice versa for several positive values.
 We also see that the standardized size of the deviations is of similar magnitude.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate standardized covariance we use the measure correlation coefficient (Pearson's r) which we defined in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pearsons r sample"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{XY}=\frac{cov\left(X,Y\right)}{s_{X}s_{Y}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(X,Y\right)$
\end_inset

 is estimated covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{X}$
\end_inset

 respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{Y}$
\end_inset

 are estimated standard deviation for each respective variable.
 The correlation coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{L,G}$
\end_inset

 then becomes:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
correlation coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{L,G} & =\frac{cov\left(L,G\right)}{s_{L}s_{G}}\approx0.9498
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result also indicates positive covariation,
 where higher life expectancy covaries with higher average income.
 As noted in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Pearsons-r"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the correlation coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is also a difficult to interpret.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall estimate the covariation between 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by using regression analysis and the least squares method.
 When we use regression analysis we must also determine which variable should be the explanatory variable,
 that is the variable that should be on the left side of the equals sign in our regression model.
 We decide to map to what extent variations in life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 can be "explained" by the regression model and the explanatory variable average income 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 We cannot draw conclusions about causation,
 since we cannot be certain that there is not some other phenomenon that affects one or both variables in the model.
 We have the following regression model:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}G+e\label{eq: socialt ex sex länder regress1, litet urval}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is life expectancy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is GDP,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient for y-intercept,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the slope coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Based on the least squares method we shall now estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 That we use Greek letters for the coefficients has no mathematical significance.
 In table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-för- d och m"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have the calculations required to give us the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\alpha_{2}} & =\frac{\sum\left(G_{i}-\bar{G}\right)\left(L_{i}-\bar{L}\right)}{\sum\left(G_{i}-\bar{G}\right)^{2}}\approx\frac{758.48}{1869.41}\approx0.4057
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This we use to estimate the y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\alpha_{1}} & =\bar{L}-\hat{\alpha_{2}}\bar{G}\approx73.47-0.4057*19.01\approx65.758
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

