\begin_layout Plain Layout
plot!histogram
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have previously used histograms to illustrate variables.
 Another type of graph that is often used to illustrate distribution of values is box plots,
 which are also called box-and-whisker plots.
 Now we shall compare the distribution of our two variables in histograms and box plots simultaneously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_gdplife_hist_box.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: histogram boxplot kolada 290 kommuner"

\end_inset

Histograms and box plots for life expectancy and GDP per capita
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: histogram boxplot kolada 290 kommuner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the distribution of the two variables income and life expectancy for all countries.
 The upper graphs show histograms while the lower graphs are box plots.
 In the histogram for GDP,
 the upper graph to the left,
 we see how the distribution has a slightly longer "tail" upward,
 which arises because a few countries have unusually high GDP per capita,
 while the great majority are clustered around the distribution's median and mean,
 to the left in the graph.
 In the histogram for life expectancy,
 upper graph to the right,
 we see that the values are somewhat more evenly distributed below and above the mean,
 which in turn means that the median and mean lie close to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also in the two box plots at the bottom of the figure we can read the mean at the line in the middle of the white boxes.
 The white rectangles' left and right edges respectively are the first and third quartile,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The lines outside the rectangle mark 1.5 * the interquartile range,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $1.5*\left(Q_{3}-Q_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
cov\left(L,G\right)\approx94.84
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall estimate the following regression model with data for all countries in the dataset:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}G+v
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the error term and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients we estimate using the least squares method.
 Life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a linear function of GDP per capita 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The model thus has the same form as the one in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: socialt ex sex länder regress1, litet urval"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The reason we now define the new coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the regression model is that we want to clarify that this is a different regression model than the previous one.
 Now we use more observations,
 which therefore by definition is a different collection of data than last time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the mathematics with this many observations becomes relatively extensive to perform manually,
 by hand,
 this type of calculation takes less than a second for a computer.
 This time we get the following result for our regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{\beta}_{1}+\hat{\beta}_{2}G+v\approx67.645+0.281*G_{i}+v_{i}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also indicate a pretty strong positive correlation between GDP and life expectancy.
 The result is not that far from the results we found in the previous section when we only used data for a few countries.
 The regression result is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ols livslängd inkomst, 290 kommuner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where the regression line (the straight dashed line) between the points is calculated using the least squares method.
 In the graph the vertical distances between the points and the regression line are also drawn,
 which corresponds to the residuals.
 Note how we in the graph on an overview level can see how the observations for the two variables are distributed.
 A few points lie a bit further to the right in the picture,
 which corresponds to the countries with unusually high GDP.
