\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall estimate the linear trend over time for GDP using regression analysis.
 We shall estimate two regression models and compare the results.
 One regression model where we use the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}=$
\end_inset

 GDP in billions USD in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and one model with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln G_{t}=$
\end_inset

 natural logarithm of GDP.
 The explanatory variable in both models is time (years).
 In the first regression model we use the variable GDP as a function of the variable year:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{t}=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}\text{year}_{t}+e_{t}\label{eq: bnp linjär trend modell k19}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients we shall estimate using the least squares method and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Note now that we use a linear model to describe a variable whose data is not particularly linear.
 In the table above the values for the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

 increase exponentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second regression model we use the natural log of GDP:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
logarithm
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln G_{t}=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}\text{year}_{t}+\epsilon_{t}\label{eq: ln bnp linjär trend modell k19}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Note that even though we now use 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln b$
\end_inset

 we still estimate the covariation against the variable year without logarithmic transformation of this variable.
 We use different letters to describe the coefficients in this model to clarify that these are two different regression models.
 We begin by estimating the first model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: bnp linjär trend modell k19"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: beräknar inför OLS log BNP trend"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the calculations we need to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are described:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\alpha_{2}} & =\frac{\sum\left(\text{year}_{t}-\bar{\text{year}}\right)\left(G_{t}-\bar{G}\right)}{\sum\left(\text{year}_{t}-\bar{\text{year}}\right)^{2}}=\frac{1,039,905.15}{25,000}=41.6\label{eq: resultat linjära modellen}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{1}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\alpha_{1}} & =\bar{G}-\hat{\alpha_{2}}\bar{\text{year}}\approx2,115.0236-41.6\times1,900=-76,917.8
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slope coefficient indicates the average annual linear GDP growth between year 1800 and 2000 in the US.
 Our result thus indicate that GDP on average has increased by approximately $41.6 billions per year.
 The result for the y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{1}$
\end_inset

 indicates that in year zero GDP was minus $76,917.8 billion,
 which is impossible.
 This result comes from the use of a linear model to describe a development that is not linear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second regression model,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ln bnp linjär trend modell k19"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the natural log of GDP,
 we instead get the following result for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\beta_{2}} & =\frac{\sum\left(\ln G_{t}-\bar{\ln G}\right)\left(\text{year}_{t}-\bar{\text{year}}\right)}{\sum\left(\ln G_{t}-\bar{\ln G}\right)^{2}}\approx\frac{1,231.986}{25,000}\approx0.04928
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\beta_{1}} & =\bar{\ln G}-\hat{\beta_{2}}\bar{\text{year}}\approx2,115.0236-0.04928\times1900\approx-89.98
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we now use the natural log of GDP the estimated coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is an approximate measure of how the model estimates the annual percentage growth rate:
 
\begin_inset Formula $0.04928\approx4.9\%$
\end_inset

.
 The other coefficient,
 y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta_{1}}$
\end_inset

,
 gives us the level of ln GDP at year zero.
 To get the level in billions USD we now need to set 
\begin_inset Formula $-89.98$
\end_inset

 as exponent on the number 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 which we calculate with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the anti-logarithm of the natural log:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left(\hat{\ln G_{t}}\right)=e^{\hat{\ln b_{t}}}=\hat{b_{t}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For year zero we then get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln\left(\hat{G_{t}}\right) & =\hat{\beta_{1}}+\hat{\beta_{2}}\text{year}_{0}\\
\ln\left(\hat{G_{0}}\right) & =-89.98+0.04928\times0\nonumber \\
\ln\left(\hat{G_{0}}\right) & =-89.98\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we see that our model estimates GDP year zero to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{GDP year zero } & =\exp\left(-89.98\right)=e^{-89.98}=\frac{1}{e^{89.98}}\text{ bn USD.}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{89.98}$
\end_inset

 is a high value,
 a bit over 1 duodecillion,
 a 1 followed by 39 zeros.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/e^{89.98}$
\end_inset

 is a very low value,
 close to 0.
 This is logically a more credible result than any negative number,
 which we estimated GDP to be in year 0 in the first regression model.
 What this exercise primarily illustrates is that the natural log of GDP has a more linear correlation with time,
 compared to GDP.
 But none of our estimates of GDP in year 0 should be taken particularly seriously.
 We use simple models and just a few observations to compare complex processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slope coefficient for time in each respective regression model gives us the average growth rate for GDP,
 as well as the growth rate for the natural log of GDP.
 Results are shown in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Predikterad-BNP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with predicted values (the regression lines) for each regression model,
 the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G_{t}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ln G_{t}}$
\end_inset

 as well as the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e_{t}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the column furthest to the right we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(\hat{\ln G_{t}}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the level of GDP that is predicted with the regression model that uses the natural log of GDP.
 Based on this we then calculate the sum of squared residuals.
 For the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}\text{year}_{t}+e_{t}$
\end_inset

 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{t}\hat{e_{t}}^{2} & =39,549,636.76
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln G_{t}=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}\text{year}_{t}+\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{t}\hat{\epsilon_{t}}^{2} & \approx1.31
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To convert the results for the natural log variable to billions of dollars we use the exponential function:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!exponential
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left(\sum_{t}\hat{\epsilon_{t}}^{2}\right)\approx\exp\left(1.31\right)\approx3.71
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As can be seen in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Predikterad-BNP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the predicted results for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}_{t}$
\end_inset

 from the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: bnp linjär trend modell k19"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are further from observed GDP,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 compared,
 to the difference between predicted values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ln G_{t}}$
\end_inset

 (from the regression model in equation 
