In this section we will also compare GDP in the US over time.
 But instead of the explained variable or the coefficients,
 we are now interested in the residuals of the following regression model with the natural log of GDP as the explained variable:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln G_{t}=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}\text{year}_{t}+\epsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this regression model the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon_{t}}$
\end_inset

 indicates the difference between observed 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln G_{t}$
\end_inset

 and estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ln G_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 In the previous section we estimated the coefficients for this regression model to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta_{1}}=-89.98$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta_{2}}=0.04928$
\end_inset

.
 When we study economic development we are often interested in both the long-term trend and deviations from this trend.
 The deviation from the trend is in this case a measure of more short-term variation in GDP growth.
 This type of short-term variations has been the subject of great discussion within social science.
 In this case we measure deviations from the trend by observing the residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall compare different deviations from estimated measures of long-term trend.
 This provides additional illustrations of the least squares method and how certain data lie closer to the predictions we estimate using a linear regression model.
 We have already estimated the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon_{t}}=\ln G_{t}-\hat{\ln G_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we want to calculate the deviation from trend in billions of USD,
 which we for year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 call 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{t}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!residual
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d_{t} & =G_{t}-\exp\left(\hat{\ln G_{t}}\right)\\
 & =G_{t}-e^{\hat{\ln G_{t}}}\nonumber \\
 & =G_{t}-\hat{G}_{t}^{\text{from ln}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

 is GDP in billions USD.
 In the first row we use the exponential function 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 to set the logarithmic expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ln G_{t}}$
\end_inset

 as exponent with base 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 which gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 In the last row we mark this term with the text "from ln",
 as a reminder that this predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

 is from the regression model with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln G_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us our first result.
\end_layout

