\begin_layout Plain Layout
GDP!and happiness
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: log bnp och lycka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we compared the covariation between self-assessed life satisfaction and GDP per capita.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Lycka o BNP - data för OLS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 repeats this data and now we will use this to estimate the covariation between these phenomena using two regression models.
 The first model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{i}=\gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}Y_{i}+e_{i}\label{eq: regmodell lycka 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is happiness in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is GDP per capita,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term and we shall estimate the two coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 using the least squares method.
 The second regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{i}=\delta_{1}+\delta_{2}\log_{10}Y_{i}+\epsilon_{i}\label{eq: regmodell lycka 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}\left(\text{GDP per capita}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the error term and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients we shall estimate.
 The results for the first model (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regmodell lycka 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\gamma_{2}} & =\frac{\sum\left(H_{i}-\bar{H}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)}{\sum\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}\right)^{2}}=0.05622\\
\hat{\gamma_{1}} & =\bar{H}-\hat{\gamma_{2}}\bar{Y}=4.7311\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the other model (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regmodell lycka 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) the results are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\delta_{2}} & =\frac{\sum\left(H_{i}-\bar{H}\right)\left(\log_{10}Y_{i}-\bar{\log_{10}Y}\right)}{\sum\left(\log_{10}Y_{i}-\bar{\log_{10}Y}\right)}=2.222\\
\hat{\delta_{1}} & =\bar{H}-\hat{\delta_{2}}\bar{\log_{10}Y}=3.503\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time we leave the details of the calculation as an exercise for the reader.
 If we focus on the slope coefficients see that according to the first model an increase in GDP per capita of 1,000 PPP USD is associated with on average around 0.056 higher self-assessed happiness.
 According to the second model one unit higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}$
\end_inset

GDP per capita coincides with around 2.22 units higher life satisfaction.
 As can be seen in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Lycka o BNP - data för OLS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}$
\end_inset

GDP per capita with one corresponds to almost a tenfold increase of GDP per capita,
 for example the approximate difference between Congo and Sweden or the difference between Haiti and Brazil.
 
\end_layout

