\begin_layout Standard
Let us also compare 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 how large a proportion of the variation in happiness can be explained by the variation of the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}Y.$
\end_inset

 For the first model we get:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
coefficient of determination
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r@
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\text{model 1}}^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum\left(H_{i}-\hat{H_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(H_{i}-\bar{H}\right)^{2}}\approx0.719
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the other model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\text{model 2}}^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum\left(H_{i}-\hat{H_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(H_{i}-\bar{H}\right)^{2}}\approx0.948
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to this measure the first model explains about 72% of the variation in average happiness between countries.
 The second model explains about 95% of the variation in happiness between countries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Lycka-och-BNP per capita, regresutat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the data we used and the two regression models' prediction lines.
 The result indicates that higher and relatively higher GDP covary with higher self-assessed life satisfaction,
 where we called the latter "happiness".
 When we compare the covariation with relative income differences (log GDP) almost all variation in happiness can be explained by the variation in the explanatory variable log GDP per capita.
 A relatively higher measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 means that the sum of the residuals is relatively smaller.
 This can also be seen in the graphs if we compare the distance between the points and the regression lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an observational study.
 For the same reasons as we discussed earlier we cannot draw any more detailed conclusions about causal effects from these results.
 
\end_layout

