\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
least squares method
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us now start from a regression model where the explained (dependent) variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is explained by the two explanatory (independent) variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{i}=a+bX_{i}+cZ_{i}+V_{i}\label{eq: regressionsmodell 3 variabler}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are constant coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We will now estimate the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 and thereafter 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 will give us the average change in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that is associated with an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by one unit,
 given the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 shows the average change in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that is associated with an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 by one unit,
 given the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is,
 by using both explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 in the same regression model,
 the calculation will show the covariation between Y and X,
 taking into account variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 The covariation between 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 will be estimated taking into account variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This is a central aspect of this type of regression analysis and we return below to what this means.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as when we only had one explanatory variable in the regression model,
 we shall now,
 when we have two explanatory variables,
 find those values for the constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 that minimize the squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\hat{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 compare equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OLS minimeringsproblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We therefore again describe our calculation as a minimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}=\min_{\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 can be defined from our regression model as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{y_{i}}=\hat{a}+\hat{b}x_{i}+\hat{c}z_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 can be inserted into our minimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\min_{\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2} & =\min_{\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y_{i}}\right)^{2}=\min_{\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{c}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}-\hat{c}Z_{i}\right)^{2}\label{eq: minimera e^2 med y x z}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this equation we know 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 since these are our observed data.
 We have three factors to take into account in the form of the three constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate the first-order conditions by differentiating the expression in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: minimera e^2 med y x z"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 respectively and setting each result equal to 0.
 Since we have three factors we get the following three results:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{a}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}\right) & =\sum-2\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}-\hat{c}Z_{i}\right)\label{eq: OLS förstagradsvillkor 3 variabler}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{b}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}\right) & =\sum-2X_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}-\hat{c}Z_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\hat{c}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\hat{V}_{i}^{2}\right) & =\sum-2Z_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{a}-\hat{b}X_{i}-\hat{c}Z_{i}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a similar way as we did in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Härled OLS med vanliga f"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we set the first condition equal to 0 and solve for a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =-2\sum y+\sum\hat{a}+\sum\hat{b}x_{i}+\sum\hat{c}z_{i}\label{eq: a-intercept def 1 för regmodell med 2 var}\\
n\hat{a} & =ny-\hat{b}nx_{i}-\hat{c}nz_{i}\nonumber \\
\hat{a} & =\bar{y}-\hat{b}\bar{x}-\hat{c}\bar{z}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare the definition for the y-intercept when we only have two variables in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OLS konstanter definition 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is a function of the observations in all three variables included in the regression model:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 From here we continue to solve for the slope coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Here,
 however,
 we only look at the final results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations below describe the estimators for the two slope coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

.
 To compress the algebra we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{X_{i}}=X_{i}-\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 and correspondingly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Z_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the coefficients' estimators are described based on the observations' deviations from their respective means:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b} & =\frac{\left(\sum\tilde{y_{i}}\tilde{x_{i}}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{z}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{y}_{i}\tilde{z}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{x_{i}}\tilde{z_{i}}\right)}{\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{z}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}\tilde{z}_{i}\right)^{2}}\label{eq: OLS-konstanterna b och c}\\
\hat{c} & =\frac{\left(\sum\tilde{y}_{i}\tilde{z}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{y}_{i}\tilde{x}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}\tilde{z}_{i}\right)}{\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{z}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{x}_{i}\tilde{z}_{i}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 depend on the observed values in the three variables in the regression model:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 We see this because values for all three variables are included in each respective equation.
 This means that even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 measures the covariation between 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 And despite the fact that the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 measures the covariation between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 is also a function of observations in all three variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Had we had more variables and coefficients in our regression model,
 the equations would have become even more extensive.
 At the end of this chapter we will go through another way to derive equations for the coefficients in a regression model regardless of the number of variables and coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we add a variable to our analysis,
 this can affect the results for all coefficients included in the model.
 Say that the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 should be included in the model but that this for some reason is not included in the analysis.
 In that case the result for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 will become misleading.
 We do not get the correct result until we include 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 This is central to understanding this type of method and analytical work in general.
 
