\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: 3d regression y x z "

\end_inset

Results from the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=a+bx_{i}+cz_{i}+v_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we estimated the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 we found that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 When we now added the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to the regression model we see how the result for the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 goes from 0.5 to 0.3.
 We use the results for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a} & =3.5-\hat{b}*5-\hat{c}*1.5\\
 & =3.5-0.28*5-\left(-0.54\right)*1.5\nonumber \\
 & \approx2.89\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We summarize our estimated coefficients by inserting the results into our regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{i} & =\hat{a}+\hat{b}x_{i}+\hat{c}z_{i}+v_{i}=2.89+0.28x_{i}-0.54z_{i}+v_{i}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we may also estimate predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 which is summarized in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-av y och e"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with rounded results.
 When we have three variables it is more difficult to illustrate covariation in a graph.
 Despite this,
 an attempt is made in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: 3d regression y x z "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where the four observations are placed in the graph based on their values for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y,X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 The vertical axis is the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-axis while the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 each have their own horizontal axis.
 The black dot at the top of the graph is observation 3 whose values are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y,X,Z\right)=\left(5,6,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the regression model has three variables,
 the regression line 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\hat{Y}\right)$
\end_inset

 now becomes a plane surface with three dimensions,
 which is illustrated by the grid.
 This plane surface is angled with regard to the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

,
 depending on their respective slope coefficient.
 Since the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}<0$
\end_inset

 the grid slopes downward along the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

-axis seen from the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-axis.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}>0$
\end_inset

 the grid slopes upward along the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-axis seen from the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-axis.
\end_layout

