\begin_layout Standard
We illustrate this with the help of data on average life expectancy and earnings for women and men respectively in three countries,
 described in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender per country"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The column furthest to the right describes a dummy variable for gender where women = 0 and men = 1.
 Let us begin by comparing the relationship between life expectancy and earnings with the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=a_{1}+a_{2}I+\epsilon\label{eq: allt annat lika , reg mod 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is life expectancy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is earnings,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients we will estimate with the least squares method and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 The slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 we estimate to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a_{2}} & =\frac{\sum_{i}\left(I_{i}-\bar{I}\right)\left(L_{i}-\bar{L}\right)}{\sum_{i}\left(I_{i}-\bar{I}\right)^{2}}\approx\frac{-5.7321}{47.6187}\approx-0.1204
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 we estimate to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a_{1}} & =\bar{L}-\hat{b}\bar{I}\approx81.6598-\left(-0.1204\right)19.4448\approx84
\end{align}

\end_inset

The calculations are not described here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to our calculations there seems to be a negative relationship between life expectancy L and earnings I,
 which means that people with higher earnings on average live shorter lives.
 Let us now add the variable gender G to our regression model.
 In table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender per country"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 this is a dummy variable that only takes the value 0 or 1.
 We will now estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=b_{1}+b_{2}I+b_{3}G+V\label{eq: allt annat lika , reg mod 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L,\:I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are our variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\:b_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{3}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients we will estimate using least squares,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 To estimate the slope coefficients we now use the definitions in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OLS-konstanterna b och c"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We begin with the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b}_{2} & =\frac{\left(\sum\tilde{L_{i}}\tilde{I_{i}}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{G}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{L}_{i}\tilde{G}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{I_{i}}\tilde{G_{i}}\right)}{\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{G}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}\tilde{G}_{i}\right)^{2}}\\
 & \approx\frac{\left(-5.73\right)\left(1.5\right)-\left(6.84\right)\left(-3.79\right)}{\left(-3.79\right)\left(1.5\right)-\left(14.4\right)^{2}}\nonumber \\
 & \approx0.3044\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Tilde over a letter describes deviation from the mean,
 for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{G}=G_{i}-\bar{G}$
\end_inset

.
 The slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{3}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b}_{3} & =\frac{\left(\sum\tilde{L}_{i}\tilde{G}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{L}_{i}\tilde{I}_{i}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}\tilde{G}_{i}\right)}{\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(\sum\tilde{G}_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\sum\tilde{I}_{i}\tilde{G}_{i}\right)^{2}}\\
 & \approx\frac{\left(6.84\right)\left(47.6\right)-\left(-5.73\right)\left(-3.79\right)}{\left(47.6\right)\left(1.5\right)-14.4}\nonumber \\
 & \approx5.3311\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Finally we estimate the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b_{1}} & =\bar{L}-\hat{b_{2}}\bar{I}-\hat{b_{3}}\bar{G}\\
 & \approx81.66-0.3*19.44-5.33*0.5\nonumber \\
 & \approx73.0746\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let's put our estimates into the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: allt annat lika , reg mod 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{b}_{1}+\hat{b}_{2}I+\hat{b}_{3}G=73.0746+0.3044I+5.3311G
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result now indicates a positive relationship between our explained variable life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

 and the explanatory variable earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 taking into account gender 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(G\right)$
\end_inset

.
 People with higher earnings live on average longer lives.
 When we estimated the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: allt annat lika , reg mod 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we found that earnings and life expectancy related negatively.
 
