\begin_layout Section
Least Squares with Matrices
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Minstakvadratmetoden-med-matrise"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Härled OLS med vanliga f"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we derived the coefficient estimators for the least squares method for a regression model with two variables.
 In this section we will derive a more general expression for the estimators based on a regression model with any number of coefficients and variables.
 For this we will use matrices.
 We begin with the assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose we have a regression model with many coefficients,
 variables and observations.
 The model can be summarized as 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=b_{1}+b_{2}x_{1}+b_{3}x_{2}+...+b_{k}x_{k-1}+v_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the explained variable for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients we will estimate using the least squares method.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 are the explanatory variables.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the constant term and is not multiplied by any explanatory variable (similar to a in the model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

).
 In matrix notation,
 this constant term is represented by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 with a column of ones.
 Therefore,
 the first column in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consists of the number 1 in each cell,
 followed by one column for each explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We collect all coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 with as many rows as coefficients.
 Since we have 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We collect our explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Each column in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains the values for one explanatory variable.
 The first column in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consists of the number 1 in each cell,
 which we will multiply with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The next column in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains observed values for the first explanatory variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 followed by one column per explanatory variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The number of rows in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the same as the number of observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has the dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We collect the error term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},...,v_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We have as many error terms as observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our regression model can now be written with matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\begin{matrix}y_{1}\\
y_{2}\\
\vdots\\
y_{n}
\end{matrix}\right]_{n\times1} & =\left[\begin{matrix}1 & x_{11} & x_{21} & ... & x_{k1}\\
1 & x_{12} & x_{22} & ... & x_{k2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
1 & x_{1n} & x_{2n} & ... & x_{k-1,n}
\end{matrix}\right]_{n\times k}\left[\begin{matrix}b_{1}\\
b_{2}\\
\vdots\\
b_{k}
\end{matrix}\right]_{k\times1}+\left[\begin{matrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{matrix}\right]_{n\times1}\label{eq: ols reg modell matriser Y=XB+E}\\
Y & =XB+V\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We get a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with a column with ones and the variables,
 a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with the coefficients and a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with the error terms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on our regression model we now formulate our minimization problem using matrix notation.
 We seek the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 that minimize the sum of squared residuals.
 We begin by inserting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 into our equation and rearrange a bit so that we get an equation where the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 are a result of the other terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{V}=Y-X\hat{B}\label{eq:E def matrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix and we cannot get squared residuals by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}\hat{V}$
\end_inset

,
 since this is not defined for matrices (the number of columns in the left matrix must equal the number of rows in the right matrix).
 To get the sum of squared residuals in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 we instead multiply the transposed 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}^{T}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Multiplikation-och-transponering"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V}=\left[v_{1}+v_{2}+...+v_{n}\right]\times\left[\begin{matrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{matrix}\right]=\left[v_{1}^{2}+v_{2}^{2}+...+v_{n}^{2}\right]\label{eq: feltermer i kvadrat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be rewritten by using the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E def matrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V} & =\left(Y-X\hat{B}\right)^{T}\left(Y-X\hat{B}\right)\\
 & =Y^{T}Y-Y^{T}X\hat{B}-\hat{B}^{T}X^{T}Y+\hat{B}^{T}X^{T}X\hat{B}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{T}\hat{B}X=\left(\hat{B}^{T}X^{T}Y\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 we write:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V}=Y^{T}Y-2\hat{B}^{T}X^{T}Y+\hat{B}^{T}X^{T}X\hat{B}\label{eq: RSS med matriser}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have an expression for the squared residuals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 and it is this equation we will minimize with respect to the coefficients in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{\hat{B}}\left(\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We differentiate equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: RSS med matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 and set the result equal to 0,
 which gives us the first-order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\hat{V}^{T}\hat{V}}{\partial\hat{B}}=-2X^{T}Y+2X^{T}X\hat{B}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The first step is to move the negative term 
\begin_inset Formula $-2X^{T}Y$
\end_inset

 to the right-hand side:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-2X^{T}Y+2X^{T}X\hat{B} & =0\\
\left(X^{T}X\right)\hat{B} & =X^{T}Y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)$
\end_inset

 is square and symmetric with dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

,
 where k is the number of explanatory variables plus the constant.
 Given that the inverse of this matrix exists,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 we multiply both sides by this and thereby get a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The multiplication of the inverted matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)$
\end_inset

 equals the identity matrix I,
 a matrix with the value 1 on the diagonal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\hat{B}=\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(X^{T}X\right)\hat{B} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y\label{eq: OLS beta-matrisen definitionen}\\
I\hat{B} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y\nonumber \\
\hat{B} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We now have an expression for the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the explanatory variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and the explained variable in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 include all observations for each respective variable.
 This means that all coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 are a result of all variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 regardless of the number of variables.
 All variables in the regression model can therefore affect the results for all coefficients in the regression model.
\end_layout

