\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!interaction effect
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset

Interaction effect means that we combine two or more of the explanatory variables into a new variable.
 Thereby we check whether an explanatory variable's relationship with the explained variable varies depending on the values in another explanatory variable.
 Consider the following regression model as an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+bx+cz+\epsilon
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the error term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are explanatory variables and y is the explained variable.
 Now we have reason to believe that the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 may also depend on what value the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 has.
 We also believe that z relates to y in its own way,
 which in turn may also vary with the values in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say for example that we believe the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is slightly positive for low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 but that the slope is different for higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This interaction effect we estimate by creating a new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $k=x*z$
\end_inset

,
 where we for each observation multiply the value in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with the value in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We add the new variable k
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

 to our regression model with its own slope coefficient:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{i} & =a+bx+cz+dxz+\epsilon\label{eq: reg model interaktion introduktion}\\
 & =a+bx+cz+dk+\epsilon\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 the model's intercept,
 is just as before the value that y takes when all other variables equal zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x=z=k=0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 which is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $k=xz$
\end_inset

 measures the average change in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that is associated with an increase of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by one unit and an increase of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by one unit.
 Coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicates how large a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is associated with one unit higher 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 To estimate the total relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 we also need to add 
\begin_inset Formula $d*z$
\end_inset

,
 since variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is included as a multiplier in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The total relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can therefore be summarized as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=b+d*z\label{eq: interaktionseffekt 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y$
\end_inset

 means change in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is change in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are the same as in the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: reg model interaktion introduktion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 For those values when 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 measures the change in y that coincides with an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by one unit.
 In a corresponding way we get the total relationship between variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 through the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta z}=c+d*x\label{eq: interaktionseffekt 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the values 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
 the slope coefficient c indicates how much y increases when z increases by 1.
 Let us illustrate the interaction effect with the help of data.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: konstanthåller"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated the relationship between life expectancy and earnings for men and women in three countries.
 Now we will use the same data again but this time add an interaction effect.
\end_layout

