\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender _ interaction 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the same data that we used in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: konstanthåller"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 but with the addition of a new variable that is created by multiplying the two variables earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and gender 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The new variable has the heading "Interaction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $I*G$
\end_inset

".
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a dummy where three of six observations have the value 0,
 the new variable also gets the value 0 in these cases.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: konstanthåller"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated two regression models.
 First a model for the relationship between life expectancy and earnings,
 with the following result:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{a_{1}}+\hat{a}_{2}I=92-4.2*I
\end{align}

\end_inset

The second model also included the dummy variable gender 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{b}_{1}+\hat{b}_{2}I+\hat{b}_{3}G=69.6+6.64I-6.66G
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we will estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=c_{1}+c_{2}I+c_{3}G+c_{4}GI+v
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},c_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{4}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients we will estimate with the least squares method and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 We recognize the variables in the model from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender _ interaction 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

,
 earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 gender 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and the interaction term 
\begin_inset Formula $GI$
\end_inset

.
 With matrices we may describe our regression model in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=CX+V
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with the values for the explained variable life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with all coefficients in the model,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a matrix with all explanatory variables in the model and the observations for each variable in its own column.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},...,v_{n}$
\end_inset

 where n is the number of observations.
 To estimate the coefficients we have the estimator,
 with corresponding setup as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OLS beta-matrisen definitionen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 but with other letters:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{C}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}L
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Matrix 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
 is in this case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 17.597 & 1 & 17.597\\
1 & 19.897 & 0 & 0\\
1 & 21.641 & 1 & 21.641\\
1 & 23.982 & 0 & 0\\
1 & 15.302 & 1 & 15.302\\
1 & 18.25 & 0 & 0
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All elements in the first column in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have the value 1 since the first coefficient in the regression model is not multiplied by any variable.
 The other values in the matrix are taken from the observations for the three explanatory variables in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender _ interaction 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The transposed version of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The values in 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X'=\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 1 & 1 & 1 & 1 & 1\\
17.597 & 19.897 & 21.641 & 23.982 & 15.302 & 18.25\\
1 & 0 & 1 & 0 & 1 & 0\\
17.597 & 0 & 21.641 & 0 & 15.302 & 0
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The values in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are also taken from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender _ interaction 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\left[\begin{matrix}85.137\\
79.179\\
84.284\\
80.597\\
82.4\\
78.362
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in previous examples we estimate the regression model's coefficients with the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}L$
\end_inset

.
 Our result is now:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{C} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}L\\
\left[\begin{matrix}c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
c_{3}\\
c_{4}
\end{matrix}\right] & \approx\left[\begin{matrix}71.4732\\
0.3818\\
8.121\\
-0.1427
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This we may put in our regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{c}_{1}+\hat{c}_{2}I+\hat{c}_{3}G+\hat{c}_{4}GI\label{eq: ols interaktion main result exempel}\\
 & =71.4732+0.3818I+8.1211G-0.1427*GI\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the capital letters now indicate individual variables,
 not matrices.
 Now we shall estimate how the interaction term 
\begin_inset Formula $GI$
\end_inset

 contributes to the covariation between the explanatory 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: interaktionseffekt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw that the total effect for a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 must include both the coefficient for that variable as well as the interaction effect:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=b+d*z$
\end_inset

.
 To estimate the total covariation between earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 we therefore take:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta I} & =\hat{c}_{2}+\hat{c}_{4}G=0.3818-0.1427*G\label{eq: beräknad interaktion 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta L/\Delta I$
\end_inset

 can be read as that for men,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G=0$
\end_inset

,
 on average one extra PPP USD in annual earnings on average coincides with 0.3818 years longer life expectancy.
 For women,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

,
 one extra PPP USD in annual earnings on average coincides to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3818-0.1427=0.2391$
\end_inset

 years (almost three months) longer average life expectancy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Men have lower life expectancy than women,
 but the relationship between life expectancy and earnings is more positive for men compared to women.
 The total relationship between gender 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and average life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 we can estimate from our regression model to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta G} & =\hat{c}_{3}+\hat{c}_{4}*I=8.1211+0.1427*I\label{eq: beräknad interaktion 2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 in our regression model we estimated to 71.4732 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols interaktion main result exempel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is the average life expectancy that our regression model indicates that people have,
 where the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 equal zero,
 that is,
 a woman 
\begin_inset Formula $G=0$
\end_inset

 without earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $I=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the person without earnings is a woman,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{3}=8.1211$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: beräknad interaktion 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 indicates that we expect that person to on average live 8.121 years longer.
 This relationship changes however at higher earnings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: livslängd inkomst kön"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates parts of the results in a diagram where we see the relationship between life expectancy and earnings.
 Two regression lines are drawn in the diagram,
 one for women and one for men.
 The regression line for women is drawn with the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{a}+\hat{b}\left(I|G=1\right)=79.5943+0.2391\left(I|G=1\right)\label{eq: interaktion ex, endast kvinnor}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(I|G=1\right)$
\end_inset

 means that we only use the observations for life expectancy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: earnings lifeexp gender _ interaction 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that represent women.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 are estimated with the least squares method .
 The regression line for men is drawn in the diagram with the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\hat{c}+\hat{d}\left(I|G=0\right)=71.4732+0.3818\left(I|G=0\right)\label{eq: interaktion ex endast män}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

