\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G=0$
\end_inset

,
 since the first two coefficients in both regression models are the same:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{1}=\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{2}=\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results in the regression model for men in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: interaktion ex endast män"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can simply be described as us adding together the coefficients in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols interaktion main result exempel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}=\hat{c}_{1}+\hat{c}_{3}=71.4732+8.1211=79.5943$
\end_inset

.
 And coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}=\hat{c}_{2}+\hat{c}_{4}=0.3818-0.1427=0.2391$
\end_inset

.
 The slope coefficient in the regression model for only men,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}$
\end_inset

,
 is the same value as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta L/\Delta I$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
