\begin_layout Section
Adjusted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: adj r^2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ssr sse sst vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which measures what proportion of the variation in the explained variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 that can be explained by the variation in the explanatory variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R^{2}=1-\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}-\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 indicates the difference between observed 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}-\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 indicates the difference between observed 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Say now that we have a regression model with k number of explanatory variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=b_{0}+b_{1}x_{1}+b_{2}x_{2}+...+b_{k}x_{k}+e\label{eq: regmodell ex r^2 inflatio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where all 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constant coefficients and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are explanatory variables.
 Coefficients and variables are numbered to mark that they differ from each other.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Let us rewrite the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 by reminding ourselves of how 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 is defined from the regression model:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =1-\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\left(\hat{b}_{0}+\hat{b}_{1}x_{1}+...+\hat{b}_{k}x_{k}+\hat{e}_{i}\right)\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 marks the number of the observation.
 Now we will add to our regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regmodell ex r^2 inflatio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 another explanatory variable:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 and its slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 The new regression model will have 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 number of explanatory variables.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for this new model becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{R^{2}}=1-\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\left(\hat{b}_{0}+\hat{b}_{1}x_{1}+...+\hat{b}_{k}x_{k}+\hat{b}_{k+1}x_{k+1}+\hat{e}_{i}\right)\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The squared parenthesis in the numerator increases,
 or alternatively remains unchanged if the new term 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k+1}x_{k+1}=0.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for this new model is equal to or greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the model with fewer variables.
 If we add more variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 risks increasing even though the new regression model we thereby create cannot explain variations in the explained variable more than the previous regression model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This does not mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a worthless measure but we must be aware of these characteristics when we use it.
 Another common measure is adjusted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\text{adj}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R^{2}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r@
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

!adjusted
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{R^{2}}=1-\left(1-R^{2}\right)\frac{n-1}{n-k-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

