where k is the number of explanatory variables and n is the number of observations.
 For the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx+v$
\end_inset

 we have one explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with an associated coefficient,
 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 In the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx+cz+v$
\end_inset

 we have the two explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx+cz+e$
\end_inset

 from the chapter's introduction.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-med y yhat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes with rounded results the calculations we need,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R^{2} & =1-\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}\approx1-\frac{0.34}{5}\approx0.9324
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (adjusted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{R^{2}} & =1-\left(1-R^{2}\right)\frac{n-1}{n-k-1}\\
 & =1-0.0676*\left(\frac{4-1}{4-2-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \approx0.7973\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result shows that our estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R^{2}}<R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The difference arises due to the adjustment for the number of explanatory variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
If we have too few variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: omitted variable bias"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the least squares method we can estimate the covariation between two variables and hold constant other important variables by including these in the regression model.
 We may describe it as the goal of the method being that the covariation we estimate between the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and one of our explanatory variables,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 is the covariation that applies all else being equal.
 Sometimes the Latin phrase ceteris paribus is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But to be able to estimate the covariation between two variables all else being equal,
 the method requires that we in our regression analysis have in one way or another taken into account everything else.
 What is not included in the regression model must covary with our explanatory variable y in such a way that it is only random and can be captured by the regression model's error term.
 If we for example conduct a randomized experiment,
 create treatment and control groups through random assignment and compare the outcome for the groups with regression analysis,
 then our ambition with the random assignment is to ensure that nothing disturbs the covariation between the variables in the regression analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we work with a model of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx$
\end_inset

 the result can become seriously misleading if the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 actually depends on variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 If some other variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 can be expected to affect 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in a way that is not captured by the variable x that already is included in the model,
 we may need to include 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 to get a correct result.
 If one or more variables that should be included in the regression model are missing,
 this is called the regression model being underspecified.
