\begin_layout Plain Layout
omitted variable bias
\end_layout

\end_inset

The impact a missing variable in a regression model has on the other variables is called omitted variable bias (often abbreviated OVB).
 We illustrate OVB by comparing the two regression models with the fictitious data we used in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ols på tre variabler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna y x z k20"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 repeats the observations we will use.
 We reuse the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{i} & =\hat{a}_{1}+\hat{b}_{1}x_{i}+v_{i}=1+0,5x_{i}+v_{i}\label{eq: OVB regmodell 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we number the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to indicate that this is model 1.
 We also have the results from the second regression model,
 which we have also estimated previously:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{i} & =\hat{a}_{2}+\hat{b}_{2}x_{i}+\hat{c}_{2}z_{i}+e_{i}=2.9+0.3x_{i}-0.5z_{i}+e_{i}\label{eq: OVB regmodell 2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we number the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 with 2.
 We see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{1}=0.5$
\end_inset

 when we have one explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{2}=0.3$
\end_inset

 when we have two explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Given that variable z should be included in our model,
 we note that there is a bias in the result for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 In this simple fictitious example it is possible to estimate the size of the bias,
 that is,
 how incorrect our estimated result for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 becomes due to our omitting 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 For this we use the observations in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variablerna y x z"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to estimate the covariation between the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 With the least squares method we now estimate a regression model where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{i} & =\hat{\beta}_{1}+\hat{\beta}_{2}z_{i}+u_{i}=5.7-0.4z_{i}+u_{i}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 The calculation of the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not described here but is left as an exercise for the reader.
 The results for these are rounded.
 The bias in the result for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 that arises in the first regression model (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: OVB regmodell 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is what is called omitted variable bias (OVB):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Omitted Variable Bias: }} & =\hat{b}_{2}+\hat{c}_{2}\hat{\beta}_{2}\\
 & =0.3+\left(-0.5\right)\left(-0.4\right)\nonumber \\
 & =0.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the same result as what we found for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the first regression model where we only have one explanatory variable x.
 This example is fictitious and here we easily get to know that z should be included in the regression model and moreover we have observations for all involved variables.
 The purpose of this exercise is however to illustrate a more complex problem.
 Whether an additional variable,
 such as z,
 should be included in a regression model is often a more complicated question,
 many times without any simple answer.
 In many situations this is primarily a qualitative question that is best answered by the theory behind the analysis.
 Unfortunately there is rarely or never any simple clear answer to exactly which variables should be included in a regression model.
 It depends on what is being studied and in what way,
 that is,
 what the purpose and method of the investigation is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation we have performed in this section of bias as a result of a missing variable illustrates the importance of not missing any variable.
 In practice we may sometimes reason our way to conclude that a variable,
 a phenomenon,
 is missing in our regression model but simultaneously face the problem that no data exists for this phenomenon.
 That we lack data is however no reason to ignore a problem.
 It simply means that our results become misleading,
 regardless of whether we have all the data we wish for or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
If we have too many variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: overfitting"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!over specified
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the previous section we described how the result in a regression analysis can become incorrect if one or more variables are missing in the regression model.
 It is easy in such a situation to be tempted to insert more variables into the model for safety's sake.
 But since all variables included in a regression model can affect also the results concerning all other variables,
 this can lead to other problems.
 As an example,
 our estimates can become incorrect if we insert wrong variables into the model.
 Having too much information in a regression model leads to the regression model becoming overspecified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regression analysis can among other things be used to predict future outcomes.
 A regression model with many variables may possibly explain variations in the explained variable's historical observations.
 But if the result is too dependent on a large and complex regression model,
 it risks reducing our possibilities to make statements about future observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we suspect that our regression model may be overspecified,
 there are several methods for testing and handling this.
 A simple method is to remove one or a few observations at a time and estimate the regression model without this or these.
 A regression model that is overspecified will have difficulty predicting the observations that are removed.
 But just as with underspecification,
 there is unfortunately no simple method that can guarantee identification of exactly which variables should be included in a regression model and often it is simply something we must reason and work our way towards in each individual analysis and situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The error term does not need to 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

approach zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In regression analysis it is easy to believe that the error term 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 always should approach 0,
 that is,
 that the regression model should create a line that lies very close to the points and thereby be able to explain all variation in the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 That might be the case for some models.
 But not in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use regression analysis to study a causal relationship and estimate what effect a phenomenon X has on Y.
 Given that we have controlled for all important factors that affect the effect,
 the error terms capture variation in Y that is not explained by our analysis.
 The error terms instead capture other things that do not affect the effect we are interested in.
 As long as the error terms are random noise,
 there is no reason why the sum of error terms should approach 0.
 X can still affect Y even if many other things can also affect Y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand this we may think of an example.
 Suppose we want to study whether medicine X affects headache Y in a collection of patients,
 divided into treatment and control groups.
 We find that medicine X affects headache Y.
 But medicine X is of course not the only thing that affects a headache.
 Other potential factors include a patient's age,
 food,
 drink,
 general health and so on.
 Our analysis is correctly designed (there is a true effect between medicine and headache) but cannot explain all variation in Y.
 The variation we cannot explain is captured by the error term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The error terms can also represent uncertainty in measurements,
 such as our variables being data about people that contain small random measurement errors.
 Many social science phenomena are studied based on scarce information,
 partly because people are complex and a lot of parts of life is not easy to measure in any simple way.
 We often work with approximate measures and more or less subjective estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many times our regression model also describes a simplification of the relationship between the variables.
 In reality the relation we study is not exactly linear.
 But even so,
 linear covariation often works surprisingly well.
 In these cases the error terms also do not become 0.
 In certain situations it would require very much work to construct a non-linear regression model that represents the relationship between the variables.
 But a completely correct model might still not help for the specific purpose with our analysis.
 Linear models instead give a rough and often sufficiently good picture of the relationship between variables,
 even if the error terms do not become 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regression models can be described with matrices:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=XB+V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations for the explained variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix where all rows in the first column have the value 1 and the other columns consists of the observations for the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},...,x_{k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with all coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},...,b_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the constant.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 error terms.
 The least squares estimator:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\left(X'X\right)^{-1}X'Y$
\end_inset

 where all coefficients in the model are a function of all explanatory variables in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The purpose of a regression model with multiple explanatory variables is to estimate the covariation between one explanatory variable and the explained variable,
 taking into account the covariation between all the other explanatory variables and the explained variable.
 This is called estimating the covariation for one explanatory variable while holding constant the variation in all other explanatory variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The goal of regression analysis is that we should take into account or control for all phenomena that are significant for the covariation we are studying.
 The phenomena that are not included in the model are represented by the error term.
 Underspecified:
 one or more variables are missing in the regression model.
 Overspecified:
 variables should be removed from the regression model.
 Both over- and underspecification can lead to incorrect results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a rough measure of what proportion of the variation in the explained variable Y that can be "explained" by the regression model and the explanatory variables.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 risks increasing if we add more variables.
 Adjusted
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not necessarily increase because more explanatory variables are included in the model.
\end_layout

