\begin_layout Section
Regression discontinuity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Regressionsdiskontinuitet"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!discontinuity
\end_layout

\end_inset

Regression discontinuity is a method for identifying and comparing treatment and control groups in an observational study.
 The method is based on us being able to observe variations around a threshold with significance for both treatment and outcome.
 Small variations around the threshold can be assumed to be random,
 which is why this can be used to divide observations into treatment and control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us again imagine that we are to study what effect an education has on participants' future earnings.
 Admission to the education occurs with an entrance exam where one must get at least 92 points to be admitted.
 We now think that those who got just over and under 92 points have equivalent skills.
 Some had a bad day and some had an unusually good day.
 The students who ended up just over 92 points and were admitted become our treatment group.
 The students who ended up just under 92 points and were not admitted become our control group.
 To check whether the treatment and control groups have equivalent skills we may compare the relevant characteristics,
 such as age,
 previous performance,
 previous education and so forth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider another example.
 Many countries have age limits for when one may buy stronger alcoholic beverages.
 That alcohol is directly harmful and also indirectly increases the risk of various negative effects is well-known.
 At the same time it can be difficult to estimate in detail the harmful effects (phenomenon Y) of increased access to alcohol (phenomenon X) at the societal level since people who fare badly may have other destructive habits (phenomena P and Z).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to estimate the effect is to use the age limit for purchasing alcoholic beverages as a threshold to estimate variations in consumption and harm around the time when people get increased access to alcohol.
 Carpenter and Dobkin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "carpenterEffectAlcoholConsumption2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present such an analysis for the USA,
 where the age limit is 21 years.
 Their work shows that drinking increases relatively sharply shortly after the 21st birthday while traffic accidents,
 suicides and various alcohol-related deaths increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exactly how we should design our regression model when we use regression discontinuity depends on what type of effects we want to study.
 We illustrate here two examples based on the data that Carpenter and Dobkin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "carpenterEffectAlcoholConsumption2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present.
 We begin with the following regression model:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{i}=a_{1}+a_{2}X_{i}+a_{3}T_{i}+u_{i}\label{eq: rdd ex1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the number of alcohol-related deaths per 100,000 inhabitants in respective age group i,
 where each age group is divided into months:
 19 years and 1 month,
 19 years and 2 months,
 and so on.
 Variable X is age calculated in months.
 T is a dummy variable that is 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 for the age groups that are under 21 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

 for the age groups that have turned 21.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error term for age group i.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 that is multiplied by T will in this regression model describe the effect that the 21st birthday has on alcohol-related mortality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rdd ex1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 estimates the covariation between mortality 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y\right)$
\end_inset

 and age 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But this covariation can also be thought to change when a person turns 21.
 To control for this we add an interaction term for X*T:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{i}=b_{1}+b_{2}X_{i}+b_{3}T_{i}+b_{4}\left(X_{i}*T_{i}\right)+V_{i}\label{eq: rdd ex2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},b_{2},b_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{4}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y,X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are the same variables as in the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rdd ex1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 The interaction term 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{4}\left(X_{i}*T_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 estimates changes in the covariation between alcohol consumption and mortality.
