Compare figure 3 in Carpenter and Dobkin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "carpenterEffectAlcoholConsumption2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Data available here:
 https://github.com/jrnold/masteringmetrics/blob/master/
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The vertical line in the middle of each graph marks the time when the people in the study turn 21.
 To the left of the line the average number of deaths is shown for people just under 21 and to the right deaths for those who have just turned 21.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the left graph we see two regression lines,
 where both are estimated with the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rdd ex1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The regression line to the left,
 for the age groups under 21,
 is drawn with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 and slopes downward.
 For the age groups over 21,
 to the right in the left graph,
 the regression line is drawn with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

.
 The right regression line in the left graph shifts up at 21 years of age,
 which indicates that mortality rises sharply after the 21st birthday as people have the opportunity to buy alcohol.
 The two regression lines in the left graph have the same slope,
 since we only estimate one slope coefficient for age in the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rdd ex1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the right graph we also see two regression lines that are estimated based on the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: rdd ex2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the age groups over 21,
 to the right in the graph,
 the line shifts up.
 The slope also changes.
 For the age groups under 21,
 to the left in the right graph,
 a positive correlation between alcohol-related mortality and age is visible.
 For the age groups over 21 a negative correlation between alcohol-related mortality and age is instead visible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Instrumental variable
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Instrumentell-variabel"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
instrumental variable
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to handle the problems that observable and non-observable phenomena like P and Z entail is to use instrumental variable analysis.
 The method is based on us finding another phenomenon S that is not affected by Z,
 does not affect Y directly but affects X,
 and thereby Y.
 A random variation in S causes a variation in X which in turn affects Y.
 The effect S has on X is possible to isolate and thereby also estimate the variation in X (caused by S) that affects Y.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: iv instrumentell var"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the basic logic in this.
 Phenomenon S affects only Y via its impact on X.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../texten/g_iv.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: iv instrumentell var"

\end_inset

Instrumental variable S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instrumental variable analysis is used for different things within social science.
 The oldest known example was presented in a book by Philip G.
 Wright 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "wrightTariffAnimalVegetable1928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and was based on work together with his son Sewal.
 Wright wanted to estimate the price elasticity in supply and demand for linseed oil,
 that is,
 percentage changes in supply or demand at percentage price changes (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Elasticitet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Utbud-och-efterfrågan"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we directly compare the covariation between price and quantity in society we cannot distinguish whether we observe the shape of the supply and demand curves (elasticity),
 or observe different points where supply and demand meet (price and quantity in equilibrium).
 To handle this Wright instead observed different phenomena that can be thought to shift the supply or demand curve,
 without affecting the other curve.
 For example Wright argued that the yield per cultivation hectare affects supply without affecting demand,
 which is why short-term changes in yield can be used as an instrumental variable to study how the supply curve moves while the demand curve is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instrumental variables are also commonly occurring within studies concerning cause and effect.
 Angrist 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "angristLifetimeEarningsVietnam1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 compared in a well-known study economic effects for American soldiers who participated in the Vietnam War.
 One way to study this is to compare former military personnel's earnings with the rest of the male population.
 The selection of soldiers risks however distorting the results,
 if the men who did military service perhaps had other conditions than the rest of the population.
 For example,
 perhaps many men knew that they had poor conditions in the labor market and therefore chose voluntarily to enlist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the early 1970s the American state arranged a lottery that gave young adult men a number randomly,
 which determined whether they would be forced to go to Vietnam.
 The lottery (instrumental variable S) explains variation in war participation (variable X) but has no direct impact on participants' earnings (variable Y).
 However S can affect Y via the effect S has on X and thereby on Y.
 Angrist's analysis shows that the men who through the lottery were assigned military service had clearly worse earnings ten years after the war compared to corresponding men who did not participate in the war.
 This broke at least partly with other previous studies that instead found that war veterans on average had better economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practical terms regression analysis with instrumental variables can proceed in slightly different ways.
 Here we content ourselves with a simpler description of a popular method,
 called Two-Stage Least Squares (abbreviated 2SLS),
 which in Swedish means roughly the least squares method in two stages.
 We have the regression model:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Two-Stage Least Squares
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+u\label{eq: 2sls ex1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where a and b are coefficients,
 u is error term and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are the variables.
 We have good reasons to believe that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 causes changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 but that another factor (phenomenon 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

) explains variations in both 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Mathematically this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 covaries with the error term u,
 that is,
 the covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(cov\right)$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and u is not equal to 0:
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(X,u\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

 (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Minstakvadratmetodens villkor . Gauss-Markov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To handle this we use the instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 which correlates with 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 but not with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to describe this is that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 does not covary with the error term 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(S,u\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 explains variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and thereby indirectly also affects 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 What we are now seeking is a measure of what influence 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and thereby on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 which we can describe with the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=c+dS+v\label{eq: 2sls ex2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model captures the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that is caused by 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The predicted variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 from this regression model we then use to create the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=e+f\hat{X}+\epsilon
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is error term and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is still the explained variable that we are primarily interested in.
 Given that we have done right and not missed any other important phenomenon,
 the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can now be interpreted as the effect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 has on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 For more comprehensive descriptions and discussions about instrumental variables see for example 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "angristInstrumentalVariablesSearch2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 och 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bollenInstrumentalVariablesSociology2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Difference-in-differences
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Skillnad-i-skillnad"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
difference-in-differences
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!difference-in-differences
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to distribute observations between treatment and control groups and study causal relationships and effects is the method called difference-in-differences (diff-in-diff or DiD).
 The method is based on us identifying a treatment group whose development we follow over time.
 We also manage to identify a group that is untreated but that we have good reasons to believe illustrates the parallel development that our treatment group would have had if cause X had never taken place.
 By comparing the difference between the groups before and after a treatment the difference in the difference can be interpreted as a measure of effect size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Skillnad-i-skillnad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the method where we compare the development for a control and treatment group.
 The time before X occurs the outcome variable Y for the two groups develops in parallel.
 When X occurs the upper solid line shows the development for the treatment group.
 The dashed line for the treatment group shows the counterfactual development that we theoretically assume that the treatment group would have had if no treatment X had taken place.
 The dashed line follows the control group in parallel and is based on the theoretical assumption that the two groups would have followed each other in precisely this way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_did.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Skillnad-i-skillnad"

\end_inset

Difference-in-differences
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A well-known example of this method was presented in an academic article by Card and Krueger 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "cardMinimumWagesEmployment1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 During the spring of 1992 minimum wages were raised in New Jersey,
 a state in the US,
 from $4.25 to $5.05.
 Corresponding wages were unchanged in the nearby state of Pennsylvania.
 Card and Krueger used this difference to study how minimum wages and employment within the fast food industry in the two states changed between February and November 1992.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors' results indicate that despite minimum wages being raised in New Jersey but not in Pennsylvania,
 no increased differences in employment between the states are noticeable among the groups affected by the minimum wages.
 These results,
 together with several others on similar themes,
 contributed to a renewed discussion about how both minimum wages and wages in general function in a social economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now describe a regression model to estimate difference-in-differences.
 Suppose we have data over individuals distributed across treatment and control groups and want to compare these before and after a treatment (as in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Skillnad-i-skillnad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We set up the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{it}=a+bT_{t}+cG_{i}+d\left(T_{t}*G_{i}\right)+u_{it}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 are coefficients.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the explained variable we are interested in for individual i at time point t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the error term per individual and time point.
 We have only two time points,
 before and after,
 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The number of individuals is all participants in the treatment and control groups.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a dummy variable for time point 1 respectively 2,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 (before) respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

 (after).
 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a dummy variable for the control group 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(G=0\right)$
\end_inset

 respectively the treatment group 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(G=1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $bT_{t}$
\end_inset

 measures any difference in the y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 before and after treatment.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}*G_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a combined dummy variable that equals 1 for the treatment group at time point 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 (after treatment).
 The slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 measures the difference-in-differences between the two groups,
 which we interpret as an effect of cause 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pros and cons with these methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
research design
\end_layout

\end_inset

This section briefly goes through some known challenges with the methods described in the chapter.
 Challenges do not mean that a method is bad.
 Understanding a method's limitations is important for us to understand methods in depth.
 We began this chapter by noting that there is no objective method for determining which variables should be included in a regression model.
 Unfortunately there is also no objective method for testing whether our theoretical assumptions in an effect analysis are correct.
 The design of an analysis is a largely qualitative aspect of analytical work.
 We need to familiarize ourselves with a specific situation and have good knowledge of the processes behind the emergence of the experimental situation.
 We must in each study examine and think about whether our treatment and control groups are comparable in the way that our analysis requires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to think about and study carefully what is a suitable instrumental variable and ensure that its impact on the outcome variable goes precisely via our explanatory variable.
 If we are to use the difference-in-differences method we need to be sure that the groups are comparable in precisely the way that our regression model describes.
 In the same way we must be sure that the threshold we use for our regression discontinuity really is useful for dividing the observations into control and treatment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes quasi-experiments can be conducted based on variations in nature,
 such as weather or natural disasters.
 Sometimes precisely this type of quasi-experiment is described as natural experiments.
 But even then we must ensure that our treatment and control groups are comparable and that no phenomenon P or Z affects our analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we want to be able to generalize our results to large groups of observations that lie outside the data we have access to for our study.
 By using quasi-experiments we may capture a causal effect.
 But to be able to measure causal effects we must often delimit our analysis carefully and then the results also risk becoming more limited.
 For example the results in Angrist 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "angristLifetimeEarningsVietnam1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 indicate that military service in Vietnam during the 1970s as a result of state coercion had a negative impact on soldiers' future earnings.
 But most American soldiers in the Vietnam War participated voluntarily and their earnings were perhaps affected in other ways compared to those who were forced 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "cf."
key "angristEstimatingLaborMarket1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Skillnad-i-skillnad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described how Card and Krueger 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "cardMinimumWagesEmployment1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 concluded that raised minimum wages in New Jersey did not lead to decreased employment compared to the development in the nearby state of Pennsylvania.
 This does not mean that we can draw the conclusion that a raise of all wages simultaneously in the entire labor market would not affect employment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An individual study should as a rule be interpreted carefully.
 There is today an enormous amount of research around masses of phenomena.
 It is first when we get a more coherent picture of the research literature that it is possible to form a more general opinion about the world.
 On the other hand there are unfortunately many questions that are important for society but that probably will never be possible to study with either controlled experiments or quasi-experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Causality without covariation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
causality
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we design our analysis to study causal relationships it is required that we find covariation for us to be able to claim that a causal relationship exists.
 In practice it is however easy to imagine different situations where a causal relationship exists between two variables,
 but where a regression analysis still will not find any covariation.
 This is yet another reason to be humble before estimated results.
 This section gives some simple examples of why we could fail to find covariation between two phenomena despite there being a causal relationship between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Wrong sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we investigate why so few students want to take our course in mathematics and statistics.
 To find this out we conduct a survey among the students who are already taking our course.
 Regardless of how we design this type of survey the study will not give us particularly much useful information.
 The students who are already taking the course are probably not representative of the entire population of potential students,
 which is the group we are really interested in.
 That is,
 there may be a result,
 a causal relationship,
 in a population.
 But our study examines a sample where we will not find any results for the population we are really interested in (compare section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Den-sanna-regressionsmodellen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Wrong variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through how both the presence and absence of variables in a regression model can affect all results from the model.
 Suppose we investigate the covariation between disease X and its impact on mortality and people's lives in general.
 This particular disease has however been known for a long time and in recent years several effective medicines have been developed that slow its effects.
 If we miss taking into account the counteracting treatments our results will also become misleading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Wrong model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: en linje är en linje"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw examples of covariation that we do not succeed in capturing with a linear regression model (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: weird ols 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Say for example that the government introduces an education program for the unemployed and we are to study what effect this has on participants' opportunities to get jobs.
 But the effect of the program varies between time periods,
 depending on the economy's ups and downs.
 In bad times the education program shortens participants' time in unemployment.
 In good times people are encouraged to participate in an education they do not need.
 When we estimate the covariation between education and participants' opportunities for work we miss controlling for these circumstances and find no relationship,
 despite such a one existing,
 sometimes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Within social science it is difficult to conduct controlled experiments,
 which is why we instead often use quasi-experimental observational studies.
 Often we want to identify a process that means that the distribution to treatment and control groups has occurred randomly.
 We must also adjust for all observed and non-observed phenomena that can be thought to affect cause and outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regression discontinuity is a way to compare treatment and control groups through random variation around a threshold.
 Differences between the groups can be interpreted as an effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instrumental variable analysis can be used to study how X causes an effect in Y.
 An instrumental variable Z can predict variation in variable X and thereby Y,
 but has no direct impact on Y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The difference-in-differences method means that we assume that the counterfactual outcome can be described as a parallel trend of a control group.
 Difference in the differences between treatment and control before and after a treatment is interpreted as effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Causal relationships require some form of covariation.
 But causal relationships can also exist when we do not find covariation,
 if we for example have the wrong sample,
 wrong variables or wrong regression model.
\end_layout

