In previous chapters we have worked with variables defined by a mathematical function over a domain,
 for example the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 defined over all real numbers.
 We have worked with data variables consisting of collected information,
 observations.
 When we went through regression analysis in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Regressionsanalys"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we worked with variables that we predicted using regression models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we are now going to work with probability and chance we will use random variables.
 A random variable is a variable whose results are affected by a random process.
 For example,
 when I go to the bus in the morning I do not know exactly how many other passengers will ride the same bus as me.
 The buses run frequently and the number of passengers varies for each trip from zero to around 50 passengers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Random variables are defined by mathematical functions that describe the probability for the values (outcomes) that the variable can assume.
 Say for example that we have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that can assume two different values:
 the number 1 or 2.
 These values are the sample space for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M:\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The probability for each outcome is 50%.
 We describe 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with the probability function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the function is called 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 after the word probability:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(M=1\right) & =\frac{1}{2}=0.5=50\%\label{eq: singla slant}\\
P\left(M=2\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
probability!event
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
probability!experiment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!discrete
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!continuous
\end_layout

\end_inset

The total probability for the two possible outcomes in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 0.5 + 0.5 = 1,
 that is 100%.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: singla slant"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is an example of a probability distribution.
 We say that the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 follows a discrete probability distribution,
 since the distribution has a limited number of outcomes.
 An experiment,
 or trial,
 is called the process that leads to an outcome.
 An event refers to one or several outcomes,
 a subset of the sample space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A continuous probability distribution has an infinite number of outcomes within one or several intervals.
 Say for example that a random variable X can assume all possible decimals between 0 and 1 (the sample space) with the same probability.
 Theoretically,
 X can assume the value 0.23 with the same probability as 0.9999345.
 There are infinitely many decimals and therefore infinitely many outcomes.
 Since there are infinitely many outcomes,
 the probability,
 mathematically,
 for each specific value approaches 0.
 For a continuously random variable we therefore instead calculate the probability for an interval of outcomes.
 For example,
 there is a 50% probability for the event that X assumes a value between 0 and 0.5 and 50% probability that X assumes a value between 0.5 and 1.
 We return to discrete probability distributions in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Diskret-sannolikhet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and to continuous probability distributions in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:kontinuerlig sannolikhet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are infinitely many probability distributions.
 As long as we can come up with a new description of a probability distribution,
 it exists.
 Say now that we have a six-sided die T with the numbers 1 to 6 and that each side has an equal probability of coming up,
 one sixth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability for the different outcomes can be described:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(T=t\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{6} & t=1,2,3,4,5,6\\
0 & \text{annars}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total probability for all outcomes is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}*6=1=100\%$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we instead have a six-sided die 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 with the integers 1 to 6,
 which is unbalanced in such a way that the probability for outcome 3 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{7}$
\end_inset

 while the probability for each other outcome is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{7}$
\end_inset

.
 The number 7 in the denominator is not the number of sides on the die but follows from the variable's probability distribution.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be summarized as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(X_{2}=x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{7} & x=1,2,4,5,6\\
\frac{2}{7} & x=3\\
0 & \text{annars}
\end{cases}\label{eq: sannolikhetsfunktion viktad tärning}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

