status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!two dices
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us now assume that we have two six-sided perfectly balanced dice,
 one red and one black with the numbers 1 to 6.
 The probability for each unique result with t number of perfectly balanced six-sided dice can generally be described as:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{6}\right)^{t}=\frac{1}{6^{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 With one die the probability for each result is 1/6.
 With two dice it is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/6^{2}=1/36$
\end_inset

.
 With two dice there are 36 possible combinations.
 The probability that we get the point sum 2 is the same as the point sum 12:
 1/36.
 With three dice 
\begin_inset Formula $1/6^{3}=1/216$
\end_inset

.
 
