Now we will calculate the probability for the total point sum for the two dice,
 which we call variable Z.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Två-tärningar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this probability distribution in a table with the 36 possible combinations of the two dice and a graph that shows the number of possible outcomes that result in each point sum,
 from 2 to 12 points.
 The probability for outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=3$
\end_inset

 is 2/36,
 which we see by adding together the probability for each unique result that gives this point sum,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{red},\text{black}\right)=\left(1,2\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The result that red die = 1 and black die = 2,
 is considered the same result as red die = 2 and black = 1:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(Z=3\right)=\frac{1}{36}+\frac{1}{36}=\frac{2}{36}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Outcome 7 is given by most combinations:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,6\right),\left(6,1\right),\left(2,5\right),\left(5,2\right),\left(3,4\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4,3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This outcome therefore has the highest probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(Z=7\right) & =\frac{1+1+1+1+1+1}{36}=\frac{6}{36}=\frac{1}{6}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The probability of getting 3 points or less with the two dice,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\leq3$
\end_inset

,
 can be calculated in the following way.
 There are three squares out of 36 possible for this result and the probability can therefore be calculated as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(Z\leq3\right) & =P\left(2\right)+P\left(3\right)=\frac{1}{36}+\frac{2}{36}=\frac{3}{36}=\frac{1}{12}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

