\series bold
Conditional probability:

\series default
 Conditional probability describes the probability that a variable X assumes a value x,
 given that another random variable Y assumes a value y,
 which can be written:
 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X=x|Y=y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Say for example that we are to choose a ball at random from one hundred balls,
 of which 80 are red and 20 are yellow.
 Half of the balls of each color are hollow and half are filled,
 see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Tre-sorters-bollar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The probability of getting a red ball is 80/100=4/5 and a yellow ball 20/100=1/5.
 The probability for hollow or filled is 1/2 regardless of color.
 If X = color and Y = hollow/filled then the probability of getting a red ball,
 given that the ball is hollow:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X=\text{red}|Y=\text{hollow}\right) & =\frac{40}{50}=\frac{4}{5}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We divide the number of red hollow balls 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(40\right)$
\end_inset

 by the number of hollow balls in total 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(50\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that a ball is filled,
 given that it is yellow is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(Y=\text{filled}|X=\text{yellow}\right) & =\frac{10}{20}=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expected value and variance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Väntevärde"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: väntevärde och varians"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mean!weighted
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a random variable we cannot estimate (calculate) a mean in the way that we do for a collection of discrete values,
 such as a collection of numbers.
 Instead we use what is called expected value,
 also called expectation value.
 Expected value is a generalization of the weighted mean.
 The expected value for a random variable is the sum of each outcome multiplied by its probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(M\right)=\sum_{i}^{n}m_{i}P\left(m_{i}\right)\label{eq: väntevärde viktat medel}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the expected value function,
 which can also be written 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[M\right]$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for population 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 For variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that has outcomes 1 and 2 each with 0.5 probability,
 the expected value is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(M\right) & =m_{1}*P\left(m_{1}\right)+m_{2}*P\left(m_{2}\right)=1*0.5+2*0.5=1.5\label{eq: väntevärde mynt ex 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we instead have a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with outcomes 1 and 2 with 75% and 25% probability respectively.
 The expected value then becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(H\right) & =1*0.75+2*0.25=1.25
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value function 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 is a linear function,
 which can be described as that given that we have the random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 the following applies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X+Y\right)=E\left(X\right)+E\left(Y\right)\label{eq: väntevärde plus väntevärde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have two six-sided perfectly balanced dice 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 each with the possible outcomes 1 to 6 where each outcome has 1/6 probability,
 then the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=E\left(Y\right)=3.5$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 plus the expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)+E\left(Y\right)=3.5+3.5=7\label{eq: väntevärde tärning 1 plus 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us call the point sum for the two dice 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Its expected value is given by:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(Z\right) & =\frac{2+6+12+20+30+42+40+36+30+22+12}{36}=7\label{eq: väntevärde 2 tärningar}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we added the expected value for X and Y we got result 7,
 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde tärning 1 plus 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another way to write this is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(Z\right)=E\left(X+Y\right)=E\left(X\right)+E\left(Y\right)=7
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Compare equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde plus väntevärde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The linearity of expected value also has significance when we multiply a random variable by a constant.
 Say for example that we have an arbitrary constant,
 a.
 If we multiply the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 by a this is the same thing as a multiplied by each individual value in variable X:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(aX\right)=aE\left(X\right)\label{eq: väntevärde konstant}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!and variance
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance!and expected value
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we instead add a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we may also move this out of the expected value function,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(aX+b\right)=aE\left(X\right)+b$
\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we defined variance for population and sample.
 For a random discrete variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 variance can be defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}=E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability for each value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value we defined in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde viktat medel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}P\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For a probability distribution where all values have the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations,
 the variance is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can for example describe the variance for a perfectly balanced six-sided die where all values have the probability
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

.
 We will now see how variance and expected value are connected:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(X\right) & =\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}^{2}-2\mu_{X}x_{i}+\mu_{X}^{2}\right)P\left(x_{i}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We remove the parentheses and move in the summation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a constant we can move this out of the summation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(X\right) & =\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)-2\mu_{X}\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}P\left(x_{i}\right)+\mu_{X}^{2}\sum_{i}^{n}P\left(x_{i}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}P\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the same as the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde viktat medel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 can also be written 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of probabilities for all possible outcomes is by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}^{n}P\left(x_{i}\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
 that is 100%.
 Based on this we now write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(X\right) & =\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}^{2}P\left(x_{i}\right)-2\mu_{X}\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}P\left(x_{i}\right)+\mu_{X}^{2}\sum_{i}^{n}P\left(x_{i}\right)\\
 & =E\left(X^{2}\right)-2\mu_{X}^{2}+\mu_{X}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =E\left(X^{2}\right)-\mu_{X}^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=E\left(X^{2}\right)-\left(E\left(X\right)\right)^{2}\label{eq: varians av väntevärde 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E\left(X\right)\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 squared.
 Variance can also be expressed as the expected value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=E\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\label{eq: var(x)  = E( x- mu)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One way to think about the meaning of this expression is that variance is a value (a constant) that describes the spread in a variable.
 The expected value describes this spread in a random variable's population.
 To see that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: varians av väntevärde 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: var(x)  = E( x- mu)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are the same thing we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(x\right) & =E\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\label{eq: var väntevärde mu}\\
 & =E\left(X-E\left(X\right)\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =E\left(X^{2}-2XE\left(X\right)+E\left(X\right)^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =E\left(X^{2}\right)-2E\left(X\right)E\left(X\right)+E\left(X\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =E\left(X^{2}\right)-\left(E\left(X\right)\right)^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we now have 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(aX+b\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 och 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are constants we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(aX+b\right)=a^{2}\text{var}\left(X\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is,
 a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 that is multiplied by the random variable can be moved out of the variance function 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 and multiplied by itself.
 The second constant 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 disappears.
 The positive square root of the variance for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is also in this case the standard deviation and can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}=s\left(x\right)=\sqrt{var\left(x\right)}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 represents the variance in the population (a constant).
 For standard deviation it applies that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s\left(aX+b\right)=\left|a\right|s\left(X\right)\label{eq: s(aX+b)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that if we multiply a random variable X by a constant a then its variance and standard deviation are multiplied,
 but it does not change the form of the spread (compare section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conditional expected value
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Betingat-väntevärde"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!conditional
\end_layout

\end_inset

The expected value for a variable can also depend on the outcome of another variable.
 This is called conditional expected value.
 If the outcome of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 depends on variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 the conditional expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(Y|X\right)=\sum_{i}y_{i}P\left(Y|X\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say for example that random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a perfectly balanced six-sided die,
 values 1 to 6,
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a perfectly balanced coin with sample space 1 or 2 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X=1$
\end_inset

 the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are 1 to 6.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X=2$
\end_inset

 we add 10 to the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 which is why Y=11 to 16.
 The sample space for the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 together:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6,11,12,13,14,15,16\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The conditional expected value for variable Y given 
\begin_inset Formula $X=1$
\end_inset

 and X=2 can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(Y|X=1\right)=3.5 & ,\qquad E\left(Y|X=2\right)=13.5
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!the law of total
\end_layout

\end_inset

The conditional expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is its own random variable with its own probability distribution for the sample space with integers 1 to 6 and integers 11 to 16.
 The law of total expectation:
 is a useful rule.
 For the random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 this can be formulated:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(E\left(Y|X\right)\right)=E\left(Y\right)\label{eq: lagen om totalt väntevärde, law of iterated exp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value of the conditional expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(Y|X\right)$
\end_inset

 is the same as the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(Y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate using the coin 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and the die 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 from the previous example.
 The law of total expectation gives:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(E\left(Y|X\right)\right) & =E\left(Y|X=1\right)P\left(X=1\right)+E\left(Y|X=2\right)P\left(X=2\right)\\
 & =3.5*\frac{1}{2}+13.5*\frac{1}{2}\nonumber \\
 & =8.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditional expected value function also has the following property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(XY|X\right)=XE\left(Y|X\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are random variables.
 The equation means that the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 times 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the same thing as 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 times the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 To see this we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(XY|X\right)=\sum_{i}xy_{i}P\left(Y|X\right)=x\sum_{i}y_{i}P\left(Y|X\right)=XE\left(Y|X\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Law of large numbers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: stora talens lag"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Law of Large Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

The more experiments that are conducted with a random variable,
 the greater the probability that the results approach the population value.
 This also means that the larger sample we take,
 the greater the probability that an estimated mean corresponds with the population's expected value.
 This is called the law of large numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We illustrate this with a random variable where the possible outcomes are integers 1 to 6 and where each outcome has the probability 1/6,
 which is why the expected value is 3.5 (like a six-sided perfectly balanced die).
 We let the computer choose an integer randomly between 1 and 6.
 Then choose two values and calculate the mean for these,
 then three values and so on until we have 1,000 means,
 where the last mean is calculated from 1,000 randomly created integers between 1 and 6.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_dicemeans.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Simulerade-tärningsresultat"

\end_inset

Law of large numbers with simulated results for a dice with the values 1 to 6
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Simulerade-tärningsresultat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the 1,000 results in two graphs,
 where the left graph only illustrates the first ten means and the right graph shows all calculated results,
 including those visible in the left graph.
 On the horizontal x-axis in both graphs the number of random values used to calculate the mean at that point is described.
 The point furthest to the right in the right graph is the mean of 1,000 randomly chosen integers between 1 and 6.
 Exactly as the law of large numbers predicts,
 these means approach the expected value 3.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More formally,
 the law of large numbers can be formulated in the following way:
 suppose we have an infinite sequence of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},X_{2},...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 that have the same expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X_{1}\right)=E\left(X_{2}\right)=...=\mu
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of these variables is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X_{n}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law of large numbers can then be expressed as that the following limit value is 1 when n approaches infinity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}P\left(\left|\bar{X}_{n}-\mu\right|<\epsilon\right)=1\label{eq: stora talens lag 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\bar{X_{n}}-\mu\right|$
\end_inset

 is the absolute value of the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{n}}$
\end_inset

 minus the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 describes the probability for an outcome.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary positive value,
 for example a very low value close to 0.
 The entire equation can be read as that the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\bar{X_{n}}-\mu\right|$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 approaches 100% when the number of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 grows to infinity,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to describe this is that the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{n}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 approaches 0 and this difference will be less than the low value 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The definition in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: stora talens lag 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is called the law of large numbers in weak form.
 The law of large numbers in strong form can be formulated:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\bar{X}_{n}=\mu\right)=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This should be read as that the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{n}}$
\end_inset

 instead becomes equal to the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity.
 The probability for this,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is equal to 1,
 that is 100%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Uniform Probability Distributions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Likformig diskret sannolikhetsfördelning"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!discrete variable
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
discrete!random variable
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability!function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!probability
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have now in different examples used the probability function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 to describe the probability for specific outcomes.
 For a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 we will now clarify that when we want to define the probability for a specific value we use the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 describe the same thing so far:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(m\right)=P\left(M=m\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For discrete probability distributions the probability function f is called probability mass function,
 PMF.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde viktat medel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described the expected value for a random discrete variable as possible outcomes multiplied by the probability for these.
 If we instead of the probability function P use f,
 the expected value for random variable M can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(M\right)=\sum_{i}^{n}m_{i}f\left(m_{i}\right)\label{eq: väntevärde diskret sannolikhet}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will introduce what is called the cumulative distribution function (CDF),
 or just the distribution function.
 The distribution function describes the probability that a random variable assumes a value within a specific interval.
 Here too we use the probability function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 to for example describe the probability that random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 assumes a value equal to or less than the value 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

,
 which we describe as 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(M\leq m\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We call the distribution function F:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cumulative distribution function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(m\right)=P\left(M\leq m\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we have a random variable X with sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 where each outcome has the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=P\left(X=x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{6} & x=1,2,3,4,5,6\\
0 & \text{annars}
\end{cases}\label{eq: pdf 1 tärning}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first row in the probability function describes the probability 1/6 for integers 1 to 6.
 The second row describes that for all other outcomes the probability is 0.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a uniform discrete probability distribution.
 The distribution is uniform because each outcome has the same probability.
 The distribution is discrete because there are a limited number of possible outcomes.
 That variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a uniform probability distribution can be described with the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim U\left(a,b\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where tilde 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 describes that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

,
 which is an abbreviation for uniform probability distribution.
 The letters a and b indicate the limits for the interval of the distribution's possible values.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=6$
\end_inset

,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim U\left(1,6\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For a discrete variable that follows a uniform probability distribution,
 the distribution function can be described generally as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{x-a+1}{b-a+1},\,\,x=a,a+1,...,b\label{eq: cdf uniform distro}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the lowest and highest integer that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can assume,
 that is 1 and 6 respectively.
 The distribution function for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{x}{6},\,\,x=1,2,3,4,5,6\label{eq: cdf 1 tärning}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example,
 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(2\right)=2/6$
\end_inset

,
 which means that the cumulative probability of getting outcome 1 or 2 is equal to 2/6.
 One may also describe the same distribution function as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \forall x<1\\
\frac{x}{6} & 1\leq x<6,\\
1 & 6\leq x
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we added the top row to describe that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<1$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\leq x$
\end_inset

 then increases stepwise for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1,2,3,4,5$
\end_inset

 and 6 to reach 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
 that is 100%,
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x=6$
\end_inset

 and upward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cumulative probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

 must by definition be a value between 0 and 1,
 between 0 and 100%.
 What then remains of 100% is the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X>x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-P\left(X>x\right)\label{eq: 1-P(M>m)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>x\right)$
\end_inset

 we calculate by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $1-F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which we see by rearranging the equation a bit:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>x\right) & =1-P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-F\left(x\right)\label{eq: p(X>x) omvänd sannolikhet 1- F}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the probability of getting 3 to 6 points is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>x\right) & =1-F\left(2\right)=1-\frac{2}{6}=\frac{4}{6}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is then:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(X\right) & =\sum_{i}x_{i}f\left(x_{i}\right)\\
 & =1*\frac{1}{6}+2*\frac{1}{6}+3*\frac{1}{6}+4*\frac{1}{6}+5*\frac{1}{6}+6*\frac{1}{6}\nonumber \\
 & =3.5\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


