\begin_layout Section
The binomial distribution
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Binomialfördelningen"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!binomial
\end_layout

\end_inset

Say now that we have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with the two outcomes 1 and 2 respectively,
 each with 50% probability.
 One can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as a perfectly balanced coin.
 We now define the probability for outcome 1 as the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5=50\%$
\end_inset

.
 The probability for the second outcome,
 value 2,
 must by definition be 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p=1-0.5=0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will describe the probability that we with variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 get more of outcome 2.
 Each individual result of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is independent of the previous result.
 The probability of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 number of outcome 2 in n trials can then be described with the following probability mass function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(k\right) & =P\left(M=k\right)=\binom{n}{k}p^{k}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}\label{eq: sannolikhetsfunktion pdf binominalfördelningen}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\binom{n}{k}=\frac{n!}{k!\left(n-k\right)!}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
faculty
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
binomial coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
combinatorics
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
binomial distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: sannolikhetsfunktion pdf binominalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the probability function for what is called the binomial distribution.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{k}$
\end_inset

 is called the binomial coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 is n factorial,
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $2!=2*1$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Kombinatorik"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 In a binomial distribution the outcome in one trial is independent from other trials,
 which is why the results from different rounds' do not affect each other.
 It also does not matter in which order we get 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now use equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: sannolikhetsfunktion pdf binominalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to calculate the probability that we with two trials get outcome 2 exactly two times:
 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

.
 If we summarize the results as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{result trial 1},\text{result trial 2}\right)$
\end_inset

 we get the following results:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(1,1\right),\left(1,2\right),\left(2,1\right),\left(2,2\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The probability for the result 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(k\right)=P\left(M=k\right) & =\binom{n}{k}p^{k}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}\label{eq: binomial exempel kasta 2 mynt}\\
 & =\binom{2}{2}0.5^{2}\left(1-0.5\right)^{2-2}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{2!}{2!\left(2-2\right)!}\right)0.5^{2}\left(0.5\right)^{0}\nonumber \\
 & =0.25\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 Each unique value of the four possible results has the probability 25%.
 There are two possibilities to get outcome 2 once in two trials:
 result 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,2\right)$
\end_inset

 or result 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The probability for this is therefore 50%:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(1\right) & =\left(\frac{2!}{1!\left(2-1\right)!}\right)0.5^{1}\left(0.5\right)^{2-1}=\left(\frac{2*1}{1*1}\right)0.5*0.5=0.5
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let us now calculate the probability of getting 10 outcome with 2s in 10 trials:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(10\right) & =\binom{10}{10}0.5^{10}\left(0.5\right)^{10-10}\approx0.00098\label{eq: binomial n=x=10 10 klave på 10 kast}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cumulative distribution function
\end_layout

\end_inset

For the binomial distribution,
 the cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 describes the probability that variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is equal to or less than the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(k\right)=P\left(M\leq k\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor k\rfloor}\binom{n}{i}p^{i}\left(1-p\right)^{n-i}\label{eq: CDF binomial}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
roof function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
floor function
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

 describes the sum of probabilities from the value 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

,
 up to and including the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor k\rfloor$
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor k\rfloor$
\end_inset

 is the floor function for the number 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The floor function for a real number gives the largest integer that is equal to or less than this number.
 Examples:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor3.001\rfloor=3$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor3.6\rfloor=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor3.9\rfloor=3$
\end_inset

.
 A similar function is what is called the ceiling function,
 which is instead written 
\begin_inset Formula $\lceil k\rceil$
\end_inset

 and gives the smallest integer that is equal to or greater than the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lceil3.002\rceil=4$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\lceil3.8\rceil=4$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate the cumulative probability of getting outcome 2 one or zero times in 2 trials.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and sum from 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: CDF binomial"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(1\right) & =\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor1\rfloor}\binom{2}{i}0.5^{i}\left(1-0.5\right)^{2-i}\label{eq: mynt klave binomial ex 1}\\
 & =\binom{2}{0}0.5^{0}\left(1-0.5\right)^{2-0}+\binom{2}{1}0.5^{1}\left(1-0.5\right)^{2-1}\nonumber \\
 & =0.75\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cumulative probability is 75%.
 Now we perform 10 trials 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n=10\right)$
\end_inset

 and want to know the probability of getting 3 or fewer of outcome 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(3\right) & =\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor3\rfloor}\binom{10}{i}0.5^{i}\left(0.5\right)^{10-i}\\
 & \approx0.001+0.01+0.044+0.117\nonumber \\
 & =0.172\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability of getting 0,
 1,
 2 or 3 outcome 2s in 10 trials is approximately 17.2%.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf och cdf för binomialfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the binomial distribution's probability mass function (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: sannolikhetsfunktion pdf binominalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and distribution function (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: CDF binomial"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The graphs describe probabilities for different results,
 given that we make 10 trials,
 for example 10 tosses with a coin.
 The upper graph describes the probability that we with 10 tosses of the coin get different numbers of tails.
 The almost invisible bar furthest to the left describes the low probability of getting 0 tails in 10 tosses.
 The almost invisible bar furthest to the right describes the low probability of getting tails on all 10 tosses,
 see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: binomial n=x=10 10 klave på 10 kast"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The middle bar shows the probability of getting 5 tails in 10 trials,
 approximately 24.6%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lower graph describes the cumulative distribution function.
 Note that the two graphs have different vertical scales,
 where the lower graph's scale goes from 0 to 100%.
 In a similar way as before,
 the distribution function is illustrated by stepwise levels of cumulative probability that the result is equal to or less than the values on the horizontal x-axis.
 For results under 0 the probability is 0.
 We cannot get a negative number of outcomes,
 for example a negative number of tails.
 This is illustrated by the black horizontal line furthest down to the left in the graph.
 
