\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: pdf och cdf för binomialfördelningen"

\end_inset

The binomial distribution:
 probability mass function and cumulative distribution function for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At zero the probability increases to just under 0.1%,
 which is illustrated by the first point with its associated horizontal line,
 see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: binomial n=x=10 10 klave på 10 kast"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Thereafter the cumulative probability increases stepwise since we sum the probability for more results.
 Furthest to the right in the lower graph the cumulative probability is 100% since the probability of getting 0 to 10 tails in 10 tosses,
 which covers all possible alternatives,
 by definition must be 100%.
 If a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 follows the binomial distribution this can be described in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M\sim b\left(n,p\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 stands for the binomial distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of trials and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the probability for one of the two possible values in the current variable.
 The binomial distribution's expected value is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(M\right)=np\label{eq: väntevärde binomialfördelningen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the number of trials 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M\sim b\left(2,\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 we have the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(M\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
 which should be read as that we in two trials on average will get one successful result.
 If we instead have 
\begin_inset Formula $M\sim b\left(10,\frac{1}{2}\right)=5$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(M\right)=5$
\end_inset

,
 which we also see in the upper graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: binomial n=x=10 10 klave på 10 kast"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced variance and standard deviation as measures of spread for a collection of values.
 Variance can also be used as a measure of the spread of the possible values in a probability distribution.
 The binomial distribution has variance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(M\right)=np\left(1-p\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we multiply the number of occurrences n with the probability for one value,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 and the probability for the other value,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

