	filename g_vonbort.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: Bortkiewicz data preussiska ryttare"

\end_inset

Number of deaths per cavalry corps.
 Source:
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bortkiewiczGesetzKleinenZahlen1898"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 retrieved from the R package vcd
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: Bortkiewicz data preussiska ryttare"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the data that Bortkiewicz based his work on,
 where the bars show the number of deaths per cavalry corps per year.
 The numbers for the bars are marked on the left vertical y-axis.
 The bar for 0 deaths per year is highest.
 In 91 cases one death occurred in a cavalry corps during one of the years.
 In 32 cases 2 soldiers died during one year in one and the same cavalry corps.
 In two cases 4 soldiers died during one and the same year in one and the same cavalry corps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When Bortkiewicz studied these numbers he noticed a pattern in the distribution that can be described with the help of the line that follows the bars' highest points.
 The line is drawn using the following equation,
 which describes the probability function for a Poisson distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x,\lambda\right)=P\left(X=x\right)=e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}\label{eq: pdf poisson}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability function f for the random variable X with possible outcomes x describes the probability for the number of deaths per cavalry corps per year.
 The letter e is Euler's number and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (Greek lambda) is the average number of events,
 in this case the average number of deaths.
 Bortkiewicz's data includes 280 observations and sums to 196 deaths,
 since some of the observations have 0 deaths.
 The average number of deaths therefore becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{196}{280}=0.7
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us estimate the probability that three soldiers are kicked to death in a cavalry corps during one year.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.7$
\end_inset

.
 The probability can then be estimated to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x=3,\lambda=0.7\right) & =e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}=e^{-0.7}\frac{0.7^{3}}{3!}\approx0.0284
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability is approximately 2.84%.
 We see this in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: Bortkiewicz data preussiska ryttare"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by comparing the height of the bar for 3 deaths with the right y-axis.
 The bar is not exactly that high but equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf poisson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 gives an acceptable measure for the pattern.
 The Poisson distribution's distribution function gives us the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=e^{-\lambda}\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor x\rfloor}\frac{\lambda^{i}}{i!}\label{eq: cdf poisson}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
floor function
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor k\rfloor$
\end_inset

 is the floor function of the value k (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: CDF binomial"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Function F sums the probability for integers up to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the Poisson distribution can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim Pois\left(\lambda\right),\lambda>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is also the Poisson distribution's expected value and variance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=var\left(X\right)=\lambda
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
