\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
If a variable follows the Poisson distribution this is often called that the variable's values follow a Poisson process.
 Let us estimate another example with the Poisson distribution.
 Suppose we run a customer service reception on the telephone that is open a total of 100 hours in a year.
 On average we receive 50 calls:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{50}{100}=\frac{1}{2}=0.5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now want to know the probability that someone calls within the first hour.
 We call our random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with possible outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 If no one calls we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

.
 The number of calls per hour follows a random Poisson process and we therefore estimate the probability that no one calls during the next hour using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf poisson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(y=0\right) & =e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}=e^{-0.5}\frac{0.5^{0}}{0!}\approx0.607
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability for zero calls in the first hour is approximately 61%.
 The probability for five calls in the first hour is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(y=5\right) & =e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}=e^{-0.5}\frac{0.5^{5}}{5!}\approx0.00016
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A random variable can assume different values.
 Each value has a probability.
 An example of a random variable is a perfectly balanced coin that can assume two values with 50% probability each.
 Or a perfectly balanced six-sided die,
 where each value has the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 assumes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can be written with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X=x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is short for probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A random variable's expected value can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\sum_{x}xP\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 describes the probability for the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can only assume the values 1 and 2 respectively,
 each with 50% probability,
 we get the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=1*0.5+2*0.5=1.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conditional expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(y|x\right)$
\end_inset

 describes the expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 given a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The law of total expectation:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(E\left(y|x\right)\right)=E\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 means that the expected value of the conditional expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the same as the expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to describe this is that the conditional expected value is the mean of possible expected values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 conditional on the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The variance in a random variable can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(x\right)=E\left(x^{2}\right)-\left(E\left(x\right)\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the function for variance and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the expected value function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probability distributions can be a result of two or more variables.
 Suppose we have the two random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Joint probability distribution:
 the results for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are independent of each other and sum to a coherent probability distribution,
 for example two dice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conditional probability distribution:
 one variable's outcome is dependent on the other variable.
 Conditional expected value is an example of this.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A discrete probability distribution has a limited number of possible values.
 Each value has a probability.
 The values can have the same or different probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A probability mass function describes the probability for each value in a discrete random variable,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=P\left(X=x\right)=\frac{1}{2},x=1,2$
\end_inset

,
 where 1 and 2 are the values that variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can assume.
 The probability that a random discrete variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 assumes a value that is equal to or less than x is described with the cumulative distribution function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A variable whose values have the same probability can be described as following a uniform probability distribution,
 which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim U\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the lower and upper limits for the interval that the uniform distribution covers.
 If variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can assume the values 1 and 2 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The binomial distribution:
 variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can assume two values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 number of results of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 in n number of trials is estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(k\right)=P\left(X=k\right)=\binom{n}{k}p^{k}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}$
\end_inset

.
 If a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the binomial distribution this can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim B\left(n,p\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of trials and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the probability for one outcome.
 Its distribution function can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq k\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor k\rfloor}\binom{n}{i}p^{i}\left(1-p\right)^{n-i}$
\end_inset

.
 Expected value:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=np$
\end_inset

.
 Variance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=np\left(1-p\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Poisson distribution can be used to describe the probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 number of results within a limited time period or a physical area.
 The probability function describes the probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 number of occurrences 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=P\left(X=x\right)=e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=e^{-\lambda}\sum_{i=0}^{\lfloor x\rfloor}\frac{\lambda^{i}}{i!}$
\end_inset

.
 Expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\lambda$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The law of large numbers means,
 in weak form,
 that given the infinite sequence of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},X_{2},...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 with the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X_{1}\right)=E\left(X_{2}\right)=...=E\left(X_{n}\right)=\mu$
\end_inset

,
 and the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{n}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}P\left(\left|\bar{X}_{n}-\mu\right|<\epsilon\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The law of large numbers in strong form:
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\bar{X}_{n}=\mu\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

