\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!continuous uniform
\end_layout

\end_inset

A continuous random variable can assume an infinite number of different values,
 for example all decimals between two integers.
 Let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a uniform continuous probability distribution and has the same probability of assuming all values between 0 and 1.
 Since the number of possible values is infinite,
 the probability for a specific value is zero.
 However,
 the probability is greater than 0 for an interval of values.
 The probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<X\leq0.5$
\end_inset

 is 50% and the probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5<X\leq1$
\end_inset

 is also 50%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a discrete variable we used a probability function to describe the probability for different outcomes.
 The corresponding function that describes the probability for possible outcomes in a continuous variable is called a density function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A continuous probability distribution with constant probability over the possible outcomes is called a uniform probability distribution.
 The density function for a random continuous variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can then be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x;a,b\right)=P\left(X=x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{b-a} & \forall a\leq x\leq b\\
0 & \text{annars}
\end{cases}\label{eq: pdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function!cumulative distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cumulative distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 delimit the interval for the possible outcomes for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can assume all values between 0 and 1 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the cumulative probability for a continuous random variable we use a cumulative distribution function,
 which we call F.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Integraler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we covered how we with integrals can sum values over continuous intervals.
 This we also use to derive the cumulative distribution function for a random continuous variable.
 We take the integral of the density function f in equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{-\infty}^{b}f\left(x\right)dx= & \int_{-\infty}^{a}0dx+\int_{a}^{b}\frac{1}{b-a}dx
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We divide the integral into one part that sums 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for values from negative infinity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

,
 to a.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is 0 for all these values.
 The integral of 0 therefore also becomes 0.
 If we take the integral from the value 
\begin_inset Formula $X=a$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X=b$
\end_inset

 we get the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 will assume any of all possible outcomes.
 The cumulative probability is then 1,
 that is 100%:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=\left.\frac{x}{b-a}\right|_{a}^{b}=\frac{b-a}{b-a}=1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally we describe 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x;a,b\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & x<a\\
\frac{x-a}{b-a} & a\leq x<b\\
1 & b\geq x
\end{cases}\label{eq: cdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the values 
\begin_inset Formula $x<a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 For values 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
 since we cannot have more than 100% probability.
 Suppose we want to calculate the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 takes a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x\right) & =\left.\frac{x}{b-a}\right|_{a}^{c}=\frac{c}{b-a}-\frac{a}{b-a}=\frac{c-a}{b-a}\label{eq: cdf integral uniform distro}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also calculate the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 assumes a value within an interval,
 for example between 0.3 and 0.5:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(0.3\leq x\leq0.5\right) & =\left.\frac{x}{b-a}\right|_{a}^{c}=\left.\frac{x}{1-0}\right|_{0.5}^{0.3}=\frac{0.5-0.3}{1}=0.2
\end{align}

\end_inset


