\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Kontinuerlig-likformig-sannolikh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the density function f and cumulative distribution function F for the random continuous variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 which follows a uniform probability distribution.
 In the left graph the density function is illustrated in the way it is described in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we have a continuous random variable,
 the line that the density function draws in a graph is called a probability curve.
 The probability on the vertical y-axis is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{b-a}$
\end_inset

 for all values between 0 and 1.
 The density function for a uniform probability distribution is characterized by always looking like a rectangle in a graph.
 In the right graph the cumulative distribution function is illustrated,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf kontinuerlig likformig uniform prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The cumulative probability increases from 0 to 1 over the interval 0 to 1.
 That variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a uniform continuous probability distribution can in a similar way as for a discrete variable be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim U\left(a,b\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the limits for the interval of possible outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expected Value and Variance for Continuous Random Variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Väntevärde varians kontinuerliga var"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!continuous variable
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Väntevärde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced expected value for discrete random variables as the sum of outcomes multiplied by their probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\sum xf\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for a continuous random variable is in a similar way the sum of outcomes multiplied by the probabilities.
 Since we now will sum a continuous interval we use integrals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}xf\left(x\right)dx\label{eq: väntevärde kontinuerlig slumpmässig variabel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which should be read as that we sum from negative infinity to positive infinity all possible outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the probability per value,
 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows a uniform continuous probability distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim U\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

,
 can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(a+b\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 delimit possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has the expected value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(X\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\left(0+1\right)=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance!continuous variable
\end_layout

\end_inset

Variance for a continuous random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be described as the same expected value as variance for discrete random variables:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=E\left(\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\right)=\sigma_{X}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we write out the definition of the expected value from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: väntevärde kontinuerlig slumpmässig variabel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}f\left(x\right)dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard deviation is,
 as for discrete variables,
 the square root of the variance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}=\sqrt{var\left(X\right)}=\sqrt{\sigma_{X}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Conditional expected value for continuous random variables X and Y is written:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!conditional
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(Y|X\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}xyf\left(x,y\right)dxdy
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is the joint probability distribution.
 The law of total expectation also applies to continuous distributions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(E\left(X|Y\right)\right)=E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

,
 as well as the rule that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(XY|X\right)=XE\left(Y|X\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exponential Distributions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Exponentialfördelningen"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!exponential
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Diskret-Poisson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the Poisson distribution.
 Now we will instead of number of outcomes within a time period calculate the probability for a time period until the next outcome.
 Say for example that your boss usually calls you three times per hour to check how it's going with that report you were supposed to write.
 This average value we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3$
\end_inset

.
 The average waiting time for a call is in that case 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{1}{\lambda}=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 hour.
 The time until the next call is a continuous random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows what is called the exponential distribution.
 The probability for the waiting time 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can then be described with the following density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x;\lambda\right)=\begin{cases}
\lambda e^{-\lambda x} & x\geq0\\
0 & x<0
\end{cases}\label{eq: pdf exponentialfördelningen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is greater than 0 and e is Euler's number.
 The exponential distribution can among other things be used to describe the probability for the waiting time until the first event in a Poisson process.
 Since we have a continuous probability distribution,
 the probability for each individual outcome is equal to 0.
 The cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of the exponential distribution can be written:
\emph on

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
Poisson!process
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-e^{-\lambda x}\label{eq: cdf lesser exponential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 shows the probability that the waiting time for the next phone call is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 If we instead want to calculate the probability that the waiting time is longer than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $X>x$
\end_inset

,
 we take:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(X>x\right)=1-P\left(X\leq x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)=F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 we replace the term 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

 with the definition of the cumulative probability distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>x\right) & =1-F\left(x\right)=1-\left(1-e^{-\lambda x}\right)=e^{-\lambda x}\label{eq: cdf greater exponential}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this definition we estimate the probability that the waiting time for the next call from the boss is longer than time 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 If the boss usually calls three times per hour then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda=1/3$
\end_inset

.
 Now we will estimate the probability that the waiting time becomes more than 1 hour,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X>1$
\end_inset

.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf greater exponential"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>1\right) & =e^{-3*1}\approx0.0496
\end{align}

\end_inset


