\end_inset

The exponential distribution:
 density function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and cumulative distribution function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability that the boss does not call the first hour is approximately 5%.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf exponentialfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the density function and cumulative distribution function for the exponential distribution with two examples for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the number of events on average over a time interval.
 The value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is what determines the shape of the probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The upper graph shows the density function,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf exponentialfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined for all positive values,
 the probability never reaches 0 by definition,
 but only infinitely close.
 In the lower graph the cumulative distribution function is illustrated.
 The cumulative distribution function never reaches the value 1,
 but instead comes infinitely close to 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To read the probability of approximately 5% when we calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>1\right)=1-F\left(x\right)=e^{-3}$
\end_inset

 we look in the lower graph and the solid black line,
 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $X=1$
\end_inset

 on the x-axis this line is near 
\begin_inset Formula $y=1$
\end_inset

,
 that is 100% probability.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $X=1$
\end_inset

 this line is at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F\left(X=1\right)\approx0.95$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>1\right)=1-F\left(x\right)\approx0.05$
\end_inset

.
 If a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the exponential distribution we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim EXP\left(\lambda\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value for a variable X that follows the exponential distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=\frac{1}{\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 = average waiting time.
 Variance for the exponential distribution:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=\frac{1}{\lambda^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For higher values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 more events on average per time unit,
 we get a smaller expected value,
 shorter waiting time,
 and smaller variance.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf exponentialfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the line with higher value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 has steeper slope closer to 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
From Poisson to Gamma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: från poisson till gamma"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
gamma!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Poisson!process
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!gamma
\end_layout

\end_inset

Say now that we have a variable that follows a Poisson process and that we want to calculate the probability that event number 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 occurs within time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is any positive integer.
 For this we use the Gamma distribution,
 whose density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be written:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x;k,\theta\right) & =P\left(X=x\right)=\frac{x^{k-1}e^{-x/\theta}}{\Gamma\left(k\right)\theta^{k}}\label{eq: pdf gamma distro}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
faculty
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
gamma!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the average waiting time for an event.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the Greek letter lowercase theta and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is as before the average number of events per time unit.
 The density function uses three input values:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 the time interval we will calculate the probability for,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 number of events that should have occurred within the course of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 the average expected waiting time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 in the denominator of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf gamma distro"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is what is called the gamma function,
 which is a generalization of factorial.
 There is no room here to go through the gamma function in detail.
 For our review it suffices to note that for all positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,3,...$
\end_inset

 the gamma function can be described as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\left(k\right)=\left(k-1\right)!\label{eq: gammafunktionen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is the Greek letter capital gamma.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(3\right)=\left(3-1\right)!=2*1=2$
\end_inset

.
 One way to write the gamma function is the following integral:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\left(x\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty}y^{x-1}e^{-y}dx,\text{ där }y>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
gamma!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

which sums from 0 to positive infinity for all positive real numbers.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 the gamma function's integral is positive.
 The cumulative distribution function of the gamma distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x;k,\theta\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-e^{-x/\theta}\sum_{n=0}^{k-1}\frac{\left(x/\theta\right)^{n}}{n!}\label{eq: cdf gamma}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the waiting time,
 k is the number of the event we will estimate the probability for and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the average waiting time for such an event.
 Let us use function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to estimate the probability that we have to wait for more than two hours before the boss (from the example in the previous section) has managed to call us three times,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

.
 The boss usually calls three times per hour,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda=1/3$
\end_inset

 hour.
 The waiting time two hours we write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 and we therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $x/\theta=2/1/3=6$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will calculate the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>2\right)$
\end_inset

 but the cumulative distribution function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf gamma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is defined so that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X<x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>x\right)$
\end_inset

 we write (compare equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf greater exponential"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>x\right) & =1-F\left(x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the right side with the definition from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf gamma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>x\right) & =1-\left(1-e^{-x/\theta}\sum_{n=0}^{k-1}\frac{\left(x/\theta\right)^{n}}{n!}\right)=e^{-x/\theta}\sum_{n=0}^{k-1}\frac{\left(x/\theta\right)^{n}}{n!}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we calculate the probability for 
\begin_inset Formula $X>2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P\left(X>2\right) & =e^{-6}\sum_{n=0}^{3-1}\frac{6^{n}}{n!}=e^{-6}*25\approx0.06197\label{eq: gamma beräknat ex}
\end{align}

\end_inset


