\end_inset

The gamma distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

:
 density function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and the cumulative distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is approximately 6.2% probability that we have to wait for more than 2 hours for the boss to call us for the third time.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf gammafördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the gamma distribution's density function and cumulative distribution function with three different examples.
 All lines describe the probability that the boss calls three times,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

,
 but based on different average waiting times,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

,
 1 or 2.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 20 min and that the boss calls three times per hour.
 The number 1 means one hour and that the boss calls once per hour.
 The number 2 corresponds to two hours and means that the boss calls every other hour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The upper graph illustrates the density function,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf gamma distro"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and the lower graph illustrates three versions of the cumulative distribution function,
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf gamma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note in the upper graph how larger values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 mean greater spread in the probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both graphs 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 is marked on the horizontal x-axis.
 The calculation in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gamma beräknat ex"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can for example be compared with the lower graph and the solid line.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 the line is near 
\begin_inset Formula $y=1$
\end_inset

,
 which means that most of the cumulative probability is covered by the values 
\begin_inset Formula $X<x$
\end_inset

.
 If a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the gamma distribution we write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim\Gamma\left(k,\theta\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the number of the event for which we will estimate the probability and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the average waiting time,
 which we described above.
 Sometimes the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\theta=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

 are used instead.
 The expected value for a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows the gamma distribution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=k\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\Gamma\left(3,\frac{1}{3}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 as the example above with the calling boss,
 we get the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=3*\frac{1}{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The average waiting time for 3 calls is one hour.
 The variance for the gamma distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=k\theta^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that higher values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 longer waiting time,
 result in greater expected value and variance.
 This is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf gammafördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where the lines in the upper graph with higher values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 show probability distributions with higher mean values that are also more spread out along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chi-squared Distributions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Chitvå"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
chi-square distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!chi-square
\end_layout

\end_inset

Say now that we have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows a gamma distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=r/2$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is any positive integer.
 The distribution we then get is called the chi-squared distribution and is central to a large amount of analytical work.
 The density function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf gamma distro"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can then be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x;k=r/2\right) & =\frac{x^{\frac{r}{2}-1}e^{-x/2}}{\Gamma\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)2^{r/2}},\,0<x<\infty\label{eq: pdf chi2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the gamma function.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf chi2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the density function for the chi-squared distribution.
 The cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x;r\right)$
\end_inset

 for the chi-squared distribution can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x;r\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=\int_{0}^{x}\frac{y^{\frac{r}{2}-1}e^{-y/2}}{\Gamma\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)2^{r/2}}dy\label{eq: cdf chi2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf chitvåfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the density function and cumulative distribution function for the chi-squared distribution.
 The upper graph describes the density function for three different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The lower graph describes the corresponding cumulative distribution functions with the three values for 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 If a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the chi-squared distribution we describe this as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\sim\chi^{2}\left(r\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\chi_{r}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is the Greek letter lowercase chi.
 Capital chi is written as capital X.
 Generally the expected value for the chi-squared distribution can be described as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(X\right)=r
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value for a chi-squared distribution is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The variance for the chi-squared distribution is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2r$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(X\right)=2r
\end{equation}

\end_inset


