The chi-squared distribution is often used in statistical analysis.
 Here we give only a simple example.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:En-frekvensfördelning-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes a frequency distribution where the first row indicates the value and the second row indicates observed frequencies of each value.
 Say now that we want to know the probability that these observations come from a discrete uniform probability distribution (introduced in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Likformig diskret sannolikhetsfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We compare the observed frequencies against the value we could have "expected" at uniform probability.
 If all values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 5,6,7,8,9,10\right\} $
\end_inset

 have the same probability,
 all values should have the same frequency:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\sum x_{i}}{n} & =\frac{12+14+15+13+12+11}{6}=12,83
\end{align}

\end_inset


