\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the probability we use the following statistic:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\mu\right)^{2}}{\mu}\label{eq: chitvå teststatistiska}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where in this case we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=12.83$
\end_inset

,
 the expected value we want to compare against.
 The statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 follows the chi-squared distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $r=n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom,
 which in this case becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $r=n-1=6-1=5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: chitvå teststatistiska"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 calculates the cumulative probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 that our observations deviate from the value we "expect",
 based on the hypothetical uniform probability distribution that we want to check if the observations come from.
 That is,
 the higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 we calculate,
 the lower probability that our observations come from the type of distribution we compare against.
 We sum the squared deviation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 for each frequency value.
 For observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i}-\mu\right)^{2}=\left(12-12.83\right)^{2}=-0.6889$
\end_inset

.
 Our test statistic becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\chi^{2} & =\frac{\sum\left(x_{i}-\mu\right)^{2}}{\mu}\approx10.833
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chi-squared distribution is so common that we here compare our calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 against pre-calculated results for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Chitvåfördelningen-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes probabilities for calculated results from the chi-squared distribution's cumulative probability function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The percentages in the column headers describe how large a proportion of the distribution is equal to or less than the values in this column.
 In the table we see that our calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-value 
\begin_inset Formula $10.833>9.236$
\end_inset

,
 which is in the column for 90%.
 This indicates that with 90% probability our observations do not follow a uniform probability distribution.
\end_layout

