\begin_layout Plain Layout
F-distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here follows a brief introduction to the F-distribution,
 which is also commonly occurring in statistical analysis.
 If we have two independent random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that both follow the chi-squared distribution with degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{y}$
\end_inset

,
 we calculate a new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{X/r_{x}}{Y/r_{y}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 follows what is called the F-distribution,
 which can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\sim F\left(r_{x},r_{y}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the F-distribution's shape is dependent on the values in 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We do not go through the distribution's density function and cumulative distribution function here but are content to just call these 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf F-fördelningens"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the upper graph,
 and the cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the lower graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
