\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A continuous probability distribution has an infinite number of possible values,
 for example the continuous interval between 0 and 1.
 The density function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 describes the probability for all these possible values.
 The cumulative distribution function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 describes the cumulative probability that variable X will assume a value less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can also calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X>x\right)=1-P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the number of possible values in a continuous probability distribution is infinite,
 the probability for each individual value also approaches 0.
 Instead we use 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and calculate the probability for an interval in the variable:
 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A uniform probability distribution has the same probability for all values of variable x it is defined for.
 Density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=1/\left(b-a\right),\,a\leq x\leq b$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicate the interval for which 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\left(x-a\right)/\left(b-a\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq x<b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=0,\,x<a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=1,\,x\geq b$
\end_inset

.
 Expected value:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(a+b\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exponential distribution's density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\lambda e^{-\lambda x},\,x\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all other 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=1-e^{-\lambda x}$
\end_inset

.
 If variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the exponential distribution this can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim EXP\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 where the expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=1/\lambda^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Gamma distribution's density function for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x;k,\theta\right)=\frac{x^{k-1}e^{-x/\theta}}{\Gamma\left(k\right)\theta^{k}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is the gamma function,
 a generalization of factorial,
 which for the positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(k\right)=\left(k-1\right)!$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the number of the event for which we will calculate the probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the average waiting time for such an event:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the average number of events per time unit.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the time period for which we will calculate the probability.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=1-e^{-x/\theta}\sum_{n=0}^{k-1}\frac{\left(x/\theta\right)^{n}}{n!}$
\end_inset

.
 Expected value:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=k\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Variance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=k\theta^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chi-squared distribution's density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x;r,\theta\right)=\frac{x^{\frac{r}{2}-1}e^{-x/2}}{\Gamma\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)2^{r/2}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\int_{0}^{x}\frac{y^{\frac{r-2}{2}}e^{-y/2}}{\Gamma\left(r/2\right)2^{r/2}}dy$
\end_inset

.
 If variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows the chi-squared distribution it can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\chi_{r}^{2}orX\sim\chi^{2}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where r is also called degrees of freedom.
 Expected value:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(X\right)=r$
\end_inset

.
 Variance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=2r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
F-distribution:
 If the individual variables
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 follow the chi-squared distribution with
\begin_inset Formula $r_{x}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $r_{y}$
\end_inset

,
 the following variable follows the F-distribution:
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left(X/r_{x}\right)/\left(Y/r_{y}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If variable
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 follows the F-distribution this can be written
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim F\left(r_{1},r_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

