status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
normal distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!normal
\end_layout

\end_inset

The normal distribution is recognized by its symmetric bell-shaped illustration.
 It occurs from time to time in social debate and media.
 Similar to the chi-square and F-distribution,
 we will also in this case use pre-calculated probabilities and critical values,
 but before that we shall go through some of the mathematics behind it.
 If we have a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows a normal distribution,
 the probability density function f of the normal distribution can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x,\mu,\sigma\right)=\frac{e^{-\frac{\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}}{\sigma_{x}\sqrt{2\pi}},\,-\infty<x<\infty\label{eq: pdf normalfördelningen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined for all values 
\begin_inset Formula $X=x$
\end_inset

 between negative and positive infinity.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 (Greek letter lowercase mu) symbolizes expected value and mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is Euler's number,
 approximately 2.718,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is the number pi,
 approximately 3.142.
 The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 (Greek letter sigma) stands for standard deviation for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of the normal distribution is written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(x,\mu,\sigma\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{1}{s_{x}\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{x}e^{-\frac{\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}dx\label{eq: cdf normalfördelningen}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we take the integral from negative infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 to the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The normal distribution is a collective name for distributions with certain common characteristics but which can have different mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 That the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a normal distribution can be written:
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 represent the current mean and standard deviation for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf och cdf för normalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 gives three different examples of normal distributions where the upper graph illustrates the probability density function of the normal distributions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and the lower graph shows the cumulative distribution function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The only difference between the three distributions is that they have different mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the upper graph where the density function is illustrated,
 all three curves are evenly distributed around their respective means.
 On both sides of the mean the lines go down,
 which means that the further from the mean we move,
 the more unusual the results become.
 In the tails below and above the mean the probabilities are relatively smaller.
 A normal distribution with larger variance has thicker tails to the right and left of the mean.
 In the lower graph the three corresponding cumulative probability functions are illustrated.
 Each of the three lines in the upper graph has a corresponding line in the lower graph.
 
