probability distribution!Z
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
standard normal distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

A normal distribution which have mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

 is called the standardized normal distribution or Z distribution.
 If we put 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

 into the density function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf normalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{X}\left(x,\mu=0,\sigma=1\right) & =\frac{e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}}}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}=\frac{e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-0}{1}\right)^{2}}}{1*\sqrt{2\pi}}=\frac{e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2}}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\label{eq: pdf standard normal fördelningen}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cumulative distribution for the standardized normal distribution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{X}\left(x,\mu=0,\sigma=1\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{x}e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2}}dx\label{eq: cdf standard normal distro}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we use 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 to calculate the probability that variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X\leq x$
\end_inset

,
 by calculating the integral from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 up to and including the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The standard normal distribution is so common that its cumulative distribution function (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf standard normal distro"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{X}\left(x\right)=F_{X}\left(x,\mu=0,\sigma=1\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the Greek letter capital phi.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 follows a standardized normal distribution we write 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We rarely encounter any real data that naturally follows a normal distribution with exactly mean 0 and standard deviation 1.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Standardiserade-värden"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through instead how we standardize a collection of values so that these get exactly mean 0 and standard deviation 1 (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: standardiserat värde 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Standardiserad }X_{i}=Z_{i}=\frac{X_{i}-\bar{X}}{s_{X}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{X}$
\end_inset

 is estimated standard deviation for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Standardized normal distributions are so commonly occurring that they are often described as variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 whose specific values are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This probability distribution has several known probability measures based on standard deviations,
 which are often used in statistical analysis.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf Standardiserad normalfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this,
 where the upper graph describes the probability density function f of the standard normal distribution and the lower graph describes the cumulative distribution function F.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the upper graph some of the standard deviations below and above the mean 0 are marked.
 The cumulative distribution function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(Z\leq z\right)$
\end_inset

,
 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: cdf normalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes,
 as before,
 what proportion of all values in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 are less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Since the standard normal distribution is also called the Z-distribution,
 this type of probabilities are often described as precisely Z-values.
