\begin_layout Standard
The normal distribution is symmetric and has equally large outcome space below and above the mean,
 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(0\right)=P\left(X\leq0\right)=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 50% of all possible values exist below and above the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(-x\right)=1-F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(-1\right) & =1-F\left(1\right)=1-0.8413=0.1587
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the table we see that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(2\right) & =P\left(X\leq x\right)=0.97725
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also means that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(-2\right) & =1-0.9772=0.02275
\end{align}

\end_inset

which illustrates how the area beyond two standard deviations below and above the mean respectively represents approximately 4.55% of the distribution (upper graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf Standardiserad normalfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have in various examples compared average expected life expectancy for men and women 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: livslängd kommunerna, män kvinnor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Say now that life expectancy for men and life expectancy for women respectively represent two populations and that both of these are approximately normally distributed (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: normalfördelningen användbar 2, approximationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 Now we want to know if the two populations' means differ,
 that is if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{women}}=\mu_{\text{men}}$
\end_inset

.
 To estimate the probability of this we use the standard normal distribution and the following statistic:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=\frac{\bar{X}_{\text{kvinnor}}-\bar{X}_{\text{män}}}{\left(\frac{s_{\text{kvinnor}}^{2}}{n_{\text{kvinnor}}}+\frac{s_{\text{män}}^{2}}{n_{\text{män}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 is variance (standard deviation squared) for each group and n is number of observations.
 We calculate the z-value with the observations that we used earlier:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=\frac{\bar{X}_{\text{women}}-\bar{X}_{\text{men}}}{\left(\frac{s_{\text{kvinnor}}^{2}}{n_{\text{kvinnor}}}+\frac{s_{\text{män}}^{2}}{n_{\text{män}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx\frac{83.95-80.38}{\left(\frac{1,032}{290}+\frac{1,663}{290}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx37.045
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This z-value can be compared against the pre-calculated values for the standard normal distribution's cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(Z\leq z\right)$
\end_inset

 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: standardnormalfördelningen sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our calculated z-value deviates so much from the mean 0 that it is not reported in the table,
 which only extends to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=3.09$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(3.09\right)=0.999$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(-3.09\right)=1-0.999=0.001$
\end_inset

.
 In this case our z-value is so far from the mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 becomes even closer to 0 than the values included in the table.
 Our z-value thus ends up far out in the standard normal distribution's tail to the right of (above) the mean,
 which indicates that it is very unlikely that the two populations (men's and women's life expectancy) have the same mean.
\end_layout

