\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall again look at how probabilities are distributed using random values.
 We ask the computer to randomly choose 100,000 values,
 where each value is either 0 or 1.
 Each time the computer chooses a value both values have the same probability of being chosen:
 50%.
 The result is illustrated in the upper left graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: simulerade mynt normal approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Just as expected the results are distributed approximately 50% on each of 0 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we let the computer choose 4 values at a time,
 0 or 1,
 and each time with 50% probability each.
 For the 4 randomly chosen values the computer calculates a mean and then repeats this until we have 100,000 new means.
 With four random values we have the following five possible results:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,0,0\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,1,1\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1,1,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,1,1,1\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 which gives the following possible means:
 0,
 0.25,
 0.5,
 0.75 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is illustrated in the upper right graph.
 On the horizontal x-axis we see the means between 0 and 1.
 The y-axis and the height of the bars show number of calculated means.
 Furthest to the left in the graph we see the relatively few occasions when the mean became 0 and furthest to the right in the graph we see the relatively few occasions when the mean became 1.
 Most observations are gathered in the middle around the mean 0.5.
 Despite all 100,000 results being gathered around the expected value 0.5,
 we do not get the mean 0.5 every time we create 4 values randomly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next step we let the computer choose 20 random values for 0 or 1,
 calculate a mean for these and repeat this procedure 100,000 times,
 with equally many means as a result.
 The result is illustrated in the lower left graph.
 In the lower right graph each mean now consists of 200 randomly chosen values for 0 or 1,
 where each individual value is chosen with 50% probability.
 Again the computer has calculated 100,000 means.
 Now the distribution begins to feel familiar.
 The more values we add,
 the more the distribution of these values begins to resemble a normal distribution.
 The mean is consistently 0.5,
 which is because the values that are chosen,
 and thus the calculated means,
 are consistently 0 or 1.
