\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
binomial distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we flip a coin and want to know the probability of getting a certain number of outcomes,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 number of tails on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of attempts,
 we use the binomial distribution (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Binomialfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The probability function for a binomially distributed variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: sannolikhetsfunktion pdf binominalfördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(k\right) & =P\left(X=k\right)=\left(\begin{matrix}n\\
k
\end{matrix}\right)p^{k}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation we let the computer do above is precisely this function with ever higher value for n.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: simulerade mynt normal approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we see equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 with n = 1,
 4,
 20 and 200.
 As n becomes larger the binomial distribution approaches an approximate normal distribution.
 We call this an approximation since the binomial distribution by definition is a discrete probability distribution while the normal distribution is continuous.
 Mathematically this can be described as given that 
\begin_inset Formula $np$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(1-p\right)$
\end_inset

 are both large numbers,
 the following applies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b\left(n,p\right)\approx N\left(np,np\left(1-p\right)\right)\label{eq: binom noirmal approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal distribution is defined by mean and standard deviation,
 which for a standardized normal distribution is written 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: binom noirmal approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 should be read as a binomial distribution with the input values n and p is approximately equal to a normal distribution with mean = 
\begin_inset Formula $np$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation = 
\begin_inset Formula $np\left(1-p\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same phenomenon applies to many other probability distributions – given certain conditions,
 many different probability distributions approach the normal distribution.
 Another example can be illustrated by simulating perfectly balanced dice,
 which means we let the computer choose among the integers 1 to 6 randomly where each integer has the same probability:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{6}$
\end_inset

.
 We start with one die and let the computer generate 100,000 values.
 The result is illustrated in the upper left graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: clt dices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bars show number of results that gave each point sum respectively.
 The bars are almost equally large,
 which illustrates that each integer has been chosen approximately equally many times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next step we let the computer choose two values,
 among the integers 1 to 6,
 and sum so that we get a point sum between 2 and 12.
 Result 2 we get if both values,
 the dice,
 are 1.
 Result 12 if both values are 6.
 The computer repeats this until we have 100,000 point sums.
 The result is illustrated in the upper right graph,
 where the sums are distributed like a pyramid with the point sums 2 and 12 furthest out on the edges and 7 in the middle,
 which we recognize from section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:slumpmässiga variabler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where we discussed probability with two dice.
 The lower left graph shows the distribution of point sums with six dice.
 The possible point sum now goes from 6 to 36,
 where result 6 means that all six dice show 1 and result 36 means that all six dice show 6.
\end_layout

