\begin_layout Standard
The lower right graph shows the distribution of point sums when the computer for each point sum has chosen eight integers between 1 and 6,
 that is eight dice.
 The more randomly chosen values,
 dice,
 that are included in a point sum,
 the more the distribution of the results begins to resemble a normal distribution.
 The dice results can also be described as becoming increasingly approximately normally distributed.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Diskret-Poisson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through the Poisson distribution,
 whose probability function we retrieve from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf poisson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)=e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{x}}{x!}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Poisson!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 was average number of events per time unit.
 The Poisson distribution can also approach an approximation of the normal distribution if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 becomes sufficiently large:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Pois\left(\lambda\right)\approx N\left(\lambda,\lambda\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
gamma!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: från poisson till gamma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced from the Poisson distribution the continuous gamma distribution,
 whose density function (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pdf gamma distro"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x;k,\theta\right)=\frac{x^{k-1}e^{-x/\theta}}{\Gamma\left(k\right)\theta^{k}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the number of the event we shall calculate the probability for and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the average waiting time for such an event:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The gamma distribution approaches an approximation of the normal distribution for large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 which means the following:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!normal
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\left(k\right)\approx N\left(\frac{k}{\lambda},\frac{k}{\lambda^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also see an indication of this in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf gammafördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in the upper graph where we already for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

 see that the density function for the gamma distribution begins to approach the shape of a normal distribution,
 but then still with a long tail for values above the mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chi-square distribution was introduced in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Chitvå"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and can be described as a gamma distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=r/2$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer.
 A variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows a chi-square distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\chi^{2}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

,
 approaches an approximate normal distribution for large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
 which can be written as:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!chi-square
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}\left(r\right)\approx N\left(r,2r\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the approximate normal distribution has mean = 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $2r$
\end_inset

.
 Compare the upper graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: pdf cdf chitvåfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We described above how a normal distribution that has mean 0 and standard deviation 1 is called the standardized normal distribution.
 If the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 it also applies approximately that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z^{2}\sim\chi^{2}\left(1\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 squared thus follows the chi-square distribution with 1 degree of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The usefulness of the normal distribution 3
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: normalfördelningen användbar 3 CLT"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now gone through examples of how the normal distribution is common in real data as well as how other probability distributions resemble the normal distribution in different situations.
 In this section we shall look at how repeated samples from distributions that themselves are not normally distributed can lead to approximate normal distributions.
 For this example too we shall take help from the computer.
 We first create four different types of distributions that we call X,
 Y,
 Z and W with 10,000 values each.
 These four made-up collections of values we regard as population data for each variable respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall let the computer take random samples from each of the four collections.
 The computer takes 300 observations at a time and calculates a mean of these observations.
 Then the computer repeats the sample again until we have calculated 10,000 means per population variable.
 The computer chooses randomly from the populations and can hypothetically happen to choose the same values one or more times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: clt illustration Fyra-populationer-med"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the results of this exercise in eight graphs.
 The graphs to the left show data over the four different populations X,
 Y,
 Z and W,
 which illustrates that the four populations have different dispersion.
 The top population,
 X,
 has many observations toward the edges and some in between.
 Population Y and Z have values that are mainly gathered at the bottom and top of their respective scales.
 The bottom graph to the left shows the population for W,
 which is concentrated to three delimited intervals.
 The graph looks as if it only has three collections of values in the form of three peaks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the graphs to the right 10,000 samples from each population respectively are illustrated in the form of one mean per sample.
 Each of the four graphs to the right illustrates means calculated from data retrieved from "their" population.
 Despite the population looking very different in the graphs to the left,
 repeated samples lead to collections of values that resemble a normal distribution in the graphs to the right.
 The phenomenon arises when we retrieve sufficiently large amounts of samples from the populations.
 If we were only to take a few observations from the population there is nothing that says the sample will resemble a normal distribution.
\end_layout

