\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Central Limit Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset

This phenomenon is well-known within statistics and is described in what is called the central limit theorem,
 which is an important theorem within statistics and probability theory.
 The central limit theorem shows that if we take random samples from a large quantity of variables,
 the distribution of these samples' means will approach the normal distribution,
 even if the samples are retrieved from other types of distributions.
 The central limit theorem can be described as we have the random samples 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\:X_{2},\:...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 from a population with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The mean for the samples is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the law of large numbers (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: stora talens lag"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) the mean of the samples 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 will converge toward 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 when the number of observations in the sample n becomes sufficiently many:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Law of Large Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{X_{1}+...+X_{:n}}{n}=\mu
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When n becomes sufficiently large,
 the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{n}$
\end_inset

 will approach a normal distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}/n$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the population's variance.
 In addition,
 the central limit theorem means the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\sqrt{n}\left(\frac{\bar{X}_{n}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)=N\left(0,1\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 is the square root of number of means,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is n number of means from the random samples,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the population's mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the population's standard deviation.
 This means that if we are to calculate probability for variables that are not actually normally distributed,
 we often still start from the normal distribution,
 as long as the size of the sample is sufficiently large.
 A common rule of thumb says that if the sample has more than 30 observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n>30$
\end_inset

,
 then the central limit theorem applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
T-distribution
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:t-fördelningen"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probability distribution!t
\end_layout

\end_inset

Suppose we have a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows the standardized normal distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that follows the chi-square distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In that case we create the new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=\frac{X}{\sqrt{Y}/\sqrt{k}}\label{eq: pdf t-fördelningen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This variable follows a type of probability distribution that is called the t-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 number of degrees of freedom,
 where for our examples we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

.
 The t-distribution has variance:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t!distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(T\right)=\frac{k}{k-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that follows the t-distribution can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim t\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim t_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 Like the other probability distributions covered above,
 the t-distribution has both a density function and a cumulative distribution function.
 Rather than examining these mathematical functions in detail,
 we will focus on the distribution's general properties and practical importance.
 
