\end_inset

T-distribution:
 density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: PDF CDF t-fördelningen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the t-distribution's density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=P\left(X=x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the upper graph and the cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the lower graph.
 As can be seen,
 the t-distribution resembles the standardized normal distribution in shape.
 The degrees of freedom affect the density function's shape as well as what proportion of the distribution is under the cumulative distribution curve for a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim t\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 mean that the tails become thicker,
 as in the upper graph in the figure.
 In the same way as the normal distribution,
 the t-distribution is also symmetric around the mean.
 This means that at the same time as we have 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)$
\end_inset

 we also have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F\left(-x\right) & =1-P\left(X\leq x\right)=P\left(X>x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
significance level
\end_layout

\end_inset

Table 
