\begin_layout Standard
Above we went through how different probability distributions approach approximate normal distributions in different situations.
 The same thing also applies to the t-distribution.
 For a t-distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 it applies that for large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\left(k\right)\approx N\left(0,1\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With many degrees of freedom,
 high values for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 the t-distribution approaches the standardized normal distribution.
 A t-distribution with k degrees of freedom where k>0 has mean 0,
 the same as the standardized normal distribution.
 As described above,
 the t-distribution has variance 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(t\right)=k/\left(k-2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that when 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 then it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(t\right)\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 which makes the t-distribution approach the standardized normal distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last row in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the critical t-values for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\infty$
\end_inset

,
 which can be compared against the standardized normal distribution's pre-calculated probabilities.
 Example:
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\infty$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=3.09$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq x\right)=99.9\%$
\end_inset

.
 If we look in table 
