\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The normal distribution:
 written 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is standard deviation.
 Density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x;\mu,\sigma\right)=e^{-\frac{\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}/\left(\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}\right)for-\infty<x<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x;\mu,\sigma\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{x}e^{-\frac{\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}dx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since the normal distribution is symmetric we have 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=F\left(-x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x=\mu\right)=P\left(X\leq\mu\right)=0.5$
\end_inset

,
 with 50% of the distribution above and below the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The standardized normal distribution has 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

 and is written 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Density function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\left(e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2}}\right)/\left(\sqrt{2\pi}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution function:
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=P\left(X\leq x\right)=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{x}e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2}}dx$
\end_inset

.
 The standardized normal distribution is also called the standard normal distribution or the Z-distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many real data within both natural and social sciences follow the normal distribution.
 Many other probability distributions approach the normal distribution approximately in different situations.
 Example:
 the binomial distribution approaches the normal distribution approximately under the condition that the number of events 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 assume such values that 
\begin_inset Formula $np$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(1-p\right)$
\end_inset

 are large numbers.
 In that case 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(n,p\right)\approx N\left(np,np\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The central limit theorem (CLT):
 if we take random samples from a variable that follows another probability distribution,
 the mean of the samples will approach the normal distribution approximately when the number of samples becomes sufficiently large.
 The mean will according to the law of large numbers approach 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{X_{1}+...+X_{:n}}{n}=\mu$
\end_inset

,
 while the CLT describes how the dispersion around the mean will approach a normal distribution as the number of samples,
 n,
 approaches infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The t-distribution:
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim\chi^{2}\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $T=X/\left(\sqrt{Y}/\sqrt{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 follows the t-distribution,
 which is written 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim t\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 becomes sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(k\right)\approx N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The t-distribution is,
 like the normal distribution,
 symmetric which means that
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x=0\right)=0.5$
\end_inset

 and that
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=F\left(-x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

