\begin_layout Chapter
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Statistiska-test"

\end_inset

Statistical analysis and inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter,
 we continue the description of how statistical analysis can be conducted.
 We go through how we can estimate individual values,
 points,
 and intervals.
 We also introduce the concept of standard error,
 which gives us a measure of the uncertainty in an estimated value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Point estimation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Estimera-punkter"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: population urval superpopulation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the difference between the population,
 whose values are generally unknown,
 and the sample data we have access to.
 Statistical inference is the process by which we attempt to draw conclusions about unknown properties in a population using empirical data.
 This is what we do when we try to estimate the values in a population by calculating results with sample data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to know the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

,
 we estimate this with sample data and the usual formula for the mean:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}/n$
\end_inset

.
 If the mean we calculate aims to make statements about a (larger) population beyond the data we have access to,
 then this is by definition an estimate of the population mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to know the population's unknown variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

 we estimate this as 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(X\right)=\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\right)\sum_{i}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the mean and variance,
 we estimate specific values,
 which is called estimating points,
 point estimates,
 or point estimation.
 The mean is thus an example of a point estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each estimated mean is a constant,
 but the equation we use to estimate the mean with a collection of sample observations is called an estimator.
 The equation we use to estimate the variance is called the variance estimator.
