\begin_layout Standard
The expected value of the mean estimator is the population mean:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\bar{x}\right)=E\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}\right)=\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 When we estimate the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 we know that this differs more or less from the population value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we do not have access to all information about the population,
 there are random errors in our estimates.
 The difference between the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and the population value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 can be described as the sampling error 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}-\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 This sampling error cannot be calculated as long as we do not know the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 and is therefore often more to be regarded as a theoretical concept.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate a measure of the uncertainty in a point estimate,
 we estimate what is called the standard error.
 The standard error is calculated in different ways depending on which point estimate we study.
 The standard error of the mean is estimated in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Standard error of the mean}}=\frac{s_{x}}{n^{\frac{1}{2}}}=\frac{s_{x}}{\sqrt{n}}=\sqrt{\frac{s_{x}^{2}}{n}}\label{eq: medelvärdets standardfel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation,
 estimated with the sample observations and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations in the sample.
 The equation shows different ways to write the same thing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation can be read as:
 the smaller the dispersion we have in the observations (the numerator),
 the smaller the standard error becomes.
 Since we have the number of observations n in the denominator,
 this means that the standard error tends to decrease the more observations we include in our sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of these things are logical.
 The less dispersed the population's values are,
 the more likely our calculation is to be correct.
 The more we know about the population (more observations),
 the closer our estimate of the population mean will be to the correct mean in the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Confidence interval
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Konfidensintervall-för-t-test"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
estimation!interval
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
confidence level
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
confidence interval
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another way to study a population is to estimate intervals,
 which is also called interval estimation or interval estimate.
 A particular interval that is often used in statistical analysis is the confidence interval,
 which is an interval between two values within which a specified proportion of repeated samples will contain the population value we seek.
 We determine ourselves for what proportion of samples we want to estimate the confidence interval,
 for example 90 or 95%,
 where the percentages thus indicate for what proportion of samples the interval will include the population value.
 The percentages are called the confidence level,
 which is discussed more below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in the population's (unknown) mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 With our sample data we estimate the mean as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But now we instead want to estimate a confidence interval.
 Our estimation depends on what distribution the population has.
 We start here from a normally distributed variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The confidence interval can then be defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Confidence interval:} }\bar{x}\pm z\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is an estimated mean in a collection of sample observations.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 represents a value that we obtain from the standard normal distribution's cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 which can be read from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: standardnormalfördelningen sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 depending on which confidence level we have chosen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The table should be read as:
 if we choose confidence level 90%,
 we look up the value 0.95 in the table or the nearest value.
 In the table we only read the distance in the upper tail.
 We want to exclude 10% of the population's values.
 By taking 0.95 we exclude 5% in the distribution's upper tail and 5% in the distribution's lower tail (below the mean).
 Based on the current row and column we get the z-value and its decimal.
 For 0.95 we see in the table that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx1.65$
\end_inset

.
 If we want to estimate a 95% confidence interval we choose 0.975,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1.96$
\end_inset

.
 For confidence level 99% we choose 0.995,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $z=2.58$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 describes,
 as before,
 plus and minus.
 The confidence interval therefore results in a value below the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and a value above.
 The two values are called the confidence interval's lower and upper limits.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 (the population's standard deviation) is generally unknown,
 the estimated confidence interval can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Estimated confidence interval:} }\bar{x}\pm z\frac{s_{x}}{n^{\frac{1}{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated standard deviation.
 Say for example that we have a data sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=28$
\end_inset

 observations and estimate the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=13$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}=3.7$
\end_inset

.
 We choose confidence level 90%,
 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1.65$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the following limits for the confidence interval:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{x}+z\frac{s_{x}}{n^{\frac{1}{2}}} & =13+1,65*\frac{3,7}{\sqrt{28}}\approx14,15\\
\bar{x}-z\frac{s_{x}}{n^{\frac{1}{2}}} & =13-1,65*\frac{3,7}{\sqrt{28}}\approx11,85\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This indicates that if we take repeated samples,
 the population mean will be in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $11.85<\mu_{X}<14.15$
\end_inset

 in 90% of cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sverige > uppdatera detta exempel
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Standardiserad-normalfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we calculated the probability that two estimated means came from the same population,
 by calculating the difference between average life expectancy for men and women respectively in Sweden's municipalities.
 The confidence interval for the difference between the estimated means for these two populations can be estimated in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\bar{x}_{1}-\bar{x}_{2}\right)\pm z*\sqrt{\frac{s_{x_{1}}^{2}}{n_{1}}+\frac{s_{x_{2}}^{2}}{n_{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are estimated means for the two populations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the value from the standard normal distribution's cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 is estimated variance (standard deviation squared) and n is the number of observations in the respective sample.
 In this case we have the following values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{x}_{\text{men}} & =80.38\\
\bar{x}_{\text{women}} & =83.95\nonumber \\
s_{\text{men}}^{2} & =1,663\nonumber \\
s_{\text{women}}^{2} & =1,032\nonumber \\
n_{\text{men}}=n_{\text{women}} & =290\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time we choose confidence level 95%,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1.96$
\end_inset

.
 The confidence interval's lower and upper limits then become:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(80.38-83.95\right)+1.96\sqrt{\frac{1,032}{290}+\frac{1,663}{290}} & \approx3.76\\
\left(80.38-83.95\right)-1.96\sqrt{\frac{1,032}{290}+\frac{1,663}{290}} & \approx3.38\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimate indicates that with repeated samples the difference between the two populations will in 95% of cases be 
\begin_inset Formula $3.38<\left(\mu_{\text{Women}}-\mu_{\text{Men}}\right)<3.76$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hypothesis testing
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:hypotesprövning"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
statistical test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis
\end_layout

\end_inset

When we study patterns in data and covariation,
 we do this by testing hypotheses with statistical tests.
 A scientific hypothesis must be falsifiable,
 which means that it must be capable of being disproven with facts.
 We formulate a hypothesis and use a statistical test to assess the probability that the hypothesis is false.
 The probability that a hypothesis is false can never be below 0 or above 100%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statistical tests use a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.
 The null hypothesis is often denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the alternative hypothesis is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The two hypotheses are formulated so that they are mutually exclusive.
 Both hypotheses cannot by definition be true or false simultaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We formulate our hypotheses based on the covariation we want to study.
 The null hypothesis is generally formulated as there being no covariation – a non-relationship.
 In simplified terms,
 we have a theory we want to test with a statistical test.
 The null hypothesis describes the situation we must accept until we have shown valid reasons to believe otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example,
 suppose we conduct an experiment and study how a medicine covaries with disease symptoms in a group of patients,
 divided into a treatment group (receives medicine) and a control group (does not receive medicine).
 Our theory is that the medicine will reduce the patients' disease condition.
 If after treatment we observe that the disease conditions in the treatment group are less severe than those in the control group,
 we interpret this as an effect of the medicine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When translating this to a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis,
 we formulate the null hypothesis as a non-relation between cause and effect.
 If the medicine has no effect on the disease,
 the treatment group will be equally sick or sicker than the control group:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}:\text{sickness}_{\text{treatment}}\geq\text{sickness}_{\text{control}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The alternative hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 becomes in this case the alternative situation where the disease condition is less in the treatment group than in the control group (which according to our theory is due to the medicine):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{1}:\text{sickness}_{\text{treatment}}<\text{sickness}_{\text{control}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that the hypotheses are not formulated regarding the actual causal relationship of the medicine.
 The hypotheses are instead formulated regarding observable differences.
 We are interested in a causal relationship,
 which we study by observing covariation between medication and disease condition.
 The causal relationship is an interpretation we add based on the covariation we observe.
 Our hypothesis test therefore tests a theory regarding the data we study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hypotheses are formulated regarding the population.
 In this hypothetical example we imagine that the population is all observations we generate with repeated experiments.
 The superpopulation is all adult patients in the world with the same disease symptoms.
 Suppose we find that the treatment group has 5% less disease.
 The next step is then to estimate how certain we be that this difference is large enough for us to consider our null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(H_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 as false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hypothesis tests are often used in connection with regression analysis.
 Suppose we study whether variations in a phenomenon 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 cause a certain type of variations in phenomenon Y,
 which we do using the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+u$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the error term and a and b are the coefficients that we use the least squares method to estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have reason to believe that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 covary and that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this we formulate a null hypothesis in the form of a non-relation between the variables.
 A non-relation between X and Y in our regression model means that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

,
 therefore our null hypothesis becomes:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}:b=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The alternative hypothesis is formulated in this case as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{1}:b\neq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis thereby cover all possible alternatives:
 b is either equal to 0 or not equal to 0.
 This means that if our analysis shows that the covariation between X and Y is either positive or negative,
 we may have reason to reject our null hypothesis.
 Even a small covariation can be sufficient for us to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 But again,
 we are both interested in estimating the covariation between X and Y and in estimating the probability that the covariation we find could also have arisen by chance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test our hypotheses by calculating the probability that we would have gotten the result we get given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is true.
 That is,
 we estimate a slope coefficient b in a regression model and then want to know what is the probability that we would have gotten this estimate,
 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is correct,
 that is,
 that we actually have 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of this depends among other things on which probability distribution we compare against,
 for example the standard normal distribution,
 and what variance we observe in our data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Statistical significance,
 power and type errors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Statistisk-signifikans"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Statistisk-styrka"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph off
significance level
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
statistical!significance
\end_layout

\end_inset

In classical statistics it is usually described that we should choose in advance with what probability we want to risk rejecting a true 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 when conducting statistical tests.
 This is called choosing significance level or alpha value and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to describe significance level is that it is the probability that a value deviates from an expected value,
 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is true.
 For example,
 what is the probability that we in the population have 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

,
 given the value we estimate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 in our regression model with our sample data?
 For 10% significance level,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0,1=10$
\end_inset

 %:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Significance level 10\%: } }1-\alpha & =1-0.1=0.9=90\%\label{eq: signifikansnivå ex 90}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on this,
 one also usually says that a result is statistically significant for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.1$
\end_inset

 or statistically established,
 given 10% significance level.
 There is no objective method for choosing significance level.
 95 percent is often used,
 which is common in academic articles within social science,
 but it is completely arbitrary and there is no mathematical logic behind why we would not use 94%,
 96% or some completely different significance level instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is true is usually denoted by what is called the p-value.
 The p-value gives the probability that we would have gotten an equally extreme value in a statistical test given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false.
 While significance level is generally stated in rounded numbers,
 for example 90,
 95 or 99 percent,
 the p-value is calculated exactly through the statistical test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sverige > uppdatera exempel
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us illustrate with an example.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Standardiserad-normalfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated the difference between the average life expectancy for men and women respectively in Sweden's municipalities by calculating the following statistic:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p-value
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=\frac{\bar{X}_{\text{kvinnor}}-\bar{X}_{\text{män}}}{\left(\frac{s_{\text{men}}^{2}}{n_{\text{men}}}+\frac{s_{\text{women}}^{2}}{n_{\text{women}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx\frac{83.95-80.38}{\left(\frac{1,663}{290}+\frac{1,032}{290}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx37.045\label{eq: z-test statistiskt test}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us set this up as a statistical test.
 We have a theory that life expectancy differs between men and women.
 We formulate our null hypothesis as the corresponding non-relationship (that there is no difference):
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{0} & :\mu_{\text{men}}=\mu_{\text{women}}\\
H_{1} & :\mu_{\text{men}}\neq\mu_{\text{women}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the null hypothesis is formulated,
 this means that we have a two-sided test.
 Both positive and negative difference can mean that we have reason to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 To test the credibility of the hypothesis we determine significance level (for example 5%),
 calculate the statistic in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: z-test statistiskt test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and compare the result against the critical z-values in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: standardnormalfördelningen sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for the standard normal distribution.
 The values in the table's header and columns are the critical z-values 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The values in the table describe the probability,
 for one tail of the distribution,
 of getting a 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-value like this or higher,
 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we start from significance level 5%,
 a calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-value equal to 0.975 or higher (2.5% from each side) would mean that we should reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 As we noted in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Standardiserad-normalfördelning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 our calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-value is 37.045,
 which is so high that it is not included in the table and the probability is therefore far above 0.999 (a value very close to 1,
 thus 100%).
 The result from our statistical test indicates with good margin that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false.
 This is called that the result is statistically significant at the 1% level,
 which means that it is unlikely that it would have arisen through a random process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we use statistical tests and calculate probabilities to reject or not reject the null hypothesis,
 there is always a risk that we draw the wrong conclusion.
 Type 1 error is what it is called when we in a statistical test reject a null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 despite 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 being true.
 The probability of a type 1 error is the same thing as the significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 which we have so far used as the threshold value for the critical value required to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this we describe 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha$
\end_inset

 as the probability that we reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Type 2 error means that we instead accept a null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 despite this actually being false.
 The probability of type 2 error is usually denoted by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 (Greek letter beta).
 Statistical power is the probability (a value between 0 and 1) that we succeed in rejecting 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false,
 which we describe as the following conditional probability:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
statistical!power
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
type 1 error
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
type 2 error
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{\textbf{Statistical power}}=P\left(\text{reject }H_{0}|H_{0}\text{ is false}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us summarize:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\textbf{Type 1 error}} & =\alpha=\text{significance level, reject true \ensuremath{H_{0}}.}\\
\text{\textbf{Correct inference}} & =1-\alpha=\text{do not reject true \ensuremath{H_{0}}.}\nonumber \\
\text{\textbf{Type 2 error}} & =\beta=\text{do not reject false \ensuremath{H_{0}}.}\nonumber \\
\text{\textbf{Statistica power}} & =1-\beta=\text{reject false \ensuremath{H_{0}}.}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The power of a statistical test can be calculated in different ways and is affected by different things.
 Let us illustrate with an example.
 Suppose we have 290 observations with sample data for two approximately normally distributed variables with the means 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{1}=80$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{2}=81$
\end_inset

 and the same standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=s_{2}=1.5$
\end_inset

.
 We want to test whether the means differ and therefore set up the following hypotheses:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}:\mu_{1}=\mu_{2},\quad H_{1}:\mu_{1}\neq\mu_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We decide on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 that is 95% significance level,
 and estimate the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-value in the same way as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: z-test statistiskt test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=\frac{\bar{x}_{2}-\bar{x}_{1}}{\left(\frac{s_{2}^{2}}{n_{2}}+\frac{s_{1}^{2}}{n_{1}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}=\frac{81-80}{\left(\frac{1,5^{2}}{290}+\frac{1,5^{2}}{290}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx8,03
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our statistical test this is our test function.
 According to table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: standardnormalfördelningen sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 our calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-value indicates a statistically significant difference between the two populations at a level above 99%.
 This means therefore that we reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 In these situations our conclusion is that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false,
 one does not say that a hypothesis is false "with 99% probability" or similar.
 
