\begin_layout Standard
To estimate statistical power (the probability of rejecting false 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

) for this test we imagine that there exist two populations 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 that have the population means 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X_{1}}=80$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X_{2}}=81$
\end_inset

 as well as standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X_{1}}=\sigma_{x_{2}}=1.5$
\end_inset

.
 Given our determined significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 a deviation from the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X_{1}}=80$
\end_inset

 of 82.93 means that we reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 (that the populations have the same mean).
 But for the other population 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 approximately 90% of the cumulative probability (proportion of the population) 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}<82.93$
\end_inset

.
 This is in that case the probability that we here commit a type 2 error:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\approx0.9=90\%$
\end_inset

.
 The test's power is therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta\approx1-0.9=0.1=10\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Statistisk-styrka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates this,
 where the black line shows the normally distributed population 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the gray line shows the population 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The dashed lines mark the critical values based on significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 The dark gray areas represent 2.5% of population 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 in each tail.
 The light gray area is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

,
 the probability of type 2 error,
 from which we estimate the test's power 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta$
\end_inset

.
 If we for example lower the significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.1$
\end_inset

,
 then the critical values move closer to the mean for population 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the area that represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 Conversely,
 higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 results in less risk for type 2 error 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 but increased risk for type 1 error 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Point estimation:
 estimates of specific values in a population,
 for example mean.
 Interval estimation:
 estimates of intervals in a population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Confidence interval:
 interval in a population,
 within which a specified proportion of repeated samples will contain a population value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Statistical tests are based on a null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 which is generally formulated as a non-relation,
 and an alternative hypothesis,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 which is formulated as the null hypothesis's antithesis.
 Not rejecting 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 does not mean that we have proven that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The tables with pre-calculated critical values describe the percentage probability of getting the corresponding value for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In classical statistics,
 a significance level is chosen before the statistical test,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and is the same thing as the probability of type 1 error:
 rejecting true 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 = probability of type 2 error:
 not rejecting false
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Statistical power
\begin_inset Formula $=1-\beta=$
\end_inset

 the probability of rejecting false
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

