 we described how we use regression analysis and the least squares method to estimate a regression model that exists in a population,
 which we call the population's regression model or the population model:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+V\label{eq: ols reg modell t-test}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 With sample data we want to estimate the population values for the constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and find a value that is as close as possible to the population values.
 In this process there is always a measure of uncertainty,
 which exists regardless of how many observations we have and regardless of how high quality our data has.
