\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Statistiska-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced statistical tests with null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis.
 Now we will go through how we formulate statistical tests and test hypotheses regarding the coefficients in connection with regression analysis.
 We start from the population model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

.
 For both coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we set up separate statistical tests and formulate separate null and alternative hypotheses.
 Often we are primarily interested in the slope coefficient b because our estimate for this describes the possible occurrence of a linear covariation between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 A common way to formulate the null hypothesis for b is whether there is any covariation between the variables,
 that is,
 whether b is different from zero:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{0}: & b=0\\
H_{1}: & b\neq0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also formulate corresponding null and alternative hypotheses for coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Say for example that we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}>0$
\end_inset

,
 perform a statistical test and find that we cannot reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

 as false given the chosen significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 .
 This indicates that the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}>0$
\end_inset

 could just as well be the result of a random process and we therefore have no reason to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Starting Points and Assumptions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: OLS Antaganden 1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance!error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance!regression model
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this section we introduce some of the assumptions that the least squares method is based on.
 These assumptions may at first glance seem abstract but will hopefully appear more logical as the chapter progresses.
 They are also discussed more thoroughly in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Minstakvadratmetodens villkor . Gauss-Markov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The assumptions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: linjär modell enl populationen"

\end_inset

Our regression model is linear in its coefficients (the coefficients have exponent equal to one) and specified in exactly the way that the relationship between the variables in the population looks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: X random var"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a random variable from a population with unknown properties.
 The explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is either from a random sample (observational study) or from a designed process,
 which may be the case in a controlled experiment where we design 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Regardless,
 the process that generates the variables' observations must be unrelated to the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Here we assume that both 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are random and that each observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y_{i},X_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent and identically distributed,
 i.i.d.),
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Gauss-Markov-1:-Slumpmässiga"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: E(u|X)=0"

\end_inset

The conditional expected value for the population model's error terms is zero:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 do not covary with the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 which is why the covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(v,X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: homoskedasticitet"

\end_inset

The population model's error terms have constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 regardless of which value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 we compare against:
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(V|X\right)=\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}{}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a positive value whose exact population value is unknown.
 This means that along the regression line for the population regression model,
 for the different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 the error terms have the same variance.
 The variance of the error term is also called variance of the regression model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: Feltermernas korr"

\end_inset

The error terms for different observations do not correlate with each other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: felterm normal"

\end_inset

The error of the population model follow a normal distribution,
 regardless of which values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 we compare against:
 
\begin_inset Formula $V|X\sim N\left(0,\sigma_{V}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 0 is the mean of the normal distribution and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of this normal distribution,
 which corresponds to the variance of the error terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we use these assumptions as purely theoretical starting points to introduce this part of regression analysis.
 When we work with real data it is common that we encounter situations where one or more of these assumptions are not fulfilled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Variance of the Regression Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Regressionsmodellens-varians"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols reg modell t-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we described in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 how to estimate coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{b}=\frac{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\label{eq: bhatt def regmodell varians}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t!test
\end_layout

\end_inset

The estimated coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is an estimate,
 an estimated constant.
 The actual equation,
 the method for how we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 based on the random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 we call the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is the population value 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\hat{b}\right)=b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given among other things assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: felterm normal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 (that the error terms follow a normal distribution) we assume that the coefficients' estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 follow a t-distribution (we do not go through proofs and derivations here).
 To test the hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:b\neq0$
\end_inset

 we therefore use a two-sided t-test where the t-value is estimated with the following statistic:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\frac{\hat{b}-b_{0}}{se\left(\hat{b}\right)}\label{eq: t-test för beta-koeff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the standard error for the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 In the numerator we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 the hypothetical value that we test coefficient b against based on our null hypothesis,
 which here is 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t & =\frac{\hat{b}-b_{0}}{s_{\hat{b}}}=\frac{\hat{b}}{s_{\hat{b}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the standard error 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 we take the square root of the variance (standard deviation squared) for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 which is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(\hat{b}\right)=\frac{\sigma_{V}^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\label{eq: var bhatt härled 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance!error term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!variance
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the denominator we have the observations for variable x.
 In the numerator we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 which is the constant that describes the error term's variance,
 according to assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: homoskedasticitet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The error terms' variance in the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is usually unknown but we estimate this with the mean square of the residuals (MSR) which we introduced in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ssr sse sst vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which we then write as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\hat{V}}^{2}=\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}=MSR=\frac{\sum_{i}\hat{v}_{i}^{2}}{n-p}=\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\label{eq: estimerad varians residualerna reg.modellen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of coefficients,
 parameters,
 that cannot vary in the calculation.
 For the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols reg modell t-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have the two coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 which gives two restrictions that must hold 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We also see this in the least squares method's first-order conditions in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols foc 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ols foc 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\hat{v_{i}}=0,\text{ och }\sum_{i}x_{i}\hat{v}_{i}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $n-p$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom now remain.
 If we replace the population value 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: var bhatt härled 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 we get the estimated variance for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{b}\right) & =\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}\frac{1}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\label{eq: var bhatt def 1a}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{i}\hat{v}_{i}^{2}}{n-p}\right)\frac{1}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding variance for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{a}\right) & =var\left(\hat{b}\right)\left(\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n}\right)\label{eq: var ahatt def 1a}\\
 & =\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\left(\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard error is then the positive square root of the variance for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{a}\right)=\left(var\left(\hat{a}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 and:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
se\left(\hat{b}\right)=\left(var\left(\hat{b}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}=\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\label{eq: se för b^}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis with t-test
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: regressionsanalys med t-test"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t!test
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we will use some observations to illustrate how we use the t-test and the statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\hat{b}/se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 to test the null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

 and the alternative hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The example is solely intended to illustrate the method and to make it more easily comprehensible we will only use the four observations for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Variabel x y k28"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which have appeared in several previous examples.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we showed how an estimation of the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 based on the least squares method with these four observations gives that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
