\begin_layout Standard
We will now use the t-test with the statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\hat{b}/s_{\hat{b}}$
\end_inset

 that we introduced in the previous section.
 The test is based among other things on our assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: felterm normal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 that the error terms follow the normal distribution.
 In this example we do not worry about whether this is a reasonable assumption or not.
 For the calculation of t we know that the numerator is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

 and want to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\hat{b}}$
\end_inset

 for the denominator according to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: se för b^"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we used the four observations to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}=2.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}=10$
\end_inset

.
 We have four observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{gathered}n=4\end{gathered}
\right)$
\end_inset

 and are to estimate two coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=2\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $n-p=4-2=2$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us the following 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
se\left(\hat{b}\right) & =\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-2\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\right)^{1/2}=\left(\frac{2.5}{2*10}\right)^{1/2}\approx0.354\label{eq: std dev b_hat OLS ex 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now also insert this into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: t-test för beta-koeff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to estimate our t-value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t & =\frac{\hat{b}}{se\left(\hat{b}\right)}=\frac{0.5}{\left(\frac{2.5}{2*10}\right)^{1/2}}\approx1.414
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the t-value we have 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n-p=4-2=2$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 Since we have a two-sided t-test we compare whether our estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|t\right|>t^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the critical t-value from the cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 that we find in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us start from the significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 which for a two-sided test takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha/2=0.025$
\end_inset

 on each side of the probability distribution's mean.
 Statistical confidence then becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha/2=0.975\%$
\end_inset

.
 In table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 on row 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

 we see that our estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $t\approx1.414$
\end_inset

 is below the critical 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 which is why we do not reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 Let us also perform the corresponding t-test for coefficient a,
 where we have the null and alternative hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Our t-value becomes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\frac{\hat{a}-a}{se\left(\hat{a}\right)}=\frac{\hat{a}}{\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-2\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n}\right)^{1/2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we found that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}=2.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}=10$
\end_inset

.
 From the observations we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum x_{i}^{2}=110$
\end_inset

.
 This gives:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t & =\frac{1}{\left(\frac{2.5}{2*10}\frac{110}{4}\right)^{1/2}}\approx\frac{1}{1,854}\approx0.539
\end{align}

\end_inset

which we compare against table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 on the row for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

.
 This t-value is also well below the critical 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 so we do not reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 We therefore have no reason to assume that a or b differ from 0.
 If we use a computer program to estimate a regression model with the least squares method,
 the program often has exactly this type of statistical test for all coefficients in the regression model as default,
 based on null hypotheses that each coefficient equals 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw how estimation of the regression model's coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is affected by observations from all variables included in the model,
 which in this case are 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 When we calculated the t-test we note that here too the statistical tests for both coefficients are affected by the values in both variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 All data used to estimate the regression model can potentially affect both the calculation of the coefficients and the associated t-tests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have previously established that more observations n,
 all else equal,
 increases the probability that we obtain statistical results indicating that our results did not arise from a random process.
 In this case this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 should be rejected as false.
 The same principle applies to the t-tests we have used to test hypotheses,
 which we see in the definitions for the coefficients' standard errors in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: se för b^"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis with confidence interval
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: Konfidensintervall för regressionsanalys"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Konfidensintervall-för-t-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced confidence intervals for t-tests.
 Confidence intervals can also be estimated for the estimated coefficients in our regression analysis.
 For the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 and the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left\{ 3,2,5,4\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

 we found:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a}=1 &  & \hat{b}=0.5\\
se\left(\hat{a}\right)=1,854 &  & se\left(\hat{b}\right)=0.354\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to estimate the confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{a}\pm t_{k,\alpha}*se\left(\hat{a}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k,\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the critical t-value depending on the number of degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n-2=4-2=2$
\end_inset

 and significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Let us estimate a 95% confidence interval,
 so we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 We find 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k,\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in the row for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

.
 To allocate 5% to each tail of the probability distribution we use the 97.5% column,
 which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k,\alpha}=4.3$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 we then obtain the confidence interval:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{a}\pm t_{k,\alpha}*se\left(\hat{a}\right) & =1\pm4,3*1,854\approx1\pm7,97
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{b}\pm t_{k,\alpha}*se\left(\hat{b}\right) & =0.5\pm4.3*0.354\approx0.5\pm1.52
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two confidence intervals show within which boundaries 95% of the coefficients' estimates would be located in repeated sampling.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 the confidence interval's lower and upper bounds are approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $-6.97$
\end_inset

 and 8.97.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 the confidence interval's lower and upper bounds are approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $-1.02$
\end_inset

 and 2.02.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Confidence interval for the regression line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 we make a point estimate for the predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}$
\end_inset

 based on any chosen value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{p}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 indicates that it is a specifically chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-value.
 For this point estimate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}$
\end_inset

 we also estimate a standard error,
 which can be described as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
se\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)=\left(\sigma_{V}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\left(x_{p}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the error terms' variance in the population (the regression model's variance),
 which we estimate with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 With the help of 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)$
\end_inset

 we estimate a confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}$
\end_inset

,
 which we call 
\begin_inset Formula $CI\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CI\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)=\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\pm t_{k,p}*se\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write out the definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)$
\end_inset

 with the definition for the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
CI\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right) & =\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\pm t_{k,p}*\left(\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\left(x_{p}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
 & =\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\pm t_{k,p}*\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\left(\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\left(x_{p}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k,\alpha}$
\end_inset

 just as above is taken from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 depending on the number of degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This confidence interval is thus dependent on which value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{p}$
\end_inset

 we estimate the interval for.
 Values further away from the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 mean that the confidence interval becomes larger,
 since the uncertainty about where the population value is located increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will estimate a confidence interval for a point along the regression line.
 We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 estimate a 95% confidence interval,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k,\alpha}=4.3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate the confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{p}=3$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}\approx2.5$
\end_inset

.
 We start by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 based on equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: estimerad varians residualerna reg.modellen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}=\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)}=\frac{2.5}{2}=1.25
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This give us 
\begin_inset Formula $CI\left(\hat{Y}_{x_{p}}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
CI\left(\hat{Y}=2.5\right) & =2.5\pm4.3*\left(1.25*\left(\frac{1}{4}+\frac{4}{10}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
CI\left(\hat{Y}=2.5\right)_{\text{upper}} & \approx6.38\nonumber \\
CI\left(\hat{Y}=2.5\right)_{\text{lower}} & \approx-1.38\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


