\begin_layout Section
Statistical Power in Regression Analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Statistisk-styrka-för"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!statistical power
\end_layout

\end_inset

In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Statistisk-styrka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the concept of statistical power as a measure of the probability that we reject a false 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 given the conditions for our statistical test.
 Statistical power is measured as 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the probability of type 2 error (not rejecting a false 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 Even when we work with regression analysis it is important to consider statistical power.
 Here we content ourselves with a more general illustration.
 Suppose we are interested in a population with a total of 1,000,000 observations.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The concept for this example is taken from the excellent blog Ekonomistas:
 https://ekonomistas.se/2015/03/03/varning-for-signifikanta-resultat/
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the population there exists the following linear relationship:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =a+bX=100+5X
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have no possibility to study the entire population but analyze sample data.
 We let the computer make 2,000 separate random samples from this population with n = 500 observations in each sample.
 Then we let the computer take another 2,000 samples with n = 20,000 observations per sample.
 Each sample is unique and has no impact on the other samples.
 The same observations can occur in different samples.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_styrka_regression.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Beräknade-lutningskoefficienter"

\end_inset

Estimated Slope Coefficients from Samples
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t!test
\end_layout

\end_inset

For each sample we estimate the linear regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+u$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 We use statistical t-tests with significance 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

 to test the probability that coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 differs from zero.
 The results are illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Beräknade-lutningskoefficienter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 where we see the distribution of estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 from the regression model for the two collections of samples in separate graphs.
 The upper graph shows the distribution for the 2,000 estimates with a small sample,
 n = 500.
 The lower graph shows the distribution for the 2,000 estimates with larger sample,
 n = 50,000.
 The black bars show results that are statistically significant with 95% confidence.
 The gray bars show results that are not statistically significantly different from zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the upper graph the estimates have large dispersion around the population value 5 but they are mostly not statistically significant.
 The statistically significant results are instead far from the population value and distributed either around 
\begin_inset Formula $-30$
\end_inset

 or 30.
 In the lower graph most estimates are statistically significant.
 All estimates are clearly centered around the population value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we estimate our results based on a relatively small sample,
 a larger deviation is required to reject the null hypothesis,
 given the chosen significance level.
 The more observations we include in our sample,
 the more accurate the results become,
 all else equal.
 This is logical in the sense that the larger proportion of the population we include in our sample,
 the greater the probability that our estimates actually reflect the values in the population correctly.
 By calculating the power of a test we ideally have the opportunity to adjust our analysis to minimize the risk of type 1 and type 2 errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Statistical and Economic Significance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Ekonomisk-och-statistisk"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
economical significance
\end_layout

\end_inset

A statistically significant estimate does not necessarily mean that a result has great importance for the world or the real phenomenon we are studying.
 In this context,
 statistical analysis often refers to economic significance,
 which simply refers to how much importance our results have in reality.
 This question generally has no straightforward answer.
 It depends on the purpose of the study,
 type of data,
 and how the results should be interpreted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many people experience,
 for example,
 that weather affects their mood.
 But few people would probably compare normal variations in weather with the effect that their earnings or work environment has on their lives.
 If we imagine from this that we would succeed in measuring the causal effect of these phenomena with a regression analysis,
 then the slope coefficient for the weather variable would be relatively small.
 The slope coefficient for earnings would be larger.
 Both the estimated slope coefficient for weather and earnings could be statistically significantly different from zero.
 But only one of the variables would have an economically significant effect,
 that is,
 have great importance for people's lives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Our goal with regression analysis is to estimate the regression model in a population,
 the true regression model.
 With sample data we estimate the model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assumptions for regression analysis with the least squares method (do not necessarily need to match real data):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The regression model is linear.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a random variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is either random (observational studies) or from a designed process (for example from an experiment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 do not covary.
 The error terms have constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(v|X\right)=\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The error terms do not correlate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V_{i}V_{j}|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for different observations 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The error terms follow the normal distribution:
 
\begin_inset Formula $V|X\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and can then perform statistical tests for each coefficient,
 for example two-sided t-test with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 For coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left(\hat{b}-b_{0}\right)/se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the expected value that we want to test 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 against,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the standard error of the coefficient.
 If the calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|t\right|>t^{*}$
\end_inset

 given the chosen significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 this indicates that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be rejected as false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note the difference between statistical significance (can we reject
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 at the chosen significance level) and economic significance (what importance does the result have for reality).
\end_layout

