\begin_layout Chapter
Statistical Tests in Regression Analysis with Multiple Variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Regressionsanalys med test, flera variabler"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter describes how we can use statistical tests with regression analysis when we have two or more explanatory variables.
 For this we will use matrices and linear algebra,
 which we introduced in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: Linjär algebra"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Starting Points and Assumptions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: OLS antaganden 2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
least squares method!assumptions
\end_layout

\end_inset

We start from the following regression model written with matrices for a population with unknown characteristics,
 the population model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=XB+V\label{eq: populationsmodellen matriser varians-kovariansmatris}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 column matrix with the explained variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times1$
\end_inset

 column matrix for all coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 column matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 error terms.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix with the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in separate columns and the observations in separate rows.
 Our regression model includes the y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 which is the first coefficient,
 why all elements in the first column of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have the value 1 (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Theoretical assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: linjär modell matriser"

\end_inset

The population model reflects a linear relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that exists in the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: Y X random var matriser"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are random variables from a population,
 whose characteristics are unknown.
 Explanatory variables can also be a result of a controlled process,
 as in a controlled experiment.
 Observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y_{i},X_{1,i},...,X_{k,i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent and identically distributed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: autokorrelation matriser"

\end_inset

The explanatory variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have no strong correlation among themselves.
 For example,
 none of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be described as a linear relationship of any of the other variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: feltermerna okorr matriser"

\end_inset

The error terms are not correlated with each other,
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(v_{i}v_{j}|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are index numbers for two different observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: E(v|X)=0 matriser"

\end_inset

The conditional expected value of the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 do not covary 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(V,X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: homoskedastic matriser"

\end_inset

The error terms have constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 across all values for all explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We describe this as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(VV^{T}|X\right) & =\sigma_{V}^{2}I=\left[\begin{matrix}\sigma_{V}^{2} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \sigma_{V}^{2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \sigma_{V}^{2}
\end{matrix}\right]\label{eq: E(ee') diagonal matris}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the transposed column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with the error terms and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 diagonal matrix with the constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 along the diagonal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu: feltermerna normal matriser"

\end_inset

The error terms follow the normal distribution across all observations and variables:
 
\begin_inset Formula $V|X\sim N\left(0,\sigma_{V}^{2}I\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimators of the Coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the least squares method,
 we estimate the coefficients in the population model (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: populationsmodellen matriser varians-kovariansmatris"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y\label{eq: beta hat matriser}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which we went through in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 As we saw in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Regressionsmodellens-varians"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 each estimated coefficient is a constant,
 which is estimated with an estimator,
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: beta hat matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The expected value of the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is the population model's coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\hat{B}\right)=B$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this,
 we rewrite equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: beta hat matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{B} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y\label{eq: bhat - b matriser}\\
 & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}\left(XB+V\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(X^{T}X\right)B+\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V\nonumber \\
 & =B+\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where in the second row we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with the regression model in the population 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=XB+V$
\end_inset

.
 In the fourth row we use the fact that for matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $AA^{-1}=I$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix,
 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $IA=A$
\end_inset

 (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: beta hat matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Now we have an expression where the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is a function of the population coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the expected value of the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 conditional on matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\hat{B}|X\right)=B+E\left(\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V|X\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are the population values,
 which are constant,
 so the expected value of these is the same thing.
 Since we take the expected value conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are not correlated (assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: feltermerna okorr matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 all factors with 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be moved out of the expected value function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =B+\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}E\left(V|X\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

 (assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: E(v|X)=0 matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) which is why the second term on the right-hand side becomes 0 and can be deleted:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\hat{B}|X\right)=B
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
expected value!unbiased
\end_layout

\end_inset

This means that,
 given that the assumptions hold,
 the least squares method gives unbiased estimates of the coefficients.
 Each estimated coefficient does not correspond to the population value,
 but if we were to take an infinite number of samples from the same population,
 the mean of these results would correspond to the expected value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 we get the weighted average of this conditional expected value.
 Since the population values 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are still constants,
 this is also equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(E\left(\hat{B}|X\right)\right)=E\left(\hat{B}\right)=B
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that the least squares method's estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is unbiased both with and without consideration of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we now want to calculate a statistical test for each coefficient in B and test whether each coefficient is statistically significantly different from zero.
 We construct a null and alternative hypothesis respectively,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:b_{j}\neq0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 is one of the coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 According to,
 among other things,
 assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: feltermerna normal matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 (that the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 follow the normal distribution) this means that the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 follows the t-distribution.
 Based on the null hypotheses we therefore test this with a two-sided t-test,
 whose statistic can be described in the same way as in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Regressionsmodellens-varians"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\hat{b}_{j}/se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the standard error for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Variance-Covariance Matrix
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Varians-kovariansmatrisen"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!variance
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!covariance
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance-covariance matrix
\end_layout

\end_inset

We will now go through how we may describe the variance and standard errors for all coefficient estimators in a regression model with any number of coefficients,
 like the population model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=XB+V$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by defining what is called the regression model's variance-covariance matrix.
 The variance-covariance matrix is also called the variance matrix,
 covariance matrix or autocovariance matrix.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a more detailed description,
 see
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
after "section 4.6."
key "hansenEconometrics2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance for a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 conditional on variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(y|x\right)=E\left[\left(y-E\left(y|x\right)^{2}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The variance for the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the variance-covariance matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =E\left[\left(\hat{B}-B\right)\left(\hat{B}-B\right)^{T}|X\right]
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will go through a description of what this matrix consists of.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: bhat - b matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we see that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}-B=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}-B$
\end_inset

 we use in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =E\left[\left(\hat{B}-B\right)\left(\hat{B}-B\right)^{T}|X\right]\\
 & =E\left[\left(\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V\right)\left(\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V\right)^{T}|X\right]\nonumber \\
 & =E\left[\left(\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}V\right)\left(V^{T}X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\right)|X\right]\nonumber \\
 & =E\left[\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}VV^{T}X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}|X\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the expected value is conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 we factor out all 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 from the expected value function (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Betingat-väntevärde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =E\left[\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}VV^{T}X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}|X\right]\label{eq: varians-kovariansmatrisen matris def 1A}\\
 & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to our assumption no.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu: homoskedastic matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the error terms in the population model have the constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)=\sigma_{V}^{2}I$
\end_inset

.
 We use this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}\sigma_{V}^{2}IX\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\sigma_{V}^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\sigma_{V}^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unknown population value 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}=\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{n-p}$
\end_inset

,
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: estimerad varians residualerna reg.modellen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{V}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 we get the estimated variance-covariance matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}=\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\label{eq: estimerade var-kovar matrisen OLS}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of coefficients (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Varians-och-standardavvikelse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Now we have defined the variance-covariance matrix for the population and the estimated version.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To better understand the content of 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 we illustrate with an example.
 Suppose we have the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 with the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the two coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as well as the error term 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The estimated variance-covariance matrix then becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}=\left[\begin{matrix}var\left(\hat{a}\right) & cov\left(\hat{a},\hat{b}\right)\\
cov\left(\hat{b},\hat{a}\right) & var\left(\hat{b}\right)
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the coefficient a in the regression model corresponds to the y-intercept,
 all elements in the first column of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have the value 1 and the number of rows equals the number of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 To see the details in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 we start by describing the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1} & =\left[\begin{matrix}n & \sum x_{i}\\
\sum x_{i} & \sum x_{i}^{2}
\end{matrix}\right]^{-1}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{n\sum x_{i}^{2}-\sum x_{i}\sum x_{i}}\right)\left[\begin{matrix}\sum x_{i}^{2} & -\sum x_{i}\\
-\sum x_{i} & n
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{n\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}\right)\left[\begin{matrix}\sum x_{i}^{2} & -n\bar{x}\\
-n\bar{x} & n
\end{matrix}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}\\
\frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \frac{1}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In row three the initial parenthesis is a description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\det\left(X^{t}X\right)}$
\end_inset

,
 see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: invers av 2x2 A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Now we have an expression for the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 To illustrate how the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: estimerade var-kovar matrisen OLS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be described in our example we now multiply our expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with the estimated variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \hat{s}_{\hat{V}}^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}=\\
= & \left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}\\
\frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \frac{1}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}
\end{matrix}\right]=\nonumber \\
= & \left[\begin{matrix}\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}\\
\left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\frac{-\bar{x}}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)} & \left(\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\right)\frac{1}{\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\right)}
\end{matrix}\right]=\nonumber \\
= & \left[\begin{matrix}var\left(\hat{a}\right) & cov\left(\hat{a},\hat{b}\right)\\
cov\left(\hat{b},\hat{a}\right) & var\left(\hat{b}\right)
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diagonal elements of the variance-covariance matrix are the variance for each coefficient's estimator.
 The square root of these gives us the standard error for each coefficient,
 which we need to calculate the two-sided t-tests for each coefficient.
 Above we defined the variance for the estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{a}\right)=\left(se\left(\hat{a}\right)\right)^{2} & =\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\frac{\sum x_{i}^{2}}{n}\\
var\left(\hat{b}\right)=\left(se\left(\hat{b}\right)\right)^{2} & =\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same notation as in the diagonal of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 variance-covariance matrix.
 We see this by rewriting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2} & =\sum x_{i}^{2}-2\sum x_{i}\bar{x}+\sum\bar{x}^{2}\\
 & =\sum x_{i}^{2}-2n\bar{x}^{2}+n\bar{x}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum x_{i}^{2}-n\frac{1}{n}\sum x_{i}\frac{1}{n}\sum x_{i}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum x_{i}^{2}-\bar{x}\sum x_{i}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where in the last row we now get the same expression as found in the denominator of each element in the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the definition of the coefficient estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y$
\end_inset

 we see how every other variable in the regression model can affect the estimates for all coefficients in the model.
 The variance-covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 illustrates how each explanatory variable that is included or excluded in the regression model can also affect the results for the statistical tests for all coefficients in the model,
 since all explanatory variables are represented in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The significance of this for analytical work in general and the social sciences as a whole cannot be overstated.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: ols kvasiexperiment"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we went through how we need special methods to study causal relationships,
 not least because there is no method to objectively prove that a phenomenon should be included or excluded in an analysis.
 The variance-covariance matrix illustrates even more clearly why this type of challenge is important to consider.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
T-test for regression models with more than two variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:T-test regression flera variabler"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we have everything we need to use statistical tests when we have more than two coefficients in a regression model.
 In this section we go through a computational example of how this can be done technically.
 The example is greatly simplified and aims only to illustrate the method and the mathematical calculations.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=a+bx_{i}+cz_{i}+v_{i}\label{eq: t-test reg modell 3 vars}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y,x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Based on the four observations in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Fyra-observationer k 29"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated the coefficients as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{a}\approx2.89,\,\hat{b}\approx0.28,\,\hat{c}\approx-0.54
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will use t-tests to test the probability that the three coefficients are different from zero.
 We therefore set up three null and alternative hypotheses:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{matrix}H_{0}:a=0\\
H_{1}:a\neq0
\end{matrix}\, &  & \begin{matrix}H_{0}:b=0\\
H_{1}:b\neq0
\end{matrix}\, &  & \begin{matrix}H_{0}:c=0\\
H_{1}:c\neq0
\end{matrix}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t!test
\end_layout

\end_inset

We start from the significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 All three tests are two-sided t-tests and the t-values are estimated as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t_{\hat{a}}=\frac{\hat{a}}{se\left(\hat{a}\right)}\,, &  & t_{b}=\frac{\hat{b}}{se\left(\hat{b}\right)}\,, &  & t_{\hat{c}}=\frac{\hat{c}}{se\left(\hat{c}\right)}
\end{align}

\end_inset


