\begin_layout Standard
When we now have three variables in the regression model,
 the variance for our three estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 becomes the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{a}\right) & =\hat{s}\left(\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\bar{x}^{2}\sum\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)^{2}+\bar{z}^{2}\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}-2\bar{x}\bar{z}\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)}{\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\sum\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)^{2}-\left(\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)\\
var\left(\hat{b}\right) & =\hat{s}\left(\frac{\sum\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\sum\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)^{2}-\left(\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)\nonumber \\
var\left(\hat{c}\right) & =\hat{s}\left(\frac{\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}\sum\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)^{2}-\left(\sum\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(z_{i}-\bar{z}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\size default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated standard deviation for the residuals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{s} & =\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}}{n-p}\approx\frac{0.338}{4-3}\approx0.338
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 we take from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Beräkningar-med y yhat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The letter n is the number of observations and p is the number of coefficients in the regression model,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $n-p=4-3=1$
\end_inset

.
 The standard deviation for the residuals is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}\approx0.338$
\end_inset

.
 We estimate the standard deviation for the three coefficients by taking the square root of the variance (compare the calculations in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
se\left(\hat{a}\right) & =+\left(0.338\left(\frac{1}{4}+\frac{25*9+2.25*10-2*5*1,5*\left(-4\right)}{10*9-\left(-4\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{1/2}\approx1,22\\
se\left(\hat{b}\right) & =+\left(0.338\left(\frac{9}{10*9-\left(-4\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{1/2}\approx0.203\nonumber \\
se\left(\hat{c}\right) & =+\left(0.338\left(\frac{10}{10*9-\left(-4\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{1/2}\approx0.214\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Now we estimate the t-values for the t-tests:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t_{\hat{a}} & =\frac{2.89}{1.22}\approx2.37\\
t_{\hat{b}} & =\frac{0.28}{0.203}\approx1.4\nonumber \\
t_{\hat{c}} & =\frac{-0.54}{0.214}\approx-2.52\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p-value
\end_layout

\end_inset

We compare these to the critical t-values in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:t-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|t\right|>t^{*}$
\end_inset

 we reject the respective 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 The probability for our t-values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(X\leq t\right)$
\end_inset

,
 corresponds to approximately 25,
 39 and 24% probability respectively that each 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is false,
 which corresponds to the tests' p-values.
 We reject none of the three null hypotheses and therefore have no reason to believe that the coefficients a,
 b or c are different from zero.
 The coefficient estimates could just as well have arisen through a random process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
F-test for the regression model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:F-test-för-hela"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regression!analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
F-test
\end_layout

\end_inset

Another commonly occurring statistical test in connection with regression analysis is the F-test for comparing entire regression models.
 Say for example that we have the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{modell 1 }(m1):\,\,y=b_{0}+b_{1}x_{1}+...+b_{k}x_{k}+u\label{eq: full model f-test}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where y and x are variables and u is the error term.
 a and b are the coefficients that we will estimate based on the least squares method.
 The F-test we will use now tests whether this model can better explain variation in variable y compared to a more stripped-down,
 restricted,
 regression model.
 A more stripped-down model could for example be a regression model with only the y-intercept a,
 without explanatory variables:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{modell 2 }(m2):\,\,y=a+v\label{eq: reducerad modell f-test}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have the coefficient a and the error term v.
 We formulate our null hypothesis as the absence of covariation,
 a non-relationship,
 in this case for all coefficients in the unrestricted regression model m1:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hypothesis!test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{0} & :b_{1}=...=b_{k}=0\\
H_{1} & :\text{Minst en av }b_{i}\neq0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The alternative hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 means that if any of the coefficients is statistically significantly different from 0 we have reason to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we prefer we can also compare a complete model with different variants of restricted regression models.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ssr sse sst vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we introduced the sum of squared residuals,
 
\begin_inset Formula $SSR=\sum_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\hat{Y}_{i}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $MSR=SSR/\left(n-p\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 = number of observations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 = number of coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-p$
\end_inset

 is the number of degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(df\right)$
\end_inset

 for a regression model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now define 
\begin_inset Formula $q=df_{m1}-df_{m2}=k_{m1}$
\end_inset

,
 which corresponds to the number of restrictions since in model 2 we set all explanatory variables to 0.
 To test our hypotheses we now calculate the test function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F & =\left(\frac{SSR_{m2}-SSR_{m1}}{SSR_{m1}}\right)/\left(\frac{q}{n-k_{m1}-1}\right)\label{eq: F-test regressionsanalys}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum\hat{v}_{i}^{2}-\sum\hat{u}_{i}^{2}}{\sum\hat{u}_{i}^{2}}\right)/\left(\frac{q}{n-k_{m1}-1}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letter n is the number of observations and k is the number of explanatory variables.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m2}-k_{m1}>0$
\end_inset

 since model 2 is a stripped-down variant of model 1.
 In this example we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m1}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Our estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\left(q,n-k-1\right)}$
\end_inset

 is compared with critical values in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:F-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 based on chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $df_{1}=q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $df_{2}=n-k-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F>F^{*}$
\end_inset

 we reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us illustrate by again using the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=a+bx_{i}+cz_{i}+e_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left\{ 3,2,5,4\right\} ,\,x=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\left\{ 1,4,0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:T-test regression flera variabler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}\approx2.89$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}\approx0.28$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}\approx-0.54$
\end_inset

.
 Now we will perform an F-test to check this.
 We choose significance 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

 and have the following null and alternative hypothesis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{0}:b=c=0, & \;H_{1}:b\text{ eller }c\neq0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unrestricted regression model is 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=a+bx_{i}+cz_{i}+u_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m1\right)$
\end_inset

 and the restricted 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=a+v_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For unrestricted 
\begin_inset Formula $m1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\hat{u}_{i}^{2}=\sum\left(y_{i,m1}-\hat{y}_{i,m1}\right)^{2}=0.338
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the restricted regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $m2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\hat{v}_{i}^{2}=\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}\right)^{2}=\sum\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}=5
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m1}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=2$
\end_inset

,
 which gives us:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F & =\left(\frac{\sum\hat{v}_{i}^{2}-\sum\hat{u}_{i}^{2}}{\sum\hat{u}_{i}^{2}}\right)/\left(\frac{q}{n-k_{m1}-1}\right)\\
 & \approx\left(\frac{5-0.338}{0.338}\right)/\left(\frac{2}{4-2-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \approx6.9\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compare this to the pre-calculated critical 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}$
\end_inset

 in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:F-fördelningens-sannolikheter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 based on the degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $df_{1}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $df_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Our estimated F-value is not statistically significant and we therefore do not reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 as false.
 This gives us no reason to regard the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 as different from 0.
 This type of F-statistic is often presented in ANOVA tables,
 which many analysis tools have ready commands for (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: ssr sse sst vilken modell är bäst"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Theoretical assumptions for the least squares method:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The population's regression model written with matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=XB+V$
\end_inset

 describes a linear relationship between the explained 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the explanatory variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that exists in the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a random variable.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is either random (observational study) or the result of a controlled process (for example experiment).
 The process that generates the variables is unrelated to the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No strong multicollinearity between the variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No strong autocorrelation between the error terms:
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(v_{i}v_{j}|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

,
 which is why 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 do not covary:
 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(V,X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The error terms have constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)=\sigma^{2}I$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix.
 The error terms follow the normal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $V|X\sim N\left(0,\sigma^{2}I\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For a regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+V$
\end_inset

 the variance-covariance matrix can be described:
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)=\left[\begin{matrix}var\left(\hat{a}\right) & cov\left(\hat{a},\hat{b}\right)\\
cov\left(\hat{b},\hat{a}\right) & var\left(\hat{b}\right)
\end{matrix}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The diagonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 is the variance for each coefficient's estimator.
 The square root of each variance gives the standard error for each estimated coefficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For each additional coefficient added to the regression model,
 a row and a column is added to 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The estimated variance-covariance matrix for a regression model that fulfills all the theoretical assumptions is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)=\hat{s}\left(X'X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated standard error of the regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can use t-tests to test the probability that each coefficient in matrix B is statistically significantly different from 0.
 Observations from all variables included in the regression model can affect both the estimates of the coefficients and the statistical tests.
 We see this in the variance-covariance matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
F-tests can be used to test the statistical certainty of the entire regression model compared to an analysis where none of the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 covary with the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The null hypothesis can then be formulated as all coefficients in a model being equal to 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even for the statistical tests we use in connection with regression analysis,
 statistical power can be estimated.
 If we estimate the coefficients on a relatively small sample,
 a larger estimated deviation in a coefficient is required,
 all else being equal,
 for us to reject the null hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even for the coefficients and predicted
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 in the regression model we can estimate confidence intervals,
 which among other things depends on significance level and degrees of freedom.
 Confidence intervals for predicted
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 vary for different values of
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

