\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gauss-Markov theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset

The theoretical assumptions for the least squares method are described in the Gauss-Markov theorem,
 or Gauss-Markov theorem,
 named after Carl Friedrich Gauss and Andrey Markov.
 The theorem describes the conditions for the least squares method estimator to have the smallest sampling variance among all linear unbiased estimators.
 The word "unbiased" refers to the model estimating the population value correctly.
 The conditions can be presented in slightly different ways and the description depends partly on what type of data we are studying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one or more of these conditions are not fulfilled,
 the results we estimate using the least squares method risk becoming misleading.
 When we analyze real data,
 it is common that one or more conditions are not fulfilled.
 This may sound discouraging,
 but fortunately there are also several established methods for handling these challenges.
 This chapter provides occasional simple examples of solutions,
 but for those interested there is a large amount of literature to delve deeper into.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 1:
 Linearity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gauss-Markov-2:-Linjäritet"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start from the following regression model for the population,
 the population model,
 described with matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=XB+V\label{eq: gauss markov POPULATIONSMODELLEN matriser}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have n number of observations and k number of explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},...,x_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 number of coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},b_{1},...,b_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The letters in the regression model symbolize the same matrices as described in previous examples,
 such as chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regression model describes a linear relationship that is found in the population.
 In the population model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gauss markov POPULATIONSMODELLEN matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we can think of the coefficients as there being explanatory variables that are already in logarithmic form or otherwise calculated in such a way that the relationship becomes linear.
 Linearity means that all coefficients in a regression model have exponent = 1.
 The following models are not linear:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =a+\frac{1}{b}X+e\\
\log Z & =\alpha+\beta D+\epsilon\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

In the first regression model we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{b}=b^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the second model we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(Z_{1}+Z_{2}\right)\neq\log\left(Z_{1}\right)+\log\left(Z_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two arbitrary values in variable Z (compare section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:När är ekvation linjär"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 chapters 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Logaritmer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomekvationer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: en linje är en linje"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw examples of how we get incorrect results if we try to estimate a linear regression model on variables that have nonlinear relationships.
 The risk is that we miss covariation that exists in the data,
 or find some form of covariation that becomes misleading.
 If our regression model is misspecified,
 we can try to reformulate the model so that it better describes the covariation we are looking for.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be difficult to test whether a regression model is a good linear approximation of the data we are studying.
 We may for instance inspect the data in a scatter graph or histogram,
 and compare different measures of dispersion.
 We can both compare how the explained variable covaries with our explanatory variables,
 and compare how the residuals are distributed around a regression line.
