\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_gdp pred residuals.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "

\end_inset

Linear trend for GDP and ln GDP
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have previously gone through several examples of how to use logarithms to handle nonlinear relationships between variables,
 such as when we studied gross national product,
 GDP (sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: log linjär ex BNP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: log bnp och lycka"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Let us again illustrate this by comparing US GDP every tenth year during the period 1800–2000,
 see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BNP-1800–2000"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with years,
 GDP and logarithmic GDP (compare sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: linjär trend OLS log bnp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Cykler och vågor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the linear trend over time for GDP and ln(GDP) respectively is illustrated in separate graphs.
 In the left graph the trend is estimated based on the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{t}=a+b\text{YEAR}_{t}+V_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is GDP in year t,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{YEAR}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a variable for the years 1800,
 1810,
 ...,
 1990,
 2000.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 In the right graph we have estimated the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln Y_{t}=c+d\text{YEAR}_{t}+U_{t}\label{eq: gauss-markov log bnp trend}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is logarithmic GDP in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As seen in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: linjär trend OLS log bnp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 a linear model fits the data relatively poorly when we use GDP,
 which we see in the left graph.
 The data points in the graph are placed approximately in the shape of a lying L.
 The development is exponential and not linear.
 The regression line does capture the positive development but does not give a representative picture of the long-term trend in GDP.
 During the years 1800–1850,
 to the left in the graph,
 the regression line is below 0.
 This means that the regression model predicts that GDP was negative all years before 1850.
 Since GDP is a measure of everything that is produced,
 bought and sold in a society,
 this is not possible.
 The linear model does however capture the long-term trend in logarithmic GDP relatively well,
 which is seen in the right graph where the points follow the regression line for all the years 1800–2000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to compare how well the linear regression model captures the covariation in the data is to compare the residuals.
 In the two graphs vertical lines connect each point and the regression line.
 In the left graph the distance between the points and the regression line varies in a way that they do not in the right graph.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: linjär trend OLS log bnp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 logarithms can often be used to create a more linear relationship between variables.
 This often works well for exponential series.
 Unfortunately there is no general solution that works for all regression models.
 In the right graph the points follow a more linear pattern,
 and is closer to the regression line.
 Note however how the data points in the right graph do not describe an exact linear relationship.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice,
 we often in analytical work encounter populations with variables with nonlinear relationships.
 But even then we benefit from a linear regression model as a linear approximation,
 rather than an exact description of the population.
 When this is more or less suitable depends on what the purpose of the analysis is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 2:
 Independent and identically distributed observations (i.i.d.)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gauss-Markov-1:-Slumpmässiga"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gauss markov POPULATIONSMODELLEN matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a random variable drawn from the population.
 The explanatory variables in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can either be random (as in an observational study) or created through a controlled process,
 for example in a controlled experiment where we ourselves design the treatment.
 Regardless,
 none of the variables are correlated with the error term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the description of the least squares method above we assume that each observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{i},x_{1,i},...x_{k,i}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,n$
\end_inset

,
 is independent and identically distributed.
 That is,
 each observation is drawn in a random sample from a population with the same distribution.
 That the observations are independent means that the observations do not covary with each other in a systematic way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say for example that we want to study the covariation between some characteristics that people have.
 The characteristics are our variables and each person has their own observation.
 We draw a random sample from the population,
 which fulfills the assumption of i.i.d (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: OLS Antaganden 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But say now that we want to follow people over time,
 so that each observation is information about a person at a point in time.
 One of the variables is earnings.
 Even though people's earnings vary over time,
 we will be able to see patterns where different observations can be followed in patterns.
 The observations for a person's earnings are therefore not independent of each other and therefore also do not fulfill the assumption of i.i.d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 3:
 Expected value and variance of the error terms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gauss-Markov-3:-Homoskedasticite"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value of the error terms with respect to the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(V|X\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This also means that the error terms V do not covary with any of the explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This can be described as us having exogenous explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If any explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},...,x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is correlated with the error term v this is called the variable being endogenous.
 In addition we assume that the error terms V have the same variance,
 regardless of observation and variable:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!exogenous
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!endogenous
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(V|X\right)=\sigma^{2}I_{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
homoscedasticity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
heteroscedasticity
\end_layout

\end_inset

where the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (Greek letter sigma) symbolizes the population's constant variance and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 That the error term exhibits constant variance is usually called homoscedasticity.
 Its opposite is called heteroscedasticity,
 which means that the variance in the error term varies across the observations in one or more explanatory variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Heteroscedasticity can mean that the error terms do follow a normal distribution,
 but that the variance in the normal distribution varies across the observations.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_heteroskedasticitet.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Heteroskedasticitet:-punkternas-"

\end_inset

Heteroscedasticity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Heteroskedasticitet:-punkternas-"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates heteroscedasticity by comparing the residuals' covariation against the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The points' distance to the regression line varies across X.
 Further to the right in the graph the distance between the line and the points is larger compared to the points further to the left.
 The residuals' variance is thus not constant (homoscedasticity) across different observations but varies (heteroscedasticity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common assumption for the error terms is that these follow a normal distribution (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: Gauss-Markov 6 Normalfördelade-feltermer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 Combined with the assumption of homoscedasticity this means that the error terms' dispersion around the regression line follows a normal distribution with the same shape,
 regardless of which values for the explanatory variables X we compare against.
 With heteroscedasticity we may for example have normally distributed error terms but with different variance.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Normalfördelningar heteroskedasticitet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates an example where we have three normal distributions with different variance along a regression line.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename heteronorm_3d_plot_cropped.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	scale 26

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Normalfördelningar heteroskedasticitet"

\end_inset

Different variance along the regression line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the error term's variance is not constant across different observations,
 heteroscedasticity,
 this can lead to the statistical tests (for example t-test and F-test) giving incorrect results and not being usable.
 It is therefore often important to check for heteroscedasticity,
 which can be done in different ways.
 One way is to compare the dispersion of the residuals in graphs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Heteroskedasticitet:-punkternas-"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we also see examples of this in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the left graph further to the right we see some relatively large distances between points and the regression line.
 In the right graph the distance between the regression line and the points does vary,
 but the points overall have a more even distance to the line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above we described how we in many situations can use a linear regression model to describe a linear approximation for a relationship between two variables that is actually nonlinear.
 In such cases it is also common that the error terms do not have constant variance,
 that is,
 we find heteroscedasticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 4:
 Multicollinearity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gauss-Markov-4:-Multikollinearit"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
type 2 error
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
multicollinearity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
collinearity
\end_layout

\end_inset

The explanatory variables in the regression model must not correlate too strongly with each other.
 If a variable is a linear function of another variable in the regression model this is called them exhibiting collinearity.
 If several variables exhibit high correlation this is called multicollinearity.
 Suppose we have the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 = earnings in USD,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 = earnings in thousands of USD.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be described as a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}:x_{1}=1,000*x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
perfect collinearity
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is included in the regression model then it does not add any information to our analysis to also add 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multicollinearity can affect the results in the regression analysis and disturb the calculation of the slope coefficients.
 In addition it can cause the variance in slope coefficients to become larger than what would otherwise have been the case.
 This can in turn reduce the probability that we in a t-test discover a statistically significant covariation between the variables concerned and the explained variable.
 Instead we risk accepting a false null hypothesis,
 a type 2 error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption about the absence of multicollinearity does not mean that two or more variables in a regression model may not covary at all.
 In regression analysis it is common that many variables have some form of relationship and that they therefore often covary more or less.
 The problem arises when they exhibit too high correlation.
 Perfect collinearity is usually easy to remedy by removing one of the variables from the regression model.
 Sometimes however it happens that two variables "happen to" have high correlation.
 In such cases it is difficult to give general recommendations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To detect collinearity we can study covariation between variables in graphs.
 It is also possible to estimate covariation between our explanatory variables,
 either via regression analysis or some other method.
 A common relatively simple check is to estimate the correlation coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}$
\end_inset

 (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Pearsons-r"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for all pairs of explanatory variables.
 There is no exact value for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}$
\end_inset

 that guarantees high collinearity,
 but a common recommendation is that if two explanatory variables exhibit 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{xy}>0.8$
\end_inset

,
 this should be regarded as an indication of problematically high collinearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another common method for checking the occurrence of multicollinearity is to estimate the variance inflation factor (VIF).
 Suppose we have the following regression model:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variance Inflation Factor
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+cZ+V\label{eq: regmodell VIF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 are variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 To estimate VIF we take the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}Z+U\label{eq: VIF reg mod 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 are variables from the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regmodell VIF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients and U is the error term.
 We estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: VIF reg mod 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and thereafter the VIF factor for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 (from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: regmodell VIF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
VIF\left(\hat{b}\right)=\frac{1}{1-R^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result gives us an indication of how high the collinearity is.
 A rule of thumb is that if the VIF factor for an explanatory variable is over 5 or 10 this indicates high multicollinearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 5:
 Correlation between residuals
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gauss-Markov-5: autokorr"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
autocorrelation
\end_layout

\end_inset

The error terms in the regression model are assumed to be uncorrelated,
 which can be described as the covariance
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(v_{i},v_{j}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 refer to any observations).
 Another way to describe this is that the error term should not covary with itself.
 This phenomenon is called autocorrelation,
 or serial correlation.
 We usually don't know the error terms in the population but we may examine the occurrence of autocorrelation among our estimated residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autocorrelation can for example arise if our regression model estimates the covariation between variables over time.
 We illustrate this by again comparing the examples with linear trend for the natural log of GDP (e.g.
 section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Gauss-Markov-1:-Slumpmässiga"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln Y_{t}=c+d\text{YEAR}_{t}+U_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename g_274_residualcov.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Korrelation-mellan-residualerna"

\end_inset

The residuals from the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gauss-markov log bnp trend"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Korrelation-mellan-residualerna"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the covariation between the estimated residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}_{t}$
\end_inset

 from this model.
 In the left graph only the residuals are shown,
 where the marked horizontal line at 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=0$
\end_inset

 is the regression line from the right graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The points in the left graph (the residuals) form the shape of a U,
 kind of.
 Residuals that are positive,
 above the 0-line,
 are often followed by another positive residual.
 And the residuals that are negative,
 below the 0-line,
 are often followed by another negative residual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern in the left graph is confirmed in the right graph where we instead see the covariation between residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the residual for the previous year 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}_{t-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The straight diagonal line in the graph is the regression line from the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}_{t}=\beta\hat{U}_{t-1}+\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The correlation is positive,
 which indicate autocorrelation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autocorrelation does not affect the coefficients in our original regression model.
 But autocorrelation can lead to the standard error becoming smaller than it actually is,
 which in turn can cause the t-tests for the slope coefficients to give a higher t-value than otherwise and we may reject a true null hypothesis (type 2 error).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is,
 in the t-test for slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we estimate the t-value 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\frac{\hat{b}-b_{0}}{se\left(\hat{b}\right)}$
\end_inset

 (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:regressionsanalys med statistiska test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $se\left(\hat{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the standard error for estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

.
 If we test the hypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\frac{\hat{b}}{se\left(\hat{b}\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 If the standard error in the denominator of the t-value decreases then our estimated t-value increases and we will then get a value further out in the tails of the t-distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumption 6:
 Normally distributed error terms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: Gauss-Markov 6 Normalfördelade-feltermer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the above conditions for the least squares method,
 an additional condition is often mentioned in this context:
 that the error term is normally distributed across all observations and explanatory variables in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We describe this as 
\begin_inset Formula $V|X\sim N\left(0,\sigma^{2}I_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Gauss-Markov-3:-Homoskedasticite"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Given that the error term and the residuals are approximately normally distributed we use t-tests to calculate the probability that our estimated coefficients is a result of a random process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if we have good reasons to expect that the error term follow a normal distribution they can in practice follow any distribution whatsoever.
 This condition too (that the error term follow a normal distribution) we therefore check by studying the residuals.
 A first step can be to compare how the residuals are distributed in graphs.
 Let us illustrate this using the same data for logarithmic GDP that is shown in the right graph in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: gauss-markov linjär BNP och ln BNP "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The regression line in the right graph is created by estimating the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln Y_{t}=c+d\text{YEAR}_{t}+U_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 If we take the estimated residuals from that graph and compare how they are are distributed around their own mean,
 we get the distribution shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Histogram residualer log bnp trend tid"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

