name "fig: gauss markov residualanalys Kolada inkomst och livslängd"

\end_inset

Life expectancy and GDP,
 regression line and distribution of the residuals from the model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gauss markov kolada reg model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we shall instead look at the residuals,
 whose distribution is illustrated in the graph to the right.
 The residual is the difference between predicted and observed life expectancy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}_{i}=L_{i}-\hat{L_{i}}$
\end_inset

,
 thus the vertical difference between the regression line and each observation.
 The bars in the right graph show the proportional distribution of the residuals and a normal distribution density curve with the same mean (zero) and variance as the residuals in the graph.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compare the bars to the density curve to judge if the residuals' (estimation of the population error terms) distribution resembles a normal distribution.
 The bars do not really follow the normal distribution curve.
 The negative tail is longer than the positive tail,
 thus meaning that the negative residuals extend further away from zero,
 compared to the positive ones.
 Whether we accept the residuals' distribution as an indication that the population error terms follow a normal distribution depends,
 at least partly,
 on how big deviations from a normal distribution we wish to tolerate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes a transformation of the variables in the regression model,
 for example taking logarithms,
 can lead to the residuals following a normal distribution.
 Sometimes the log version of a variable can follow a log-normal distribution despite the variable not following the normal distribution (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Normalfördelning användbar 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 There are also specific methods for how to perform a regression analysis and instead assume that the error terms follow other types of probability distribution,
 which there is no room to go through here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Adjusted standard errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
robust standard errors
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this chapter we have gone through the conditions of the least squares method as well as examples of phenomena that violate these.
 Some of these deviating phenomena can be remedied by thinking through the model's design.
 Some deviating phenomena can be handled by adjusting the data we study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also many well-known alternative methods for estimating regression models and using statistical tests.
 A well-known such example is what is called robust standard errors,
 also called heteroscedasticity-robust standard errors or heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors.
 Sometimes the same thing is called White's standard errors after an article by Halbert White 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "whiteHeteroskedasticityConsistentCovarianceMatrix1980"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that contributed to the spread of this method within economics.
 Here follows a brief description,
 largely based on Hansen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "hansenEconometrics2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 chapter 4.
 Many computer programs for statistical analysis have simple shortcut commands for all such calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Robust standard errors is a summary term for a type of adjustment that we can perform on the residuals so that these can be used for regression analysis based on the least squares method,
 even in the presence of heteroscedasticity.
 Suppose we have the following regression model for the population:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=XB+V
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are matrices with explained and explanatory variables respectively,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the error terms.
 We have previously defined the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y$
\end_inset

 and in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: varians-kovariansmatrisen matris def 1A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we defined the variance-covariance matrix:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variance-covariance matrix
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}E\left[VV^{T}|X\right]X\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\label{eq: robusta se , var-kovar-matrisen}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that the error terms exhibit constant variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (homoscedasticity) is 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)=\sigma^{2}I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)=\sigma^{2}\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If we work with sample data it is common that the residuals exhibit irregular variance (heteroscedasticity).
 What we now seek is an alternative version of the variance-covariance matrix that takes into account whether we have heteroscedasticity in our data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to estimate the residuals' variance as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}^{2}=\frac{\sum\left(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}}{\left(n-p\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 The letters 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(VV^{T}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 are the error terms in the population,
 which we do not know.
 Instead we use the estimated residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 and get 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\hat{V}\hat{V}^{T}|X\right)=\text{diag}\left(\hat{v}_{1}^{2},\hat{v}_{2}^{2},...\hat{v}_{n}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which is a diagonal matrix where the diagonal elements consist of the squared estimated residuals.
 We insert this into the variance-covariance matrix in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: robusta se , var-kovar-matrisen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and rewrite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(X^{T}E\left(\hat{V}\hat{V}^{T}|X\right)X\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\label{eq: var-covar robust 1}\\
 & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}^{T}\hat{v}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a variant of the variance-covariance matrix,
 robust for heteroscedasticity.
 We mark this version of the variance-covariance matrix with "
\begin_inset Formula $\text{HC0}$
\end_inset

":
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Estimated results in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}}$
\end_inset

 we use to for example estimate t-tests for the coefficients in regression models where the data exhibit heteroscedasticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Regressionsanalys med test, flera variabler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we saw how the variance-covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric,
 the elements in the diagonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

 are the variance for each coefficient's estimator,
 while the other elements are covariance for the coefficients' estimators.
 The difference with 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}}$
\end_inset

 consists in how the estimates are estimated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also additional variants of 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The following version is often denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}\right)^{\text{HC1}}$
\end_inset

 and aims to adjust for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v}_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 risking becoming too low 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hinkleyJackknifingUnbalancedSituations1977"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
var\left(\hat{B}\right)^{\text{HC1}}=\left(\frac{n}{n-k}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}^{T}\hat{v}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


