 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap: OLS flera variabler, matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =XB+V\\
\left[\begin{matrix}3\\
2\\
5\\
4
\end{matrix}\right] & =\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 3 & 1\\
1 & 4 & 4\\
1 & 6 & 0\\
1 & 7 & 1
\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}a\\
b\\
c
\end{matrix}\right]+\left[\begin{matrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
v_{3}\\
v_{4}
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where V is the error terms.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: beräkna OLS med matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we estimated this regression model,
 found the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}\approx\left\{ -0.2,0.14,0.41,-0.34\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the variance 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{V}\right)=\hat{s}^{2}\approx0.338$
\end_inset

.
 We now estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{HC0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{HC1}$
\end_inset

.
 We do not go through the calculations in detail here but primarily describe the results:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right) & =\hat{s}^{2}\left(XX^{T}\right)^{-1}\\
 & \approx0.338\left(\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 3 & 1\\
1 & 4 & 4\\
1 & 6 & 0\\
1 & 7 & 1
\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 1 & 1 & 1\\
3 & 4 & 6 & 7\\
1 & 4 & 0 & 1
\end{matrix}\right]\right)^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & \approx\left[\begin{matrix}1.49 & -0.23 & -0.16\\
-0.23 & 0.04 & 0.02\\
-0.16 & 0.02 & 0.05
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}}$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}} & =\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}^{T}\hat{e}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\\
 & \approx\left[\begin{matrix}0.247 & -0.041 & -0.025\\
-0.041 & 0.0086 & 0.002\\
-0.025 & 0.002 & 0.0066
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC1}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC1}} & =\left(\frac{n}{n-k}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i}^{n}X_{i}X_{i}^{T}\hat{e}_{i}^{2}\right)\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}\\
 & \approx\left[\begin{matrix}0.987 & -0.164 & -0.102\\
-0.164 & 0.034 & 0.008\\
-0.102 & 0.008 & 0.026
\end{matrix}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n}{n-k}=\frac{4}{4-3}=4$
\end_inset

.
 Note how the elements in the diagonal for each variance-covariance matrix represent the variance for the coefficients' estimators.
 Of these three matrices we get the highest values in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Second highest values are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC1}}$
\end_inset

,
 while the lowest variance for the coefficients' estimators is found in 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\hat{B}|X\right)^{\text{HC0}}$
\end_inset

.
 These are three variants of the variance-covariance matrix among many conceivable ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Gauss-Markov theorem describes the theoretical assumptions that must hold for the least squares method's estimator to have the smallest sampling variance among all linear unbiased estimators.
 A common,
 but not necessary,
 assumption in regression analysis with the least squares method is that the error terms follow a normal distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is common that one or several of the assumptions in the Gauss-Markov theorem are not fulfilled.
 There are different methods and tests to check if the conditions are fulfilled as well as different methods to handle deviations from the conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As an example,
 in the presence of heteroscedasticity one can use adjusted standard errors (robust standard errors).
\end_layout

