\begin_layout Part
Computer Programs for Social Scientist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This part of the book introduces computer programs that can be used for analysis.
 In separate chapters,
 a brief introduction is given to three analysis tools:
 the computer program Microsoft Excel,
 the program Stata,
 and the programming language R.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Why use computers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analysis tools like Excel,
 Stata and R contain an enormous amount of possibilities and different types of commands.
 In analytical work with this type of program,
 there are usually many different ways to solve one and the same problem.
 There is rarely a simple answer to exactly which method is best,
 but it depends on both situation and user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose here is for you to get started as quickly as possible with independent work and be able to learn more on your own.
 This text is relatively brief and offers no in-depth knowledge.
 The instructions given can therefore best be described as examples of how we can use the programs.
 As you learn more,
 you will probably soon discover other ways to solve the same problems described here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These instructions require no advanced prior knowledge of computers,
 analysis programs,
 mathematics,
 or statistics.
 However,
 the reader should have basic computer skills and at least a superficial understanding of concepts such as hard drive,
 working memory,
 file,
 and how to download a file from the internet and save it on the computer's hard drive in a specific directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the description of the analysis tools,
 keyboard shortcuts are used in several places.
 For Windows,
 the Ctrl key is often used.
 The corresponding key on Mac is the CMD key.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Three analytical tools
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three tools are introduced through examples based on similar tasks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Saving and editing information,
 primarily by working with data organized in tables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Importing and exporting information from and to files on the hard drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mathematical operations and commands for working with matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Describing quantitative data using measures of central tendency and dispersion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Commands for calculating probabilities with common probability distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Creating charts and graphics to illustrate data and mathematical functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Commands for basic regression analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first analysis tool is Microsoft Excel,
 which is included in the Microsoft Office software package.
 First released in 1985,
 Excel is today a versatile program for editing spreadsheets and other tasks.
 It is now one of the most widely installed computer programs in the world and is used across different types of organizations for analytical work and other purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second program is Stata,
 commonly used for statistical analysis at universities,
 government agencies,
 and private companies.
 First released in 1985,
 Stata is today one of the world's best-known analysis programs.
 The program is developed by StataCorp,
 which operates the website www.stata.com.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third tool is R,
 a programming language designed for statistical analysis and other purposes.
 First introduced in the 1990s,
 R has since become one of the world's most popular programming languages.
 Unlike Excel and Stata,
 R is open source and therefore available as a free download.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three tools offer extensive functionality and applications,
 of which we introduce only a fraction.
 Each tool also supports various add-ons and functions that can be downloaded at no additional cost.
 For Stata and R,
 users commonly create and share their own functions and commands freely,
 rapidly expanding the programs' capabilities.
 We will use several such examples in their respective chapters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many people hold strong opinions that their particular computer program,
 analysis tool,
 or method is superior.
 Such debates are often pointless.
 The best tool or method depends on the task,
 objectives,
 available resources,
 and other factors.
 Often the best program is simply the one we feel most comfortable using.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 there are compelling reasons to become proficient with multiple analysis tools and programs.
 Different programs have distinct advantages and disadvantages.
 Sometimes specific tools offer particularly elegant solutions to particular problems.
 Knowledge of various tools can inspire new thinking and reveal innovative solutions.
 Sometimes we must use a program simply because others in our organization use it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we become familiar with a particular tool,
 it's easy to become complacent and feel we don't need to learn more.
 But both computers and analysis programs evolve constantly.
 It's therefore generally wise to maintain an open mind and occasionally invest time in learning something new.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Programming:
 Why bother?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Varför-skriva-kod?"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large portions of this book focus on introducing written commands and programming code for Stata and R.
 For readers unfamiliar with programming,
 this approach may seem unnecessarily complex.
 However,
 most computer programs require only a few hours of introduction to get started.
 Once we grasp a program's underlying logic,
 learning new solutions becomes straightforward.
 In data analysis work,
 regardless of the program we use,
 we typically benefit from knowing perhaps 20 commonly used commands.
 With knowledge of these fundamental commands,
 it is usually easy to look up new commands as needed.
 Moreover,
 programming languages for data analysis share many similarities,
 meaning that once you learn one,
 learning others becomes relatively easy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those who have never worked with programming may struggle to see its value.
 Since programming requires practice,
 there is usually at least a small learning curve to overcome initially.
 However,
 the better we become at programming,
 the better we become at recognizing when our skills prove useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For analytical work,
 computers particularly benefit us for at least two types of tasks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Complex tasks:
 For example,
 intricate mathematical calculations that would be time-consuming to solve manually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Repetitive tasks:
 For example,
 performing simple calculations many times,
 or finding all instances of a word in a text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most work ultimately involves substantial repetition,
 where similar tasks recur.
 This pattern is not always immediately apparent.
 Sometimes identifying which tasks we actually repeat becomes a crucial part of the work process itself.
 The more skilled we become with analysis tools,
 the better we become at recognizing situations where computers can assist us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instructing computers to perform repeated tasks with slight variations between iterations is relatively straightforward—
for example,
 summing a collection of numbers.
 The more proficient we become at writing code,
 the more sophisticated repetitions we can request from the computer.
 Many such repetitive tasks would be virtually impossible,
 or prohibitively time-consuming,
 without programming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond technical capabilities,
 programming serves as an excellent method for documenting our work processes,
 which proves valuable for several reasons.
 When working with data,
 projects often require substantial time compiling and editing source material before producing the main results.
 Sometimes we need to correct minor errors or simply reformat information.
 Frequently we want to add rows or columns to tables,
 or merge multiple tables.
 Every work step carries the risk of error.
 With large datasets,
 detecting mistakes becomes increasingly difficult.
 However,
 when we program all steps,
 finding and correcting errors typically becomes much easier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
You have to practice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To learn how to use a computer program or analysis tool,
 we cannot simply read about the methods.
 We must spend considerable time working independently,
 finding and solving our own problems,
 and making many mistakes before getting things right.
 To benefit from this book,
 you should follow along with the examples and work hands-on with the programs yourself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many (all?) computer programs have at least some form of pedagogical help sections accessible from within the program.
 The internet also offers enormous amounts of educational material,
 including exercises,
 instructional videos,
 free books,
 articles,
 and more.
 AI tools can be used to create programming code and give advice on which program and which function you may use to solve specific problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many analysis programs are designed so that users can create their own new functions and then share them freely with other users via the internet.
 This means that the number of commands in these programs are constantly growing.
 All programs are also updated regularly by their producers.
\end_layout

