\begin_layout Standard
A weighted average for variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{\text{weighted}}=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}v_{i}}{\sum_{i}^{n}v_{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the value for observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the weight for this observation.
 Say that the two school classes A and B have 10 and 20 students respectively.
 On the latest math test,
 the students in the two classes scored 32 and 42 points respectively.
 The weighted average of their test results:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X}_{\text{weighted}}=\frac{\sum_{i}^{n}x_{i}v_{i}}{\sum_{i}^{n}v_{i}}=\frac{10*32+20*42}{10+20}=\frac{1160}{30}\approx38.7\label{eq: viktat medelvärde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will use Excel to calculate a weighted average.
 Excel has no ready-made function for this,
 but we can combine the SUMPRODUCT() and SUM() functions.
 In the numerator of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: viktat medelvärde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have the sum of products 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and in the denominator we have the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Beräkna-viktat-medelvärde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows an example of how it can look in Excel.
 Column B contains the test scores for classes A and B.
 Column C contains the number of students.
 In cell E4 we calculate the sum of products in the numerator of equation [eq:
 viktat medel 2 skolklasser].
 In cell E5 we calculate the sum in the denominator.
 In cell E6 the weighted average is calculated by combining the two functions.
 In the parentheses of SUMPRODUCT() we refer as the first argument to cells B2:B3.
 As the second argument we refer to cells C2 and C3.
 The SUMPRODUCT() function then calculates the following expression:
 32 * 10 + 42 * 20 = 1160.
 If we divide this by the sum of the weights 10 + 20,
