\begin_layout Subsection
Solving a system of equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we have the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x_{1}-2x_{2} & =3\\
4x_{1}+5x_{2} & =6
\end{cases}\label{eq: ekvationssystem 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This system has the unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=\frac{27}{13},x_{2}^{*}=-\frac{6}{13}$
\end_inset

.
 There are several ways we can use Excel to help find these solutions.
 One way is to use matrix calculations.
 Let us write the system of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: ekvationssystem 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
KX=Y\left[\begin{matrix}1 & -2\\
4 & 5
\end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}
\end{matrix}\right]=\left[\begin{matrix}3\\
6
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution can now be given by matrix multiplying both sides with the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K^{-1}KX=K^{-1}YX=Y^{*}\left[\begin{matrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}
\end{matrix}\right]=\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{27}{13}\\
-\frac{6}{13}
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Lösa-ekvationssystem- matrisräkning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows how we can calculate these matrices in Excel.
 Cells A2:B3 contain matrix K.
 Cells D2:D3 contain matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Cell A6:B7 contains the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and cell D6:D7 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{*}=K^{-1}Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

