\begin_layout Section
Input-output analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Input-outputanalys Excel"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Matrices can be used for input-output analysis and network analysis,
 among other things.
 Input-output analysis often starts from flow tables that describe how companies in different industries in an economy produce input goods for their own and other industries in the economy,
 as well as goods and services for final consumption.
 We call the flow matrix Z.
 We take the multiplicative inverse of total production for industry j that goes to input goods and final consumption per industry,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{s_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 These inverses for all industries we collect in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 From this we can define matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=Z*\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with the multiplicative inverse of total production per industry along the diagonal.
 We define matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as a column matrix with the production per industry that goes to final consumption.
 The total production required from industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for all input goods and final consumption we call 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 We collect the values for this for all industries in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y & =AY+SY-AY\\
 & =S\left(I-A\right)Y\nonumber \\
 & =SY\nonumber \\
 & =\left(I-A\right)^{-1}S\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/Excel1 matris IO1.png
	lyxscale 60
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Input-output-analys-med-Excel"

\end_inset

Input–output analysis with Excel,
 step 1
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an identity matrix with the same dimensions as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The values in Y are the total production required for this economy taking into account both input goods and final consumption.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(I-A\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the same dimensions as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of column 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the output multiplier for industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the input multiplier for industry 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 These things we can calculate in Excel using the functions we used above.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
