\begin_layout Standard
If we want to know which value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a specified probability in the normal distribution's cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 we can use Excel's NORM.INV() function.
 The function has three arguments:
 a value for the probability,
 the distribution's mean,
 and the distribution's standard deviation.
 Say as an example that we have a standard normal distribution,
 like the example in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: normalfördelningen 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since the mean marks half of the probability distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 gives that the cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(0\right)=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 If we want to know which value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 gives this cumulative probability,
 we write =NORM.INV(0.5,
 0,
 1) in a cell in our worksheet and press Enter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several functions that correspond to NORM.DIST() but for other probability distributions.
 If we want to work with the standard normal distribution and avoid having to specify mean and standard deviation,
 we can use the NORM.S.DIST() function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The T.DIST() function returns the probability for a left-tailed t-distribution based on three arguments:
 variable value x,
 degrees of freedom,
 and whether the function should return values for the distribution function (TRUE) or density function (FALSE).
 The corresponding function for getting probabilities for a right-tailed t-distribution is T.DIST.RT(),
 which only has two arguments:
 variable value x and degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The T.DIST.2T() function returns the probability for a two-tailed t-distribution based on two arguments:
 variable value x and degrees of freedom.
 To instead obtain the variable value x that corresponds to a specified probability for a two-tailed t-distribution,
 we can use the T.INV.2T() function.
 This function has two arguments:
 probability and degrees of freedom.
 If we for example write T.INV.2T(0.05,
 300),
 the function returns approximately 1.9679.
 If we then specify T.DIST.2T(1.9679,
 300) based on this,
 this function in turn returns the value 0.05.
 That is,
 5 percent.
\end_layout

