	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/Excel1 ztest1.png
	lyxscale 60
	scale 77

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Z-test"

\end_inset

Z test
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say as an example that we have two normally distributed variables with means 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{1}=83.95$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{2}=80.38$
\end_inset

 with variance (standard deviation squared) 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}^{2}=1.663$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}^{2}=1.032$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=n_{2}=3$
\end_inset

.
 We use a z-test (based on the standardized normal distribution) to calculate the probability that these two variables come from the same population with the same mean:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z=\frac{\bar{X}_{1}-\bar{X}_{2}}{\left(\frac{s_{1}^{2}}{n_{1}}+\frac{s_{2}^{2}}{n_{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx\frac{83.95-80.38}{\left(\frac{1.032}{3}+\frac{1.663}{3}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}\approx3.767\label{eq: z-värde 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which we can compare against the standard normal distribution's distribution function.
 Our calculated z-value is so far from the mean that the probability that the two samples would come from a population with the same mean is under one hundredth of a percent.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Z-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows how we can calculate this with Excel.
 Rows 2 to 5 contain information from samples for variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In cell B7 we calculate equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Z-test"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In cell B8 we calculate the p-value by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $1-F\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z=3.767$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $p\approx0.000083$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 the probability that the two populations have the same mean is very low.
\end_layout

