\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes different methods for performing regression analysis with Excel.
 First we go through how we can estimate the coefficients in the regression model using matrix calculations,
 and then how we can use various shortcuts in Excel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis using matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will estimate the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a+bx+u\label{eq: reg mod Excel1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 A regression model can be written with matrices as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=BX+U
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with the dependent variable and its observations.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has as many rows as observations.
 Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the coefficients.
 Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains the explanatory variables.
 The first column in matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has the value 1,
 because in the regression model in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: reg mod Excel1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 which is not multiplied by any variable (the model's y-intercept).
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a column matrix with the error terms (number of rows = number of observations.
 The least squares estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 can be described with the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 0
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width ""
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/Excel1 matris regression.png
	lyxscale 60
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-matriser"

\end_inset

Regression analysis with matrices
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the transposed matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}X$
\end_inset

.
 We will now estimate the regression model with an example where we use four observations for the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left\{ 3,2,5,4\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The first observation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y,x\right)=\left(3,3\right)$
\end_inset

 and the second 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y,x\right)=\left(4,2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=\left[\begin{matrix}3\\
4\\
6\\
7
\end{matrix}\right],\:X=\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 3\\
1 & 2\\
1 & 5\\
1 & 4
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-matriser"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows how we can estimate the regression model using Excel's matrix functions that we introduced above.
 In cells A2:A5 we find the values for variable y,
 which are also the elements in matrix Y.
 In cells C2:D5 we find the values for matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In cell A8 we use the TRANSPOSE() function to create the transposed matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 In cell A12 we use MINVERSE() to create the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In cell A16 we use the MMULT() function to matrix multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 In cell C16 we use MMULT() to matrix multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{T}Y$
\end_inset

,
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

.
 In the two cells C16 and C17 we obtain the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 From here we can continue and for example calculate t-tests for the coefficients,
 but for this we will instead use shortcuts in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis with LINEST()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Excel,
 we can estimate regression models using the LINEST() function.
 We estimate again the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx+u$
\end_inset

.
 In the parentheses of LINEST() we first need to specify the observations for our dependent variable,
 which in this case is y.
 After a comma we specify a reference to the cells where we have observations for our explanatory variables,
 which in this case is only variable x.
\end_layout

