 shows an example where column A contains the values for variable y and column B contains variable x.
 In cell C6 we use the LINEST() function.
 In the parentheses of the function we refer to the values in columns A and B.
 The function returns the estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 in cells C6 and D6.
 Note that the function first reports the slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The result is exactly as before 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 Let us take another example.
 We will now use LINEST() to instead estimate the regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=c+dX+eZ+\epsilon\label{eq: Excel regmod 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

