\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\lang swedish
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-REGR 2"

\end_inset

REGR() med två förklarande variabler.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 are variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-REGR 2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows an example where we use LINEST() and in the parentheses refer to cells A2:A5 (variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

) and B2:C5 (variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

).
 In cells D6,
 E6 and F6 the three coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}\approx2.89$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}\approx0.28$
\end_inset

 and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}\approx-0.54$
\end_inset

 are returned,
 which is thus in reverse order compared to how we set up our regression model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LINEST() function has two optional arguments,
 const and stats,
 which we can choose to leave unchanged.
 The const and stats options are controlled by the logical arguments TRUE and FALSE.
 The default setting for LINEST() is that const=TRUE and stats=FALSE,
 which is used if we don't specify anything else in the parentheses of LINEST().
 The results illustrated in figure [fig:Regressionsanalys-med-REGR 2],
 presented above,
 are created with these default settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead specify const=FALSE,
 then the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=dX+eZ+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is estimated,
 without the y-intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 The second optional argument in LINEST() is stats,
 which controls whether LINEST() should also report results for t-tests for the coefficients,
 F-test for the entire model,
 and estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

