 or Change Colors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GDP per working hour increases over the period in the long term.
 One way to compare the development is to create an index per country.
 We choose 1990 as the base year and give this year the index value 100.
 We calculate index 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{it}$
\end_inset

 for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 with the following formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{it}=\frac{BNP_{it}}{BNP_{i1990}}*100
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: index per land - Excel tcb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows how this calculation can look in Excel.
 The data on GDP per working hour is collected in cells B2:E7.
 Index per country is calculated in cells B11:E16,
 compare section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Beräkna-index excel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 To fill in all cells faster,
 we can use one of the tricks we went through in the example in that section.
 We can,
 for example,
 enter the formula in cell B11:
 =B2/$B$2,
 select cells B11:E16 and press Ctrl + D and Ctrl + R.
 This makes the formula in B11 copy to all other cells we selected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cell reference in our index calculation's numerator,
 B2,
 is updated.
 The cell reference in the denominator $B$2 is locked on column B but not on row 2.
 The cell reference will therefore update the row but not the column,
 which means that each country will use the year 1990 as the base year,
 which is what we want.
\end_layout

