\begin_layout Standard
Another way to compare the long-term development is to estimate the following regression model per country:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{it}=a_{i}+b_{i}T_{it}+\epsilon_{it}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the natural logarithm of GDP per working hour in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (the y-intercept,
 the constant),
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the slope coefficient for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with respect to the explanatory variable 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{it}$
\end_inset

 which is the year for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the error term for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take the natural logarithm of GDP per working hour,
 because we can then interpret slope coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as an approximate measure of average percentage increase in GDP per working hour per year (when variable 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 increases by one).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate this regression model in Excel,
 we can for example use LINEST().
 As the first argument we use the natural logarithm of the values in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BNP-per-arbetstimme excel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 As the second argument we use the years 1990,
 2000,
 2010,
 and 2020.
 Figure 
