\begin_layout Standard
Somewhat simplified,
 we can describe it as Stata working with one data table at a time,
 or at least one main table.
 All commands we give the program are interpreted by the program as wanting to perform on this main table,
 unless otherwise specified.
 This is a difference from,
 for example,
 Microsoft Excel where we can have several tables with different types of information in the same worksheet,
 together with charts and more,
 for example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means,
 among other things,
 that a column in Stata is intended to contain only one type of information.
 All data in the column is classified as one data type,
 for example real values or text strings.
 As a comparison,
 in Excel we have the possibility to have different types of information saved in the same column or on the same row.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Data Editor window can be opened in two modes:
 Browse,
 with data write-protected,
 and Edit,
 without write protection.
 If we open the Data Editor in Edit mode,
 we must be careful not to accidentally edit data and lose information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Commands in Stata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Stata we can control the program using the menus or by writing commands,
 also called writing program code or scripts.
 Stata has its own language,
 its own syntax,
 which is specially designed for data analysis.
 The chapter focuses primarily on how we can write code.
 We begin with an example of how we can use the menus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Commands with menus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Stata we often work with data retrieved from existing data files,
 for example data that is saved in an Excel sheet or some other program and data format.
 We can also enter data manually,
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Mata-in-data"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Say we want to import an Excel file to Stata from the computer's hard drive (see also section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: stata Importera-och-exportera data"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 We can then choose menu File > Import...
 > Excel spreadsheet (*.xls,
 *.xlsx).
 A new dialog box opens,
 where we can choose different options for how the file should be imported to Stata.
 Under Import...
 we can also choose to import other file types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata can retrieve the information that is saved in the Excel sheet.
 If we then work with this data in Stata,
 the Excel sheet is not affected.
 Note that this is a difference compared to if we open the same file in Excel.
 If we edit an Excel sheet in Excel and save the file again,
 old information is overwritten.
 If we want to overwrite the Excel file in Stata,
 we must export the data we are working with to the hard drive and overwrite the old file.
 This is practical because it reduces the risk of us overwriting useful information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/Stata dialogrutan importera excel1.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: Stata importera excelfil "

\end_inset

The dialog box for importing an Excel file to Stata
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: Stata importera excelfil "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows what the dialog box for importing Excel files can look like.
 In the top box in the dialog box we choose which Excel file we want to import data from.
 By clicking on the Browse...
 button we get the opportunity to click our way through the directories to the file.
 Excel sheets can contain several tabs (worksheets) with data.
 In the box for Worksheet in the dialog box we specify the name of the tab in the Excel sheet from which we want to retrieve data.
 Under Cell range we can specify which cells in the Excel sheet's tab the data should be retrieved from.
 To retrieve data in cells A1 to B4 we can write A1:B4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata generally uses a period as the decimal separator,
 which is standard in many countries in the world and therefore also in many computer programs.
 In Sweden,
 a comma is generally used as the decimal separator,
 which can sometimes cause problems when we are going to use computer programs.
 If the data we want to import is saved with commas,
 Stata can generally read our data but then interprets the information as text data.
 We can easily remedy this,
 which we will return to below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Commands using do-files
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All commands we can perform using the menus can also be performed with written commands.
 Sometimes we also benefit from combining the methods.
 When we specify a command through the menus,
 Stata shows how the same command would have looked as a written command.
 Stata has a large collection of functions pre-installed,
 which can be accessed both through menus and Stata's own programming language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Written commands can be entered either in the lower right window Command in Stata (compare figure [fig:Stata]) or in the window called the Do-File editor.
 If we write commands in the Command window,
 the command is executed but the text we wrote is not saved.
 What we write in the Do-file editor can be saved as a text file,
 which is why we focus on that method here.
 To open the Do-file editor we can click on the menu Window > Do-file editor > New Do-file editor.
 We can also use the keyboard shortcut Ctrl + 9,
 compare figure [fig:Do-File-Editor] below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A practical way to work with Do-files is to begin the file by specifying the working directory for this particular work project.
 By specifying a working directory,
 we instruct Stata where on the hard drive the program should retrieve files from and where the program should save files,
 if we give instructions to export information to a file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first time we want to define a working directory,
 it may be easiest to do this using the menu File > Change Working Directory....
 This opens a dialog box where we can click our way to the directory on our computer that we want to use as the working directory.
 Select the directory and click OK.
 If we choose,
 for example,
 a directory called Documents that is located on the computer's hard drive C,
 and everything is correct,
 the following text will now appear in the results window:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
.
 cd "C:
\backslash
Documents"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Written commands in Stata are often written with the name of a function followed by the arguments the function should use.
 In many functions we can then,
 if we want,
 write a comma and specify various options.
 To choose a working directory we use the function 
\family typewriter
cd
\family default
,
 which is an abbreviation for current directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can copy the text 
\family typewriter
cd "C:
\backslash
Documents"
\family default
 from the results window and paste it into the do-file editor.
 The text we write in the do-file editor can be sent to the program,
 which then performs various actions.
 Sending written commands,
 program code,
 to the program is called executing the program or running the code.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To run a line of program code in the do-file editor,
 we select one or more characters on the line we want to run and click Execute selection (do) or press Ctrl + D.
 To run all code in the current do-file we can use the keyboard shortcut Ctrl + D.
 The code that is run is reported in the results window along with any results from the execution.
 If we are unsure about which working directory we have chosen,
 we can use the function 
\family typewriter
pwd
\family default
 (abbreviation for present working directory).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The text in the do-file editor can be saved as a file on your computer's hard drive,
 and then gets the file extension .do.
 A do-file is a plain text file (in Windows these can be saved as .txt files).
 Thanks to the file extension .do,
 however,
 the program recognizes this file as a do-file for Stata.
 That is,
 if we save the text in the do-file editor,
 only the actual text is saved,
 which does not take up much space on the hard drive.
 Any results that the code creates when it is run are not saved,
 such as data,
 tables and charts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we want to import an Excel file called my_file.xlsx.
 The file is saved in the directory we specified as the working directory.
 For this we can use the function 
\family typewriter
import excel
\family default
 and specify filename and other options.
 If we have run the 
\family typewriter
cd
\family default
 command above and specified our working directory,
 we can place our Excel file in this directory and write the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_file.xlsx
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want,
 we can also write a comma and define which tab in the Excel file data should be retrieved from by defining the option 
\family typewriter
sheet()
\family default
.
 If we do not specify a tab,
 data is retrieved from the first tab in the file.
 If the tab we want to retrieve data from is called sheet1,
 we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_file.xlsx,
 sheet(sheet1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also specify which cells we want to retrieve data from in this tab by defining the option 
\family typewriter
cellrange()
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_file.xlsx,
 sheet(sheet1) cellrange(A1:B5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By specifying 
\family typewriter
cellrange(A1:B5)
\family default
,
 only the information stored in cells A1 to B5 in the current tab and file is imported.
 If we already have data open in Stata's main table (the data editing window,
 Data Editor),
 the program will abort the command with a warning that data loaded in Stata will be lost:
 no;
 data in memory would be lost.
 This is a helpful warning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Always be careful to save the information we are working with if we want to be sure not to lose our work.
 After we have saved our work,
 we can either use the command clear all to delete all data that is open in Stata.
 Then we can import data and the program will not give any error message.
 A faster method is to,
 after we have saved our data,
 use the option clear,
 which also deletes all data in Stata's main table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_data.xlsx,
 clear
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Stata's data window,
 figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Stata-datafönster"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we noted how the variable names are specified as column names above the observations.
 If the first,
 top row in the data we import is the name of the variables,
 we can specify the option first.
 The program will then use the information in this top row to name the variables.
 For example,
 we can write like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_data.xlsx,
 clear first
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/stata do-file editor1.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Do-File-Editor"

\end_inset

The Do-File Editor
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Do-File-Editor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows what it can look like in the do-file editor in Stata.
 To run the code we select some of the characters on both lines and click Run or use the keyboard shortcut Ctrl + R.
 Written commands in Stata are generally written one per line.
 We can also let a command continue on the next line by adding the symbols /// at the far right of a line.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel ///
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

min_data.xlsx,
 ///
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

clear first
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the example above we use indentation,
 the spaces at the beginning of line two and three.
 This is often practical to make the code more readable,
 but it is only a matter of taste and does not affect the program.
 If we are unsure about how something should be written in the code,
 we can use the menus.
 If we click through a command using the menus,
 Stata prints out how the same command can be written as code.
 We can then reuse this text for our do-file,
 in the way we went through above for choosing the current working directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to learn more about the options for a function and also find new functions is to look up the help pages for a function,
 which we find via the functions help or search,
 followed by the name of the function we want to read about.
 If we want to read about import excel we can for example write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
help import excel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is displayed in the window called Viewer.
 Often a list of search results is displayed that we can click through.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many times we also benefit from documenting our work to simply remember exactly what we have done.
 It can be surprising how quickly one can forget things one worked with just a few days earlier.
 For the same reason,
 programming facilitates collaboration with other analysts.
 If someone has written program code that clearly describes what happens in an analysis,
 it facilitates the possibility for others to continue the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A central part of writing readable code is to write good comments in the code that explain what the code does.
 We do this so that we ourselves,
 or other users we want to show the code to,
 can more easily follow along with the code.
 Many people have an amazing ability to surprisingly quickly forget what we have done and thought.
 To write comments in Stata's do-files we use the asterisk *.
 A line in the do-file that begins with * is ignored by the program.
 We can therefore use * to add comments that describe what the code does.
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Line that begins with asterisk is ignored by the program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Next line defines working directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
cd "C:
\backslash
Documents"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Next line imports data from an Excel file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import excel my_data.xlsx,
 clear first
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata has a large number of ready-made functions pre-installed when we install the program.
 There are also additional functions that we can download for free from the internet.
 On this webpage there are a large number of links with more information about many different types of functions and tools:
 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

www.stata.com/links/resources-for-adding-features/
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of these is the Statistical Software Components (SSC) database,
 which is run by Boston College in the USA.
 This database has a large number of functions that are largely created by other users on a voluntary basis.
 SSC is so well-known that there is a special function for installing new functions from there:
 
\family typewriter
ssc install
\family default
.
 One such function that we can download to Stata from SSC is called outreg2.
 Right now we don't need to worry about what outreg2 can be used for,
 we will return to that below.
 To install outreg2 we can write and run the following code:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
ssc install outreg2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we run this command,
 Stata will connect to the internet and download a package with the function 
\family typewriter
outreg2
\family default
 as well as instructions for how the function works to our computer and save it on the hard drive.
 The function is now installed in Stata and we can then use one or more new functions that came with the package.
 After installation we can also read the function's help section by running the command help outreg2.
 An installation generally only needs to be performed once.
 The next time we restart Stata,
 outreg2 is already installed in our program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Importing and exporting data
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: stata Importera-och-exportera data"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata can read data from different types of files.
 Above we went through how we can import an Excel file of type xls or xlsx to Stata.
 Stata's own file format for data files is called .dta.
 Dta-files generally contain a table with columns and rows,
 where each column represents a variable,
 as well as information about the different variables.
 To import the information in a dta-file named my_stata_data.dta,
 saved in the current working directory on the computer's hard drive (see above),
 to Stata we can use the function 
\family typewriter
use
\family default
.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
use my_stata_data.dta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we import data to Stata we need to remove the data we have open in the program's data window,
 just as we went through above.
 We can either do this with the command clear all,
 or use the option clear (same as when we used the function 
\family typewriter
import excel
\family default
 above):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
use my_stata_data.dta,
 clear
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To export the data that is open in Stata's main table (Data Editor) to a dta-file we can use the function 
\family typewriter
save
\family default
.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
save my_stata_data.dta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will go through more about how this works later,
 when we give examples with data.
 As mentioned in the previous section,
 we can import Excel files to Stata with the function 
\family typewriter
import excel
\family default
.
 We can also export data from Stata to Excel files such as .xlsx using the function 
\family typewriter
export excel
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata also has ready-made functions for importing and exporting data from and to file formats from other analysis programs.
 As an example,
 we can import data files from the program SAS with the function 
\family typewriter
import sas
\family default
.
 To import data files from the program SPSS we can use the function 
\family typewriter
import spss
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particularly useful file format is .csv (Comma-Separated Values).
 Csv-files are an example of a type of data file that many analysis programs can both import data from and export data to.
 Csv-files often consist of,
 as the name suggests,
 data where each value is separated by a comma.
 However,
 it is possible to save information in this file format and separate the values with some other symbol,
 for example semicolon ;
 which often occurs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To import a csv-file to Stata we can use the function 
\family typewriter
import delimited
\family default
,
 which is a function for importing data files with comma- or tab-separated values.
 After the function's name we write the filename,
 for example my_datafile.csv.
 We can also specify the option delimiters() and in the parentheses for this option describe what type of character the data values in the file are separated with.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
import delimited my_datafile.csv,
 delimiters(";")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function also has several other options,
 which you can read more about on the function's help pages.
 To export data from Stata to a csv-file we can use the function 
\family typewriter
export delimited
\family default
.
 Read more about this function in its help section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Enter data manually
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mata-in-data"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have described how we can import data from existing data files on the computer's hard drive.
 We can also enter data manually if we prefer.
 As we went through above,
 Stata generally works with one main table,
 that is the rows and columns shown in the Data Editor window.
 When we specify commands and run code in Stata,
 the program assumes that all commands refer to this data table,
 unless we specify otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to start with an empty table and enter data ourselves,
 we begin with the command clear all,
 to remove the variables we have open.
 To enter new variables we must start by specifying how many observations our table should have.
 We do this with the command set obs,
 followed by a number that specifies the number of observations.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
set obs 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This defines that we want to have 4 observations.
 To create a new variable in our main table we can use the function 
\family typewriter
generate
\family default
,
 followed by the name of the new variable,
 an equals sign and the information we want the variable to contain.
 Here is an example where we create a new variable named 
\family typewriter
new_variable
\family default
 where all observations have the value 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate new_variable = 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we instead want to create a variable that we call 
\family typewriter
n_obs
\family default
 where each row contains the current row number for this observation.
 We can do this by writing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate n_obs = _n
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The code 
\family typewriter
_n
\family default
 instructs the program to retrieve the number of this row for each row of our new variable 
\family typewriter
n_obs
\family default
.
 In this case,
 this will create a new column with the numbers 1,
 2,
 3 and 4,
 since we defined above that we want to have 4 rows.
 If we instead prefer to enter each observation manually,
 we can also open the Data editor window in editing mode,
 edit mode.
 Then we can click on the box we want to edit and change the value there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To enter observations manually we can also use the function 
\family typewriter
input
\family default
,
 followed by the name of the new variable we want to create.
 For example 
\family typewriter
input Y
\family default
.
 On the next line we then specify the value for observation 1.
 The line below that we specify the value for observation 2,
 and so on.
 Below follows an example of code with comments where we use the commands clear all,
 set obs,
 generate and input.
 Feel free to try using the same code in Stata and check the result in the program's data window.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Remove all variables that are open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
clear all
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Next line defines number of observations to 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
set obs 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create a variable that specifies row number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate n_obs = _n
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create variables Y and X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
input Y X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
3 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
2 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
5 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
4 7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have written some code in our do-file and hopefully also added some comments that explain what the code does,
 it is high time to save our script as a file on the computer's hard drive.
 Press Ctrl + S or choose in the menu File > Save as....
 What is now saved is,
 as mentioned,
 only the actual text in the do-file.
 The data that the file can create,
 for example,
 is not saved.
 This is generally just good.
 The text takes up very little space on the computer's hard drive and it often goes quickly to run through even relatively long do-files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we also want to save the actual data table that we are working with in Stata.
 Partly because we may have done something special that we are afraid of losing.
 Or because we want to show our data to someone else.
 To save the information in Stata's data table in a file on the hard drive,
 we must use one of the functions we went through above for exporting data (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: stata Importera-och-exportera data"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
save my_data.dta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to save the table as a Stata file.
 Or if we want to save our data in an Excel file that can more easily be opened in Excel,
 we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
export excel "my_data_from_stata.xlsx",
 replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Edit Columns and Rows
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:stata Redigera cols rows"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A large part of data analysis generally consists of editing columns and rows.
 In Stata we can,
 as described above,
 create new columns with for example the function 
\family typewriter
generate
\family default
.
 If we want to remove two variables 
\family typewriter
variable_X
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
variable_Y
\family default
 from the main table we can use the function 
\family typewriter
drop
\family default
,
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
drop variable_X variable_Y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we specify the name of the variables after the function 
\family typewriter
drop
\family default
,
 these variable names must match the name of the variables in the data table.
 The program distinguishes between small and capital letters so our spelling of the variables must be exactly the same as the spelling in the data table.
 If the program cannot find one or more of the variables we name in the data table,
 we get an error message.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to remove all variables and observations from the data table we can write drop _all or clear all,
 as we did above.
 If we instead want to choose which variables we want to keep and delete the rest,
 we can use the function 
\family typewriter
keep
\family default
.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
keep variable_X variable_Y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which lets us keep these two columns and deletes all other columns in the main table.
 If we have a variable and want to change the name of it,
 we can use the function 
\family typewriter
rename
\family default
 followed by existing variable and new variable name.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
rename variable_old_name variable_new_name
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To sort observations in numerical or alphabetical order we can use the functions sort or gsort.
 The function 
\family typewriter
sort 
\family default
sorts in ascending order.
 The function 
\family typewriter
gsort
\family default
 sorts in either ascending or descending order.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
sort var_X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
sorts all observations in the entire data table by arranging the values in variable var_X in ascending order.
 We get the same result if we instead use the command gsort var_X.
 To sort in descending order we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
gsort -var_X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also add several variables to sort the table in several steps.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
gsort country year
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
sorts the table by placing the values in variable country in ascending order.
 Within each unique value in variable country,
 variable year is sorted in ascending order.
 Each variable in Stata has a data format,
 which partly controls how the values in a variable are displayed in the data table and partly controls how the program handles the values.
 To change format on one or more variables we can use the function 
\family typewriter
format
\family default
.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
format %9.0g x y z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This command sets the three variables x y and z to have the format right-aligned general,
 with a maximum of 9 characters visible in the variable.
 If we write 0 as decimal for the g-format,
 the program determines how many decimals are shown,
 depending on the maximum number of allowed characters (in this case 9).
 If we want to use commas instead of periods we can replace the period in the format %9.0g with a comma %9,0g.
 The command to change format on variables x,
 y and z then reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
format %9,0g x y z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Read more about the function 
\family typewriter
format
\family default
 and its various options in the function's help pages,
 which we as usual find by calling the command help format.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata,
 like many other computer programs,
 handles numbers and text strings in different ways.
 A number can be saved as a text string and is then regarded as text.
 Stata cannot perform mathematical operations on text strings,
 even if a string consists only of something that we humans regard as a number.
 There are special display formats for both numbers and text.
 If we want to convert a variable from numbers to text strings we can use the function 
\family typewriter
tostring
\family default
 and either add the option replace (which overwrites existing variable) or gen(my_new_variable),
 which creates a new variable that we can name:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Convert the numerical variable to text:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tostring X,
 replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Keep numerical variable and create new text variable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tostring X,
 gen(X_as_string)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead have a variable that is saved as text but contains numbers,
 and we want to recode so that the program regards the numbers in the variable as numbers,
 we can use the function 
\family typewriter
destring
\family default
.
 This function also has the options 
\family typewriter
replace
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
gen()
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Convert the text variable to numerical:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
destring Z,
 replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Keep text variable and create new numerical variable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
destring Z,
 gen(Z_as_numerical)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\family typewriter
destring
\family default
 can be used if we have data with numbers where commas are used as decimal separators and Stata interprets these numbers as text strings.
 With the option 
\family typewriter
dpcomma,
 destring
\family default
 can convert numbers saved with decimal commas to numbers with periods instead.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
destring Z,
 replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to overwrite all or parts of an existing variable with new values we can use the function 
\family typewriter
replace
\family default
 (not the same thing as the option replace that we used above).
 Say we have a variable called income that contains values for income.
 If we want to take the natural logarithm of the observations in the variable we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
replace income = log(income)
\end_layout

