\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate L = Z + K if K!=.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will create a new variable L with the values .,
 21,
 31,
 42.
 Row 1 gets missing value because variable K=.
 on this row (missing value).
 We get the same result if we instead specify the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate L = Z + K
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the missing value is interpreted as unknown.
 Since the program does not know what value Z=10 should be added to on row 1,
 the result in the new variable L is also left as a missing value.
 Let us now look at the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate Zsum = sum(Z)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This creates a new variable 
\family typewriter
Zsum
\family default
 using the function 
\family typewriter
sum()
\family default
.
 The function 
\family typewriter
sum()
\family default
 gives us in this case the cumulative sum of the values in variable Z,
 that is:
 
\begin_inset Formula $Zsum=\left\{ 10,30,60,100\right\} $
\end_inset

 .
 We can compare this with if we instead sum variable K with the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate Ksum = sum(K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case,
 the missing value K in the first observation is treated as 0,
 not as a missing value.
 To calculate a constant in the form of the total sum we can instead use the function total(),
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
generate K_total_sum = total(K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we work with data analysis we often benefit from being able to transpose our data,
 that is change whether our data is organized in width or height.
 Let us use the data in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Information-för-person A B Stata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as an example.
 In Stata's data table we have some type of information for two people,
 A and B,
 for the years 2020,
 2021 and 2022.
 The development per person is described in width where each year has its own column.
 Variable names in Stata cannot begin with a number so the three columns with years are named x2020,
 x2021 and x2022.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

