\begin_layout Section
Probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata also has several pre-installed functions for working with commonly occurring probability distributions.
 As an example,
 if we want to know the cumulative probability for the standard normal distribution,
 given a specified z-value,
 we can for example use the function normal().
 In the parentheses we specify a z-value and the function returns the proportion of the distribution that is equal to or less than this z.
 As long as we do not use Mata we cannot use this type of function without saving the results somewhere.
 The following command therefore results in an error message:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normal(0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
One way to use the function outside Mata is to save the result in a local macro,
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
local zd = normal(0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
display `zd'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
With Mata,
 however,
 the function returns results without us saving these anywhere new.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normal(-1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normal(0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normal(1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
end
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead want to calculate the probability for exact values on the standard normal distribution,
 based on its density function,
 we can use the function normalden() and specify a z-value in the parentheses.
 If we specify two arguments in the parentheses for normalden() we can change the mean 
\backslash
mu for the normally distributed density function we want to use.
 If we specify three arguments we can also change the standard deviation 
\backslash
sigma.
 Here follow some examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
// Probability for the value 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normalden(0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
// Probability for 1 if mean = 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normalden(1,1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
// Probability for 2 if mean = 2,
 standard deviation = 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
normalden(2,2,1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
end
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table [tab:Funktioner-för-sannolikhetsförde stata] describes some examples of functions in Stata that can be used to calculate with different known probability distributions.
 See each function's help section for more information about how these work and available options,
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
help runiform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the help sections there is also information about additional functions that can be used to calculate probability in Stata.
 Stata also has several pre-installed functions for statistical tests.
 See for example the function ttest and its help section.
\end_layout

