\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section introduces how we can work with regression analysis in Stata.
 First by using matrix calculations,
 compare section [subsec:Regressionsanalys-med-matriser excel].
 Then with the help of ready-made functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis with matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say that we have four observations for the two variables Y and X saved in Stata's data table,
 see figure [fig:
 y och x i statas datatabell].
 Now we are going to estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+u\label{eq: reg modell 1 stata}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where a and b are the coefficients and u is the error term.
 We can write this regression model with matrices as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=XB+U
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/stata data y x reg mat.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\lang swedish
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: y och x i statas datatabell"

\end_inset

Variablerna Y och X i Statas datatabell.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y,B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 are column matrices and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a matrix where the first column has the value 1 in each element and column 2 is the explanatory variable X.
 As we described in section [subsec:Regressionsanalys-med-matriser excel],
 the coefficient estimator for the least squares method can be written with matrices in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 we start by saving the variables from the data table as matrices using the function 
\family typewriter
mkmat
\family default
.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create two matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mkmat Y,
 matrix(Y_mat)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mkmat X,
 matrix(X_mat)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Add column 1 to matrix X_mat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix define X_mat = ((1
\backslash
1
\backslash
1
\backslash
1),
 X_mat)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have what we need to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

,
 which we can do with the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix define B_hat = inv(X_mat' * X_mat) * X_mat' * Y_mat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead want to use mata to estimate 
\backslash
hat{B} we can first use putmata to save the two matrices that we need to work with them in mata,
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
putmata Y X=(1 X),
 replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This command first creates the column matrix Y,
 from variable Y in Stata's data table.
 Then matrix X is created by giving all elements in the first column the value 1 and the remaining columns are defined by variable X in Stata's data table.
 The option replace can be added to replace any previous matrices saved in mata with the same name as these.
 Then we can perform the same operations on the matrices as we did above.
 Below follows an example of how we can write these commands.
 All results are printed in Stata's results window:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Display the content of matrix Y and X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Estimate the coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Bhat = luinv(X'*X)*X'*Y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Display the result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Bhat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
end
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis using 
\family typewriter
regress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stata has a large number of pre-installed functions for statistical analysis and regression analysis.
 There are also additionally a large number to download for free on the internet.
 Say now that we again have four observations for the two variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\left\{ 3,2,5,4\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ 3,4,6,7\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 compare figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: y och x i statas datatabell"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We will now again estimate the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+U$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 To estimate this model with the least squares method in Stata we can use the function regress in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result of this command is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-Stata 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the image three different collections of results are visible.
 At the top left an ANOVA table is shown with estimated sum of squares,
 mean sum of squares and degrees of freedom for SSE (sum of squares explained),
 which in Stata's results appears on the row Model.
 The row labeled Residual shows SSR and the bottom row,
 Total,
 shows SST.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the top right in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-Stata 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 a list with mixed results is shown:
 At the top the number of observations is shown and then the calculated F-value as well as the calculated probability based on this F-value that we would have gotten this type of result if this test's null hypothesis were true.
 This F-test is automatically formulated as all coefficients for the regression model's explanatory variables being equal to zero,
 which in this case means 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

.
 The result in this example indicates that we do not have reason to reject the F-test's null hypothesis with high statistical probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below the two results that concern the F-test,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 and adjusted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 are reported,
 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 At the bottom among these results is Root MSE,
 which is the square root of the mean sum of squares for the residuals,
 that is:
 Root MSE 
\begin_inset Formula $=\sqrt{MSR}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 are in the lower table under the heading Coef.
 From top to bottom in this table the estimated coefficients for the explanatory variable(s) are shown.
 In this case it is thus only 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 At the far left in the bottom row is _cons,
 which refers to this being an estimate concerning the regression model's constant,
 the y-intercept,
 which here is estimated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next column to the right of the coefficients' estimates is the coefficients' standard errors (Std.
 Err.).
 Then the calculated t-value is given for a t-test where the null hypothesis,
 unless otherwise specified,
 is formulated as the coefficient in question being zero.
 For the top row the t-test's null hypothesis is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:b=0$
\end_inset

.
 The next column has the heading 
\begin_inset Formula $P>|t|$
\end_inset

 and gives the probability that the absolute value of the calculated t exceeds the critical t-value for the current t-distribution.
 The two columns at the far right show the lower and upper bounds for estimated confidence intervals for each coefficient with confidence level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/stata reg 1.emf
	scale 55

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-Stata 1"

\end_inset

Regression analysis with Stata
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function regress assumes that the first variable we write out is the explained variable in a linear regression model and that if we write out more variables after this,
 these are set as explanatory variables.
 This means that if we write the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X Z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then Stata interprets this as us wanting to estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=a+bX+cZ+u\label{eq: reg modell 2 stata}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where a,
 b and c are coefficients.
 If we have a dataset with a continuous variable Y and a factor variable Z we can for example manually create dummy variables in our data table using the functions and commands we went through in section [sec:stata Redigera cols rows] and [sec:
 stata Funktionen-egen].
 The disadvantage of this solution is that it is time-consuming and increases the risk of mistakes,
 especially if we need to create many new variables.
 If our dummy variables are only to be used to estimate the regression model,
 we can fortunately use a faster method.
 By writing i.
 before the variables that we want to be treated as indicator variables (factor variables),
 the program will automatically create dummy variables for all unique values in the current variable,
 excluding one value that becomes the base level.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y i.Z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If our factor variable Z has three unique values,
 this means that Stata in this case will estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}D_{1}+\alpha_{3}D_{2}+\epsilon
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 are dummy variables for two of the three unique values in variable Z.
 The three 
\backslash
alpha_{i} are the coefficients that we estimate with the least squares method.
 
\backslash
epsilon is the error term.
 For regress there are also options if we want to create interaction terms without having to edit our data table.
 Say for example that we have variables Y,
 X and Z and want to estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}X+\beta_{3}Z+\beta_{4}XZ+v
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients and v is the error term.
 To estimate this model with the least squares method in Stata we can use the following commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X##Z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This causes the program to add both the interaction term for XZ and the coefficients X and Z separately.
 The command therefore gives the same result as the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X Z X#Z
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use one hash symbol,
 only the actual interaction term,
 XZ,
 is included.
 If we use two hash symbols ##,
 both the interaction term and each variable included in this term separately are included.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we would like to estimate the regression model Y=a+bX+cZ+u,
 with robust standard errors,
 that is with an adjusted variance-covariance matrix,
 we can use the option vce().
 In the parentheses for vce() we write which method we want to use to adjust the standard errors and the variance-covariance matrix.
 For adjustment with HC1 we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Regression analysis with HC1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X Z,
 vce(robust)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See more options in the function's help section.
 The regression results in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Regressionsanalys-med-Stata 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 report a large number of figures.
 If we want to use any of these figures specifically we can retrieve these by using one of the functions 
\family typewriter
return list
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
ereturn list
\family default
 or 
\family typewriter
sreturn list
\family default
 directly after regress.
 These three functions return information that is saved by Stata in slightly different ways.
 If we run the command ereturn list directly after the command with regress we get a list of information that was created in memory from the latest run of regress and from which we can now retrieve one or more values,
 see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Resultat-av-regress ereturn Stata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information is divided into scalars,
 macros,
 matrices and functions.
 From the list returned by 
\family typewriter
regress
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
ereturn list
\family default
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Resultat-av-regress ereturn Stata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we can refer to named scalars and macros as local macros,
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
ereturn list
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
display `e(r2)'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To display a matrix we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix list e(b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to save any matrix from the results from regress we can for example use the function matrix define.
 From the list of results we can among other things retrieve matrix e(b) which contains estimated coefficients and matrix e(V) which contains the variance-covariance matrix.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Save the variance-covariance matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix define var_covar = e(V)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Save matrix B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix define B = e(b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/stata regress ereturn1.emf
	scale 75

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Resultat-av-regress ereturn Stata"

\end_inset

Results 
\family typewriter
of regress
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
ereturn list
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Export results to disk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we estimate regression models we often want to present all or parts of the results in some other form than Stata's results window,
 such as in Microsoft Word.
 Stata has several ready-made functions for exporting results to different file formats on the hard drive,
 for example the functions 
\family typewriter
putexcel
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
putdocx
\family default
 or 
\family typewriter
putpdf
\family default
.
 There are also "homemade" functions by other users that we can download for free from the internet.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For an introduction to some of these,
 see 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

www.stata.com/support/faqs/data-management/copying-tables/
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 One of these functions is outreg2,
 which requires that we download and install it,
 which we can do by running the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
ssc install outreg2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we estimate a regression model with the function regress,
 as above,
 we can directly after this run a command with the function outreg2 to export our regression results to a file on the hard drive.
 The function outreg2 has several options that we can use to influence exactly which results are saved,
 to what type of file the results are saved and how the result presentation looks in more detail.
 outreg2 can among other things save the results in an Excel file or a Word document,
 but also other file formats,
 which we can read more about in the function's help section.
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Estimate the regression model Y = a + b*X + u
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress Y X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Export the results to a Word and an Excel file
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
outreg2 using my_results,
 word excel replace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This command first runs the function regress to estimate the regression model,
 exactly as above.
 Then we run outreg2,
 which then assumes that we want to save precisely the latest results we produced.
 The expression using my_results,
 means that we instruct the function outreg2 to save data in a file that we name my_results.
 After the comma we specify three options:
 word,
 excel and replace.
 The option word instructs the function to save the results in an rtf-file (Rich Text Format,
 a format for Word documents).
 The option excel instructs the function to save the results in an xml-document,
 which is a file format for Excel files.
 The option replace means that in case there is already a file called either my_results.rtf or my_results.xml,
 these old files are overwritten without warning.
 Figure 
