\begin_layout Standard
The function twoway can be combined with different types of functions and commands to create different types of charts and influence their appearance.
 If we instead of the regression line want to draw a chart where we have both points and a line that connects the points,
 we can combine the functions twoway,
 scatter and line.
 Here follows an example where we also use the options color() and legend() in the parentheses for the function line.
 By placing color() and legend() in respective parentheses we can influence how scatter and line display the data in the chart:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
twoway ///
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 (scatter Y X,
 color(black)) /// 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 (line Y X,
 color(black) ///
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad\qquad\qquad$
\end_inset

 legend(position(3) cols(1)))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write color(black) to define the color of the points created by scatter,
 and the line created by line,
 respectively,
 as black.
 In the parentheses for line we also add the option legend() where we define the legend's position using position().
 The position is specified in this case as placement according to the dial on a clock with 12 numbers.
 Position 3 = 3 o'clock = to the right of the chart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The option 
\family typewriter
cols()
\family default
 in the parentheses for legend() in the parentheses for line,
 specifies the number of columns in the legend,
 which is why cols(1) means that everything written in the legend is placed in one column.
 The result is shown in figure 
