\begin_layout Standard
We can also name the charts we create by specifying the option name() and writing any name without spaces in the parentheses.
 Then we can combine our saved charts,
 for example to save them in one and the same image file.
 To check which charts are saved in memory we can use the function graph dir.
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create a scatter plot and call it graf_1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
twoway scatter Y X,
 title("Scatter Plot") name(graf_1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create a line chart and call it graf_2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
twoway line Y X,
 title("Line Chart") name(graf_2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Check which charts are saved in memory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
graph dir
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To combine the two charts we can then use the function graph combine,
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
graph combine graf_1 graf_2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This creates a common image for the two charts.
 In the help section for the function graph combine we can read about different options for influencing the layout of the image and the charts.
 The image we now create with graph combine can then be exported as an image file to the computer's hard drive,
 in the same way as we did above with graph export.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create an image of the two charts in memory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
graph combine graf_1 graf_2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Export the image as an image file to the hard drive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
graph export "Combo graf.pdf"
\end_layout

