\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the same functions we can also create a chart over the indices we created per country:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
twoway line gh_index year,
 colorvar(country)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now estimate the following regression model per country:
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\lang swedish
regressionsanalys!Stata
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{it}=a_{i}+b_{i}t_{it}+u_{it}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where y_{it} is the natural logarithm of GDP per working hour in country i year t,
 a_{i} is a coefficient (y-intercept,
 the constant) for country i,
 t_{it} is year t for country i year t and u_{it} is the error term.
 Estimated 
\backslash
hat{b}_{i} will give us an approximate measure of average percentage change of y_{it} per year and country.
 To estimate one model per country we can for example use foreach:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
foreach a in Denmark Sweden Finland ///
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Norway `United States' `United Kingdom' {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress gh year if country=="`a'"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also combine levelsof with foreach.
 Below follows an example where we also add a command that saves the slope coefficient from each regression result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Retrieve unique values for the variable country
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
levelsof country,
 local(tc)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create local macro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
local vlist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Create loop over the unique values in country
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
foreach c of local tc {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
regress gdphour year if country=="`c'"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Round and save the slope coefficient in a local macro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
local temp = round(_b[year],
 .01)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
* Add the result to the local macro coef
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
local coef `coef' `temp'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To display the macro coef we can use the function 
\family typewriter
display
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
.
 display 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

`coef'
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
1.08 .99 1.06 1.17 .78 1.19
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chapter Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stata is a program designed for data analysis where we generally work with one main table at a time,
 which is displayed in the program's data window.
 Information can also be saved temporarily in the program's memory in various ways.
 Stata can be controlled through the menus and through written commands.
 The written commands can be given in the program's Command window or through do-files.
 The do-files can be saved as plain text documents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Data to the program can be entered manually via the data window,
 via commands in the Command window or the do-files.
 We can also import data files in different formats from the hard drive to the program,
 whereupon these are opened in the program's main data table,
 the data window Data editor.
 Stata generally works with one main table with data.
 Variables and observations for this data table are what we can see in the data window.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stata has a large number of functions pre-installed.
 For example,
 we can create and edit variables in Stata's data table using the functions 
\family typewriter
generate
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
replace
\family default
.
 To change specific values or observations we can combine replace with conditions,
 such as 
\family typewriter
replace x=1 if y==2
\family default
.
 Another useful function for creating and editing variables is 
\family typewriter
egen
\family default
,
 which has many options and additions.
 To merge the columns in two tables with matching observations we can use the function merge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In Stata we can work with matrix calculations by for example using the function matrix define.
 We can also use Mata,
 which is a special programming language that we can work with in Stata to for example perform matrix calculations.
 To save data from Stata's data table in matrices we can use the functions 
\family typewriter
mkmat
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
putmata
\family default
.
 To save matrices as data we can use 
\family typewriter
svmat
\family default
 or 
\family typewriter
getmata
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stata has several pre-installed functions for calculating variation and covariation.
 For example 
\family typewriter
correlate
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
pwcorr
\family default
.
 Stata also has several functions for working with commonly occurring probability distributions,
 such as 
\family typewriter
normal()
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
runiform()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
binomial()
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To estimate the regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+bx+u$
\end_inset

 we can use the command 
\family typewriter
regress y x
\family default
.
 Using the functions 
\family typewriter
return list
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
ereturn list
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
sreturn list
\family default
 we can work with the estimates that regress returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To create charts we can use the function 
\family typewriter
twoway
\family default
 in combination with for example 
\family typewriter
scatter
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
line
\family default
 or 
\family typewriter
lfit
\family default
.
 By specifying options to these we can define how the charts should look and how data should be illustrated.
 For example 
\family typewriter
twoway (line x y,
 color(red))
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To create loops with repetitions in Stata we can use the functions 
\family typewriter
forvalues
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
foreach
\family default
.
\end_layout

