\begin_layout Section
General Overview of R
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure [fig:Programmet-R-behöver] shows the R program.
 This program needs to be installed on your hard drive for you to be able to use R in RStudio,
 but we never need to open the R program.
 We can instead work in RStudio.
 Figure [fig:Programmet-RStudio] shows how RStudio generally looks when you open it for the first time.
 In the bottom left you see the console.
 In the top right the Global Environment is displayed.
 In the bottom right help sections and charts are shown,
 among other things.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the top left of RStudio you see the script window (Script).
 If you don't see it,
 you can open a new script window by pressing Ctrl + Shift + N (Windows) or Cmd + Shift + N (Mac).
 You can also open the script window by choosing in the menu `File > New File...
 > R Script`.
 You can also use the menu File > New File > R Script file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can control RStudio through the menus or through written instructions,
 that is writing R code.
 In RStudio you can enter commands ("code") in the console.
 If you place the cursor in the console and write 1 + 2 and press Enter,
 the result is output directly,
 that is the number 3.
 Neither the command nor the result is saved in the program's memory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also write R code in the script window in the top left.
 To run a command in your script you can place the text cursor at the command,
 on the same line,
 and press `Ctrl` + `Enter` (Windows) or `Cmd` + `Enter` (Mac).
 You can for example try writing 1 + 2 on a line and running this.
 The result is output in the console.
 But unlike when we write commands in the console,
 the command remains in the script when we have run the command.
 We can also select exactly the code we want to run and send this to the program with the same commands.
 If we want to run the entire script and *all* commands found in the script,
 we instead press `Ctrl` + `Shift` + `Enter` (Windows) or `Cmd` + `Shift` + `Enter` (Mac).
 We can also use the "Run" button that you find in the script window's upper right corner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To write comments in R scripts,
 which are ignored by the program,
 we can use the hash symbol #.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Lines that begin with hash symbol are comments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Next line is a mathematical calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
1+2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we write the above in an R script,
 select all these lines or place the cursor on the first line,
 and press Ctrl + Enter,
 this is run as a command in R.
 The first and second lines are ignored by the program and are only reported in the console as text without action.
 The third line is run as a calculation and the result is returned in the console.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The commands you write in a script can be saved as a regular text file on the computer.
 To save your script you press Ctrl + S (Windows) or Cmd + S (Mac).
 You can also choose menu File > Save.
 Your script is saved as a text file on the computer's hard drive with the file extension .R.
 If you have saved your script in an .R file on the computer's hard drive,
 you can,
 the next time you start RStudio,
 open the file and continue working with your code.
\end_layout

