\begin_layout Section
R packages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Users constantly develop new functions for R and upload these in the form of R packages on the internet.
 R packages contain one or more new functions.
 Many packages we can easily download and install in R using the function install.packages().
 A particularly useful such package is tidyverse,
 which contains several other packages with many functions.
 To download and install the package we run the following code:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
install.packages("tidyverse")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you run the above code,
 a longer download and installation starts and RStudio generally then shows different types of information and warnings.
 You don't need to do anything but let the program finish downloading.
 For this to work you need to have access to the internet and have the ability to save files on the computer's hard drive (administrator rights).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After you have installed a package it is saved on your computer.
 The next time you open R you don't need to run install.packages() again.
 But after each time we restart the R program we must activate the packages we have downloaded and installed,
 which we do with the function library().
 This function thus activates packages that we have already installed.
 Often it can be practical to begin a script with for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
library("tidyverse").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize,
 we generally need to run the command install.packages() only once.
 We need to run the command library("tidyverse") every time we restart R or RStudio if we want to use the functions in tidyverse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes packages that we have installed are updated.
 To check and update an already installed package we can in RStudio click on the menu Tools > Check For Package Updates....
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the tidyverse package there is the magrittr package and there is the special pipe function %>%.
 The pipe function sends the result of a command on the left forward to the next function on the right.
 The pipe function places the sent result as the first argument in the next function.
 In this way we can create an easily comprehensible chain of operations.
 Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# The following two lines give the same result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_result <- sum( log( c(3,4,5) ) )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_result <- c(3,4,5) %>% log() %>% sum()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last line we can read as "take the numbers in c()" AND THEN "use the function log()" AND THEN "use the function sum()".
 The result is saved in the object my_result.
 The keyboard shortcut for %>% is Ctrl + Shift + M.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have written a few lines in our R script and hopefully also added some comments that explain what the code does,
 it is high time to save our script as a file on the hard drive.
 Press Ctrl + S or choose the menu File > Save as....
 What is now saved is,
 as mentioned,
 only the actual text in our R script.
 The data that the script creates or edits,
 as well as the results that are created,
 are not saved with this command.
 We will return below to how we can export results of various kinds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Importing data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To register data in R we can,
 as mentioned,
 create objects and save information in these,
 as individual values or with the function c().
 R can save and organize information in many different forms.
 As an example,
 the function c() creates collections.
 Tables are another,
 of several,
 forms that R can save information in.
 R can in turn save several different types of tables,
 each with their special properties.
 One of the standard formats for tables in R is data.frame.
 Another type of table is tibble,
 which is defined in the tibble package that is included in the tidyverse package,
 which we installed above.
 To create an object with a table of type tibble we can use the function tibble().
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create a table of type data.frame with variables y,
 x and z.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data_table <- tibble(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 y = c(3,2,5,4),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 x = c(3,4,6,7),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 z = c(1,4,0,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To instead create a table of type data.frame we can use the same code as above but replace the word tibble with the expression data.frame.
 When we run many of the functions introduced here,
 these return precisely a table of type tibble.
 As described above,
 each R object has an object class,
 depending on what type of information is saved in the object.
 Tibble is a type of object class.
 To display the content of the object with the table we can use the name of the object as a command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data_table
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is displayed in RStudio's Command window.
 If the object contains a large table,
 the first rows and columns are displayed,
 see section [sec:Arbeta-med-datatabeller i R] below.
 In addition to entering data manually as commands,
 we can also import data from files saved on the hard drive.
 When we are going to do this we often benefit from defining our working directory.
 The working directory is the place where RStudio will look for files that we instruct the program to retrieve information from,
 if we don't specify another location.
 It is also the directory that the program will try to save files in,
 if we instruct the program to export information to the hard drive and don't specify another specific location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can specify working directory with the function setwd().
 In the parentheses for setwd() we write a text string with the directory address we want the script to work against.
 When we work with R and RStudio in Windows,
 the directory address may not contain any backslashes 
\backslash
 (reverse slash).
 If necessary they need to be changed to slashes /.
 The following will not work:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
setwd("C:
\backslash
Documents")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Write instead:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
setwd("C:/Documents")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To define working directory we can also in RStudio use menu Session > Set Working Directory > Choose Directory\SpecialChar ldots
.
 This can also be useful if we have difficulty finding the address to our working directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R has many functions that we can use to import data from files on the hard drive.
 We have already mentioned the file format .R which is the file format that R scripts are saved as.
 R also has several own file formats for saving data:
 .rds,
 .rdata and .rda.
 To export a single R object we can use the function saveRDS().
 Here are two examples that give exactly the same result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
saveRDS(my_data_table,
 file = "my_file.rds")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data_table %>% saveRDS("my_file.rds")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To import data from an rds file on the hard drive we can use the function readRDS("my_file.rds")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also export the information in several R objects to one and the same file on the hard drive if we instead use the file format .rdata or .rda.
 These two file formats are different names for the same file type,
 where .rda is an abbreviation for .rdata.
 To export information to an rda file we can use the function save().
 Say as an example that we have two objects that we want to export to the same file:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
save(my_object_1 ,
 my_object_2 ,
 file="my_file.rda")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To import the same information we can use the function load():
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
load("my_file.rda")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R can also read many different types of file formats,
 for example from Excel and Stata.
 If we want to import a data file of a particular type to the program we need to find a function that can read precisely this file format.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To import data from or export data to files with Excel's file format .xls or .xlsx we can for example install the R packages readxl and writexl and from these use the functions read_xlsx() and write_xlsx() respectively.
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Run install.packages() once
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
install.packages("readxl")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Run library() after each restart of R
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
library("readxl")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Retrieve data from an Excel file
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- read_xlsx(path="my_excel_file.xlsx")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Export the same data to an Excel file on the hard drive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
install.packages("writexl")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
library("writexl")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% write_xlsx(path="my_R_data.xlsx")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functions that aim to import or export data to and from files can also in many cases have many useful options.
 For example,
 we can with the help of these functions choose which tabs in an Excel sheet we want to read data from,
 or write data to.
 The packages readxl and writexl also contain other functions that can be useful,
 which we find for example with the help of the command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
help(package="readxl")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another package with similar functions is xlsx,
 which we can also install and load using the functions install.packages() and library().
 If some type of option or function is missing in a package,
 it can sometimes be valuable to try another similar package.
 We mentioned earlier the file format .csv,
 comma-separated files.
 Like many other programs,
 including Excel and Stata,
 R can also read csv files.
 If we want to import data from a csv file saved on the hard drive to RStudio we can for example use the function read.csv(),
 which is pre-installed in R when we install the program on the computer.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Import csv file
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- read.csv(file="my file on the hard drive.csv")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the command to work,
 the file my file on the hard drive.csv must be saved in the working directory we specified.
 The command imports the information in the file and saves it in the object my_data.
 The information is saved as a table of type data.frame,
 which is determined by the function read.csv.
 If we want the information to be saved as a table of type tibble we can for example write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- read.csv("my_file.csv") %>% as_tibble()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead want to export data from RStudio to a csv file on the hard drive we can use the function write.csv(),
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data_object %>% write.csv(file="my_file.csv")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Working with data tabels
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Arbeta-med-datatabeller i R"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R can,
 as mentioned,
 handle information in many different ways and in many different forms,
 where two variants are in data tables of type tibble and data.frame,
 which were introduced above.
 This section gives some examples of how we can edit tables of this type and is based on the following object with table,
 which we described above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- tibble( 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 y = c(3,2,5,4),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 x = c(3,4,6,7),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 z = c(1,4,0,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To display the information in an object we can,
 as mentioned,
 call the object name,
 which in this case is my_data.
 If we want to look at the table in a similar way as when we for example work in Excel and Stata,
 we can use the function view():
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
view(my_data)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function view() opens a new tab in RStudio that displays the table.
 To get more comprehensive information about a table we can use the functions str(my_data) and summary(my_data).
 For continuous variables,
 summary() returns percentiles,
 which can give us a comprehensive picture of the frequency distribution of a variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to know names of columns or rows in a table we can use the functions colnames(my_data) and rownames(my_data).
 Note that all these functions return information that we,
 if needed,
 can save in new R objects.
 If we for example want to create a list of the variables in a table we can for example use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_variables <- colnames(my_data)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The object my_variables now contains only the name of the variables.
 No other information about the variables is saved in my_variables,
 such as what type of data is found in the table my_data.
 To display the first rows in a table we can use the function head(),
 which returns any number of rows counted from the top in a table.
 To display the last rows in the table we can use tail(),
 which returns rows counted from the bottom.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Display the 22 top rows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
head(x = my_data,
 n = 22)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Next line gives the same result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% head(22)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# The 3 rows at the bottom of the table
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% tail(3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions head() and tail() can also be used if we for example want to reuse a smaller part of a table.
 Say for example that we have a table in an object called my_table and we want to export the first 100 rows in this table to a csv file on the hard drive.
 We can do this with the following code:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
my_table %>% head(100) %>% write.csv("the_data_file.csv")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To edit columns and rows in a table we can use many functions from the dplyr package.
 This package is included in the tidyverse package,
 which we installed and activated above.
 To read more about this package we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
help(package="dplyr")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions below work,
 unless otherwise stated,
 in a similar way:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The first argument in the function is an object with a table.
 For example the object my_data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then we describe what we want to do with the table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The result of the function also becomes a table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example,
 if we want to change the name of a variable we can use the function rename( new_name = old_name ):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% rename( var_y = y )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use pipe 
\family typewriter
%>%
\family default
 to specify the object my_data as the first argument in the function rename().
 The function rename() describes what we want to do with the table (change the name of one or more variables).
 The result of the function rename() is in turn also a table of type tibble.
 For the variable to be changed in the object my_data we must also overwrite the old object by reusing the name of the object,
 for example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- my_data %>% rename( var_y = y )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If for some reason we want to leave the first object untouched we can create a new object by simply naming the new object something else,
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data_2 <- my_data %>% rename( var_y = y )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a table and want to remove columns we can use the function select().
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep columns y and x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% select(y,x)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep all columns except y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% select(-y)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep columns y and x but rename them
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% select( var_x = x ,
 var_y =y )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to remove specific rows from a table we can use the function filter().
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep all rows where variable y>5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% filter(y>5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep all rows where variable x equals 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% filter(x==3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The double equals signs are used to formulate conditions.
 We can also use <,
 >,
 <=,
 >= and != where the last means "not equal to".
 That is,
 filter(x!=3),
 would here mean that we want to keep all rows in the table where variable x is not equal to 3.
 We can combine several conditions by separating these with commas in the function filter().
 The following means that we want to keep only those observations where both conditions are met:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% filter(x>2 ,
 y>3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To describe how several conditions must be met simultaneously we can use the symbol & (and).
 To describe how one of several conditions must be met we can use the function | (or).
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Keep the rows where x>2 OR y>2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% filter(x>2 | y>2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as before,
 we must also here use the function <- if we want the object my_data to be changed in memory.
 The functions select() and filter() return a table but if we don't overwrite the old object my_data,
 R will not note that any changes have been made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To sort a table by observations,
 from smallest to largest value,
 we can use arrange().
 To sort from largest to smallest we can combine this with the function desc().
 Here are two examples:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# From smallest to largest 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% arrange(x) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# From largest to smallest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% arrange(desc(x))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can change the order of columns with the function relocate().
 Example:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table %>% relocate(z,x,y)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To create new columns and edit old ones in a table we can use the function mutate().
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create new variable from existing variable x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(ln_x = log(x))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create new variable with value 1 on all rows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(new_var = 1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function mutate() can also be combined with functions such as as.numeric() and as.character() to change data format on a variable in a table.
 If we for example have a variable x saved as text and want to read this as numbers instead we can as part of a command use the following:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(x = as.numeric(x)).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to instruct R that a variable consists of text strings we can instead use the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(x = as.character(x))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By combining mutate() with conditions we can edit specific rows,
 observations,
 for example with regard to existing values in one or more variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Edit existing variable x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(x = 3 if x==2 & y==2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function row_number() returns row numbers in a table.
 We can use this to edit specific observations in a variable.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Change the value of variable x,
 row 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(x = 3 if row_number()==4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To edit specific observations we can also benefit from combining the function mutate() with the functions if_else() and case_when().
 In the function if_else() we first specify a condition,
 then comma and the value we want if_else() to return if the condition is met,
 and finally comma and the value that should be returned if the condition is not met.
 We can for example use this to edit all rows that meet a condition.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% mutate(new_variable = 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
if_else( row_number() <=2 ,
 1,
 0))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This command creates the new variable new_variable and gives it the value 1 for rows 1 and 2 and the value 0 for all other rows.
 With the function case_when() we can specify any number of conditions with associated results.
 Here follows an example where we add the new variable k:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- my_data %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(k = case_when( 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 row_number()<=2 ~ 1,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 row_number()==3 ~ 2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 TRUE ~ 3) )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last argument in the above example,
 TRUE ~ 3,
 means that the rest of the observations in the variable,
 those that don't meet any of the other conditions,
 get the value 3.
 Just as in previous examples we must use <- to overwrite the old object if we want the table saved in the object my_data to be changed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use mutate() and case_when() to edit an existing variable x,
 we can specify TRUE ~ x,
 to let the remaining observations keep previous values.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(x = case_when(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 row_number()==1 ~ 1,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 TRUE ~ x))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To group the rows in a table based on the values in a variable in the table we can use the function group_by().
 In an example above we created the variable k.
 Let us group the table based on the unique values in k.
 Here follows an example.
 All commands that follow after the grouping will take this into account.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
group_by(k) %>%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(sum_per_k_value = sum(x,
 na.rm=TRUE))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we save the table after the grouping,
 the grouping will be saved too.
 To remove the grouping we can use the function ungroup().
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
my_data %>% group_by(k) %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
mutate(sum(x)) %>% ungroup()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another good package for working with tables is tidyr,
 which is also included in the tidyverse package.
 Since we activated tidyverse earlier with the command library("tidyverse") we have already loaded the tidyr package.
 When we restart R or RStudio we must run the command library("tidyverse") again.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two good functions in tidyr are pivot_longer() and pivot_wider().
 With the function pivot_longer() we can transpose or pivot a table from wide to long format.
 With pivot_wider() we can pivot a table to wide format.
 Here follows an example where we move around the values in a small table.
 By working with a small table with few rows and columns it becomes easier to follow what happens in each step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create a table and add a new variable with row numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table <- tibble( a=c(32,14),
 b=c(5,66) ) %>%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(row=row_number())
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Pivot the table to long format
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table <- my_table %>% pivot_longer(cols=a:b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Pivot the table to wide format
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table %>% pivot_wider(names_from=name,
 values_from=value)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both pivot_longer() and pivot_wider() have different useful options,
 which we can read more about in their respective help sections.
 See also the help sections for each package:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
help(package="tidyr")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
help(package="dplyr")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to retrieve a variable from a table and convert this to a vector or a collection with values,
 in the way we can create collections of values with the function c(),
 we can for example use the function pull().
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table %>% pull(x)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where x in the parentheses for pull() is the name of a variable in the table my_table.
 We can also use the dollar sign,
 the $-operator.
 Say we have an object my_table that contains a table with variables x,
 person and gdp2.
 If we want to save a variable from the table in its own new object we can for example use the following commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
var_x <- my_table$x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
var_person <- my_table$person
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
gdp2_var <- my_table$gdp2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to retrieve a specific value we can use square brackets and specify a position,
 such as a column,
 a row or a specific element in a table.
 The following command retrieves the value in variable gdp2 on row 7:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
gdp2_row7 <- my_table$gdp2[7]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Join Tables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Sammanfoga-tabeller R"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To merge columns in two tables we can use the functions full_join(),
 inner_join(),
 left_join() and right_join().
 These functions are built in a similar way but serve slightly different functions.
 The two R objects with tables that should be merged are defined in each function as x and y,
 for example full_join(x= table_1,
 y= table_2).
 If the tables contain columns (variables) that have the same name,
 the function guesses that we want to match observations in these columns against each other in the two tables.
 The function full_join() merges all observations from two tables.
 As an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# table_1 contains persons 1,
 2 and 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_1 <- tibble(person=c(1,2,3),
 age=c(10,20,30))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# table_2 contains persons 1,
 2 and 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_2 <- tibble(person=c(1,2,4),
 height=c(120,190,180))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# The following two lines give the same result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
full_join(x=table_1 ,
 y=table_2,
 by=c("person"="person"))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_1 %>% full_join(table_2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the last line we don't define the option by,
 which is why full_join() instead assumes that we want to match the observations in the variables named person in the two tables.
 If we want to match two columns that don't have the same name in the two tables we can specify that in the option by.
 In the parentheses for by=c() we can also specify that we want to match on several variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is displayed in RStudio's Command window.
 Note the difference when we instead use inner_join(),
 which only merges the observations that match an observation in both tables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_1 %>% inner_join(table_2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function left_join() keeps all columns in the first (the left) table.
 The function right_join() keeps all columns in the second table.
 Note the difference in the results from the following 2 commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_1 %>% left_join(table_2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_1 %>% right_join(table_2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results are shown in figure [fig:
 4 join-kommandon].
 With full_join() we keep all information we have about persons 1 to 4.
 With inner_join() we only keep information about the persons for whom we have values in all columns.
 With left_join() and right_join() we keep all persons from the left and right table respectively and lose the person in each case who is not found in the other table.
\end_layout

