\begin_layout Section
Matrix calculations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In R we can,
 as mentioned,
 write mathematical expressions directly in our script or in the Command window.
 The same applies to calculations with matrices,
 given that we instruct the program that we want to perform matrix calculations.
 We start by creating the following matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\left[\begin{matrix}1 & 2\\
3 & 4
\end{matrix}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In R we can,
 as mentioned,
 write mathematical expressions directly in our script or in the Command window.
 The same applies to calculations with matrices,
 given that we instruct the program that we want to perform matrix calculations.
 We start by creating the following matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To define a matrix we can use the function matrix(),
 for example as in the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A <- matrix(c(1,2,3,4),
 nrow=2,
 byrow=TRUE) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first argument in matrix() is the data that should fill the elements in the matrix,
 by using the function c() and specifying the numbers 1,
 2,
 3 and 4.
 The option nrow=2 defines that the matrix should have 2 rows.
 The option byrow=TRUE specifies that the data that is entered should be read in row-wise.
 The values 1 and 2 therefore become the elements in the top row of the matrix.
 The following command results in exactly the same matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A <- matrix(c(1,3,2,4),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To multiply two numbers in R we can,
 just as in many other programs,
 use asterisk,
 for example 2*3.
 To matrix multiply two matrices we can instead use the command %*%.
 Here is an example where we define a new matrix B and multiply this with matrix A:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
B <- matrix(c(4,2,3,5),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A %*% B 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To add or subtract with matrices we can use + and - as usual.
 For example A - B or A + B.
 To transpose a matrix we can use the function t(),
 for example t(A) to transpose matrix A.
 The inverse of matrix A can in mathematics be described as A^{-1}.
 In R we can calculate the inverse of A with the function solve():
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate the inverse of matrix A:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
solve(A)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\family typewriter
diag()
\family default
 can be used both to return the elements in the diagonal from a matrix,
 give the diagonal in an existing matrix new values or create a new diagonal matrix from for example a vector.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# We start from matrix A:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A <- matrix(c(1,3,2,4),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Return the diagonal in A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
diag(A)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create a diagonal matrix from other values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
c(1,5,4) %>% diag()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Give the elements in the diagonal in A new values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
diag(A) <- c(5,6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Last command changed the content in A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we only specify a number in the parentheses for diag() the function returns a square identity matrix with the same number of rows and columns as the number we specify,
 where all values on the diagonal equal 1.
 For example:
 diag(2) returns a 2
\backslash
times2 identity matrix.
 To calculate the sum of the diagonal,
 the trace,
 in matrix A we can use function trace(),
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate trace for A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
trace(A)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the determinant of matrix A we can use the function det(),
 for example det(A).
 To save the value that is returned in a new object we must as usual use <-.
 In the example above we also combined diag(A) with <- to assign new values to the diagonal elements in A.
 In a similar way we can also give the columns in matrix A new names.
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix_A <- matrix(c(1,3,2,4),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Display the content
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix_A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
colnames(matrix_A) <- c("col1","col2")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Note the difference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix_A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R objects that contain matrices and vectors are not the same thing as an R object that contains a table of type tibble.
 If we want to use our matrix as a table we can convert the matrix's content to a tibble table with the function as_tibble().
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
matrix_A <- matrix(c(1,3,2,4),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
colnames(matrix_A) <- c("col1","col2")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
table_A <- matrix_A %>% as_tibble()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Input–output analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Input-output-analys i R"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section goes through the corresponding example with input-output analysis that we used in section [subsec:Input-outputanalys Excel] and [sec:Input-output-analys Stata].
 In section [subsec:Input-outputanalys Excel] we defined matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=Z*\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where Z is the flow matrix and 
\backslash
text{diag}
\backslash
left(S_{m}
\backslash
right) is a diagonal matrix with the multiplicative inverse of total production per sector along the diagonal.
 Matrix C is a column matrix with production for final consumption per sector.
 The total production from sector j required for all inputs and final consumption is y_{j},
 collected in matrix Y,
 which can be defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Y & =\left(I-A\right)^{-1}S
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where I is an identity matrix with the same dimensions as A.
 We call B=
\backslash
left(I-A
\backslash
right)^{-1},
 which has the same dimensions as A,
 where column sum j is the production multiplier and row sum j is the input multiplier for sector j.
 To perform this calculation in R we start by defining the matrices Z,
 C,
 S,
 S_{m} and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{diag}\left(S_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Z <- matrix(c(2,1,1,3),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
C <- matrix(c(3,3),
 ncol=1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
S <- c(6,7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mat_S <- matrix(c(6,7),
 nrow=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
diag_Sm <- diag(1/S)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we can calculate A,
 B and Y:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
A <- Z %*% diag(Sm) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
B <- solve(diag(2) - A)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Y <- B %*% mat_S
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note how we,
 if we wanted to,
 can write the entire calculation of Y in one command without creating any objects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
solve(diag(2) - 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

(matrix(c(2,1,1,3),
 nrow=2) %*%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

diag(1/c(6,7))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

) %*% c(6,7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Variation and covariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say that we have an R object my_data that contains the variables x,
 y and z (same as above):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data <- tibble( 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 y = c(3,2,5,4),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 x = c(3,4,6,7),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 z = c(1,4,0,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will estimate and calculate mean,
 variance,
 standard deviation as well as some percentiles and quartiles for the variables in this table.
 Parts of this information we can get through the function summary(),
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% summary()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also use one of the many functions that are pre-installed in R,
 such as mean(),
 var(),
 sd() and quantile().
 For example like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate mean for variable x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data$x %>% mean()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate mean using summarize
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
summarize(mean(x),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mean(z))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the function 
\family typewriter
quantile()
\family default
 we can calculate percentiles and thereby also deciles and quartiles.
 In the parentheses for the function we need to specify a variable and which percentiles we want to calculate.
 If we have a collection of values saved in the object x we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
quantile(x,
 .1) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function then returns percentile 10.
 The notation .1 is in R the same value as 0.1.
 To calculate several percentiles we can for example use the function c().
 Here is an example for calculating the 25th,
 50th and 75th percentile (first and third quartiles as well as the median):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
quantile(x,
 c(.25,
 .5,
 .75))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here follow examples of how we can use quantile() with the table in the object my_data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate 30th percentile for x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data$x %>% quantile(.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Calculate 3 different percentiles for x
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
summarize(Three_p = quantile(x,
 c(.1,.2,.3)))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate variance and standard deviation for a variable we can,
 as mentioned,
 use the functions 
\family typewriter
var()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
sd()
\family default
.
 In the parentheses for 
\family typewriter
sd()
\family default
 we can only specify one variable at a time.
 If we only specify one variable in the parentheses for 
\family typewriter
var()
\family default
 the function returns the sample variance.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% select(y) %>% var()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we specify several variables in the parentheses for 
\family typewriter
var()
\family default
 the function instead returns the covariance.
 R also has a specific function for calculating covariance,
 called
\family typewriter
 cov()
\family default
.
 We continue to use the object 
\family typewriter
my_data
\family default
 with the table with four observations for variables y,
 x and z.
 In this case the following two commands give exactly the same result in the form of a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix with estimated variance and covariance between the three variables x,
 y and z in our table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# The function var()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% var()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# The function cov()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_data %>% cov()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above commands we specify the entire object my_data as input value to the functions var() and cov().
 This works because all three variables in the table are quantitative and data is saved so that R understands that they are numerical values.
 If any variable in the table is not numerical,
 for example a variable with text strings,
 the functions instead return an error message.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instead want to calculate the correlation coefficient between two variables we can use the function cor().
 If we specify several variables as input value for cor(),
 for example in the form of a table with only quantitative variables,
 the function returns the pairwise correlation between all variables.
 Below follows an example where we send the table in my_data,
 which contains three variables,
 to the function cor().
 The result is shown in figure 
