\begin_layout Section
Probability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Samvariation-och-sannolikhet R"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R has several pre-installed functions for calculating probabilities based on commonly occurring probability distributions.
 Several of these are built in the same way.
 If we want to create 100 values drawn from a continuous uniform probability distribution we can use the function 
\family typewriter
runif()
\family default
 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
runif(100)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default setting is that the minimum value for this probability distribution is 0 and the maximum value is 1.
 We can also specify new values for minimum and maximum through the options min and max.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
runif(100,
 min=0,
 max=100)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual we must use the function 
\family typewriter
<-
\family default
 if we want to save these values in an R object.
 If we instead want to know probabilities based on a density function for this type of probability distribution we can use the function 
\family typewriter
dunif()
\family default
.
 The function 
\family typewriter
punif()
\family default
 returns values for the cumulative probability function.
 The function 
\family typewriter
qunif()
\family default
 returns the inverse of the cumulative distribution function,
 the quantile function.
 The corresponding R functions for the normal distribution are called 
\family typewriter
rnorm(),
 dnorm(),
 pnorm()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
qnorm()
\family default
.
 If we only specify one argument in the parentheses for these functions,
 all of these are based on the standard normal distribution.
 The following code gives the cumulative probability for z=0:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
pnorm(0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Density function's probability for z=0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions have different options for defining the distribution,
 for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
pnorm(2,
 mean=2,
 sd=1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
