\begin_layout Section
Regression analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Regressionsanalys med r"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section introduces how we can work with regression analysis in R.
 First by estimating results ourselves using matrix calculations.
 Then how we can use ready-made R functions to achieve the same results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis with matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y=XB+U
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 are column matrices with the explained variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and the error terms 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a matrix with the explanatory variables,
 where the first column has the value 1 in each element,
 for the constant (y-intercept).
 The estimator for the coefficients can be written with matrices as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\left(X^{T}X\right)^{-1}X^{T}Y
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may perform matrix calculations directly in our R script and therefore start by defining the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Y <- matrix(c(3,2,5,4),
 nrow = 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
X <- matrix(c(1,1,1,1,
 3,4,6,7),
 nrow=4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 we can then use the functions 
\family typewriter
t()
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
solve()
\family default
 and matrix multiplication with 
\family typewriter
%*%
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Bhat <- solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% Y
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Check the result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
Bhat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regression analysis with 
\family typewriter
lm()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R also has many ready-made functions for regression analysis and even more can be downloaded in the form of R packages.
 To estimate a linear regression model based on the least squares method we can use the function lm().
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Create a table
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table <- tibble(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 y = c(3,2,5,4),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 x = c(3,4,6,7),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 z = c(1,4,0,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
# Estimate the regression model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm(formula = y~x ,
 data= my_table)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we run the code above,
 the estimated coefficients a and b from the regression model y=a+bx+u are displayed in the Console window,
 where y and x are variables and u is the error term.
 The result is shown in figure [fig:Resultat-av-lm() r].
 If we want to add more variables to the regression model we can do so with the plus sign.
 As an example,
 say we instead want to estimate the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}x+\beta_{3}z+v
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients and v is the error term.
 To estimate this model with lm() we can use the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm(y ~ x + z,
 data = my_table)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../___arkiv/Datorprogram för samhällsvetare/texten/r lm results1.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Resultat-av-lm() r"

\end_inset

Results of 
\family typewriter
lm()
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we want to estimate the following regression model with the interaction term 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}x+\alpha_{3}z+\alpha_{4}xz+\epsilon\label{eq: R reg mod interaktionsterm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where y,
 x and z are the variables,
 
\backslash
alpha are the coefficients and 
\backslash
epsilon is the error term.
 The variable xz is variable x multiplied by variable z.
 To estimate this model with the function lm() we can do this with the following command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm(y ~ x + z + x:z,
 data = my_table)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term x:z is the interaction term.
 Another way to get the same result is the following notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm(y ~ x*z,
 data=my_table)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notation x*z means that the program adds both x and z as separate explanatory variables as well as an interaction term for xz,
 which is why the regression model in this case becomes the one in equation [eq:
 R reg mod interaktionsterm].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to estimate the regression model y=
\backslash
beta_{1}+
\backslash
beta_{2}x+
\backslash
beta_{3}z+v with robust standard errors,
 that is an adjusted variant of the variance-covariance matrix,
 we can do this for example with the function lm_robust().
 In the parentheses for lm_robust() we fill in as usual the regression model,
 for example y ~ x + z,
 and data,
 for example data=my_table.
 As an option we can then specify which method we want to use to adjust the standard errors and the variance-covariance matrix by defining the argument se_type.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use adjustment HC0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm_robust(y ~x ,
 data=my_table,
 se_type="HC0")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use adjustment HC1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm_robust(y ~x ,
 data=my_table,
 se_type="HC1")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See the function's help section for more options and more information.
 When we run a command with lm(),
 several other results are estimated and calculated.
 To work with these we can for example save the lm result in a new object and use the function summary().
 Here follows an example of commands.
 The result from lm() combined with summary() is shown in figure [fig:
 r lm summary]:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm_results <- lm(y~x,
 data = my_table)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
lm_results %>% summary()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
