\begin_layout Standard
In the parentheses for aes() we can specify several arguments besides x and y.
 For example,
 we can use an aesthetic command,
 like color and define this as a variable,
 like color=person,
 where person is a variable in the table we use in the ggplot command.
 The unique values in the variable we refer to will define the aesthetic property,
 which in this case becomes the color of the data points that are drawn in the chart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below follows an example with three groups,
 where each group of observations is grouped in the variable person.
 To create the variable person we use the function rep() and create three values of each unique value:
 "a",
 "b" and "c".
 The table contains nine observations,
 three per group.
 By specifying color=person in the parentheses for aes() in the parentheses for ggplot(),
 each group will get its own color in the chart.
 The result is shown in figure [
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fig:Diagram-där-linjernas r graf 3
\end_layout

\end_inset

].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tibble(time=rep(c(1,2,3),3),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 person=c(rep("a",3),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 rep("b",3),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 rep("c",3)),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 value=c(2,4,3,
 4,3,2.5,
 3,2,4)) %>%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
ggplot(aes(x=time,
 y=value,
 color=person)) + geom_line()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To draw a regression line we can use geom_smooth().
 In the parentheses we can among other things define the option method,
 which specifies which method we want to use to draw the regression line.
 Below follows an example where we use method="lm" where lm stands for linear model,
 which means that the line is estimated based on the least squares method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we in the parentheses for aes() specified that we want to use variable y for the argument y and variable x for the argument x,
 geom_smooth() assumes that we want to draw the regression line based on an estimation of the regression model y=a+bx+u,
 see section [sec:Regressionsanalys med r].
 In R this regression model can be written y ~ x.
 In the parentheses for geom_smooth() we also specify the option se=TRUE,
 which means that the confidence interval is drawn out.
 Read more in the help section for geom_smooth().
 The result of the code below is shown in figure [fig:Diagram-med-regressionslinje.
 r graf lm].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tibble(x=c(3,4,6,7),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
y=c(5,2,3,1)) %>%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
ggplot(aes(x=x,y=y)) +
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
geom_point() +
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
geom_smooth(method="lm",
 se=TRUE)
\end_layout

