\begin_layout Section
Iterations and Loops
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many ways to work with iterations in R.
 We have already used certain forms of iterations in different examples above.
 For example to calculate the sum per group in a table using the function 
\family typewriter
group_by()
\family default
 or to define colors and shapes in charts by combining options like color and fill in the parentheses for 
\family typewriter
aes()
\family default
 with the name of a variable in our table.
 The function 
\family typewriter
group_by()
\family default
 and other functions in among others the dplyr package (which was mentioned above) can many times be combined to achieve unexpected results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will introduce how we can build iterations and loops using the function 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
.
 The function 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 is for building loops and has two arguments.
 The first argument is called .x and is the input value that the function should use for each loop round.
 The input value can consist of a collection of values from the function 
\family typewriter
c()
\family default
,
 the elements in a vector,
 the columns in a table or something else.
 The second argument is .f,
 which defines what the function 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 should do with the current value in each loop round.
 We can fill .f with a single simple operation or with a long chain of commands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 returns a form of data called a list.
 A list does not only refer to a collection of values (such as from the function 
\family typewriter
c()
\family default
) but is a special form for how data can be organized.
 Each element in a list can consist of different things.
 An element in a list can be a number or a text string but it can also be an entire table.
 A list can therefore be a collection of tables.
 We will not go through this in detail here but focus on how we can work with 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 and tables,
 as well as get a table as a result of our loop in 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
.
 Here is a simple example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
c(1,2,3) %>% map(log)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens in the command above is that the function 
\family typewriter
c()
\family default
 sends the three values 1,
 2 and 3 to 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 which in turn uses the function 
\family typewriter
log()
\family default
.
 The first round the function takes the value 1 and returns the logarithm of this as the first element in the list that 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
 starts creating.
 The second round the function takes the value 2,
 creates the logarithm of this and returns this as the second element to the list from 
\family typewriter
map()
\family default
,
 and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entire command returns a list with the logarithmic values of 1,
 2 and 3.
 To instead of a list object get a vector we can add the function 
\family typewriter
list_simplify()
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
c(1,2,3) %>% map(log) %>% list_simplify()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example is of course completely unnecessary since we can instead take 
\family typewriter
log(c(1,2,3))
\family default
.
 Say now that we have the following table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table <- tibble(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 y = c(3,2,5,4),
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 x = c(3,4,6,7),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 z = c(1,4,0,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to calculate a result per column,
 for example mean,
 we can for example use the following command with map():
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table %>% map(mean) %>% list_simplify()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that we want to calculate several things at the same time and return a table.
 We can do this with the following command,
 which is explained below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
my_table %>% map(~{
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tibble(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 mean = mean(.x),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 sd = sd(.x)) %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
return()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
}) %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
list_rbind() %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(variable = my_table %>% colnames())
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The object my_table is sent to map().
 The first round now map() uses the first column as input value .x.
 The second round map() uses the second column,
 and so on.
 In the parentheses for map() we write ~{} and inside the curly brackets we write the commands we want to apply on each loop round.
 We can also write .f=~{} and get exactly the same result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case we specify that we want to create a new tibble table on each round and in this create the variables mean and sd,
 which all use the values in .x as input values to calculate results.
 On each round a tibble table is now created with only one row (since mean() and sd() return only one constant each).
 We send the tibble table to the function return(),
 which controls what is returned on each loop round.
 The result becomes the same in this case if we delete return().
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the parentheses for map() we send the result (a list) to the function list_rbind() which converts the list object to a table where each tibble table created in the loop rounds is converted to a common tibble table.
 Then we send this single table forward to the function mutate() to create a new variable,
 where we add the name of the three variables x,
 y and z from my_table using the function colnames().
 The result is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tabell-skapad-med map r"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

