\begin_layout Standard
Many work tasks in R are easier to perform with data that is organized in long format.
 We therefore start by pivoting the table to long format using the function 
\family typewriter
pivot_longer()
\family default
.
 To tidy up the table we also use in the command below the options 
\family typewriter
names_prefix
\family default
 (which identifies that the columns gh1990...gh2020 begin with the letters gh),
 values_to (to name the new column with GDP per working hour) and 
\family typewriter
names_to
\family default
 (to name the new variable with the years).
 After 
\family typewriter
pivot_longer()
\family default
 we use the functions 
\family typewriter
mutate()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
as.numeric()
\family default
 to convert the new variable year to numbers instead of text strings.
 The function 
\family typewriter
as.numeric()
\family default
 instructs the program to interpret the values in the variable year as numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
tcb_data <- tcb_data %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
pivot_longer(cols=gh1990:gh2020,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 names_prefix = "gh",
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 values_to = "gdp_hour",
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 names_to = "year") %>% 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mutate(year = as.numeric(year))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the data is in more manageable format.
 Let us now calculate an index per country.
 We can do this using the functions 
\family typewriter
group_by()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
