\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
R can be used in the RStudio program.
 Functions in R are generally written with the function's name followed by parentheses,
 for example mean().
 Generally all functions return information that we can save in R objects.
 To save something in an object we can use <-,
 for example:
 
\family typewriter
result_1 <- mean(c(1,2,3))
\family default
.
 We can then refer to the saved object,
 such as:
 
\family typewriter
result_1 * 4
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can install new functions by downloading and installing R packages.
 For example:
 
\family typewriter
install.packages("tidyverse")
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
library("tidyverse")
\family default
.
 The tidyverse package contains several R packages with many functions.
 Including pipes 
\family typewriter
%>%
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tables are one of several ways that R can handle data.
 A useful type of table is tibble.
 In tidyverse the packages dplyr and tidyr are included which contain many good functions for working with tables.
 For example:
 
\family typewriter
rename(),
 filter(),
 select(),
 mutate(),
 if_else(),
 case_when(),
 pivot_longer(),
 pivot_wider()
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrices can be saved as R objects,
 for example with the function matrix().
 Calculations with matrices can be performed directly in the R script.
 For example:
 
\family typewriter
A %*% B
\family default
 means that we matrix multiply objects A and B which contain compatible matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Examples of functions for studying variation and covariation:
 
\family typewriter
var()
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
cov()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
cor()
\family default
.
 Examples of functions regarding probability:
 
\family typewriter
dnorm(),
 pnorm(),
 qnorm()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
rnorm()
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To estimate regression models with the least squares method we can use the function 
\family typewriter
lm()
\family default
.
 A regression model 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=a+bX+U$
\end_inset

 can in the parentheses for 
